Power Spectral Density Changes in the EEG 
during Mental Arithmetic and Eye-Opening 
A. GLAss and A. W. KWIATKOWSXr 
Departments of Anatomy and Mechanical Engineering University of Birmingham 
Received July 29, 1969 
Summary. The effect of mental arithmetic (standard multiplication, with 
eyes closed) and eye-opening on the power spectral density of the EEG (recorded 
bipolarly from occipital and parietal regions) have been compared. The EEG was 
recorded on magnetic tape from normal subjects, (medical students) in a constant 
environment and subsequently analysed by an analogue computer (Noratom 
Instrument for Statistical Analysis and Computation, ISAC). 
Absolute measurements made from 15 subjects with eyes closed have shown 
that peaks of prover at l0 Itz vary from 9 to 46 ~V 2 per Hz. Qualitatively, 
suppression of power at 10 Ilz is greater due to eye-opening than mental arithme- 
tic. 
Analysis of pooled power spectral density functions from 11 subjects showed that 
the effect of eye-opening differed significantly from the effect of mental arithme- 
tic at 2.5 and 12.5 Itz. Suppression of lower frequency alpha activity was more 
pronounced during calculation than during eye-opening. Compared with the eyes 
closed condition, eye-opening showed a highly significant suppression at 10 and 
12.5 tiz (alpha activity) and from 15 to 25 Hz (beta activity). Mental arithmetic 
induced significant suppression at 7.5 and 10 tIz and from 15 to 30 tIz. Eye- 
opening enhanced lower frequency activity which calculation suppressed. 
Variation was greater between first, second and third calculations in pooled 
power spectral densities than between corresponding eye-opening epochs. It is 
suggested that these differences in effects of eye-opening and mental arithmetic 
reflect differences in underlying cerebral activity, rather than that an underlying 
factor common to both effects may be orbital in origin. 
Introduction 
The EEG changes in man associated with increased mental activity 
while the eyes are closed, for example, during calculation. (Adrian and 
Matthews, 1934; Lorens and ])arrow, 1962; Chapman etal., 1962 ; Glass, 
1964, 1967) resemble superficially the changes induced by eye-opening 
alone. The problem is the extent to which the EEG changes associated 
with eye-opening can be ascribed to increased mental or cerebral activity 
(in the striate cortex) or conversely the extent to which these changes and 
those due to calculation may reflect activity of purely orbital factors. 
Quantitative comparison may help to evaluate these fundamental rela- 
tionships. Alpha activity is more intensely suppressed by eye-opening than 
7 Psychol. l%rsch., Bd. 33 
 86 A. Glass and A. W. Kwi~tkowski: 
by calculation with eyes closed, which has the effect of enhancing beta 
activity (Mundy-Castle, 1957; Volavka et al., 1967). Percent time alpha 
activity and the amplitude of the alpha rhythm are also reduced by 
calculation and affected by the order of the task and the correctness of 
its solution (Kreitman and Shaw, 1965; Glass, 1964, 1967). 
However, during calculation, the pupils dilate (Hess and Polt, 
1964); Mulholland and Evans (1966), Dewan (1967) and Lippold and 
Novotny (1968) have proposed that ocular movements associated with 
eye-opening may be important influences on alpha activity. If so, the 
degree of resemblance of the EEG effects of eye-opening and mental 
arithmetic could be a factor in determining whether eye-movement might 
be a contributory cause of these changes in both conditions. To investi- 
gate this problem, in alpha and other frequency bands, power spectral 
density measurements of the EEG were made and compared during men- 
tal arithmetic with eyes closed and during eye-opening alone. Changes 
in power spectral density functions have been found during continuous 
photic and auditory stimulation (Sato and Mimura, 1956; Mimura 
et al., 1962; Suhara and Suzuki, 1964) and detailed spectral analysis 
of electrical activity from different cerebral regions (Walter et al., 
1966) have been reported. A preliminary account of these experiments 
has been given (Glass and Kwiatkowski, 1968). 
Method 
Environment 
Environmental control was achieved by recording the EEG while each subject 
s~t in an acoustically and electromagnetically shielded chamber mounted on rubber- 
in-shear, in which total (audible and non-audible) sound-pressure levels were 
attenuated by 54 db, and all components were joined by metal-to-metal contacts 
of braided monel strip. The shielded EEG cable passed through the chamber 
wall. Two way- audio-communication was maintained between subjects and experi- 
menters. Subjects were illuminated, from behind, by a constant source. 
Experimental Procedure 
Subjects were medical students at the University of Birmingham, in normal 
health. The channels for analysis were selected from both anterior and posterior 
parietal and occipital regions [bipolar electrodes C3~P3, P3--01, C4--P4 and 
P4--02 (Jasper, 1958)]. Lint covered and silver disc electrodes were applied and 
supraorbital electrodes used to monitor eye-movements (Lorens and Barrow, 
1962). 
A six-to-ten minute EEG recording was taken. Each test was carried out in 
11 subjects in two sets. The first set contained three resting periods during which 
the eyes were closed, lasting thirty seconds, each followed by a period during which 
eyes were open of the same duration. The second set consisted of three similar 
thirty-second eyes-closed periods each followed by the presentation of three two- 
digit multiplications exclusively composed of digits of 5 and over (Glass, 1966). 
 EEG Spectrum in Calculation and Eye Opening 87 
The effect of order was balanced out by the experimental design. Power spectral 
densities were measured on 15 subjects in total, but the complete experiment was 
carried out on the 11 subjects referred to above. 
EEG Recording and Analysis 
The EEG was monitored by oscilloscope and recorded on magnetic tape on a 
seven track Ampex Portable Instrumentation recorder (SP 300) and simultaneously, 
graphically on a Beckman 8 Channel Dynograph or an S.E.L., UV galvanometer. 
One tape*recorder channel was reserved for coded or spoken information. 
The signal was later played back on to a tape-loop of an analogue computer, 
I SAC, (Noratem, Instrument for Statistical Analysis and Computation). 
The output of the analyser, which was a power spectral density function was 
written out by a graph plotter. If an EEG channel contained evidence of 
excessive eye-movement artefact or electromyographic activity it was not analy- 
sed. Also, if a portion of the channel contained eye-movement artefact or electro- 
myographic activity it was not analysed. Apart from applying these criteria, no 
selection of samples for analysis was made which might might have biased the 
results. Ten seconds of real time of EEG trace were taken at random from each 
condition for each subject. This was played back at twice the recording speed 
to improve the relative frequency resolution. 
Measurement and Comparison o/Power Spectral Densities 
Measurements of the magnitude of the power spectral density were made at 
increments of 2.5 Hz from zero to 30 Hz and the effects of eye-opening and mental 
arithmetic with the eyes closed on the power spectral density compared at each 
frequency. At each frequency level, the ratio of the magnitude of the power 
spectral density during eye-opening to the magnitude of the power spectral density 
of the same frequency level during the preceding eye-closure period was found for 
each of the three eye-opening periods for each subject. Similarly, the ratios of the 
magnitudes of the power spectral densities at each frequency level during calcu- 
lation with eyes closed to the preceding periods of eye-closure without calculation 
were found for each calculation by each subject. The difference between these 
ratios for eye-opening and mental arithmetic conditions and the differences of these 
to the resting eyes-closed condition were compared by ""t"" tests at each frequency 
level (Schallek et aI., 1968). Absolute values of spectral density at different 
h'equencies were calculated in units of tzV 2 per Hz (Walter, 1968). 
Results 
Observations on Individual Subjects 
Comparisons by way of example of the direct effects of eye-opening 
and calculation on the EEG (Fig. l A) show that suppression of the alpha 
rhythm by mental arithmetic, is less intense than that induced by eye- 
opening. Considerable suppression at 10 Hz can be seen in the power 
spectral density function of one subject (Fig. 1 B), and at other frequen- 
cies. The other subject shows a characteristic bimodal peak of energy 
at two frequencies both within the alpha range (at 8--9 and 12--13 Hz). 
