The mean power during eye-opening and mental arithmetic, at diffe- 
rent frequency levels, as ratios of the power with eyes closed, was 
compared. Statistical analysis (see Table) of the effects of eye-opening and 
eye-closing showed that in the lower frequencies (delta and low theta), 
power was enhanced by eye-opening but only at 2.5 Hz was this even 
doubtfully significant (mean difference of ratios: 0.203; p ~-0.1--0.05). 
At 7.5 Hz, in the region of low alpha, suppression of power was 
doubtfully significant during eye-opening, but in the remainder of the 
alpha range, 10.0 and 12.5 Hz mean differences of ratios were large 
(5.827 and 3.676) and highly significant (79 = 0.02--0.01 and 0.01--0.001 
respectively). In the beta range, from 15 to 25 Hz, a statistically signi- 
ficant suppression of power occurred during eye-opening compared with 
the eyes closed condition. 
Quantitative effects of mental arithmetic on the pooled power spec- 
tral density function were not identical with the effects of eye-opening. 
Up to 5.0 Hz in thetheta/delta band there was suppression of power 
which did not reach the level of statistical significance. Suppression of 
power at 7.5 Hz and 10 Hz (low alpha) was highly significant (mean 
difference of ratios; 0.871 and 1.032; p=0.0l--0.001 and 0.02--0.01) 
but only doubtfully significant at 12.5 Hz (high alpha). From 15 to 30 Hz 
(beta) (except 25 Hz) suppression of power during mental arithmetic 
compared with the eyes closed condition was statistically significant. 
Statistically significant suppression of power in the upper beta fre- 
 EEG Spectrum in Calculation and Eye Opening 93 
quencies at 27.5 and 30 Hz occured during mental arithmetic, in contrast 
to the effect of eye-opening. 
Direct comparison of the effects of eye-opening with the effects of 
mental arithmetic showed that in the lower frequencies, only at 2.5 Hz 
was the suppression of power significantly greater during mental 
arithmetic (p ~0.05--0.02). At 10 Hz suppression of power by eye- 
opening was considerably greater than that due to mental arithmetic 
(mean difference of power ratios: 4.79) but only doubtfully significant 
(p z0.1--0.05) because of the increased variance of ratios at this fre- 
quency level. At 12.5 Hz suppression by eye-opening was also greater 
than that due to mental arithmetic (mean difference of ratios: 2.480; 
p z 0.05--0.02). 
The results of statistical analysis, therefore, have reinforced the quan- 
titative findings and have shown a significant difference between effects 
of mental arithmetic and eye-opening on low frequencies of the EEG. 
Power at 2.5 Itz was enhanced by eye-opening and suppressed by 
calculation. In the alpha range, significant suppression of power occurred 
during both conditions, but more intensely with eye-opening. Suppression 
of lower frequency alpha (circa 7.5 ttz) was more pronounced during 
calculation than during eye-opening, and suppression of high frequency 
alpha (12.5 Hz) was greater during eye-opening than during calculation. 
The Time Course o/Power Spectral Changes 
The EEG was recorded and power spectral densities measured during 
three periods of eye-opening and three calculations. The first, second 
and third periods of each condition pooled for all subjects have been 
examined at each frequency (Fig. 5). Suppression at 10 Hz (alpha) 
was less in the third eye-opening period (70%) than in the first two 
eye-opening periods (90 % ), qualitatively suggesting habituation. Suppres- 
sion of power at 20 Hz occurred progressively less markedly, also 
suggesting habituation. Enhancement of power did not occur at low 
frequencies in the second of the three eye-opening periods. Each change 
induced by eye-opening was characteristically similar to the others, 
strikingly, the ratios of power at 10 and 12.5 Hz were very nearly con- 
stant at each period. 
The time course of the three calculations differed qualitatively from 
those of eye-opening (Fig. 6). There was more variability between 
sucessive calculations. Suppression of power at alpha frequencies was 
only 55% in the first, 80% in the second and 40% in the third, 
where maximum suppression was at 12.5 Hz. Some increased suppres- 
sion was also found at 20 Hz during the first two calculations, but, in 
general, suppression of power at low frequencies occurred during all 
calculations. 
