 EEG Spectrum in Calculation und Eye Opening 95 
Discussion 
These results of comparison of power spectral density changes during 
eye-opening and calculation have demonstrated a characteristic distri- 
bution in the normal resting record for different individuals and variation 
of the power distribution at different times over the period studied. 
Eye-opening has produced a more consistent effect on power spectral 
density of the EEG than mental arithmetic and significantly greater 
suppression at 10 Hz and enhancement of power at lower frequencies 
than calculation. Greater suppression at 20 Hz occurred during eye- 
opening although,in this, the effect of sequence of presentation may be 
important. Mental arithmetic with eyes closed showed greater variation 
between the first, second and third calculations than eye-opening. 
The quantitative findings will be discussed, firstly, in relation to earlier 
work, both in power spectral density and low frequency EEG analysis, 
secondly, the relevance of the interpretation of the results to possible 
mechanisms of alpha activity, that is the relation of those EEG changes 
to underlying cerebral processes associated with calculation and eye- 
opening, will be considered and finally, the scope and limitations of 
power spectral analysis in this field of EEG work will be outlined. 
Quantitative Findings 
It might be considered advisable to assess and evaluate these 
quantitative findings against the background of earlier experiments in 
this field. 
Suppression of alpha activity at l0 and 12.5 Hz was found during 
eye-opening and mental arithmetic, but suppression due to eye-opening 
was more intense. This is in agreement with the findings of Volavka 
et al. (1967) and Suhara and Suzuki (1964). Significant suppression of 
beta activity up to 30 Hz was found during eye-opening at different 
light intensities (Sato and Mimura, 1956). More augmented beta activity 
occurred during mental calculation than eye-opening (Mundy-Castle, 
1957). In delta and low theta frequency bands, slight enhancement 
occurred around 2.5 Hz during eye-opening which differed significantly 
from suppression at this frequency associated with mental calculation. 
Suppression of beta activity found during calculation and eye-opening 
is unlikely to be due to electromyographic activity as this only in- 
fluences frequency analysis of the EEG above 27.5 Hz (Ellis and Last, 
1953). Variations in the effect of beta activity during mental arithmetic 
may be due to differences in the problems presented or to discrete, in 
contrast to continuous, presentations of calculations (Sato, 1955; Mimura 
et al., 1962). 
 96 A. Glass and A. W. Kwiatkowski: 
The quantitatively significant ""alpha shi~t"" effect, that is, more 
pronounced suppression of the low frequency alpha during calculation 
than during eye-opening and a suppression of high frequency alpha 
greater during eye-opening than calculation, is compatible with the 
concept of polyrhythmic alpha activity, (Walter, 1950; Cobb, 1963). 
Esser and Bicldord (1950) and Mimura et al. (1962) found that the 
dominant alpha frequency was depressed but that slower and also 
faster rhythms were augmented by continuous auditory stimuli. After 
repetition, these ultimately shifted back to the dominant alpha fre- 
quency of the resting condition, suggesting an incomplete habituation. 
Following continuous photic stimulation, Sato and Mimura (1956) 
found that low frequency alpha wave peaks diminish and those of 
high frequency are enhanced. A bimodal power spectral function of 
occipital alpha similar to subject Re. (see Fig. 1 B) has been described 
(Sato, 1955). Intermittent click stimuli enhanced the dominant alpha 
frequencies and some higher frequencies (Sato et al., 1959) but a single 
flash stimulus caused temporary blocking of alpha frequencies followed 
by enhancement of alpha activity especially at 8.0 Hz. Bell stimulation 
diminished some elements and augmented others in different regions of 
the brain, (Mimura et al., 1962). 
Concerning the sequence of presentation, Kreitman and Shaw (1965) 
showed mean significant changes for a visual task and for continuous 
mental arithmetic but the effects of eye-opening and closing were not 
statistically significant. A significant increase in percent time alpha 
activity occurred during the presentation of twenty calculations (Glass, 
1967). In the light of these results, our findings of no statistically 
significant change in the time-course of power spectral densities are not 
wholly expected. This difference may be due to a smaller number of 
calculations in the present experiment, or to the possibility that sup- 
pression of power at alpha frequencies and decline in percent time 
alpha may well not be exactly equivalent measures. 
Relation o~ EEG to Underlying Cerebral Processes Associated with 
Calculation and Eye Opening 
The contribution which these results make to the solution of the 
problem of the extent to which EEG changes associated with eye- 
opening and calculation can be ascribed to increased mental activity 
(in the widest sense) or cortical function, can be evaluated. In so far 
as eye-opening and mental arithmetic induced EEG changes that were 
specific to each condition, that is, which differed significantly at 2.5 
and 12.5 Hz (eye-opening enhanced lower frequency activity which 
calculation suppressed) then a more intimate relation of these EEG 
changes to underlying cerebral processes is indicated. Non-specific 
 EEG Spectrum in Calculation and Eye Opening 97 
differences are more likely to be related to more general cerebral 
processes common to both mental arithmetic and eye-opening, for 
example, the general arousal response or orientating response (Sokolov, 
1963) or perhaps associated with eye-movements or oculomotor function. 
Returning to the possibility that a common origin for these changes 
might be found in eye-movement or orbital factors, Lorens and Barrow 
(1962) have shown a marked increase in eye-movements during mental 
arithmetic. On the hypothesis that the alpha rhythm originates as an 
interaction between the corneo-retinal potential and eye-muscle tremor, 
when the cortico-retinal fixation system is inactive (Lippold and 57ovotny, 
1968) it might be predicted that increased eye-movement would reduce 
the amount of alpha activity, but it is doubtful that, with eyes shut, 
retinal fixation could occur during calculation. Therefore, on this hypo- 
thesis, suppression at alpha frequencies would not be anticipated during 
calculation, Increased eye-movement leading to increased ""oculomotor"" 
imbalance (Mulholland and Evans, 1966), would be expected to augment 
the amount of alpha activity rather than decrease it. Thus an enhance- 
ment rather than overall suppression of alpha activity would be pre- 
dicted during calculation if the effect of calculation on the EEG were 
solely mediated through ocular factors. The appearance of alpha activity 
by the upward movement of the eyes has been explained by Dewan 
(1967) as a consequence of a tendency of the eyes to defocus and relax 
convergence. If the hypothesis that the alpha rhythm is dependent on 
peripheral ocular activity is valid, then the effect of increased eye- 
movement during calculation would be to increase not to lessen alpha 
activity. Mental multiplication (when eyes are open) causes dilation of 
the pupil (Hess and Polt, 1964) (implying defocussing and de-accommo- 
dation) which would lead to the prediction from Dewan's theory oh 
more, not less, alpha activity during calculation. 
From these results and considerations, it must be concluded that the 
suppression of alpha activity is an effect not of changes solely in 
orbital factors but a direct result of calculation or the mental activity 
associated with underlying cerebral or cortical processes and, in the case 
of eye-opening, with the functional activity associated with visual pro- 
cesses in the striate cortex. 
Role o] Power Spectral Density Function in EEG Analysis 
It may be worthwhile commenting on the scope and limitations 
of the power spectral density function in EEG analysis in this field. 
Power spectral density analysis was selected from other forms of time- 
series analysis because it measured energy distribution, a parameter 
which has already proved empirically useful in the field of the neuro- 
physiological correlates of behaviour by graphical measurement of the 
EEG (Glass, 1959, 1964). 
 98 A. Glass and A. W. Kwiatkowski: 
In applying a time-series analysis to the EEG, it can beassumed that 
the EEG signal consists of a random and a non-random component. The 
process giving rise to random functions is termed stationary when these 
functions are time-invariant. If it transpired that the random part of 
the EEG signal were significant then the corresponding random process 
should be stationary under constant conditions but should change charac- 
ter systematically under changing experimental conditions. 
The power spectral density functions give a useful, preliminary means 
of description. The chief difficulty in interpretation is due to the fact 
that the length of an EEG record is finite whereas the mathematical 
description is based on infinity. With a finite length of EEG record, 
accuracy in a statistical sense can only be achieved if frequency reso- 
lution is sacrificed. Instead of examining power of discrete frequency 
components, which would require infinite time, it is necessary to 
measure power contained in a band of frequency, thereby performing 
a smoothing operation. 
In this experiment, the smoothing of the power curve takes place 
over a range of 2.5 Hz and no finer frequency resolution should be 
attempted. 
