journal homepage: www.else vier.com/locate/clinph
 The electroencephalographic (EEG) approach to connectivity is
based on coherence and phase locking analysis between EEG elec-
trode sites, it has become a reliable way of detecting abnormalities
in schizophrenia ( Bowyer, 2016 ). Coherence reﬂects the coordinal
inter-relation between brain networks and is closely linked to cog-
nitive processing, as EEG/MEG parameters allow the quantiﬁcation
of interactions between sensor/source-estimates of rhythmic activ-
ity (Decker et al., 2017; Fries, 2005, 2015 ). Coherent neuronal con-
nections capitalize on the neurotransmission dynamics driven by
amino acids glutamate, GABA and others ( Maran et al., 2016 ). This
method was successfully applied for delineation of schizophrenia
and bipolar disorder in resting state EEG ( Kam et al., 2013 ). Specif-
ically, Kam et al. (2013) , demonstrated an increased power in high
frequency bands with few disruptions in neural synchronization in
bipolar patients. In contrast, schizophrenia patients generallyexhibited enhanced synchronization of high frequency bands
within and across hemispheres. The alterations in the resting state
coherence in various frequency bands, measured by EEG/MEG in
patients with schizophrenia, has been intensively studied,
although it remains contradictory ( Boutros et al., 2008; Winterer
et al., 2001 ). The studies suggest that alterations in fast oscillations
at beta and gamma band frequencies are elevated at rest ( Di
Lorenzo et al., 2015 ), reduced ( Kam et al., 2013 ) or even intact
(Winterer et al., 2001 ).
It is well established that cognitive dysfunction constitutes a
hallmark feature of schizophrenia and schizophrenia spectrum dis-
orders ( Heinrichs and Zakzanis, 1998; Keefe, 2008 ). Neurocognitive
deﬁcits in schizophrenia patients correspond to structural and
functional changes in the brain ( van Haren et al., 2008; Lewis,
2012; Schultz et al., 2012 ). Analogously to schizophrenia, schizoaf-
fective disorder (SA) has been associated with cognitive decline in
the same cognitive domains, although it is less pronounced than in
schizophrenia (for a review see Madre et al., 2016 ).
The neurophysiological mechanisms underlying cognitive dys-
functions and their distinct proﬁles in schizophrenia and
schizophrenia spectrum disorders are not well understood
(Garakh et al., 2015; Maran et al., 2016 ). In cognitive tasks, patients
with schizophrenia exhibited altered EEG coherence during the
processing of acoustic stimuli or recognition of emotional expres-
sion ( Brenner et al., 2009, Popov et al., 2014 ). A task that would
probe executive functioning or working memory ( DeStefano and
LeFevre, 2004 ), presumably being the mostly affected in
schizophrenia and schizophrenia spectrum disorders, has not been
widely applied. In one early report, Morrison-Stewart and authors
used a mental arithmetic task and suggested an aberrant func-
tional organization of the brain in schizophrenia, particularly
affecting the left hemisphere ( Morrison-Stewart et al., 1991 ).
Although a mental arithmetic task is easy to administer, it is acomplex task that involves attention, working memory, and exec-
utive functions, which are necessary for performance of even sim-
ple mathematical operations such as addition or subtraction.
Therefore, its application may be beneﬁcial to test the hypothesis
of dysconnectivity in schizophrenia and schizophrenia spectrum
disorders.
The utility of a task-related EEG coherence approach in under-
standing the variability of cognitive processing in clinical popula-
tions has not yet been applied; however, we assume that
functional connectivity changes during task processing presum-
ably having various trajectories ( Shmukler et al., 2015 ) may con-
tribute to the understanding of the common and the distinct
mechanisms of cognitive dysfunctions in the schizophrenia spec-
trum disorders and serve for differentiation of the disorders. The
aim of the study was to evaluate the variation of coherence during
a task-induced activity and resting condition in clinically homoge-
nous groups of patients with ﬁrst episode schizophrenia and
schizoaffective disorder. We hypothesized that the groups may dif-fer in cognitive task processing. In addition, inclusion of patients
with ﬁrst episode psychosis allowed us to study EEG correlates
regardless of the confounding effect of medication and duration
of the illness.
2. Methods
2.1. Experimental sample
The study was conducted in a sample of patients with ﬁrst epi-
sode psychosis and healthy volunteers as previously described in
Garakh et al (2015) . Patients in their ﬁrst psychotic episode diag-
nosed with schizophrenia (n = 32) and schizoaffective disorder of
both manic and depressive episodes (n = 32) were enrolled into
the study. The psychopathology was evaluated in the routine clin-
ical examination and Structural Clinical Interview for PANSS. Diag-
nosis was based on ICD-10 and was conﬁrmed in a 1-year follow-
up.
Control group consisted of 40 healthy volunteers without diag-
nosis of mental illness or neurological disorder or brain injuries.
The groups of patients and controls were matched by gender, age
and years of education. Demographic and clinical characteristics
of the samples are given in Table 1 . The study was approved by
the local ethics committee and all of the participants read and
signed the informed consent.
2.2. EEG acquisition, experimental task and data analysis
Electroencephalogram was recorded from 19 sites based on a
standard ‘International 10–20 System’ (Jasper, 1958): Fp1, Fp2,
F3, F4, F7, F8, C3, C4, T3, T4, T5, T6, P3, P4, O1, O2, including three
midline sites (Fz, Cz, Pz). Reference electrodes were placed on the
linked earlobes. Low pass ﬁlters set at 70 Hz with a time constantof 0.3 s were used during the recording. EEG mapper (MBM, Russia)
was used to quantify EEG traces of 100 s. with a 200 Hz sampling
rate. The electrode impedances were equal or below 10 k
X, with
an average of 5 k X. For four patients and four controls the data
were obtained from 16 cortical electrodes with the same technical
characteristics. Post-processing was performed using a custom
designed variant of the multi-source eye correction method
(Novototsky-Vlasov et al., 2007 ) with a subsequent rejection of
the EEG segments with artefacts (eye movements, muscle arte-
facts). Finally, 10–15 ﬁve-second artefact-free sets (epochs/inter-
vals) were selected by an expert for further analysis.
EEG was recorded during the resting state and during the task
performance. In the resting state the subjects were instructed to
close their eyes and not think of anything in particular. In the
experimental task the participants were asked to perform a mental
arithmetic task known as Kraepelinean counting, in which they
had to perform a subsequent subtraction from 200 in steps of 7
during a 100-sec. time interval. After the task the subjects under-
went a debrieﬁng, in which they were asked for the actual result
of the count. The detailed description of the task is given in
Garakh et al (2015) .
Custom designed software was used for coherence computa-
tion. The data were analysed using coherence analysis of 6 fre-
quency bands: delta (1.5–3.9 Hz), theta (4–7 Hz), alpha (8–13 Hz),
beta1 (13–20 Hz), beta2 (20–30 Hz) and gamma (30–40 Hz). Coher-
ence was calculated using standard algorithms ( Bendat and Piesol,
2010 ):
Cohðc1;c2ÞðfÞ¼jCSc1;c2ðfÞj2=ðCSc1;c1ðfÞ/C3jCSc2;c2ðfÞÞ;
where CS c1;c2ðfÞ¼Pc1;iðfÞc2;iðfÞ;
where CS – complex spectrum; c1 (c2) – channel 1 (2); f –
