puted from the cross spectrum of selected electrode pairs. The
coherence between all site combinations was computed in 171
pairs, then all of the EEG coherence values were transformed using
an Arctan transform in order to provide the normal distribution.
The interhemispheric coherence was analysed in total of 64 pairs
of sites i.e. in 28 pairs of sites of the left and 28 pairs of sites of
the right hemisphere as well as between and within the midline
sites (Fz, Cz, Pz).
2.3. Statistical analysis
Statistical analysis was performed using STATISTICA 10.0 soft-
ware. Demographic and clinical parameters (PANSS scores) were
compared between the groups using a t-test. Separate repeated
measures ANOVAs were conducted for the inter-hemispheric,
intra-hemispheric and midline site pairs for each of the six fre-
quency bands. To examine the inter-hemispheric and midline
coherence, we conducted ANOVAs including one between-subject
factor (group) and two within-subject factors (condition: rest, task;
pairs of sites). To examine the intra-hemispheric coherence, we
conducted ANOVAs including one between-subject factor (group)and three within-subject factors (condition: rest, task; electrode
pairs; hemisphere: left, right). To follow up signiﬁcant interactions,
we conducted one-way or two-way ANOVAs for each condition or
group. Greenhouse-Geisser corrections were applied to correct for
violations of sphericity and homogeneity. Repeated Measures
ANOVAs was performed with FDR correction and was signiﬁcant
at the level p /C200.001 and p < 0.0021 for between (48 comparisons)
and within group (24 comparisons) comparisons, respectively. Sig-
niﬁcant main effects were followed up with post-hoc between-
group and within-group comparisons, which were adjusted using
a Bonferroni correction.
Explorative correlations were obtained with the sum of positive,
negative and total score PANSS and the coherence values of the
patients’ groups that deviated from the coherence values of the
healthy individuals. Correlations between EEG coherence values
in the resting state and the in-task condition and PANSS scores
were obtained for each diagnostic group using Pearson correlation
coefﬁcients with subsequent FDR correction.3. Results
Behavioural task performance results have previously been
thoroughly reported by our group ( Garakh et al., 2015 ). Brieﬂy,
based on the debrieﬁng, the number of the correct answers didnot differ between the groups (p = 0.82), although the speed of
counting was signiﬁcantly higher in the controls (p /C200.05).
Repeated measures ANOVAs revealed the main effect of
‘GROUP’ and the main effect of ‘CONDITION’ and their interaction
in the alpha, beta1, beta2 and gamma frequency bands for inter-
hemispheric, intra-hemispheric and midline coherence values.
The results of the ANOVAs are summarized in Table 2 .
3.1. Between-group comparisons of coherence in the resting state
Signiﬁcant differences of inter-hemispheric coherence between
the three groups were found in the alpha, beta1, beta2 and gamma
bands and for intra-hemispheric and midline coherence in the
beta1, beta2 and gamma bands. Follow-up tests results are summa-
rized in Table 3 .
HC vs. SZ comparison . Interhemispheric coherence was higher in
HC in the alpha beta 1beta2 and gamma bands in the anterior sites,
with the exception of the connections between P3-P4 in the beta2
band, and C3-P4, P3-P4 in the gamma band, which was higher in
SZ. In terms of intra-hemispheric coherence, differences were
determined in the beta2 and gamma bands, which were higher in
the anterior sites in HC than in SZ. Beta1 band intra-hemispheric
coherence was higher in HC in the anterior sites and lower in the
P3-T5 sites. For the midline sites, coherence was higher in HC in
thebeta1 band. In the beta2 band, the midline coherence in HC
was higher in the Fp2-Fz and lower in the P4-Pz sites. For the
gamma band differences were found in the connections between
the particular sites, notably C4-Pz, P3-Pz, P4-Pz, being lower in HC.
HC vs. SA comparison . Differences in inter-hemispheric coher-
