3.4. Correlation analysis between total PANSS scores and EEG
coherence parameters under resting and task conditions
Given the obtained differences in the coherence values between
patients’ groups and healthy controls, we analysed the correlations
between 134 coherence values for inter-hemispheric, intra-
hemispheric and midline connections and PANSS scores values
(sum of positive, sum of negative and total PANSS score) in SZ
group and 42 values and above mentioned PANSS parameters in
SA. FDR correction for SZ group was p = 0.00015 and for SA –
p = 0.0004. The signiﬁcant negative correlations were obtained
only in SZ group and only in the task condition in inter-hemispheric connections in the beta1 band and positive symptoms
score (F4-F7, r = /C00.638, p < 0.05; F7-F8, r = /C00.597, p < 0.05)
(Fig. 4 ).
4. Discussion
This is the ﬁrst study to examine the differences between coher-
ence in ﬁrst episode schizophrenia and schizoaffective disorder
Fig. 2. Between- group comparison of the coherence values in task condition. Increased coherence – brown line (p < 0.01), red line (p < 0.05). Decreased cohere nce – violet
line (p < 0.01), blue line (p < 0.05). (For interpretation of the references to colour in this ﬁgure legend, the reader is referred to the web version of th is article.)2320 Y. Zaytseva et al. / Clinical Neurophysiology 129 (2018) 2315–2324 during both the resting state and the performance of an arithmetic
cognitive task. Our results provide support for neurophysiological
distinctions between both psychotic disorders.
In the resting state, SZ patients presented lower coherence in
the alpha, beta-1, beta-2 bands compared to HC. SA patients
showed similar patterns to SZ patients in these bands. Comparison
of SZ and SA patients showed increased coherence in SA as opposed
to SZ in high frequency ( beta-gamma ) bands in posterior regions.
Altered resting state coherence in schizophrenia is well docu-
mented in the literature ( Hillebrand et al., 2012, Douw et al.,
2011 ). The prefrontal changes observed in our SZ sample are con-
gruent with the majority of the previous reports, which highlighted
a consistent decrease in alpha band coherence in the frontal as well
as parietal and occipital regions in SZ patients at rest, often associ-
ated with psychopathological indicators (for a review see Maran
et al., 2016 ). In the study by Tauscher et al., delta ,theta and alpha
band coherences were observed to be lower in the prefrontal cor-
tex in schizophrenia patients compared to healthy subjects
(Tauscher et al., 1998 ). More recently, a reduction in the inter-
hemispheric coherence of oscillations in the theta band in patients
has been demonstrated ( Koenig et al., 2001, Kam et al., 2013 ).
However, early reports proposed an increase in coherence in low
frequency bands: in the delta band ( Wada et al., 1998 ), and in
thetheta band ( Merrin et al., 1989 ).
In high frequency bands the coherence differences in SZ remain
controversial. The decrease in coherence in SZ compared to con-
trols in the gamma band has been reported in the past as the most
conforming change in resting EEG in schizophrenia ( Light et al.,
2006; Bandyopadhyaya et al., 2011 ). In beta band EEG coherence,
the noted differences in SZ patients are mixed. As Kam et al.
showed, the inter-hemispheric beta1 and beta2 coherence wasnot signiﬁcantly different between patients and healthy controls
(Kam et al., 2013 ). In our previous studies, we found no differences
in interhemispheric connections in high frequency beta band in the
resting state in frontal areas ( Gruzelier, 1999; Strelets et al., 2002 ).
Our current result suggests the decreased coherence in the beta1
band in SZ. Besides, it was inversely correlated with the severity
of positive symptoms. The same result was obtained by
Higashima et al. (2007) who demonstrated decreased beta 1 coher-
ence in frontal and temporal sites being associated with the sever-
ity of positive symptoms in both medicated and drug-naive
schizophrenia patients in a longitudinal resting EEG study. The
authors assumed that disconnection between the frontal and the
temporal lobe in the left hemisphere might be associated with
the generation of acute psychotic symptoms in schizophrenia. Sup-
posedly, the discrepancies in reports on beta band coherence in SZ
might be explained by inhomogeneity of the clinical groups and
inclusion of the patients with various types of schizophrenia, var-
ious syndromes and trajectories of the disease. Since positive
symptoms have a variety of presentations, the effects of particular
symptoms e.g. the severity of delusions or hallucinations should be
addressed in further studies.
Passing on to EEG during cognitive performance, the most gen-
eral observation highlighted the brain regions that are activated
during a task result in event-related desynchronization in the alpha
band, whereas regions associated with task irrelevant and poten-
tially interfering processes exhibit event-related synchronization
(Klimesch, 2012 ). In our study, only healthy controls showed a
local decrease in coherence (desynchronization) of the alpha band
predominantly in the left frontal sites and parietal sites (symmet-
rically), i.e. in brain areas corresponding to mathematical opera-
tions. This supports the hypothesis that alpha band oscillations
Fig. 3. Changes of the coherence in task vs rest conditions. Increased coherence – brown line (p < 0.01), red line (p < 0.05). Decreased coherence – violet line ( p < 0.01), blue
line (p < 0.05). (For interpretation of the references to colour in this ﬁgure legend, the reader is referred to the web version of this article.)Y. Zaytseva et al. / Clinical Neurophysiology 129 (2018) 2315–2324 2321 contribute to information processing ( Klimesch, 2012 ). The
decreased alpha coherence during the cognitive task is supported
by previous studies ( Hoffman et al., 1991; Morrison-Stewart
et al., 1996 ). Abnormal alpha activity seems to be associated with
working memory dysfunction ( De Vico Fallani et al., 2010;
Menon, 2010 ) and lower alpha band coherence in schizophrenia
has been associated with psychomotor poverty ( John et al.,
2002 ). Interestingly, there was no selective decrease in alpha band
synchronization in SZ patients, and the synchronization in patients
of SA occurred in the sites that are not associated with mental
arithmetic. One can assume that, if there is a desynchronization
of the alpha band in the brain areas that are active during the task
performance in the healthy population, then in SA the transloca-
tion of the oscillatory activity is driven by the mechanisms of syn-
chronisation of alpha band activity in the cortical areas that are not
usually activated during the task. This may indicate a deﬁciency in
inhibitory mechanisms. In this regard, the inhibitory activity pro-
vided by alpha oscillations (having a role in the suppression of
task-irrelevant neuronal processing as suggested by Palva and
Palva (2011) ) does not occur in SA. At the same time, the excessive
decrease in spectral power and desynchronization in the alpha
band in SZ presumably indicates the inordinate inhibitory mecha-
nisms making the cognitive performance more demanding(Klimesch et al., 2007; Jensen and Mazaheri, 2010 ).
Given the potential functional roles in cognitive processing of
other frequency bands, more speciﬁc and differentiated mecha-
nisms can be affected as well. Recently, Tschentscher and Hauk(2016) suggested the functional role of the bands for an arithmetic
problem-solving task, proposing the increased midline theta power
for the retrieval strategy and reduced alpha and beta for procedural
strategies, thus being differentially addressed in executive and
retrieval demands. Furthermore, modulations of the beta 1 band
in frontal areas is well established and is associated with decision
making ( Pesaran et al., 2008; Wong et al., 2016 ) and relevant to
selective attention processing ( Spitzer and Blankenburg, 2011 ).
As further proposed, the high frequency beta band has a similar
functional role to gamma activity implying task-relevant engage-
ment ( Tallon-Baudry et al., 1998; Kornblith et al., 2016 ). In our
SZ patient sample compared to the controls, we observed a
decrease in coherence in the beta1, beta2 and gamma2 bands in
the right prefrontal and occipital, central and frontal areas. These
ﬁndings, speciﬁcally the localization of these changes, are in linewith Kissler et al., who showed reversed lateralization of the spec-
tral power of gamma activity in the right frontal area during mental
arithmetic task performance in SZ patients as opposed to the left
frontal areas in healthy controls ( Kissler et al., 2000 ), providing fur-
ther support for a relation between abnormal gamma band oscilla-
tions and the disturbance of higher cognitive processes in
schizophrenia. Other studies utilizing various cognitive tasks,
though not requiring arithmetic abilities, showed similar results(for a review see Light et al., 2006; Uhlhaas et al., 2008; Uhlhaas
and Singer, 2010, 2013 ). Spencer et al. observed decreased gamma
band coherence in schizophrenic patients compared to healthy
controls in response to visual sensory stimuli ( Spencer et al.,
2003 ). In another study by Bucci et al., gamma coherence was
reduced in a subgroup of schizophrenia patients without predom-
inant negative symptoms in response to an auditory oddball para-
digm ( Bucci et al., 2007 ).
On the contrary, SA patients showed a paradoxical increase in
coherence in both low and high frequency bands (alpha, beta1,
beta2 and gamma bands) during mental arithmetic task perfor-
mance. We assume that such a non-selective increase in connectiv-
ity in the majority of the bands may be associated with the
affective component in these patients. As a matter of fact, alter-
ations in EEG coherence, notably in the alpha and beta bands, were
demonstrated in affective disorders ( Knott et al., 2001; Fingelkurts
et al., 2007 ). Manic patients showed reduced gamma coherence in
response to stimuli compared to healthy controls ( Ozerdem et al.,
2010 ) and the same results were observed in a group of bipolar
patients ( Özerdem et al., 2011 ). On the contrary, patients with
major depressive disorders showed increased phase synchroniza-
tion in the theta, alpha and beta bands primarily in the frontal-
parietal and frontal temporal sites of the left hemisphere ( Li
et al., 2016 ). Since the majority of SA patients in the present study
experienced a depressive type of SA, our results correspond well tothe above-mentioned ﬁndings of Li et al (2016) . This is also true
with respect to the correlations with psychopathology, notably
the correlations of task-related, left-lateralized coherence and pos-
itive symptoms.
Based on our previously reported ﬁndings for spectral power
characteristics during rest and mental arithmetic task performance
in the same samples ( Garakh et al., 2015 ), we were able to identify
the physiological patterns associated with each of the study
groups. Thus, in healthy individuals, we found local changes in
spectral power (SP) and coherence. Speciﬁcally, we detected an
increase in SP in the frontal midline theta band, and SP and coher-
ence in the anterior beta1 and gamma bands, accompanied by a
decrease in SP and coherence in the low frequency alpha band. In
the SZ group, relatively to HC, we observed a decrease in SP in
thetheta, alpha and beta 2 bands and the alpha coherence was sig-
niﬁcantly decreased. In the SA group, the characteristics of the SP
during the mental arithmetic tasks mimicked the healthy group,
Fig. 4. Signiﬁcant correlations in SZ group between inter-hemispheric coherence
values in beta1 band in task condition and PANSS positive symptoms scores.2322 Y. Zaytseva et al. / Clinical Neurophysiology 129 (2018) 2315–2324 i.e. SP in the gamma band in the anterior sites of the left hemi-
sphere increased, although the SP of the alpha band signiﬁcantly
decreased similar to the SZ group. In addition, similar to the SZ
group, the SA group revealed a decrease in SP in the theta and beta2
bands. At the same time, changes in coherence in the SA group are
unique, being different from both the SZ and HC groups. Coherence
in the anterior sites was elevated in both high and low frequency
bands. Together, in healthy individuals, the increase and decrease
of the EEG SP and synchronization across various frequency bands
(each band has its own functional role) and in the particular loca-
tions can be considered as the optimal neural patterns needed for
successful cognitive task performance. These mechanisms are vio-
lated in both psychotic disorders, but in distinct ways, being less
inhibited in SA but at the same time demonstrating dysconnectiv-
ity in the frontal sites similar to SZ only in a resting state. Futurestudies should test our novel hypothesis that both these psychoses
share aberrant functional connectivity but differ in the extent to
which the inhibitory mechanisms are affected.
Several limitations should be mentioned. Firstly, the psy-
chopathology was evaluated in the routine clinical examination
and Structural Clinical Interview for PANSS, although the Structural
Clinical and Diagnostic Interview for DSM-IV-TR axis I disorders
(SKID) was not applied. This limitation was overcome by a number
of qualiﬁed physicians involved in the diagnostic procedure and
showing inter-rater reliability. Secondly, as we didn’t focus specif-
ically on factors inﬂuencing the coherence changes, we performed
just an exploratory correlative analysis of coherence changes in
patients’ groups with the severity of psychopathological symp-
toms. The inverse association between beta 1 coherence and posi-
tive symptoms severity made us conclude that the decreased beta 1
coherence in frontal sites during the task in schizophrenia might
not originate only in the task performance as being rather pre-
dicted upon the severity of positive symptoms. Further investiga-
tion may provide stronger and more detailed evidence of this
relation.
5. Conclusions
In summary, the synchronized activity of the neural networks is
required for the successful information processing. Alterations in
the behavioural task performance being at the ﬁrst glance similar
in the patients with schizophrenia and schizoaffective disorder,
are presumably driven by distinct and even polar neural mecha-
nisms. The distinctiveness and similarity indeed makes the scien-
tiﬁc study of the schizophrenia spectrum disorders challenging
(Heckers, 2009 ). The task related coherence was immensely
diverse (and not the resting state coherence) and could better dis-
entangle the clinical groups .The application of the mental arith-
metic task that is sensitive to the frontal activity being a
hallmark of schizophrenia and schizophrenia spectrum disorders
allowed to elicit the commonalities in coherences and differences
in EEG bands reﬂecting predominantly inhibitory processes
required for effective information processing. This study provides
an evidence of neurophysiological distinction of these two disor-
ders from the schizophrenia spectrum.
