its difﬁculty level using EEG signals
Binish Fatimah, Dipro Pramanickyand Pranav Shivashankaranz
Department of Electronics and Communication Engineering, CMR Institute of Technology, Bengaluru, Karnataka,
India, 560037
Email:binish.f@cmrit.ac.in,ydipr17ec@cmrit.ac.in,zprvs17ec@cmrit.ac.in
Abstract —This paper presents a methodology for automatic
detection of mental arithmetic tasks and detection of the difﬁculty
level of the given task, using single channel EEG signals. It is
vital to understand the response of cerebral cortices to different
levels of task difﬁculty and give a quantitative measure to the
role of different brain waves in cognitive tasks. Here, the EEG
signals are decomposed using a ﬁlter bank to obtain gamma,
beta, alpha, theta and delta rhythms and features such as the
energy, entropy, mean and L2norms are evaluated for each of
these rhythms. Performance of three machine learning classiﬁers
namely; support vector machines, decision tree and quadratic
discriminant analysis are compared. The algorithm detects the
rest state of the brain and the active state of the brain for the
given cognitive task. The EEG signals are also classiﬁed into two
groups based on difﬁculty level of the given task.
Index Terms—Mental arithmetic task, brain cortices, brain
waves, machine learning, EEG
I. I NTRODUCTION
Brain is known as an electro-chemical organ and its elec-
trical activity can be recorded as an Electroencephalography
(EEG) signal. EEG signals are used in various kinds of
applications such as seizure detection as well as prediction,
emotion classiﬁcation, sleep stage classiﬁcation, and drug
effects analysis etc. [1]–[6]. EEG signals can also be used for
cognitive task classiﬁcation [7]–[10], which is the objective
of this paper. In order to effectively classify the EEG signals
into different categories one must understand the physiology
of the brain and the relationship between cognitive task with
different cortices of the brain. This can be used in detecting
various learning disabilities and in biofeedback systems [11]–
[13].
Our cerebral cortex includes frontal, parietal, temporal, and
occipital lobes and each of the lobe process distinct sensory
information, for example the frontal lobe process the cognitive
skills, such as memory, language, judgement, emotional ex-
pression, problem solving, and sexual behaviours. The parietal
lobes process of sensory information, comprehending spatial
orientation, temporal lobe process sound and the occipital lobe
process visual information. EEG signals capture the electrical
activity of these four cortices and helps in the understanding
of function of these cortices [14]. The scalp EEG is commonly
acquired using electrodes placed on the scalp. For clinical
and research applications, the locations and names of these
electrodes are set by the International 10/20 system. In thiscase, the signals are obtained with 19 electrodes and one
ground and system reference electrode [15].
Several authors have studied EEG signals for mental arith-
metic tasks to detect the state of brain during rest versus
actively involved. Studies have also been conducted to ﬁnd the
functionality of different brain cortices and brain waves for the
given task and to study the response of the brain in case of task
failure, etc. We are discussing a few such works here: authors
in [16] discussed the performance for a mental task activity
using causal interaction between rhythm of Frontal lobe and
rhythm of parieto-occipital lobe. Yu et al. [17] studied the
relation between cortices and the cardiac autonomic nervous
activity while a mental arithmetic task is being performed.
Wavelet packet parameters and approximate entropy were used
as the feature set. In their study, it was observed that the there
was an increase in cerebral concious activity with reduction in
parasympathetic activity and increase of sympathetic activity.
Using EEG signals, Dornhege et al. [18] detected high mental
workload in drivers under real trafﬁc conditions when more
information was provided.
To detect the rest state or the task state, authors in [19], [20]
used statistical features obtained from the wavelet decomposi-
tion of EEG signals and machine learning algorithms. Authors
in [21] considered alpha rhythm to classify the difﬁculty level
of the given task. Power of alpha wave was computed using
Welchs’ periodogram. While in [22], alpha and theta waves
were used to detect the workload level. Rebsamen et al [23]
classiﬁed the workload levels using spectral features of the
EEG signal. Wang et al., [24] used generalized Higuchi fractal
dimension spectrum, power spectral density, autoregressive
model and spectral features of EEG signals to recognize
mental arithmetic task. The accuracies obtained with single
channel is 84:15% and multiple channels is 97:87%.
In [25], frontal EEG signals of twenty healthy subjects were
acquired for four cognitive and motor tasks, including arith-
metic operation, ﬁnger tapping, mental rotation and lexical
decision task. Their study concluded that the theta activity
increases with difﬁculty across the four tasks. The accuracy
obtained for classifying mental work load level across subjects
using support vector machine algorithm was 65%␀75%.
In [26], the difﬁculty level in a mental arithmetic task was
detected using alpha rhythm. The dataset considered in their
study included the EEG signals from eighteen male subjects.
In this work, we decompose the EEG signals into ﬁve
