each of the brain waves with the cognitive task. This paper
also provides a quantitative study of the role of each cortex
in the event of a cognitive activity. The paper also present
the classiﬁcation of EEG signal into two groups based on the
difﬁculty of the task. In this case, the EEG signals considered
belongs to both active and rest state.
This paper is organized as: Section 2 gives a brief overview
of the dataset used in this work, Section 3 discusses the
methodology proposed in this work to study the relationship
of cognitive task with brain cortices and brain rhythms. In
Section 4, we present the simulation results and Section 5
discusses the conclusions of this work and future directions.
II. D ATASET
In this work, we have used a publicly available dataset from
MIT PhysioNet [27]. The dataset contains EEG recordings
from 36 subject after removing the artefacts. The signal
has been sampled at 500 Hz and collected using Neurocom
monopolar EEG system with twenty three channels. Electrodes
were attached at symmetrical anterior frontal, frontal, central,
parietal, occipital, and temporal locations corresponding to the
international 10/20 scheme. The signals in the given dataset
has been pre-processed using a high-pass ﬁlter whose cut-off
frequency is 0.5Hz, a low-pass ﬁlter of 45 Hz passband edge
and a power-line interference removal ﬁlter. The arithmetic
exercise taken upon for this study is the serial subtraction and
has been considered as a standardized stress inciting task [28].
The subjects in this study were students of the Taras
Shevchenko National University of Kyiv, with their ages in
the range of 18 to 26 years. Students without any vision
disabilities and with no clinical indication of mental, cognitive,
verbal or non-verbal learning impairments were considered.
For every participant, the number of operations completed
in 4 minutes and accuracy of computation was recorded for
performance analysis and for identifying the task difﬁculty
level. The difﬁculty level was considered low if the result
did not vary by more than 20% from the true value. For
more detail on the dataset refer [28]. Based on the number
of correct arithmetic operations completed per minute, the
dataset has been divided into two subsets: group B where the
difﬁculty level is high and group G consisting of participants
completing the task without facing any difﬁculty i.e. reported
better computational accuracy. It is pertinent to mention here
that in [28] it was mentioned that 12 subjects belong to the
group B and 24 subjects to group G, but according to the ﬁle
“subject-info.csv” given in [27], only 10 subjects were given
score 0 and 26 subjects were given score 1. In this work,
we have referred to “subject-info.csv” ﬁle to get the required
groups B and G.III. M ETHODOLOGY
The rhythmic activity of an EEG signal can be divided
into ﬁve frequency bands, namely delta, theta, alpha, beta
and gamma, where the frequency range of delta rhythm is
less than 4Hz, theta rhythm lies between 4␀8Hz, alpha
rhythm is between 8␀13Hz, beta lies between 13␀30Hz
and gamma rhythm include frequencies above 30 Hz. Each of
these brain waves have a particular distribution with respect to
cortices and are also linked to different physical activities and
emotional states. For instance, high amplitude delta waves are
generated during sleep, when the body rejuvenates and rests.
Completely alerted brain involved in focussed tasks generates
beta waves. The beta wave generation has been associated with
concentration and problem solving abilities. Gamma waves are
helpful for information preprocessing, learning, perceptions.
Alpha waves are helpful to calm down and promotes to feel
more relax. Theta waves are related to the emotions, intuition,
and creative thinking.
We obtain the EEG rhythms termed as gamma, beta, alpha,
theta and delta using a bank of digital ﬁlters. These brain
rhythms are the sub-band signals obtained via the frequency
decomposition of the EEG signals as shown in Fig. 1, where
Hi(z)denotes the digital ﬁlters.
