ev
en inform subjects regarding their stress levels throughout 
these workload. [4-7]. 
 
Serial subtraction of two numbers is one of the 
Arithmetic tasks in this study. When the EEGs were 
recorded the participants sat comfortably in a dark 
soundproof chamber. Participants were instructed to count 
silently and not to speak or not to use finger movements. 
After 3 minutes of acclimating to the laboratory systems, the 
EEG was recorded in the rest state with closed eyelids for 
the next 3 minutes. The participants next completed a 4-
minute mental arithmetic task. 
 
The earlier research that has been done in the domain of 
Mental arithmetic task classification using LSTM 
architecture method by B. Ganguly [8] and another work 
where the Fourier Decomposition Method is used for the 
classification of Mental tasks by B. Fatimah [9]. And 
authors in [1] considered classification accuracy of 
automatic detection of metal arithmetic tasks using EEG 
signals. 
 
The aim of this assertion is to capture the electrical 
activity of the brain using EEG signals collected from 
humans performing a mental cognitive workload task 
(mental arithmetic task). We used wavelet transform to 
preprocess our EEG dataset and then proposed a statistical 
model for the DWT coefficients of EEG signals. Using 
those recovered modeling parameters, SVM and KNN 
classifiers were utilized to classify Arithmetic mental task 
signals. We have checked that our chosen statistical model 
is appropriate for our data by using two parameters which 
are- Bhattacharyya Distance (BD) and Geometrical 
Separability Index (GSI). 
II. DATASET  
 
      In our assertions, here we used a dataset collected from 
the open-source public PhysioNet database. Dataset presents 
recordings from the subjects performing mental task-serial 
substructions following the International 10/20 system. Here 
36 healthy subjects participated during the collection of 
EEG recordings with the aim of investigating EEG match up 
of mental cognitive workload, specifically arithmetic mental 
tasks. The EEGs are recorded using a 23 channel Neurocom 
monopolar device. The electrodes made of silver or silver 
chloride are placed on the subject's scalp at symmetrical 
anterior frontal (Fp1, Fp2), frontal (F3, F4, Fz, F7, F8), 
central (C3, C4, Cz), parietal (P3, P4, Pz), occipital (O1, 
O2), and temporal (T3, T4, T5, T6) recording locations as 
per 10/20 International system. The inter-electrode 
impedance was less than 5 kΩ.  The sampling frequency 
for each channel was 500 Hz. A high-pass filter with a cut-
off frequency of 0.5 Hz, a low-pass filter with a cut-off 
frequency of 45 Hz, and a power line notch filter with a cut-
off frequency of 50 Hz were utilized where the 
amplification tract's time constant was 0.3 s.  In every 
recording 60 seconds for mental workload counting and 180 
