artifact signals. The augmentation process is to remove 
noise and partitioning data in sub bands. After augmentation 
we have got EEG sub-bands.   
 
B. Dominant Channel Selection 
 
We have used Human Based Technique for observing all 
the channel magnitude to select dominant channels. We 
examine the magnitude of all of our data channels and select 
five channels for our statistical modeling. We selected those 
channels which have more than 70% average power 
magnitude in each signal of the dataset. Fig 3 shows power 
magnitudes of the channels. 
 
Fig 3: Channels histogram 
 
C. Selection of Wavelet Transform 
 
 We have worked on Discrete wavelet transform (DWT) 
and selected the Haar wavelet for analysis. The Haar 
wavelet is one of the most basic wavelets and has been 
employed in a variety of BCI applications. The Haar 
function can be used to equally estimate any continuous 
function. 
 
D. Statistical Model Selection 
 
 We have chosen the distribution: Gaussian PDF for our 
data, which best corresponds to the data. Visually we 
compared some statistical models: Gaussian, t-Location 
Scale, Stable, Logistic, Extreme and Generalized Extreme 
model of our EEG signal of complete dataset. Fig 4 shows 
different statistical model fits. 
 
E. Classifier Selection 
 
 We utilized an SVM classifier for our data. For Brain 
Computer Interface applications, the SVM classifier is 
commonly used. We also checked the results by using the k-
NN classifier. However, SVM is more significant for EEG 
signals. 
  
