III. EXPERIMENT RESULTS AND DISCUSSION  
A. Subject’s mental arithmetic performance and 
subjective feedback on task difficulty 
Table 2 shows the subjects’ mental arithmetic 
performance in providing th e correct solution for each 
difficulty level. As the difficu lty level of the tasks increase s, 
the number of incorrect answers also increases. The subjects 
also provided their subjective feedback on the difficulty level  
of the 180 tasks: and the subjective ratings for 2 subjects are  
also shown in Table 3.  Some su bjects e.g. S6 gave subjective 
ratings which were similar to t he Q-value ratings. However 
other subjects e.g. S7 perceived the tasks to be easier, where all the 60 hard tasks were rated as medium (SM) and easy difficulty (SE). 
B.
 Intra-Subject Class ification Performance 
The 10-fold cross validation (CV) accuracies averaged 
over all subjects for the trial time segments of 1s to 8s are presented in Figure 4 for 3-class (easy versus medium versus h a r d  i . e  Q E  v  Q M  v  Q H )  a n d  2 - class classification for all 
pair-wise combinations (QE v QH, QE v QM and QM v QH).  The accuracy increases as the ti me segment increases from 1s 
to 8s. For example, M1 which co mputes CSP features yielded around 90% accuracy around 5s onwards for the easy versus 
hard task. One possible reason w hy this occurs is because the 
hard task e.g. 791 + 349 takes a relatively longer time to solve as compared to the easy task e.g. 3 + 5. 
