For 2-class classification, M1 and M2 yielded the highest 
accuracies for easy versus hard tasks, compared to easy versus medium tasks, and medium versus hard tasks. For 3-class classification, M1 and M2 yielded ~60% accuracy (33% 
naïve) around trial time segment s of 5s and longer. For the 8s 
time segment, M1 yielded rela tively the highest accuracy of 
66.1%, which meant that the 3-class classifier could discriminate 2 out of the 3 cl asses on average. One possible 
reason for this could be because some subjects did not feel 
there was a difference betwee n consecutive difficulty levels 
as shown in Table 3. Hence futu re studies could also examine 
the effect of including subjec tive feedback as part of the 
classification process to i mprove the sensitivity of 
discriminating multiple lev els of cognitiv e workload. 
