Table 4 shows the br eakdown in the classi fication of the 3 
classes, as confusion matrices for M1 and M2. In both cases, the easy and hard tasks can be di scriminated much better than 
the medium tasks. The difference in performance in M1 and M2 could be attributed to an imp roved discrimination of the 
medium task (58%) versus M2 (49%). 
C.
 Comparison with existing NI RS BCI System for Mental 
Arithmetic EEG Recognition 
The previous high density NIR S study [5] use d a different 
definition of easy and hard tasks, where easy tasks were  adding 3-digits number with 2 -digits number without carry 
over, and hard tasks were adding 4 digits with 3 digits with at  
least 1 carry over.  The authors’ approach yielded around 72.6% 5 x 5 fold CV accuracies  for easy versus hard tasks 
averaged over 8 subjects. Hence, t he results in this study are 
comparable to those in the pre vious study. Furthermore the 
EEG setup used a smaller number of channels (30) compared to the NIRS setup, which r equired 1024 channels  
D.
 Analysis of features selected 
Figure 5 shows the distribu tion of the top 3 selected 
discriminative CSP (M1; left) / band power features (M2; right) for easy versus hard ta sks according to the frequency 
bands. In both cases, the top 3 features were mostly computed from the 4-16Hz, wh ich encompass theta, alpha 
and lower beta bands. This s upports findings from other 
studies, which have sugge sted theta and alpha band 
oscillations play an important role during the execution of 
mental arithmetic [1],[15]. For some subjects e.g. S3, selected features were also c omputed from frequency band 7 
(28-32Hz) around the higher beta and gamma bands, which other studies[16] have also identified changes in the gamma band in the parietal  lobe during cognitiv e task processing. 
 M1: CSP       M2: Bandpower 
 
Figure 5: Distribution of the s elected frequency bands (x-axis)  for each 
subject (y-axis), based on top 3 selected features (M1, M2) to classify Easy 
versus Hard tasks and 8s EEG time segment. There are 9 frequenc y bands 
(4-8Hz, 8-12Hz,…36-40Hz). Most of the top 3 features were from Bands 2 
and 3 which encompasses 4-12Hz (theta band and alpha band) 
IV. CONCLUSION  
This paper investigated EEG-based classification of 
cognitive workload by discrimi nating 3 different levels of 
mental arithmetic tasks (easy, medium and hard difficulties). EEG Band power features and Common Spatial Patterns (CSP) features were extracted. Subsequent feature selection 
using Fisher Ratio showed that the best discriminating features were computed from the theta and alpha bands, 
which are associated with cognitive task processing. 
Classification using the LDA cl assifier, yielded a 10-fold 
cross validation accuracy of a bout 90% for easy versus hard tasks and 66% for easy versus medium versus hard tasks.  
The easy versus hard tasks coul d be discriminated relatively 
the best amongst all possible pairs of the 3 tasks. A longer time segment ≥ 5s improves the classification accuracy.  
Hence, the classification accuracies could be influenced 
by these factors: the differen c e  i n  t h e  t a s k  n a t u r e  a n d  t h e  
length of EEG time segment sin ce the subject would require 
more time to solve hard tasks. In summary, the results in this 
study provide a starting point i n the development of a real-
time EEG-based monitoring system, to complement existing subjective measures of the su bject’s cognitive workload 
during numerical learning a nd other cognitive tasks. 
