vector machine and frequency decomposition method. 
Kruskal -Wallis method  is also used to s elect relevant statistical 
feature.  K. Nirde et al., [9] have presented EEG mental 
arithmetic task levels classification using both machine 
learning and deep learning. K -Nearest Neighbour (KNN) in 
machine learning achieved accuracy of 91% and Artificial 
neural network in deep learning has shown accuracy of 
96.80%.  M. M. Rahman et al., [10]  presented an end -to-end 
deep learning model for classification of mental arithmetic task. 
A residual -based temporal attention network (RTA -Net) is 
implemented for classif ication and it showed an accuracy of 
99.32%.  
Many papers in the current literature have demonstrated 
the classification of mental arithmetic tasks using deep learning 
methods. However, none of them have addressed relaxation 
techniques or presented EEG chan ges following relaxation 
methods. Therefore, this paper aims to investigate the 
cognitive stress of individuals during a mathematical task and 
how these levels can be modulated using audio -visual stimuli 
for relaxation.  
 
III. METHODS AND MATERIALS  
 This section gives a detailed description of methodology 
for analysis and classification of EEG signals  during math task 
and happy state.  
 
A. Data Collection  
 The EEG signals were recorded using the Enobio -8 signal 
acquisition device. This device has 8 -channels ind icating 8 -
electrodes placed on the scalp. All participants were selected 
based on their normal mental health status, with ages ranging 
from 21 to 25 years. Subjects were presented with math 
puzzles, and an example is shown in Figure 1. The signals were 
recorded while participants solved the puzzles, and afterward, 
they were presented with a funny video to induce relaxation. 
EEG signals were also recorded after watching the funny 
videos. The mental state during the math task is considered as 'stress,' while the state after watching the funny video is 
considered as 'happy.' These two classes were used for 
analysis and classification.  
 
Fig. 1 Mat h Puzzle  
B. Data Preprocessing  
The raw EEG signals include  artifacts  that can originate 
from either physiological or non -physiological sources. 
Physiological artifacts  occur internally and include  phenomena 
like eye blinks, muscle movements, and deep breathin g. Non -
physiological artifacts , on the other hand, arise from external 
factors such as cable movements, electrode pops, and 
incorrect reference placement. These artifacts were removed 
using  Parks -McClellan optimal finite impulse response (FIR) 
filter, whic h operates within a frequency range of 2 -40Hz, using 
MATLAB [11 -12]. The processed EEG signal was then used to 
extract distinct EEG frequency bands, including delta, theta, 
alpha, beta, and gamma, utilizing a multi -wavelet transformation 
technique. In this  multi -wavelet transformation, we employed 
the Daubedhies 14 wavelet to decompose the filt ered signal 
across six levels [11 ]. EEG relative band power is calculated for 
each EEG bands such as alpha, beta, delta, theta and gamma. 
Subsequently, we individuall y considered each EEG band to 
extract statistical features. These statistical features were 
standardized using the standard scaler feature scaling method, 
which ensures that the features have a mean of 0 and a 
standard deviation of 1.  
 
C. Classification using  Deep Learning method  
 The feature scaled data is used for training the deep 
learning model. The deep learning method used is described 
as follows.  
i) Long Short Term Memory (LSTM)  
 Long Short -Term Memory (LSTM) is a type of recurrent 
neural network (RNN) arc hitecture designed to handle 
sequential data and capture long -range dependencies. It is 
particularly well -suited for tasks like time series prediction, 
natural language processing, and speech recognition.  
 At the start of the sequence, the LSTM cell needs  initial 
values for its hidden state (h 0) and cell state (C 0).  
 h0=0 (Initial hidden state)  
 C0=0 (Initial cell state)  
LSTM processes one element of the input sequence at a time 
(xt). For each time step, it performs several operations to 
update its cell  state and hidden state. The forget gate  (ft) 
determines what information from the previous cell state (C t−1) 
should be discarded and what information should be retained. 
It takes the previous hidden state (h t-1) and the current input 
(xt) as input.   
ft = σ ( W f . [h t-1, xt] + b f )                    (1) Proceedings of the International Conference on Sustainable Communication Networks and Application (ICSCNA 2023)
