Authorized licensed use limited to: UNIVERSIDADE FEDERAL DO RIO GRANDE DO SUL. Downloaded on May 14,2025 at 11:43:53 UTC from IEEE Xplore.  Restrictions apply.  The input gate decides what new information should be 
stored in the cell state. It takes the previous hidden state (h t-1) 
and the current input (x t) as input.  
it = σ ( W i . [h t-1, xt] + b i )                    (2) 
Candidate Cell State  (CT) is the new candidate values that 
could be added to the cell state. It is computed using the 
previous hidden state (h t−1) and the current input (x t). 
CT = tanh ( W c . [h t-1, xt] + b c )                    (3) 
 
 The upda ted cell (Ct) state is a combination of the previous 
cell state (Ct−1) and the candidate cell state (CT) based on the 
forget gate (ft) and input gate ( it).  
 Ct = ft . (C t−1) + it . CT                   (4) 
After updating the cell state, the LSTM calcul ates the output 
at the current time step.    The output gate (Ot) determines what 
information from the cell state (C t) should be included in the 
hidden state (ht ). It takes the previous hidden state (h t-1) and 
the current input (x t). 
Ot = σ ( W o . [h t-1, xt] + b o )               (5) 
Hidden state (ht) is computed by applying the output gate ( Ot) 
to the cell state (C t).  
ht = Ot  . tanh ( Ct)                  (6) 
The hidden state ( ht) at each time step can be used for various 
tasks such as prediction, classification , or generating 
sequences .  
Where,  
xt: Input at time step t.  
ht: Hidden state at time step t.  
 Ct: Cell state at time step t.  
Wf,W i,W c,W o: Weight matrices for the forget gate, input 
gate, candidate cell state, and output gate, respecti vely.  
bf,bi,bc,bo: Bias terms for the corresponding gates.  
σ: Sigmoid activation function.  
tanh: Hyperbolic tangent activation function.  
 In this work, softmax  is used as an activation  function.  
Since it is classification problem, categorical_crossentr opy 
loss function is used. The initial  learning rate considered is 
0.001  and number of epochs is 50. Early stopping is included 
in the implementation to stop the training when there is no 
significant change in the validation accuracy  
   
IV. RESULTS  
 This section presents the results of EEG changes after 
audio -visual stimuli using funny clips and evaluation of 
LSTM method for classification of happy and stress mental 
states. The relative band power provides valuable information 
about the distribution of sign al power across EEG frequency 
bands and is typically expressed as a ratio or percentage .  
Alpha band refers to relaxed state, beta refers to stress, delta 
refers to sleep, theta refers to drowsiness  and gamma refers to 
peak performance. The relative band p ower is calculated for 
these bands for happy and stress states. Figure 2 shows the 
alpha relative band power error bars with standard error. Figure 2 clearly shows an increase in the band power in happy 
state. Increase of alpha band power indicates relaxat ion after 
watching funny clips. Figure 3 shows b eta relative band 
power error bars with standard error. In beta band, stress 
percentage is higher. Figure 4 shows delta  relative band power 
error bars with standard error. Figure 4 shows an increase  in 
happy state. Figure 5 shows theta  relative band power error 
bars with standard error. Figure 5 shows an increase  in happy 
state. . Figure 6 shows gamma  relative band power error bars 
with standard error. Figure 6 shows an increase  in stress in 
gamma band. In thi s work, alpha band is considered  vital as it 
offers relaxation. As per figure 2, there is a clear  indication of 
relaxation due to increase in relative band power of happy 
state.  
 
 
