* E-mail: huynhqlinh@hcmut.edu.vn  
 
Abstract. In this study, we investigate the characteristics of electroencephalogram 
(EEG) signals during mental arithmetic tasks. The publicly available dataset used 
in this study includes EEG recordings from 36 healthy volunteers performing serial 
subtraction tasks, with data collec ted using a 23 -channel Neurocom EEG system. 
The study aims to explore the changes in brain activity during cognitive workload 
by analyzing the power spectral density, entropy, and statistical features of the EEG 
signals. Key features such as band power in delta, theta, alpha, beta, and gamma 
frequency bands, entropy, mean power, standard deviation, kurtosis, skewness, 
autocorrelation, and RMS energy were extracted from each channel. The subjects 
were categorized into good and bad counters based on their ari thmetic 
performance. The extracted features were then used to train machine learning 
models, including Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), k -Nearest Neighbors (KNN), 
and Support Vector Machine (SVM), to classify the cognitive workload levels. The 
KNN model  demonstrated the highest overall performance with an F1 score of 
0.857. This research highlights the potential of using EEG features to assess 
cognitive workload and provides a foundation for future studies on brain -
computer interfaces and cognitive neuro science.  
1. Introduction   
Electroencephalography (EEG) has long been a valuable tool for investigating brain activity in 
various cognitive tasks, particularly in mental arithmetic, which serves as a standard model for 
cognitive workload studies. EEG record s electrical activity from the brain using electrodes placed 
on the scalp and provides insights into different frequency bands that correspond to specific 
cognitive and emotional pro cesses [1]. Mental arithmetic tasks, which involve solving 
mathematical pr oblems without external aids, are commonly used to induce cognitive load in 
experimental settings [2].  
The growing interest in understanding the relationship between EEG signals and cognitive 
workload has led to significant advances in neuroimaging techniq ues and machine learning 
approaches. Mental arithmetic, often perceived as stressful, requires sustained attention and 
working memory engagement, which can alter brainwave patterns across multiple frequency  International Symposium on Applied Science 2024 
Journal of Physics: Conference Series 2949 (2025) 012004 IOP Publishing 
doi:10.1088/1742-6596/2949/1/012004 
2bands. Studies have demonstrated that cognitive w orkload primarily affects the theta (4–8 Hz) 
and alpha (8–13 Hz) bands, with increased activity in the beta (13–30 Hz) and gamma (>30 Hz) 
bands du ring high cognitive demand [3], [4] . 
Previous research has focused on the power spectral density (PSD) of EEG signals, entropy, 
and statistical features as indicators of mental workload. By extracting key features such as band 
power, entropy, mean power, and kurtosis from the EEG signals, machine learning algorithms can 
effectively classify differen t levels of cog nitive load [5], [6] . This study aims to further explore these 
characteristics by analyzing EEG signals collected during mental arithmetic tasks performed by 
healthy volunteers.  
This study builds on previous research that uses serial subtraction tasks to i nduce cognitive 
load, allowing us to examine how the brain responds to mental workload through EEG signals. The 
key contributions of this research lie in both the data processing and analysis pipeline as well as 
the machine learning models employed. We dev eloped a comprehensive process to handle raw 
EEG data, applying techniques such as Independent Component Analysis (ICA) for artifact removal 
and extracting critical features like band power, entropy, mean power, and standard deviation. 
These features provi de valuable insights into how brain activity changes with varying cognitive 
load. Additionally, we evaluated machine learning models —including Linear Discriminant 
Analysis (LDA), k -Nearest Neighbors (KNN), and Support Vector Machine (SVM) —to classify 
different levels of cognitive load. Among these, KNN  demonstrated the highest accuracy and F1 
score, making it particularly effective for real -time cognitive load assessment. The findings not 
only contribute to a better understanding of brain dynamics under str ess but also have practical 
applications in developing more accurate brain -computer interface (BCI) systems, which could 
enhance real -time cognitive monitoring in education and healthcare settings.  
2. Material and Methods   
2.1 Materials  
The EEG dataset used in this study was obtained from 36 healthy volunteers aged 18 to 26 years 
(Mage = 18.6 years, SD = 0.87 years) [7 ]. All participants were right -handed and had normal or 
corrected -to-normal vision, with no history of neurological or psychiatric disorde rs. The 
participants were students from the Educational and Scientific Centre ""Institute of Biology and 
Medicine,"" National Taras Shevchenko University of Kyiv, Ukraine. The participants provided 
informed consent prior to the experiment, and the study was conducted in accordance wit h the 
Declaration of Helsinki [8 ]. 
2.2 EEG Recording  
EEG signals were recorded using a 23 -channel Neurocom EEG system following the international 
10/20 electrode placement system . The electrodes were positioned over frontal (Fp1,  Fp2, F3, F4), 
central (C3, Cz, C4), parietal (P3, Pz, P4), occipital (O1, O2), and temporal (T3, T4) regions. A 
sampling rate of 500 Hz was employed, with a high -pass filter of 0.5 Hz, a low -pass filter of 45 Hz, 
and a notch filter of 50 Hz to remove elec trical interference. The inter -electrode impedance was 
kept below 5  kΩ throughout the recording . 
 
 
 
