32.3 Experimental Task and Data Processing  
The participants were asked to perform a serial subtraction task, a commonly used method to 
induce cognitive load. The task required the participants to subtract a two -digit number (e.g., 17) 
from a randomly chosen four -digit number (e.g., 4753) rep eatedly over a 4 -minute period.  
This task was performed following a 3 -minute resting period, during which participan ts were 
instructed to close th eir eyes and remain relaxed .  
Figure  1 summarizes the data for the participating subjects. Females are denoted by ""F"", 
whereas males are denoted by ""M"". The ""number of subtractions"" is defined as the difference 
between the sta rting 4-digit number and the subtraction result, divided by the subtrahend. It is 
important to note that if the computation for a certain subject is incorrect, the resulting value is 
not an integer. We determined the ""count quality"" ranking based on the nu mber of subtra ctions 
for groups ""B"" and ""G"" [7 ]. 
 
Figure 1. Subjects and population data [7 ] 
Raw EEG data was preprocessed to remove artifacts caused by eye movements, muscle 
activity, and cardiac pulsations. Independent Component  Analysis (ICA) was applied t o eliminate 
these artifacts . Additionally, a 30 Hz high -pass filter and a 50 Hz notch filter were used to further 
clean the data. Each subject ’s EEG data was segmented into 60 -second intervals, and only data 
from the arithmetic  task were included in the analysis.  
