2.4.1. Band power  
Band power is calculated by summing the squared values of the EEG signal within a specific 
frequency band. The frequency bands are categorized as follows: delta (0.5–4 Hz), theta (4–8 Hz), 
alpha (8–13 Hz), beta (13–30 Hz), and gamma (>30 Hz).  
𝑃𝑏𝑎𝑛𝑑 = ∑ |X(𝑓)|2𝑓2
𝑓1 (1) 
where X(f) represents the Fourier -transformed values of the EEG signal at frequency f, f 1 and 
f2 are the limits of the frequency band. Band power is a critical metric for understanding brain 
activity across different cognitive states. Each frequency band corresponds to specific brain states, 
such as relaxation or intense cognitive effort  . For example, delta and theta waves are often 
associated with relaxation or sleep, while beta and gamma waves a re linked to higher cognitive 
functions and focus. Analyzing band power allows us to determine the level of focus and stress 
experienced by participants during complex arithmetic tasks, providing essential insights for 
classifying cognitive load levels. Th is analysis is particularly valuable in developing machine 
learning models that assess cognitive l oad based on EEG signals .  
Previous studies have focused on the relationship between band power and various cognitive 
states. Menon et al. (2000) demonstrated  that increased beta activity during arithmetic tasks is 
indicative of heightened cognitive load, while decreased alpha activity corresp onds to higher 
stress levels [3 ]. Similarly, Pinheiro -Chagas et al. (2018) found that reduced alpha waves 
corresponded w ith increased cognitive load during tasks that requir ed significant concentration 
[4]. 
2.4.2. Entropy  
Entropy is calculated using the Shannon entropy formula:  
𝐻(𝑋)=− ∑𝑝(𝑥𝑖)log(𝑝(𝑥𝑖))
𝑖 (2) 
where 𝑝(𝑥𝑖) is the probability of the occurrence of value 𝑥𝑖 in the EEG signal.  
 
Entropy measures the complexity and unpredictability of the EEG signal. Higher entropy 
values often reflect irregular and chaotic signals, which can be associated with increased cognitive 
load or stress. In this study, entropy helps capture the complexity of brain activity under different 
cognitive states. Using entropy is an effective approach to identifying chaotic patterns in EEG 
signals, thereby improving the classification of cognitive load levels u sing machine learning 
models [1 0].  International Symposium on Applied Science 2024 
