8Entropy has been widely applied in EEG studies to assess cognitive and emotional states. Peng 
et al. (1995) showed that entropy can reflect the complexity of EEG signals across different 
cognitive states, with higher entropy values often linked to incr eased stress and cognit ive load [6 ]. 
Soleymani et al. (2012) used entropy to analyze changes in EEG signals related to emotional 
responses, demonstrating that entropy is a powerful tool for emot ion recognition based on EEG 
[5]. 
2.4.3. Mean Power  
Mean power  is calculated by averaging the squared values of the EEG signal:  
