where 𝑥𝑖 is the value of the EEG signal at time i, and N is the total number of samples.  
Mean power is an important metric for evaluating the overall  activity of the brain over a 
specific period. It allows us to compare the level of activation between different cognitive states, 
such as rest versus task performance. In this study, mean power helps determine the level of brain 
activity and contributes t o classifying different levels of cognitive load. Studies have shown that 
mean power increases in higher frequency bands, such as beta and gamma, during tas ks that 
require intense focus . 
Finlay and colleagues (2016) explored changes in mean power across di fferent psychological 
states and found that mean power increases in the beta band during tasks that  demand high 
cognitive effort [11 ]. Zyma et al. (2019) also found that differences in mean power between resting 
and task states reflect brain activation lev els, indicating that mean power is a crucial metric for 
evaluating brain activity in this s tudy [12]. 
