Kurtosis and skewness are important statistical measures that describe the shape of the EEG 
signal distribution. Kurtosis assesses the ""tailedness"" or concentration of the distribution, while 
skewness measures its asymmetry. These features are particularly  useful in detecting subtle 
abnormalities in the EEG signal related to different cognitive states. For example, high kurtosis 
may indicate extreme values, reflecting intense cognitive activity. The use of kurtosis and 
skewness in the study improves the cla ssification of cognitive load levels with machine learning 
models. 
Ho ll and Kantz (2015) utilized kurtosis and skewness to evaluate EEG signal variability in 
studies of circadian rhythms, highlighting that these metrics can reflect significa nt changes in 
brain activity [13 ]. Soleymani et al. (2012) applied kurtosis and skewness in EEG analysis for 
emotion recognition, demonstrating that these metrics are powerful tools for analyzing signal 
characteristi cs related to cognitive load [ 5]. 
2.4.6. Autocorrelation  
Autocorrelation is calculated using the following formula:  
