where 𝑘 is the time lag, and 𝑥𝑖 is the value of the signal at time 𝑖. 
Autocorrelation measures the degree of similarity between the EE G signal and its lagged 
version, helping to detect repetitive patterns in the signal, such as circadian rhythms or prolonged 
cognitive activities. This is particularly important when analyzing EEG signals related to 
arithmetic tasks, where repetitive patte rns may reflect continuous cognitive load or cyclical brain 
activity. Using autocorrelation in this study enhances the detection and classification of c ognitive 
states.  
Pinheiro-Chagas et al. (2018) applied autocorrelation to analyze repetitive patterns in  EEG 
signals, showing that autocorrelation can reveal biological rhythms in brain activity du ring 
complex cognitive tasks [4 ]. Autocorrelation has been shown to be an effective tool in analyzing 
cyclic EEG signals, particularly in studies of cognitive stat es and stress . 
