10widely used in the analysis of biological signals, particularly in EEG studies related to cognit ive 
and emotional activities . 
3. Classification  
3.1. Machine Learning Models  
To classify the cognitive workload based on the extracted EEG features, we employed several 
machine learning models, including Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), k -Nearest Neighbors 
(KNN), and Support Vector Machine (SVM). These mo dels are chosen for their proven effectiveness 
in handling high -dimensional data and their ability to generalize well across different types of EEG 
datasets.  
Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) is a linear classification model that is particularly 
effective when the features are linearly separable. It reduces the dimensionality of the feature 
space while maintaining the class separability, making it a suitable choice for EEG -based 
classification tasks  [14].  
k-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) is a non -parametric meth od that classifies instances based on the 
majority vote of their neighbors. This method is advantageous in scenarios where the decision 
boundary is complex and non -linear. KNN has been shown to perform well in EEG classification 
tasks, especially when comb ined with feature selec tion techniques  [15]. 
Support Vector Machine (SVM) is a powerful model that works by finding the hyperplane that 
best separates the different classes in the feature space. SVM is particularly useful in handling 
high-dimensional data and has been widely used in EEG signal classification due to its robustness 
and ability to manage non -linear decision boundaries through  the use of kernel functions  [16]. 
The combination of these machine learning models allows for a comprehensive evaluatio n of 
the EEG data, providing insights into the most effective methods for classifying cognitive workload. 
The results obtained from these models will be analyzed to determine the most suitable approach 
for real-time cognitive load assessment.  
These finding s are consistent with similar studies in the field of cognitive load assessment. 
For instance, research by Wu and Zhang (2006)  demonstrated that KNN performs well in EEG 
classification tasks due to its ability to handle complex decision boundaries effectiv ely, making it 
a strong candidate for applications involving high -dimensional EEG data [15]. While models like 
SVM have shown strong performance in general EEG classifications, particularly in managing non -
linear separations as highlighted by Cortes and Va pnik (1995)  [16], KNN's adaptability and 
capacity to capture intricate patterns within EEG data often allow it to achieve comparable or even 
superior accuracy under conditions with well -preprocessed data. Additionally, studies such as 
those by Blankertz et  al. (2008)  have emphasized that although SVM is effective, especially in brain -
computer interface (BCI) applications where precision is critical, KNN's performance in this study 
suggests that it can offer a robust alternative with high classification accu racy when feature 
selection and preprocessing are appropriately managed [14]. Furthermore, compared to Linear 
Discriminant Analysis (LDA), which generally works well for linearly separable data, KNN's ability 
to adapt to complex, non -linear data makes it p articularly advantageous for EEG -based cognitive 
load assessments. These comparisons further validate the choice of KNN in this study as a highly 
effective model for cognitive load classification based on EEG signals.  
 
