114. Result and Discussion  
4.1 Result  
The analysis of EEG signals during mental arithmetic tasks across all subjects and channels 
revealed significant variations in key metrics, providing valuable insights into how cognitive load 
affects brain activity. The band power values demonstrated expec ted trends under high cognitive 
load conditions. Specifically, delta power (0.5–4 Hz) averaged 105.67 µV ², with a noticeable 
decrease during tasks requiring higher cognitive engagement, indicating reduced relaxation. 
Theta power (4–8 Hz), with a mean value  of 16.83 µV ², also decreased as cognitive load increased, 
reflecting a shift from relaxation to task -related focus. Alpha power (8–13 Hz) averaged 17.68 µV ² 
and decreased during mental tasks, consistent with findings that lower alpha activity is associate d 
with higher cognitive demands. In contrast, beta power (13–30 Hz), which had a mean value of 
11.94 µV², increased during tasks requiring sustained attention and working memory, indicating 
active mental processing. Gamma power (>30 Hz), with a mean value of 2.59 µV², also showed an 
increase, further corroborating its association with higher cognitive load and complex brain 
functions.  
Entropy, a measure of the complexity of neural activity, exhibited high values across all 
subjects, indicating the chaotic n ature of EEG signals under cognitive load. Entropy values ranged 
from 9261.02 µV ² to 10901.85 µV ², exemplified by Subject 22 -2, which had one of the highest 
entropy values, reflecting the subject ’s high cognitive load during the tasks. Mean power across al l 
channels and subjects provided further evidence of increased brain activity during cognitive tasks, 
with an overall mean power of 136.52 µV², where higher values indicated greater brain activation 
in response to the mental arithmetic tasks.  
Conversely, k urtosis and skewness, which describe the shape of the EEG signal distribution, 
were less influential in differentiating cognitive load levels. Kurtosis values ranged from 2.81 
(subject 30 -2) to 8.01 (subject 22 -2), indicating varying signal extremities. Sk ewness ranged from 
-1.01 (subject 25 -2) to 0.73 (subject 32 -2), reflecting different levels of signal asymmetry among 
subjects. While these features were found to be less impactful in this specific context, they were 
still included in the analysis due to t heir theoretical significance. Kurtosis and skewness are often 
used in EEG studies to provide insights into the distribution of signal amplitudes, which can 
indicate the presence of outliers or asymmetric patterns that might be relevant under different 
conditions or tasks. Their initial inclusion was based on the premise that such characteristics 
might reveal subtle differences in brain activity patterns under varying cognitive loads, even if 
they ultimately contributed less to the classification performanc e in this study.  
The results underscore that band power and entropy are the most reliable indicators of 
cognitive load, with significant changes observed in the beta and gamma frequency bands, 
alongside consistently high entropy values during mental arithm etic tasks.  
Given these observations, the EEG features were utilized in machine learning models to 
classify cognitive load levels. The models —Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), k -Nearest 
Neighbors (KNN), and Support Vector Machine (SVM) —were evaluated for  their classification 
accuracy. The KNN  model achieved the highest performance, with an F1 score of 0.857, 
outperforming both LDA and KN N models. This suggests that KNN , with its kernel -based 
approach, is particularly well -suited for distinguishing between  different cognitive load states 
based on EEG features.  
