4.2. Discussion and Future works  
The observed variations in EEG signals across different frequency bands provide valuable insights 
into how the brain responds to increasing cognitive load. Specifically, the increased activity in the 
beta (13–30 Hz) and gamma (>30 Hz) bands during complex tasks suggests that these frequencies 
are closely associated with processes involving at tention and working memory [3, 5 ]. These 
findings align with the global workspace theo ry, which posits that higher cognitive functions 
involve widespread neural  activation across the cortex  [1]. The significant decrease in delta (0.5–
4 Hz) and theta (4–8 Hz) band power further underscores the shift from relaxed states to task -
oriented menta l engagement, reflecting the brain's dynamic adaptation to cognitive demands.  
The analysis also highlighted the critical role of entropy as a measure of the complexity of 
neural activity. High entropy values across subjects indicated that increased cogniti ve load 
correlates with more chaotic and disordered neural patterns, aligning with theories that suggest 
cognitive effort leads to increased signal complexity. This insight is particularly valuable for 
distinguishing between different levels of cognitive d emand, reinforcing the utility of entrop y in 
cognitive load assessment . 
The superior performance of the KNN  model in classifying cognitive load levels underscores 
its robustness in handling high -dimensional EEG data. The kernel -based approach of KNN  allows 
it to capture complex, non -linear patterns in the data, which is crucial when dealing with the 
intricate relationships between EEG feature s. The findings suggest that KNN , when combined with 
carefully selected features such as band power and entropy, is a n effective tool for cognitive load 
assessment . The feature selection process was pivotal in enhancing the model's performance, 
demonstrating that focusing on features directly linked to cognitive processes can significantly 
improve classification accuracy . For instance, band power, particularly in the beta and gamma 
frequencies, was shown to be a strong indicator of cognitive load, while entropy provided insights 
into the complexity o f neural activity under stress . 
The study is not without limitations. The  relatively small sample size may restrict the 
generalizability of the results, as EEG data can be highly individualistic. Additionally, the study 
primarily focused on a limited number of EEG features, and there may be other relevant features 
that were not  considered. Future studies should include larger and more diverse populations to 
validate these findings across different demographics. Moreover, exploring advanced machine 
learning models, such as deep learning approaches, could potentially yield even hi gher accuracy 
and better generalization in cognitive load assessment tools based on EEG signals . 
Building on the insights gained from this study, future research should aim to address the 
limitations mentioned above. Increasing the sample size and diversit y of participants will be 
crucial in ensuring that the findings are robust and applicable to a broader population.  International Symposium on Applied Science 2024 
Journal of Physics: Conference Series 2949 (2025) 012004 IOP Publishing 
doi:10.1088/1742-6596/2949/1/012004 
13Futhermore , expanding the scope of feature extraction to include more nuanced EEG 
characteristics, such as phase -amplitude coupling or cross -frequency interactions, could provide 
a more comprehensive understanding of how cognitive load manifests in neural activity.  
Exploring deep learning techniques, such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs) or 
recurrent neural networks (RNNs), may also offe r significant improvements in classifying 
cognitive load levels. These models are particularly well -suited for capturing complex temporal 
and spatial patterns in EEG data, which could lead to more accurate and generalizable cognitive 
load assessment tools.  Furthermore, integrating multimodal data sources, such as combining EEG 
with physiological signals like heart rate variability or skin conductance, could enhance the 
robustness of cognitive load predictions.  
Finally, there is considerable potential to dev elop real -time applications of cognitive load 
assessment using EEG signals. Such applications could be used in adaptive learning environments, 
where the system adjusts the difficulty of tasks based on the user's cognitive load, or in workplace 
settings to monitor and optimize employee performance under varying cognitive demands. The 
integration of these advanced techniques and broader datasets will pave the way for more 
sophisticated and practical tools for assessing cognitive load in real -world scenarios.   
5. Conclusion  
This study aimed to enhance our understanding of how cognitive load impacts brain activity, 
specifically through the analysis of EEG signals during mental arithmetic tasks. By focusing on key 
EEG features such as beta and gamma band power an d entropy, we successfully identified reliable 
indicators of cogniti ve load. The KNN  model, which outperformed other machine learning models, 
demonstrated its effectiveness in classifying cognitive load levels, reinforcing the potential of these 
features i n practical applications.  
Our findings align with the broader goals outlined in the introduction, emphasizing the 
importance of accurate cognitive load assessment in fields such as adaptive learning and 
workplace efficiency. While the results are promising , particularly in the identification of high -
dimensional EEG patterns, the study's limitations —such as sample size —highlight the need for 
further research. Future work should build on these insights, exploring more advanced machine 
learning techniques and expanding the scope of EEG feature extraction to include additional 
neural characteristics.  
In conclusion, this research contributes valuable knowledge to the field of cognitive 
neuroscience and lays the groundwork for future developments in real -time cognitive load 
assessment tools, potentially transforming how cognitive states are monitored and managed in 
various real -world applications.  
