5) BETWEENNESS CENTRALITY (BC) AND EDGE
BETWEENNESS CENTRALITY (EBC)
BC is a measure of a node's centrality in a network. It is
equal to the number of shortest paths from all vertices to all
others that pass through that node, while EBC is exactly the
same apart from its application to edges instead of nodes.
In this analysis, we used the algorithm proposed by [45] for
the computation of BC and EBC.
6) SMALL-WORLD INDEX (S)
A small-world network is a graph in which most nodes are
not neighbors of one another, but most nodes can be reached
from every other in a small number of steps. Humphries and
Gurney [46] have dened the S of a network as:
