EEG alpha and theta time-frequency structure during a written mathematical task.pdf,2024,10,2,EEG alpha and theta time-frequency structure during a written mathematical task.pdf,"Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing (2024) 62:1869–1885
https://doi.org/10.1007/s11517-024-03028-9
ORIGINAL ARTICLE
EEG alpha and theta time-frequency structure during a written
mathematical task
Giovanna M. Bonança1·Günther J.L. Gerhardt2·André L. Molan1·Luiz M.A. Oliveira1·Gustavo M. Jarola1·
Suzana V. Schönwald3·José L. Rybarczyk-Filho1
Received: 10 May 2023 / Accepted: 17 January 2024 / Published online: 25 February 2024
© International Federation for Medical and Biological Engineering 2024
Abstract
Since the ﬁrst electroencephalogram (EEG) was obtained, there have been many possibilities to use it as a tool to access brain
cognitive dynamics. Mathematical (Math) problem solving is one of the most important cortical processes, but it is still farfrom being well understood. EEG is an inexpensive and simple indirect measure of brain operation, but only recently has
low-cost equipment (mobile EEG) allowed sophisticated analyses in non-clinical settings. The main purpose of this work is
to study EEG activation during a Math task in a realistic environment, using mobile EEG. A matching pursuit (MP)-basedsignal analysis technique was employed, since MP properties render it a priori suitable to study induced EEG activity over
long time sequences, when it is not tightly locked to a given stimulus. The study sample comprised sixty healthy volunteers.
Unlike the majority of previous studies, subjects were studied in a sitting position with their eyes open. They completed awritten Math task outside the EEG lab, wearing a mobile EEG device (EPOC+). Theta [4 Hz–7.5 Hz], alpha (7.5 Hz–13 Hz]and 0.5 Hz micro-bands in the [0.5 Hz–20 Hz] range were studied with a low-density stochastic MP dictionary. Over 1-min
windows, ongoing EEG alpha and theta activity was decomposed into numerous MP atoms with median duration around 3 s,
similar to the duration of induced, time-locked activity obtained with event-related (des)synchronization (ERS/ERD) studies.Relative to Rest, there was lower right-side and posterior MP alpha atom/min during Math, whereas MP theta atom/min
was signiﬁcantly higher on anteriorly located electrodes, especially on the left side. MP alpha ﬁndings were particularly
signiﬁcant on a narrow range around 10 Hz–10.5 Hz, consistent with FFT alpha peak ﬁndings from ERS/ERD studies. Witha streamlined protocol, these results replicate previous ﬁndings of EEG alpha and theta activation obtained during Math tasks
with different signal analysis techniques and in different time frames. The efﬁcient application to real-world, noisy EEG data
with a low-resolution stochastic MP dictionary shows that this technique is very encouraging. These results provide supportfor studies of mathematical cognition with mobile EEG and matching pursuit.
Keywords Emotive EPOC ·EEG microstructure ·Theta activity ·Matching pursuit ·Math cognition ·Mobile EEG
1 Introduction
Although it is not new that the central nervous system (CNS)
evaluates quantities in a variety of ways, it is in accuracy thatwe humans perceive good evolutionary advantage [ 1–7]. It is
therefore not surprising that numerical cognition has become
a matter of deep interest when one considers how brain cellsproduce thought or action. As the gap between neurophysiol-
ogy and cognitive neuroscience is bridged through growing
knowledge of detailed CNS circuitry and function, it has
B José L. Rybarczyk-Filho
jose.luiz@unesp.br
Extended author information available on the last page of the articlebecome apparent that real-world tasks demanding number
manipulations will recruit a very speciﬁc subset of neurons
bilaterally located in the intraparietal sulcus, but they will notbe satisfactorily carried out without involving multiple brainsites such as the left posterior temporal language area and
bilateral prefrontal and inferior temporal regions, and mul-
tiple cognitive abilities such as attention, working memoryand visuo-spatial skills [ 8,9]. These ﬁndings imply a degree
of functional vs. topological multiplicity that needs to be
considered in theories regarding cognitive strategies appliedto arithmetic problem solving [ 3]. Procedural and memory
retrieval strategies are believed to be employed in alternate
and complementary ways under the inﬂuence of individualpreference, cognitive structure, task difﬁculty, degree of skill,
123 1870 Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing (2024) 62:1869–1885
task commitment and developmental stage [ 10,11]. Reliance
on retrieval as opposed to procedural strategies is thought toincrease as one becomes more familiar with operatory func-
tions and arithmetic manipulations [ 12]. Systematic testing
of these theories, however, is still a work in progress [ 13,14].
Contemporary students, at least in Western countries, havepossibly not been exposed to the amount of mathematical
fact learning by repetition to which older generations have
been submitted [ 15]. It is not clear whether or to what extent
differences in learning paradigms will impact how the mature
brain deals with arithmetic. As Mathematics (Math) teaching
policies across different educational programs are the subjectof heated debate and learning experiences continue to extrap-
olate the context of traditional classrooms, practical methods
to assess Math cognition in realistic settings will expectedlygain importance in ensuing years [ 15–18].
One source of validation for the concept of different brain
strategies involved in Math cognition comes from electro-
physiology studies that show how electroencephalography(EEG) rhythms may be elicited over different scalp locations
employing a variety of cognitive manipulations [ 19,20]. Pre-
dominantly left-sided EEG theta activation (synchronization,power increase) has been linked with Math fact retrieval,
while widespread EEG alpha activation (desynchronization,
power decrease) has been associated with procedural numeri-cal manipulations, perhaps through more intense recruitmentof working memory and concentration [ 19,20]. EEG fre-
quency analysis is non-invasive, relatively inexpensive, easy
to conduct in large subject groups and made more attrac-tive by the introduction of mobile EEG devices, currently
undergoing technical troubleshooting and testing in natural-
istic environments such as classrooms and outdoors [ 21–24].
Extensive information on EEG spectral content has been
obtained with standard and high-density EEG equipment
over the past decades. However, variability in experimen-tal paradigms has critically limited inter-study comparisonsacross time. Seminal contributions stem from a heroic era
when digital signal acquisition was nonexistent and statis-
tical analysis was incipient [ 6,25–30]. Many conclusions
have been reached through indirect theoretical constructs,
for instance, EEG frequency ratios obtained for cognitive
tasks considered at the time to speciﬁcally engage opposedbrain hemispheres, or computed for groups contrasted by
performance level, prone to inﬂuence by many factors, or
ascribed to categories of cognitive style based on psycho-logical self-evaluation [ 19,20,31–33]. Of direct importance
to the present study, previous information has been mainly
obtained with Math tasks carried out with eyes closed, some-
times with subjects lying down on the supine position, notnecessarily reproducible when subjects are on a sitting posi-
tion with eyes open.
The ongoing EEG is highly non-stationary [ 34]. Fre-
quency analysis carried out over different time frames mayyield divergent results, and different signal analysis tech-
niques may better suit investigation on different time scales.With classical and most widely used spectral analysis by
Fourier transform, changes in EEG power spectra can be
reliably identiﬁed in association with speciﬁc stimuli in theclose range of 0.5 s, as shown for event-related desynchro-nization (ERD) and synchronization (ERS) studies [ 35,36].
This degree of time resolution is achieved at the expense of
frequency resolution [ 37]. During sustained cognitive activ-
ity, short-lasting changes will no longer be discernible, even
though long-lasting, consistent changes on narrow frequency
bands may be identiﬁed. Under this rationale, it has been con-cluded that induced cognitive EEG activity, on the timescale
of seconds, will more closely resemble a resting (reference)
period than shorter-lasting, event-related EEG epochs [ 38
,
39]. However, when attempting to characterize ongoing EEG
microstructure on the range of seconds, it may be interesting
to explore a different strategy such as the matching pursuit
algorithm, which makes use of a large dictionary of differentmathematical functions to attain a description of the original
signal [ 37]. Matching pursuits are greedy algorithms, mean-
ing that the original signal is decomposed through recursivesteps called iterations whereby the single dictionary function
that best matches the signal is identiﬁed and extracted, leav-
ing a progressively less meaningful signal residue to undergothe next iteration. It resembles the strategy employed to ﬁndthe smallest possible number of coins when giving change
in a money transaction. The result is a set of functions that
can be represented in a time-frequency plane as elementscalled atoms, deﬁned through their frequency, length and
intensity [ 37]( s e eF i g . 1). This is akin to describing a melody
through its written score, where musical notes are denoted ona time-frequency plane, with frequency (pitch) indicated on
the y axis. Unlike the melody, however, a “reverse procedure”
would only recover main characteristics instead of the entireoriginal signal, since matching pursuit is an adaptive approx-imation technique. Practical applications include digit and
face identiﬁcation and image reconstruction [ 40–42]. Among
other algorithm variations, an adaptation for large-size datalike EEG (consisting in the replacement of the original dyadic
dictionary by a stochastic dictionary of functions to avoid sta-
tistical bias in the decomposition) has been provided by [ 43].
Matching pursuit with stochastic dictionary of functions has
been successfully applied to the description of sleep EEG
microstructure and wake EEG alpha activity [ 43–49]. To our
knowledge, EEG changes induced by arithmetic calculationshave not been studied with matching pursuit procedures.
In this study, EEG alpha and theta microstructure dur-
ing a sustained arithmetic production task was investigatedwith a streamlined experimental protocol. Subjects wearing
a mobile EEG device were tested outside the EEG lab, per-
forming a written task, in the sitting position with eyes open.A matching pursuit algorithm was employed for signal anal-
123 Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing (2024) 62:1869–1885 1871
ysis, since its properties render it a priori suitable to study
induced EEG activity over long time sequences, when it isnot tightly locked to a given stimulus. The main goal was
to verify if previous results obtained in tighter experimental
protocols, over shorter time frames and employing differentsignal analysis techniques could be replicated through thisapproach. Since the Math test consisted of a multiplication
task thought to require several cognitive abilities, no theo-
retical assumptions regarding strategy or speciﬁc cognitivefunctions were implied [ 4,50].
2 Methods
2.1 Subjects and experimental protocol
Sixty healthy volunteers (mean age 21 .9, standard deviation
3.4, 29 males) recruited among local undergraduate stu-
dents and research staff with similar age distribution [ 51]
took part in the study. Manual preference and menstrual
cycle were not controlled. The protocol complied with good
clinical practice and the Helsinki declaration [ 52]. Writ-
ten informed consent was provided by all participants. Thestudy was approved by the local ethics committee (Faculdade
de Medicina de Botucatu - UNESP) under project number
59229916.4.0000.5411.
Subjects were comfortably seated in a non-shielded room
with natural lighting. Individual 20-min sessions alternated
10 times between two 1-min conditions: eyes open (Rest)and Math task (Math). Subjects were instructed not to talk
and to remain as still as possible. Blinking was allowed.
During Math, a four-by-four-digit multiplication test was tobe solved on a blank sheet of paper. Math problems wereall different, randomly generated and of similar complex-
ity. Feedback regarding performance was provided after total
completion. Score for each Math problem ranged from 0 to10 as each correctly solved line (4 multiplications plus 1
sum) was worth 2 points. A ﬁnal average score from 0 to 10
was ascribed to each subject. There was overall good perfor-mance with median score 7, mode 6. Figure 1illustrates and
summarizes the protocol.
2.2 EEG device and data acquisition
EEG was acquired on a 16-bit A/D converter, Emotiv EPOC+
portable device [ 21], that uses gold-plated contact sensors
ﬁxed to ﬂexible plastic arms of a wireless headset ( http://
emotiv.com/ ). EEG is acquired from left and right anterior
frontal (AF3, AF4), anterior temporal (F7, F8), frontal (F3,F4), fronto-central (FC5, FC6), temporal (T7, T8), parietal
(P7, P8), occipital (O1, O2) and mastoid (M1, M2) elec-
trodes aligned with 10-10 IS (International System) [ 34],
exception for T7 and T8, which are placed more posteriorlyon 10-10 IS. As it is a ﬁxed headset, there are variations on
electrode position according to head size and shape whichwere not controlled. M1 functioned as a reference point to
which amplitude of every other sensor was compared. M2
was a feed-forward reference that reduced external electri-cal interference. Room lights and, when necessary, otherelectrical devices were turned off to avoid 60 Hz noise
interference. Signal acquisition was only carried out when
EPOC+ default impedance check showed acceptable (level4) electrode impedance.
2.3 Spectral power and MP signal decomposition
Signals were internally digitized at 2048 Hz, down-sampledto 128 Hz and ﬁltered between 0.16 Hz and 43 Hz at theacquisition module before transmission [ 21]. The headset
was wirelessly connected to a PC and interfacing SDK Emo-
tiv platform. Signals were then converted to ASCII. Spectralanalysis was carried out with TISEAN 3.0.1 [ 53] default
Power spectrum feature, which yields square-windowed,
standard periodograms, implemented within a customer-builtpipeline. Sampling rate was 128 Hz. Each 1-min EEG seg-ment (7680 digital points) was zero-padded to achieve 64 s
(8192 digital points, a power of two). Frequency resolution
was 0.016 Hz. Spectral analysis was carried out to pro-vide an overview of main signal characteristics. It was not
directly compared to MP. Data were visually checked for
the presence of noise. Periodograms containing power spec-tral density (PSD) peaks exceeding an arbitrary threshold
of 1000 μV
2/Hz were discarded. These comprised less than
3% of the total sample. Band-limited theta and alpha powerwere respectively deﬁned as average absolute band power in[4 Hz–7.5 Hz] and (7.5 Hz–13 Hz] bands, expressed in μV
2.
As band limits are arbitrary, values were also computed for
each 0.5 Hz interval within the 0.5 Hz–20 Hz range.
The matching pursuit algorithm employed in this study,
hereafter referred to as MP, is freely available at https://
github.com/dellagustin ). It is a customized version of another
freely available algorithm (called MP, version mp3) which
was introduced by Durka and cols. in [ 43] and remained avail-
able at https://braintech.pl/eeg-pl/ until 2015. The algorithm
MP, version mp3 differs from the original algorithm devel-oped by Mallat and Zhang [ 37] in that a stochastic dictionary
of functions replaced the original dyadic dictionary, to avoid
statistical bias in the decomposition. The stochastic dictio-nary in MP, version mp3 is basically built from real Gabor
functions, with discrete Dirac and Fourier functions added
to deal with well-localized structures in time and frequency,respectively [ 43]. This dictionary choice is not unique as
explained in [ 54]. Our customization of MP, version mp3
consisted in the further inclusion of a Gabor chirplet dictio-nary of functions as a subroutine which allows the assessment
