123 Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing (2024) 62:1869–1885 1873
of atom internal frequency modulation [ 55,56]. We describe
this implementation in more detail in [ 46].
MP projects the signal Sg(t)on a vector gγ
gγ(t)=αe−π(( t−b)/s)2sin[2πω( t−b)/N
+(2π)2ξ(t−b)2/N2+φ], (1)
where tis time, Nis the signal digital point number (signal
size), bis position in time, sis scale, ωis angular frequency,
ξis the chirping term and φis phase. γ={α,b,s,w,ξ,φ }is
a parameter list for dictionary functions where αis selected
such that ||gγ|| = 1.
MP was implemented into successive juxtaposed windows
over the time series, run separately for each EEG channel.Each window had 2048 points and 16 s duration. The fourth
window from each minute was 12 s long, so it was zero-
padded to achieve 2048 points. The original dictionary sizewas 70.000 (this number is inﬂated at the subroutine level
by the presence of chirplet functions). A stochastic dictio-
nary size of 70 K/16 s may be considered small, as early MPimplementations for EEG signal analysis relied on stochasticdictionary sizes in the range of millions [ 57]. However, the
low-density dictionary used here has been empirically shown
to perform well to detect intermittent, short-duration sigmaactivity (sleep spindles, ≤2 s, 11 Hz–16 Hz) embedded on
highly non-stationary background rhythms, and to discrimi-
nate between different severity sleep apnea groups accordingto sleep spindle characteristics [ 45,47,58]. In intracranially
acquired signals, a dictionary size of 100 K/2 s was suf-
ﬁcient to test MP performance for epileptic seizure statediscrimination, where frequency is known to vary widelywithin a short period of time [ 59]. As we were dealing with
highly ﬁltered, intermediate/low-frequency scalp EEG activ-
ity acquired on a low-resolution mobile device, we expecteddistinctive characteristics of such a signal to be retrieved over
the ﬁrst iterations with a low-density dictionary. The stopping
criterion was established at 96 iterations. Since the decom-position easily attains 90% signal energy, 96 iterations can
only be reached by setting the energy parameter threshold to
100%. MP decomposition thus obtained 96 atoms for each16 s window in each of 14 EEG channels. This methodologytends to enforce constant global density, so it differs from
measurements of atom density such as described in [ 60].
Atoms obtained with MP have a central point in the time-
frequency plane and limits determined by their half-width
(HW), corresponding to ±σon a Gaussian curve [ 37]. Each
atom is identiﬁed through its central point in time. Atom fre-quency corresponds to its central point in frequency. Atom
length corresponds to HW in time. Atom peak amplitude
corresponds to the AT parameter in the algorithm. Data per-taining to atom count, single atom amplitude ( μV), length(s) and central frequency (Hz) were collected. Internal fre-
quency modulation was computed but not analyzed here.
2.4 Statistical analysis
After MP decomposition, theta [4 Hz–7.5 Hz] and alpha (7.5Hz–13 Hz] atoms with ≥0.5 s duration and ≤250μV ampli-
tude were selected for further analysis. Single alpha and
theta distributions were calculated for each 10-min datasetobtained from each of 60 subjects, in 2 conditions (Rest and
Math), for each of 14 electrodes. From these single distribu-
tions, the 10% lower amplitude alpha and theta atoms wererespectively discarded as additional noise control.
Variables under investigation were MP atom number/min
(count), duration in s (length), central frequency in Hz (Freq),
amplitude in μV (amplitude), and theta and alpha spectral
power in μV
2(power). Because frequency bands have arbi-
trary limits and often differ among studies, MP atom count
and amplitude, as well as spectral power, were also stud-ied in 0.5 Hz micro bins within the [0.5 Hz–20 Hz] range.
MP atom length and frequency could not be analyzed in
0.5 Hz bands due to intrinsic properties of MP description.When frequency slices start to decrease, time and frequencybecome more diffusely deﬁned. As time is known, frequency
is unknown [ 37,61].
Shapiro-Wilk tests for normalcy revealed non-Gaussian
distributions, so analyses proceeded with non-parametric
methods. Our null hypothesis is that EEG alpha and theta
time-frequency structure, as measured through a matchingpursuit procedure with the present experimental protocol, is
similar in rest and mental calculation states. Comparisons
between left and right hemispheres and between Rest andMath were implemented with two-tailed Wilcoxon rank-sumtests (W). False discovery rate (FDR) -corrected P-values
(q-values) <0.05 were considered signiﬁcant. Unless oth-
erwise speciﬁed, data are expressed as median [interquartilerange, IQR] and depicted as notched Box-and-Whisker plots
[62], where notches represent 95% conﬁdence intervals for
medians and whiskers represent standard extreme values,respectively, 1.5 times above the upper quartile and 1.5 times
below the lower quartile. Statistical analyses were run using
R version 3.6.2 [ 63,64].
