In Rest, alpha and theta power shows a clear trend toward
higher amplitude in more anterior as opposed to more poste-rior regions. The anterior-posterior amplitude gradient was
also evident for MP amplitude. Equally expected [ 34,65],
absolute power and MP amplitude were generally higher onthe right side compared to the left side (Appendix AFig. 5).
Side comparisons for MP amplitude reached signiﬁcance for
all locations under study, except frontal (F3 vs F4) sites,
for alpha as well as theta activity. When measured throughspectral power, left vs. right side amplitude differences were
signiﬁcant in mid and posterior locations both for alpha and
for theta activity.
Considerably different patterns were seen for MP atom
number distribution according to brain topography and fre-
quency range. There were no clear trends or antero-posteriorgradient on the left hemisphere. The right hemisphere stillshowed a trend toward higher median theta count on ante-
rior as opposed to posterior sites. On the alpha count,
the right hemisphere showed a trend toward an inverse(posterior-anterior) gradient. Inter-hemisphere atom num-ber comparisons showed similar patterns to power and MP
amplitude, i.e., a trend toward higher numbers on the rightside. However, signiﬁcantly higher right-sided counts were
only found for theta on fronto-central and midtemporal
regions, and for alpha on the midtemporal region.
MP frequency and length were notably stable across brain
topography during Rest. Theta length ranged between 2.62
[0.62] s on FC5 and 2.91 [0.44] s on T8, whereas alpha
length ranged between 2.88 [0.63] s on AF4 and 3.06 [0.48] son F8, respectively. No anterior-posterior gradients or inter-
hemisphere differences were identiﬁed, except for higher
alpha frequency on the right midtemporal region comparedto the left side.
