3.6 Comparisons between conditions along the [0.5
Hz–20 Hz] range
When atom number and amplitude were examined along the
[0.5 Hz–20 Hz] range in terms of the strength of the statisti-
cal difference between conditions, some interesting patternsconcerning atom number comparisons were revealed. These
results are shown in Fig. 4. It should be remembered that
alpha count was lower and theta count was higher duringthe Math task. In the ﬁrst place, theta range effects weredissociated from those on the alpha range and occurred in
a continuum with the delta range. Second, theta count dif-
ferences between conditions, where present in left frontalregion, were signiﬁcant along a diffuse range encompassing
3 Hz to 7 Hz frequencies. Conversely, alpha range differ-ences were consistent on a narrow band around 10 Hz to
10.5 Hz. Third, theta range effects were notable on the leftfrontal region, whereas alpha range effects were more diffuse
and most evident on the right hemisphere and on posterior
sites, reaching signiﬁcance on left frontal, right posterior tem-poroparietal, and bilateral occipital regions. Of note, the leftfrontal region, where atom count on the complete alpha (7.5
Hz–13 Hz] range was not signiﬁcantly different between con-
ditions, still contained a small [10 Hz–10.5 Hz] range withsigniﬁcant differences. Microbin power and MP amplitude
comparisons between Math and Rest were non-signiﬁcant.
4 Discussion
This study made use of a matching pursuit procedure to inves-tigate EEG alpha and theta time-frequency structure during a
resting baseline condition and a sustained written arithmetictask obtained with a streamlined experimental protocol, out-
side the EEG lab, with the aid of a mobile EEG device.
