Relative to resting wakefulness, there was lower MP alpha
count over posterior and right-side regions during the Mathtask, whereas MP theta count was signiﬁcantly higher on
anteriorly located electrodes, especially over the left hemi-
sphere. We interpreted these results as indicating alpha andtheta activation during the Math task, in line with previousﬁndings obtained with other signal analysis techniques and
considering different time frames [ 66–68].
4.1 Alpha and theta activation during Math task
In [66], 0.78 Hz bands were analyzed in 1280 ms EEG
segments with frequency domain variable resolution electro-magnetic tomography. During an arithmetic production task
for 10 subjects, higher primary ﬁeld currents were found for
the 3.9 Hz mini theta band over left inferior frontal gyrusand 5.46 Hz mini theta band over right prefrontal cortex,
whereas the 12.48 Hz mini alpha band showed a decrease
over left parietal cortex. In [ 67], 8 s EEG epochs obtained
from 18 medical students during two-digit multiplication rel-ative to viewing numbers showed increased absolute theta
power in the frontal region and decreased absolute alpha
power in the parietal region. In [ 68], during each ﬁrst sec-
ond of post stimulus activity, divided into 250 ms epochs,
upper alpha ERD was stronger over parietal vs. prefrontal,
and theta ERS stronger on prefrontal vs. parietal regions dur-ing implicit retrieval of multiplication fact knowledge, tested
on 17 university students. Our ﬁndings of most signiﬁcant
left-sided theta and right-sided alpha effects are also consis-tent with long-range anterior-posterior and inter-hemisphericfunctional connections between several different neuronal
populations [ 8,9]. Theta and alpha activity obtained during
cognitive and motor tasks result from different as opposedto unitary sources on frontal and central cortex [ 69–71].
Our results are also congruent with functional neuroimaging
studies that repeatedly implicate a fronto-parietal networksubserved by bilateral intraparietal and prefrontal cortex on
Math reasoning and cognition [ 8,9,72].
Alpha count differences between conditions were par-
ticularly noticeable on a narrow range around 10 Hz–10.5Hz, consistent with narrow alpha peak differences shown in
ERD/ERS studies [ 73]. On this range, differences were also
present on left frontal sites, where entire alpha range compar-isons were non-signiﬁcant. This reinforces the importance of
investigating peak alpha frequency and narrow, as opposed
to traditional alpha bands. We also found widespread lowermedian alpha frequency during the Math task relative to rest-
ing wakefulness, as the proportion of lower frequency alpha
atoms increased in association with a total decrease on alphaatom number, consistent with the concept of alpha activation.Alpha and theta activation are considered to reﬂect dif-
ferent cognitive functions related to Math problem solvingand overall cognitive processing [ 10,12]. In the above-
cited study by De Smedt and cols, higher left hemisphere
theta ERS was associated with solution of small-sized arith-metic problems and judged to reﬂect fact retrieval functions,whereas stronger bilateral alpha ERD was associated with
solution of large-sized problems and considered to reﬂect
more intense engagement of cognitive resources [ 12]. Con-
versely, Klimesch and cols proposed that “theta activity
reﬂects working memory functions whereas upper alpha
activity would be related to reactivation of long-term memorycodes during short-term memory processes” [ 73]. Because
our Math task required different cognitive abilities assumed
to overlap and rapidly alternate over time, no theoreticalassumptions regarding cognitive strategy or speciﬁc cogni-tive functions may be attempted [ 74]. Indeed, due to the lack
of a control non-Math cognitive task, it is not possible to
speciﬁcally attribute our results to mathematical reasoning,as they might be non-speciﬁcally related to cognitive engage-
ment in comparison to a resting period. Increased frontal theta
and decreased parietal alpha activity, as measured throughrelative band power, have been veriﬁed in a study that tested
different mobile EEG devices comparing a more demanding
with a less demanding cognitive task [ 23]. The four-by-
four-digit multiplication task employed in the present studyrequired the completion of sequential addition steps and
most likely recruited attentional resources as well as rote
memory functions, relying on variable verbal, visuo-spatialand quantitative processes across subjects [ 51,75]. Func-
tional neuronal networks are believed to exhibit dynamic
interactions between oscillatory activity produced in dif-ferent frequency ranges, in other words, neuronal activity
synchronization and desynchronization patterns in different
frequency bands is believed to be related to the couplingand uncoupling of dedicated functional networks [ 76–80]. It
has been shown that the sense of quantity is used abstractly
by different neural networks in the brain [ 81–83]. Brodmann
area 39, topographically related to the angular girus, has beenconsidered as a boundary between low theta and high alpha
frequency regions in EEG acquisition [
34,75,83] and mental
calculations have been claimed to be the most efﬁcient way toactivate Brodmann area 39 and adjacency [ 4,8,82,83]. It is
also known that oscillatory activity desynchronization on the
alpha range reﬂects different functional processes over dif-ferent scalp locations, for instance, suppression of mu rhythmover rolandic cortex is related to motor action and/or inten-
tion [ 84]. It should be noticed that so-called alpha activation
as shown through ERD, spectral power attenuation or MPatom number reduction might indirectly reﬂect a contribution
123 Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing (2024) 62:1869–1885 1879
of higher frequency, gamma activity synchronization over
locally dedicated workspaces rapidly changing over time[78]. In any case, due to the plasticity of the network, some
features of a dedicated workspace may be self-supporting and
remain active for a relatively longer time frame, even aftertask completion [ 79]. Future studies might show whether
dynamic inter-relations of MP atoms in alpha, theta and other
frequency bands might be informative in this way. Perhaps
the most distinctive aspect of mathematical language is that,unlike verbal language, its use absolutely requires precision.
It may be intriguing that this need for accuracy is met by
such a widespread instead of highly localized functional net-work, but that is precisely the concept conveyed in models
addressing effortful cognitive tasks [ 72,79,85].
4.2 Matching pursuit analysis, signal
non-stationarity and inhomogeneity
MP atom number translates decomposition of a strongly non-
stationary signal into numerous elements that, in this case,ﬁtted the time frame of several seconds. The fact that median
atom duration was relatively stable across scalp topography
and showed minor changes during the Math task may be rel-evant from the physiological standpoint, as the time frame
implicated in ERD/ERS effects lies within the range of a
few seconds [ 36]. However, estimations of MP atom dura-
tion depend on the employed methodology [ 86]. This study
made use of a low-sized stochastic MP dictionary. Increasing
size of the stochastic dictionary will consistently reduce atomduration, as reported by Chandran and cols [ 86]. Of notice on
that study, the ultimate dictionary size was chosen to ﬁt what
was a priori considered an optimal gamma burst duration,
as measured through other techniques. Our choice of dictio-nary size ﬁnds support on one high spatial-resolution EEG
study of ERS/ERD involving 20 healthy university students,
where individually tailored activation periods were found torange approximately between 1 s and 3 s [ 12]. Another ﬁnd-
ing that may be directly related to signal inhomogeneity was
an unexpected dissociation between amplitude and MP atomcount. No signiﬁcant changes were found for MP atom andpower amplitude during our Math task, despite consistent
inter-hemisphere differences in these quantities. Arguably,
our spectral analysis spanned long signal sections, increas-ing variance and potentially reducing statistical differences.
However, similar results for MP atom amplitude render this
explanation less plausible. Atom number may be more sensi-tive than amplitude to detect the functional interplay of alpha
and theta oscillations during a cognitive task. On a previous
investigation of resting alpha activity in a different study sam-ple, we have reached a similar conclusion about the advantageof atom number computation over amplitude or duration
measures to discriminate between eyes open and eyes closedstates [ 49]. In the present study, amplitude-related ﬁndings
are consistent with reports that, during a sustained cognitive
task, ongoing (tonic) EEG activity resembles baseline ratherthan phasic (event-related) activity [ 20,39]. Additionally, our
divergent ﬁndings on the topographic distribution of atom
number and amplitude-related quantities further suggest a
functional dissociation between these variables.
The main objective of implementing MP signal analysis
for the study of Math cognition in a realistic setting was
successfully carried out on an off-line basis. Time and com-putational cost for an online procedure remain to be veriﬁed
[22].
4.3 Study protocol for data acquisition
Another study aim was to test the feasibility of a simpli-
ﬁed experimental protocol for data acquisition. Subjects werewearing a mobile EEG device. They were tested outside the
EEG lab, in the sitting position with eyes open. They per-
formed the written Math task during a relatively prolongedperiod of time, consisting of a whole minute to carry outeach calculation. Our results suggest this experimental setup
was overall successful. However, important limitations for
data analysis and interpretation ensued from the experimen-tal setup. Blinking and eye movement artifacts were not
controlled between conditions, so data on lower (delta) fre-
quency bands was not analyzed. The written task may haveconfounded results over EEG central and parietal areas, as
hand movement and motor intention are known to inﬂuence
alpha range activity (mu rhythm), particularly picked up overC3 and C4 electrodes [ 35,87], and alpha band activity may be
suppressed on both hemispheres during writing, mainly over
the left parietal lobe [ 88]. This protocol may be more suitable
to explore anterior frontal and temporo-occipital regions,whereas depending on the study aim, central and parietal
regions might be more appropriately surveyed with non-
motor tasks. Future studies should more carefully controlfor movement and eye blinking, and differentiate between
Math tasks and other cognitive functions.
5 Conclusions
In conclusion, with the aid of mobile EEG, it was possi-
ble to test feasibility of a simpliﬁed experimental protocol
to investigate EEG alpha and theta activation during sus-
tained written arithmetic calculations outside the EEG lab,employing for the ﬁrst time a matching pursuit procedure for
123 1880 Medical & Biological Engineering & Computing (2024) 62:1869–1885
EEG signal analysis in this context and replicating previous
results obtained with different techniques and different timeframes. Over the relatively relaxed time frame of 60 s, MP
with a low density-sized stochastic dictionary loosely decom-
posed alpha and theta activity into numerous elements withduration around 3 s, similar to the duration of tightly time-locked activity obtained with ERS/ERD studies. MP alpha
and theta atom number and central alpha frequency were
informative to document regional activation during the Mathtask. MP atom number appears to be more informative thanamplitude in this type of experimental paradigm. Future stud-
ies employing higher resolution equipment, more speciﬁccognitive tasks and better exploring spatial and temporal
dynamics of MP alpha and theta activity may prove use-
ful, but the goal of achieving valid experimental results onrealistic settings remains a priority. MP merits to be furtherexplored in the context of Math cognition studies.
