Accessing small-world characteristics
The concept of ‘‘Small-World’’, originally introduced by
Watts and Strogatz in 1998, is strongly related to the
clustering coefﬁcient, C, and the characteristic path length,
L, of a given graph (Watts and Strogatz, 1998 ). Here, we
accessed ‘‘Small-Worldness’’ by means of global and local
efﬁciency. Global efﬁciency [see Eq. ( 1)] is inversely
related to L (Latora and Marchiori 2001 ). Thus, a small-
world network has a GE value that is lower than in a
random network, while LE obtains a higher value. TheTable 1 Estimated number of cycles for each frequency band, con-
