As implied by the previous equation, the multichannel EEG-
traces from the control condition constitute the ﬁrst set of objects
{Xi}, while the traces recorded during one of the mathematical-
tasks populate the second set { Yj}. The contrast-function measures
the class separability, with the J-index taking the value of 1 when
classes are highly overlapped and growing monotonically as clas-
ses are getting more distinguishable. The given formulation is as
generic as possible, incorporating the ‘‘feature extraction’’ step
within the computation of the dissimilarity-measure.
The statistical signiﬁcance of a speciﬁc value for the J-index can
be calculated based on a randomisation procedure ( Good, 2000;
Goulden et al., 2010 ), which proceeds by ﬁrst splitting the objects
(i.e., all EEG-traces from rest and active conditions) at random into
two groups and repeating the computations for Jmultiple times to
form a baseline distribution for the J-index indicative of random
partitioning. Finally, the original value of the J-index is compared
to the derived baseline distribution, and this comparison is ex-
pressed via a P-value.
After selecting an appropriate representation for a brain state
and establishing the corresponding dissimilarity, the N= 18 pat-
terns of a mental calculation task can be compared against the pat-
