Next, the contrast-function quantiﬁes differences in functional
segregation between the rest and the active condition (a schematic
illustration of the computations involved can be seen in Supple-
mentary Fig. S2 ). We should note here that the passage from EEG
signals { Xi} to clusterings { ci} includes the intermediate step of
estimating the functional connectivity patterns. This step is de-
scribed below.
2.2.2. Functional connectivity patterns and their graph representations
To accommodate the various aspects of neural synchrony, we
employed different functional connectivity estimators. Speciﬁcally,
three representative algorithms for estimating Coherence ,Nonlin-
ear Interdependence , and Phase Locking Index were employed. Every
estimator takes as input a pair of time series recorded at distinct
sites and derives an estimate of the strength for the corresponding
functional interaction. Such an interaction can have either linear or
nonlinear characteristics and can take the form of either amplitude
or phase covariation. The estimators were selected to span a wide
range of functional connectivity, with the ultimate goal (by com-
parison) to provide a deeper understanding of the interregional
coordination during a mental calculation. Speciﬁcally, coherence
(COH) is a linear measure working in the frequency domain and
incorporating both amplitude and phase characteristics. On the
contrary, Quiroga’s Nonlinear Interdependence (NI) is a nonlinear
measure based on similarities between trajectories of the underly-
ing dynamical systems ( Quiroga, Kraskov, Kreuz, & Grassberger,
2002 ; a new publicly available MATLAB toolbox for related nonlin-
ear analysis is provided in Beste, Otto, & Hoffmann (2010) ; a re-
view on dynamic connectivity in neural systems is provided in
Breakspear (2010) . Finally, the Phase Locking ind ex (PLI) neutralises
the effects of amplitude variations, utilises Morlet’s wavelet trans-
form to estimate instantaneous phases and attempts a statistical
aggregation of phase-differences (see Appendix A ). Each estimator
was applied (using signals ﬁltered within a speciﬁc frequency
band) to every possible pair of electrodes. The derived measure-
ments have a natural graph-theoretic representation via a fully
connected weighted graph, called the functional connectivity
graph (FCG), where nodes correspond to electrodes and links areweighted according to the strength of the functional coupling.
Because functional segregation is among the brain’s most prom-
inent self-organisation characteristics ( Tononi & Edelman, 1998 ),
we attempted to explore its putative role in mental calculations
using a brain state representation that would emphasise this pos-
sibility. Each FCG graph was ﬁrst entered into a graph-segmenta-
tion algorithm (as recently adopted for an EEG-synchrony study
(Dimitriadis, Laskaris, Del Rio-Portilla, & Koudoumis, 2009 )) and
functionally coupled sites were grouped into mutually exclusive
clusters. The induced grouping was then treated as the representa-
tion that could be used in our contrast function. Having all of the
clusterings available, we measured the contrast of the control con-
dition against (each one of) the cognitive tasks, using Eq. (2).
2.2.3. Prototypical functional segregations
Representative patterns of functional segregation best reﬂecting
the three brain states were derived based on all of the available
clusterings and then were presented topographically in a con-
trasted manner to facilitate comparisons (see Fig. 3 ). For this deri-
vation, we exploited the fact that VI is a true metric in the space of
clusterings and incorporated it in a vector-median estimator that
identiﬁes the ‘‘centroid’’ of a given set of clusterings ( Astola, Haav-isto, & Neuvo, 1990 ). For each one of the three conditions, the
ensemble of N= 18 clusterings S={c
1,c2,...,cN} was used in the
following computation of prototypical segregation cm:
