The above estimator bears some similarities with the notion of
median-graph , which is the graph that has the minimum average
distance to all graphs in a given set ( Bunke, Gunter, & Jiang, 2001 ).
3. Results
3.1. Functional connectivity graph (FCG) representation
Three different versions of an FCG were utilised as alternative
representations (FCGCOH, FCGNI, FCGPLI), depending on the em-
ployed functional connectivity estimator. For each type of syn-
chrony tested, the necessary parameters (for example, the
embedding-dimension and time-lag in the case of NI) were opti-
mised independently for each frequency-band to achieve the max-
imal task-discrimination score for the J function ( Laskaris,
Zafeiriou, & Garefa, 2009 ).Supplementary Fig. S1 demonstrates
this type of exhaustive search for the cases of the PLI-estimator
(which depends solely on the parameter dj(see Appendix A)) and
the NI-index.
By clustering the nodes of each single FCG, patterns of func-
tional segregation were derived for every frequency-band underexamination. These groupings were then used to estimate the con-
trast between a control and an active condition. Table 1 includes
the corresponding J-values, which express task-induced differ-
ences in functional segregation. The elevated J-scores ( J> 1) clearly
indicate that self-organisation through group formation is an
important tendency in our data. Interestingly, this tendency is bet-
ter portrayed through the connectivity measurements derived
with the phase-locking estimator. In all frequency bands, phase
synchrony appears to be the neural underpinning of functional
segregation in both cognitive tasks. Statistically signiﬁcant changes
did appear via the NI-estimator, but not with the COH estimator
(except in the gamma band). This experimental fact points to the
nonlinear-character of the interactions that are involved.
3.2. Functional-segregation prototypes
Because the node-clustering of PLI-based FCGs resulted in the
most promising representation (high J, while P< 0.001) for all of
the frequency-bands, we included in Fig. 3 the corresponding par-
titions, which portray the three tasks best (see Section 2.2.3 ). The
derived prototypical-segregations for the resting state and for both
mathematical tasks are listed in the different rows of Fig. 3 . In each
individual topography, the groups formed are indicated using dif-
ferent colours. The colour code denotes the ranks of the groups,
with red associated with the most compact group (and hence the
strongest functional cluster). In the inset associated with each
topography, the values of the Cohesion-index (an index expressing
cluster compactness, as described in Appendix B) are listed for the
groups.
The most important trend is that during math calculations,
coherent functional groups are emerging. Most of these groups
are well localised (i.e., they correspond to nearby brain regions)
with a Cohesion-index higher than the groupings that correspond
to the control-state. The only exception in the previous observation
is the fourth group (coloured light-blue), which is formed in the
a1
anda2bands during the comparison task. Interestingly, during the
control condition, the whole brain behaves as a single functional
identity (or, in a few cases, a second, weakly-connected component48 S.I. Dimitriadis et al. / Brain and Cognition 80 (2012) 45–52 appears). The above trends were observed consistently across sub-
jects, with only subtle differences among the individual cluster-
ings. More detailed observations can be made by considering the
strength of clustering tendencies (Cohesion-level). Focusing, for
example, on the a1band, we can observe two clusters for the con-
trol condition, with Cohesion-indexes 0.3898 and 0.1389, and fourclusters during the comparison task, with Cohesion-indexes rang-
ing from 0.2463 to 0.7496. The values included indicate that the
‘‘light-blue’’ cluster, formed within the a1band during the compar-
ison task, is less compact than the ﬁrst cluster extracted during the
control condition. Moreover, the Cohesion-index of the three clus-
ters formed within the a1band during the multiplication task
