In summary, node-clustering of PLI-based FCGs provided vivid
evidence about functional segregation in the brain during both
math tasks.
4. Discussion
We studied pattern formation associated with mental calcula-
tions based on derivations that rely on the raw EEG signal. Being
aware of the convoluted nature of the signal at the sensor level,
we searched for changes (associated with math calculations) in
the patterning of the neural synchrony and aimed at a topographic
description and characterisation of the underlying phenomena.
Before discussing our results, we ﬁrst set the methodological
foundation of our work as follows. Our framework is suitable by
design for handling pattern-analytic problems via dissimilarity
measures and hence encapsulates recent theoretical advances in
the pattern-recognition ﬁeld ( Pekalska & Duin, 2005 ). This study
revolves around the core idea of ﬁrst establishing a single unifying
contrast function that could discriminate between a control task
and either of two mental tasks (comparison or multiplication)
and then searching for the speciﬁc descriptor that would lead to
the maximal differentiation. Recently, a similar study has appeared
comparing various synchrony measures but with a different ap-
proach and in a different context (Alzheimer’s disease) ( Dauwels,
Viallate, Musha, & Cichocki, 2009 ).
First, we established the contrast function (see Eqs. (1) and (2)),
which captured the brain’s self-organisation tendencies during
mental tasks and could be used in many ways. Using J-index
(and the accompanying randomisation test), we explored task-in-
duced phenomena in the emerging connectivity patterns. The
application of a node-clustering algorithm in these connectivitygraphs offered an important descriptor that emphasised the task-
induced functional segregations. J-values were dependent on the
frequency band ( h,
a1,a2,bandc) and the nature of selected con-
nectivity descriptors (Coherence, NI and PLI).
When comparing the prototypical segregations ( Fig. 3 ), the
most striking observation is that the resting state is primarily char-
acterised via a single global functional cluster, while in both tasks,
functional clusters are formed corresponding not only to well-
localised but also to widely distributed networks. The above trends
were consistently observed across subjects.
Then, we need to stress that the PLI descriptor contributed to
the maximal discrimination between the mental tasks and the
baseline condition. Statistically signiﬁcant changes appeared via
the NI-estimator as well, with lower values for the contrast func-
tion, but signiﬁcant changes did not appear with the COH estima-
tor (except in the gamma band). This study is one of the very ﬁrst
times that a comparative study has been attempted in such a cog-
nitive task. The outcome underlines the nonlinear character of theinteractions involved during mental mathematics. When seen from
the perspective of complex systems, our experimental ﬁndings
about the role of phase synchronisation can be interpreted as an
indication of rather weak coupling strength ( Graben, Zhou, Thiel,
& Kurth, 2008 ).
In conclusion, we scrutinised both functional segregation and
integration, but always worked in a comparative manner (search-
ing for differences between a mental task and the rest condition).
We ﬁrst showed that phase-coupling best describes the functional
interactions that lead to segregation during the two arithmetic
tasks. Moreover, a widespread long-range phase synchrony pattern
was also found to accompany these mental mechanisms, to sub-
serve integration. Overall, the ﬁndings provide additional support
to Varela’s hypothesis ( Varela, Lachaux, Rodriguez, & Martinerie,
2001 ), according to which the most plausible mechanisms for neu-
ral integration are the formation of dynamical links that are re-
ﬂected as phase-synchronisation in the EEG signals.
5. Conclusions
This study showed that self-organisation through group forma-
tion is an important tendency in two math tasks. Interestingly, self-
organisation during math tasks is better portrayed through the
connectivity measurements derived with the phase-locking esti-
mator. In all frequency bands, phase synchrony appears to be the
neural underpinning of functional segregation in both cognitive
tasks. The most important trend is that, during math calculations,
coherent functional groups are emerging, while during the control
condition, the whole brain behaves as a single functional identity.
An obvious follow-up of the present study would be to compare
the patterns of task-induced segregations across different agegroups ( Micheloyannis et al., 2009 ) and between healthy individu-
als and patients with mathematical disturbances such as acalculia
and dyscalculia. Exploratory analysis focusing on both time–fre-
quency domains ( Dimitriadis et al., 2010 ) and a variety of imaging
modalities (including structural MRI, diffusion MRI, functional MRI,
and EEG/MEG) can further enhance current knowledge of the neu-
ral mechanisms of numerical calculations and can potentially con-
tribute to the understanding of math inefﬁciency.
