Appendix B. Graph-theoretic clustering and VI metric
The summary included here has been adapted from a recent
EEG-study ( Dimitriadis et al., 2009 ), where more details can be
found. Because a symmetrical FCG was required by the clustering
methodology of ( Pavan & Pellilo, 2007 ), in the case of a non-sym-
metric NI index ( Quiroga et al., 2002 ), the maximum coupling
was kept for every pairwise interaction regardless of direction.
Coherence and PLI are symmetric by their nature. The calculations
of the NI index were performed using the related Matlab-code(synchrom; Quiroga et al., 2002 ) with the number of nearest neigh-
bours set to 10, the Theiler-correction set to 50 (Theiler 1986) and
the remaining necessary parameters optimised, as described in
Section 2.2.2 ( Supplementary Fig. S2).
A graph-theoretic algorithm was employed for identifying the
most-cohesive group(s) of vertices given the weighted similarity
(adjacency) matrix G of an FCG. The algorithm is based on the iden-
tiﬁcation of the dominant set of nodes and, when repeatedly ap-
plied, facilitates effective clustering in a sequential mode of
pairwise relational data. In our case, the calculation takes the form
of deriving the n-dimensional vector y(n= 30) that maximises the
following objective function (i.e., the set-compactness).
