Having all of the clusterings available (the output of the graph
clustering algorithm was a 30-tuple c=[c1,...,c30], c ieZ(e.g.,
c=[13232 ...1112]) reﬂecting the graph-partition), we quanti-
ﬁed the contrast of the control condition vs. the cognitive tasks
for each frequency band using the VI-metric as the dissimilarity
measure ( Meila, 2007 ).
Variation of Information (VI) ( Meila, 2007 ) is a novel informa-
tion-theoretic criterion, which has been introduced for comparing
two different clusterings of the same data set and measures the
amount of information that is lost or gained in changing from clus-tering cto clustering c0. VI is a non-negative, symmetric metric that
is more intuitive compared to other relevant measures and more-
over, overcomes previous limitations (for example, it satisﬁes the
triangular inequality). VI is deﬁned by the function:
VIðc;c0Þ¼½HðcÞ/C0Iðc;c0Þ/C138 þ ½ Hðc0Þ/C0Iðc;c0Þ/C138 ð A:7Þ
where H(c) denotes the entropy associated with clustering candI(c,
c0) denotes the mutual information between the two clusterings, c
and c0.
The Matlab code that implements the graph-clustering algo-
rithm and the VI metric can be downloaded from the author’s web-
