2achievements in school mathematics as indicating mathematical 
giftnedness (Threlfall and Hargreaves, 2008 ; Koshy et al., 2009 ), some 
consider SAT-M scores (Prescott, Gavrilescu, Cunnington, O’Boyle and 
Egan, 2010 ; Lubinski and Benbow, 2006 ), whereas others focus on 
university mathematical majors (Amalric and Dehaene, 2016; Chi et al., 
1981 ) or students with high IQs (Davidson and Sternberg, 1984 ; Popescu 
et al., 2019 ; Taub et al., 2008 ). 
Leikin and Leikin (2009) suggested distinguishing between general 
giftedness and mathematical excellence and hypothesized that mathe -
matical giftedness is a combination of both. To examine this hypothesis, 
they introduced a 2 ×2 design consisting of the factors general gifted -
ness (G) and excellence in school mathematics (EM), and conducted a 
large-scale multidimensional study in 17–18 year old students with 
different combinations of EM and G levels (Leikin and Lev, 2013 ; Leikin 
et al., 2013a ; Leikin et al., 2013b ; Waisman et al., 2014 ; Paz-Baruch 
et al., 2014 ; Paz-Baruch et al., 2016 ; Leikin et al., 2016 ). The studies 
revealed that even though there is a correlation between EM and G 
factors, they are different in nature. For example, G was related to high 
verbal short-term memory, while EM was associated with high 
visuo-spatial working memory (Leikin et al., 2013 ). G-EM (gifted and 
excelling in mathematics) individuals excelled in visual-serial process -
ing, while pattern-recall processing was found to be related to the G 
factor only (Paz-Baruch et al., 2016 ). 
In contrast to mathematical excellence, there has been a vast amount 
of research on the neurophysiological correlates of general cognitive 
abilities or intelligence. This research has revealed that individual dif-
ferences in intelligence are associated with activation differences in a 
wide-spread network of brain regions (Colom et al., 2010 ; Deary et al., 
2010 ; Jung and Haier, 2007 ). A well-established finding in this research 
is the neural efficiency phenomenon, indicating that “brighter in-
dividuals display lower (more efficient) brain activation while per-
forming cognitive tasks ” (Neubauer and Fink, 2009, p. 1004 ). This result 
pattern was observed for a variety of different cognitive tasks, from 
rather simple reaction time tasks to more demanding working memory 
tasks (for a review, cf. Neubauer and Fink, 2009 ). 
Most of the studies demonstrating the neural efficiency phenomenon 
analyzed induced (oscillatory) EEG activity in the (higher) alpha fre-
quency band (about 10–12 Hz) while solving cognitive tasks (for a re-
view, cf. Neubauer and Fink, 2009 ). Induced EEG activity indicates 
task-related coupling and uncoupling of functional networks in the 
brain (Bastiaansen and Hagoort, 2003 ; Klimesch et al., 2005 ) and can be 
measured with event-related (de-) synchronization (for a review, cf. 
Pfurtscheller and Da Silva, 1999 ). In the alpha frequency band, the 
amount of alpha power typically decreases during cognitive activity as 
compared to a resting state, a phenomenon which is labelled 
event-related desynchronization (ERD). The percentage amount of 
decrease is then expressed in the ERD measure. In the studies on the 
neural efficiency phenomenon, higher intelligence was associated with 
lower alpha ERD, which has been interpreted to reflect lower brain 
activation during task performance (Grabner et al., 2006 ; Grabner et al., 
2004 ). 
Given that higher general cognitive abilities are associated with 
more efficient brain activation, the question arises whether this can be 
generalized to domain-specific competencies or excellence. In a seminal 
study on chess players, Grabner et al. (2006) found that chess experts 
(compared to novices) displayed more efficient brain activation (lower 
alpha ERD) while solving two domain-related tasks drawing on mental 
speed (enumeration of specific chess pieces) and reasoning (finding a 
checkmate move). This expertise-related difference was also indepen -
dent of their intelligence level. However, in a task requiring short-term 
memory of chess positions, during both encoding and retrieval experts 
displayed less efficient brain activation (higher alpha ERD) compared to 
novices. 
In the domain of mathematics, most studies on induced EEG activity 
have focused on arithmetic problem solving and examined both the 
alpha and the theta (4–7 Hz) frequency band. Specifically, it has been observed that solving easy vs. complex arithmetic problems is associated 
with higher event-related synchronization (ERS; task-related bandpower 
increase) in the theta band and lower ERD in the alpha band (De Smedt 
et al., 2009 ; Grabner and De Smedt, 2011 ; Grabner et al., 2022 ). This 
result pattern has been explained as reflecting the application of 
different cognitive strategies to solve arithmetic problems of different 
complexity levels. Easy problems (such as single-digit multiplications) 
have been found to be typically solved through arithmetic fact retrieval 
(i.e., retrieval of the solution from long-term memory). Since theta ERS 
has been assumed to link lexical-semantic representations over the 
cortex and between the cortex and the hippocampus (e.g., Bastiaansen 
and Hagoort, 2006 ; Marko et al., 2019 ; Salisbury and Taylor, 2012 ), 
higher theta ERS while solving easy (compared to more complex) 
arithmetic problems was interpreted to reflect a larger reliance on 
arithmetic fact retrieval. The higher alpha ERD in complex as compared 
to easy problems was interpreted to reflect the application of effortful 
and attention-demanding procedures, as alpha ERD has been found to 
increase with task difficulty and the associated increase in demand on 
attentional processes (Klimesch, 2012 ; Ku et al., 2010 ; Pfurtscheller and 
Da Silva, 1999 ). 
To our knowledge, induced EEG correlates of individual differences 
in mathematical competencies have only been investigated in one study 
so far. Artemenko et al. (2019) divided a sample of adults into two 
groups with different mathematical abilities based on their performance 
on an arithmetic task. During EEG recording, participants were required 
to solve multiplication and division problems of two complexity levels. 
Similar to previous studies on induced EEG activity during arithmetic 
problem-solving, the solution of more complex problems was associated 
with lower theta ERS and higher alpha ERD. This complexity effect, 
however, was not modulated by the participants ’ mathematical ability, 
indicating that the two groups showed similar complexity effects during 
problem-solving. 
Even though arithmetic problems are an essential foundation for 
mathematical skills, they are not representative of mathematical de-
mands in high school. A key concept in the high school curriculum is 
mathematical functions (Da Ponte, 1992 ; Leinhardt et al., 1990 ). Un-
derstanding of functions includes comprehension of functional relation 
(for example as a particular type of correspondence between two sets of 
objects) and knowledge and skills related to particular types of functions 
such as linear, quadratic, polynomial, rational, trigonometric, expo-
nential, or logarithmic functions. The concept of a function is the basis of 
the concepts of derivative and integral as well as of the theory of limits. 
Mathematical functions require the competence to translate and 
connect between different representations of mathematical concepts 
(Hiebert and Carpenter, 1992 ). Kaput (1998) argued that the sources of 
building mathematical meaning are found in the translations between 
representation systems. According to Duval (2006) , translations be-
tween representations are “at the heart of mathematical activity ” 
(Duval, 2006, p. 107). The learners ’ competence to translate flexibly 
between different representations allows them to comprehend the 
multifaceted nature of various concepts (Ainsworth et al., 1997 ; Cox, 
1999 ; Elia et al., 2007 ; Gagatsis and Shiakalli, 2004 ; Schonborn and 
Bogeholz, 2009 ; Van Heuvelen and Zou, 2001 ). This competence is built 
up in mathematics instruction; therefore, mathematical function tasks 
can be considered learning-based tasks. Specifically, learning-based 
tasks involve implementation of procedures, algorithms, strategies and 
representations that were studied and trained in previous learning ex-
periences. These tasks are often contrasted with insight-based tasks, 
which are unfamiliar to students and require problem restructuring to 
allow the use of knowledge and skills in a new situation. 
An EEG study on the mathematical function task was conducted by 
Waisman et al. (2014) . They examined the interplay of G and EM factors 
on high school students ’ mathematical performance (75 students, 16–18 
years old) associated with translations from graphical to symbolic rep-
resentations of functions using evoked EEG activity (i.e., event-related 
potentials; ERPs). Main effects of EM factor appeared at the I. Waisman et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 Neuropsychologia 179 (2023) 108448
3behavioral and electrophysiological levels, while main effects of G factor 
were found at the behavioral level only. When solving the function tasks, 
the accuracy of responses in EM (excelling in mathematics) students was 
significantly higher than the accuracy of NEM (non-excelling in math -
ematics) students, and the accuracy in G (gifted) students was signifi -
cantly higher than in their NG (non-gifted) counterparts. At the 
neurophysiological level, EM students exhibited significantly higher 
ERP amplitudes in the 300–500 ms interval as compared to NEM 
students. 
The reported ERP findings have provided important first insights into 
the electrophysiological correlates of G and EM while solving learning- 
based tasks representative of high school mathematics. However, their 
significance with respect to the neural efficiency hypothesis is limited, as 
the relationship between ERP amplitudes and intelligence is less well 
established than the association between alpha oscillations and intelli -
gence. While it is an often replicated finding that more intelligent in-
dividuals display lower alpha ERD during cognitive tasks, inconsistent 
results have been observed for ERP amplitudes (cf. Neubauer and Fink, 
2009 ). In addition, ERPs represent short phase-locked responses to a 
certain stimulus that do not capture the problem-solving process in more 
demanding cognitive tasks (e.g., after half a second), whereas ERD/ERS 
can flexibly measure induced activity from the problem ’s onset to its 
solution. Therefore, the aim of the present study was to evaluate the 
roles of G and EM on neural efficiency using the well-established and 
frequently used method of ERD/ERS. Since both theta and alpha fre-
quency bands have been associated with mathematical processes in 
previous studies, we conduct analyses for both bands. 
1.1. Research hypotheses 
In line with the above-noted previous findings (Waisman et al., 
2014 ), we examine the following hypotheses. 
H1.Both G and EM factors have a significant effect on behavioral 
measures when solving functions tasks. A. EM students exhibit higher 
accuracy and shorter reaction times than NEM students. B. G students 
show higher accuracy and shorter reaction times than NG students. 
H2.Due to the learning-based nature of function tasks, a pattern of 
neural efficiency can be observed only for the EM factor: EM students 
show lower brain activation (as reflected in lower alpha ERD) as 
compared to NEM students in S1 (processing of function) and S2 (veri-
fication of equation). 
No specific hypotheses regarding theta ERD/ERS can be proposed as 
there are no previous studies relating this measure to intelligence and 
mathematical excellence. Based on Artemenko et al. (2019) , no group 
differences can be expected. 
2.Methods 
2.1. Research sample 
In this study we report on a group of 118 students comprised of 45 
females and 73 males with a mean age of 16.6 (standard deviation 0.6) 
years. These participants were chosen based on a sampling procedure 
aimed at forming groups that differed in general giftedness (G factor) 
and excellence in mathematics (EM factor) (Table 1). For this purpose, 
we examined 1200 Israeli students in 10th and 11th grades (16–18 years 
old) using the Raven ’s Advanced Progressive Matrices Test (RPMT) 
(Raven et al., 2000 ) and the Scholastic Assessment Test in Mathematics 
(SAT-M) (Benbow and Lubinski, 1996 ). 
The EM factor was determined by the level of mathematics the stu-
dents studied in school and their scores on the SAT-M test. Mathematics 
is a compulsory subject in Israeli high schools and students are placed in 
one of three levels of mathematics: high (HL), regular (RL), and low (LL) 
level. The level of instruction is determined by students ’ mathematical achievements in earlier grades. Instruction at HL differs from that at RL 
in terms of the depth of the learning material and the complexity of the 
mathematical problem-solving involved. Overall, roughly 15% of stu-
dents in 10th, 11th and 12th grades study mathematics at HL. Students 
with mathematics scores above 90 (maximum of 100; scored by math -
ematics teacher) in HL mathematics represent approximately 3% of the 
general population. SAT-M is a multi-component test that includes tasks 
from different domains of mathematics. It is a recognized tool for 
measuring academic abilities in mathematics (e.g., Young and Kobrin, 
2001 ) and strategic problem-solving skills (e.g., Morrison et al., 2006 ). 
We used a short version of the SAT-M that contained 35 items with a 
time limit of 30 min (adopted by Zohar, 1990 ). The range of correct 
scores could vary from 0 to 35 and represented the number of problems 
solved correctly. A SAT-M score above 26 was chosen as a control 
measure for the EM sampling (2% of the general population). Thus, 
students were assigned to the EM group when meeting two criteria: a 
score in HL mathematics instruction above 90 and an SAT-M score above 
26. The NEM group included students with an SAT-M score less than 22 
(of 35) and a mathematics score greater than 90 in RL math or lower 
than 80 in HL math. An SAT-M score of 22 and HL math score below 80 
were used as a cut-off to ensure that the groups clearly differed in their 
mathematical achievements. 
The G factor was determined by students ’ participation in gifted 
classes and their success on the RPMT test. Students assigned to the G 
group were mainly chosen from classes for gifted students (identified by 
a national examination as having IQ F130 in the third grade). The 
students in classes for gifted students represent 2% of the population in 
Israel. Additionally, we used the RPMT test, which is considered a good 
indicator of general intelligence and ability (Carpenter et al., 1990; 
Silverman, 2009 ). We used a shortened test version containing 30 items 
(adopted by Zohar, 1990 ) so that the range of the final score (repre -
senting the number of problems solved correctly) could vary from 0 to 
30. The test time limit was 15 min. We used this test for two purposes: 
(1) for the validation of the G factor for students from gifted classes, 
which initially is determined by the ministry of education in the 3rd 
grade using IQ tests, and (2) for inclusion of students from regular 
classes in the G group, since when the classes are formed in the second 
grade students are allowed but not obliged to study in gifted classes. 
Thus, there is a possibility that G students can be found in classes that 
are not denoted as classes for gifted students. Raven scores of higher 
than 27 served as a criterion for students ’ inclusion in the G group. After 
the sampling procedure, students were divided into four experimental 
groups designed with varying combinations of the EM and G factors (see 
Table 1): 
≡G–EM group (N 25; 20 males, 5 females): Students who are iden-
tified as generally gifted and excelling in mathematics.  
≡G–NEM group (N 23; 22 males, 1 female): Students who are 
identified as generally gifted but do not excel in mathematics. Table 1 
