All participants were paid volunteers and were native speakers of 
Hebrew, right-handed, with no history of learning disabilities and/or 
neurological disorders, and who had normal or corrected to normal 
vision. All participants and their parents signed an informed consent 
form. The study received the approval of the Helsinki Committee 
(Rambam Medical Center), the Israel Ministry of Education, and the 
Ethics Committee of the University of Haifa. 
2.2. Materials and procedure 
A computerized test with 60 trials was designed using E-Prime 
software (Schneider et al., 2002 ). The test required participants to 
translate between graphical (depicted in stage 1; S1) and symbolic 
(depicted in stage 2; S2) representations of functions (Fig. 1). 30 of the 
60 trials contained a correct answer, while the other 30 trials contained 
an incorrect answer. The task design was based on the 4-strategies 
theory of problem-solving process identified by Polya (1973) : under -
standing the problem, devising a plan, carrying out the plan, and looking 
back. The design of each trial included two stages: S1 – problem con-
dition – corresponding to understanding the problem and devising a 
plan, and S2 – suggested answer – corresponding to Polya ’s looking back 
strategy. Carrying out a plan could be performed either at S1 or S2 
(Waisman et al., 2014 ) 
All trials were presented visually at the center of the computer 
screen, in black characters on a white background (Fig. 1). Participants 
received a graph of a mathematical function shown for 2000 ms fol-
lowed by an equation. They had to determine whether the graph and the 
equation represented the same function by pressing the button “3” 
(correct) or “1” (incorrect) according to their decision. The equation 
remained visible until the participant responded or for a maximum of 
5000 ms. The test was proved to be reliable with Cronbach ’s alpha of 
.859. 
2.2.1. EEG recording 
We continuously recorded the electroencephalogram (EEG) using a 
64-channel BioSemi ActiveTwo system (BioSemi, Amsterdam, The 
Netherlands) and ActiveView recording software. Pin-type electrodes 
were mounted on a customized Biosemi head-cap arranged according to 
the extended 10–20 system. Two flat electrodes were placed on the sides 
of the eyes to monitor horizontal eye movement. A third flat electrode 
was placed underneath the left eye to monitor vertical eye movement 
and blinks. During the session, electrode offsets were kept below 50 μV. 
EEG signals were amplified and digitized with a 24-bit AD converter 
with a sampling frequency of 2048 Hz and a low-pass filter at 100 Hz. 2.3. Data analysis 
2.3.1. Behavioral data 
Analyses were applied to accuracy (Acc) and reaction time for cor-
rect responses (RTc). Acc was determined by the percentage of partici -
pants ’ correct responses to all 60 trials on the test. RTc was calculated as 
the mean time spent for verification of an answer (stage S2) in all 
correctly solved trials. We analyzed differences in Acc and RTc using 
analysis of variance (ANOVA) for G (gifted vs. non-gifted) and EM 
(excelling vs. non-excelling in mathematics) as between-subject factors. 
2.3.2. EEG data 
EEG data were preprocessed offline using the Brain Vision Analyzer 
software (Brain Products). First, EEG data were bandpass-filtered be-
tween 0.53 and 30 Hz (zero-phase) and referenced to the common 
average of all electrodes. We divided the continuous EEG data into short 
non-overlapping epochs of 400 ms duration for the purpose of removing 
artifacts. We discarded all epochs containing signals exceeding ±80 μV 
on any channel. Ocular artifacts were corrected using a regression-based 
approach (Gratton et al., 1983 ). Finally, EEG data were downsampled to 
256 Hz. Using the preprocessed data, we computed ERD/ERS separately 
for two frequency bands (theta: 4–7 Hz; higher alpha: 10–12 Hz) during 
the S1 phase (presentation of the graph) and during the S2 phase (pre-
sentation of the equation). We used the median of the 500 ms fixation 
period as baseline R, and the median of the presentation time window as 
activity A to compute ERD∕ERS␀A
R␀1)
⋅100% 
In this calculation, we used only trials with correct responses and 
reaction times of at least 600 ms, grouped by trial type (there were 30 
trials with a correct answer and 30 trials with an incorrect answer). We 
selected the 600 ms cutoff to exclude trials with unusually short 
response times, since these likely do not represent valid responses. 
Furthermore, since trial duration is inversely proportional to the lowest 
frequency that can be analyzed, we selected this threshold to ensure that 
we could still compute theta band ERD/ERS. Afterwards, we averaged 
the channel data into the following nine regions of interest:  
1. Anterior left: AF7, AF3, F7, F5, F3  
2. Anterior middle: F1, FZ, AFZ, F2  
3. Anterior right: AF4, AF8, F4, F6, F8  
4. Central left: FT7, FC5, FC3, C3, C5, TP7, CP5, CP3  
5. Central middle: FC1, C1, CP1, FCZ, CZ, CPZ, FC2, C2, CP2  
6. Central right: FC4, FC6, FT8, C4, C6, CP6, CP4, TP8  
7. Posterior left: P3, P5, P7, PO7, PO3, O1  
8. Posterior middle: P1, PZ, P2, OZ, POZ  
9. Posterior right: P4, P6, P8, PO8, PO4, O2 
The regions 1 to 9 are grouped into two factors, caudality (anterior, 
central, posterior) and laterality (left, middle, right), in subsequent 
analyses. 
Repeated measures ANOVAs were computed for the theta and alpha 
frequency band separately, taking G (gifted vs. non-gifted) and EM 
(excelling vs. non-excelling) as between-subjects factors and Caudality 
(anterior, central and posterior) and Laterality (left and right) as within- 
subjects factors. 
For all analyses, p-values were corrected for deviation from sphe-
ricity according to the Greenhouse-Geisser method. Following a signif -
icant interaction, post-hoc tests using the Bonferroni adjustment were 
performed. 
