4.Discussion 
This study aimed at examining the effects of general giftedness and 
mathematical excellence on oscillatory EEG patterns associated with a 
learning-based task requiring translation between different representa -
tions of a function. Following the 2 ×2 design proposed by Leikin and 
Leikin (2009) we examined the effects of G and EM on accuracy and 
reaction times and used ERD/ERS methodology for alpha and theta 
frequency bands. 
We expected that EM students would exhibit higher accuracy and 
shorter reaction times than NEM students since functions are a central 
concept in their school mathematical curriculum (Hypothesis 1A). Our 
hypothesis was confirmed with respect to accuracy, but no significant 
main effect of the EM factor on reaction times was found. This result 
pattern replicates findings reported in Waisman et al. (2014) , who also 
observed a main effect of EM only on accuracy but not on reaction times. 
There are only slight differences in mean values, which may be traced 
back to including female participants in the current study as contrasted 
to a purely male sample in the previous publication. These findings 
indicate that students excelling in mathematics outperform their 
non-excelling peers in the number of correct solutions but not in the 
amount of time needed to verify whether an equation matches a 
graphical function. Ainsworth (1999) contends that fluent translation 
across different representations is an essential characteristic of Table 2 
