6expertise. 
Consistently with the findings of Waisman et al. (2014) , we hy-
pothesized that G students would also show higher accuracy than NG 
students (Hypothesis 1B), which was indeed observed in the present 
data. Similar to the EM factor, this general performance advantage was 
restricted to accuracy. 
However, even though no main effects of EM and G emerged for the 
reaction times, there was a significant interaction of both factors. This 
interaction revealed that within the group of NG students the reaction times were independent of the level of EM. Only in the G students did we 
find faster responses in the EM compared to the NEM students, which is 
in line with Waisman et al. (2014) . This finding extends those by 
Waisman et al. (2014) , who only analyzed main effects, and suggests 
that when students possess a high level of general intelligence, their 
learning-related mathematical excellence has a beneficial impact on 
their speed of response. 
On the neurophysiological level, we hypothesized a pattern of neural 
efficiency (i.e., lower alpha ERD in more able individuals) for the EM 
