7factor (Hypothesis 2). This hypothesis was not supported. At both S1 and 
S2, the EM factor had a significant main effect on alpha ERD in that EM 
students elicited higher ERD than NEM students. Even though ERPs 
cannot be directly compared with alpha ERD, it can be argued that this 
unexpected result resembles that of Waisman et al. (2014) who found 
that at S1 EM students had larger late ERP amplitudes as compared to 
NEM students. 
At S1, a significant interaction of G factor with EM factor was found. 
G-EM students showed significantly higher alpha ERD as compared to G- 
NEM students while NG-EM and NG-NEM elicited similar ERD. The in-
teractions of Laterality with G and EM factors and Caudality with G and 
EM factors revealed that this result pattern was quite representative for 
different regions. Specifically, the interaction between G and EM factors 
was similar in the central and posterior sites and in the left and middle 
sites. 
The alpha ERD results in S1 (given in Fig. 3a) appear to be similar to 
the interaction on reaction times (shown in Fig. 2b) but in the opposite 
direction. While lower reaction times reflect higher performance, higher 
alpha ERD (i.e., more negative values) is indicative of higher and, thus, 
less efficient brain activation. Those students with the best performance 
overall – the G-EM students – displayed the highest level of brain ac-
tivity, while those with the worst performance – the NG-NEM students – 
showed a comparably low level of activation. In addition, within the NG 
students EM did not have an effect, whereas in the G students EM was 
associated with higher upper alpha ERD, the opposite of what we ex-
pected based on the neural efficiency phenomenon. 
One possible explanation for the absence of neural efficiency in EM 
students is the learning-based nature of the administered task, i.e., the 
fact that it relies strongly on previously acquired knowledge. Neuro -
imaging studies on domain-specific competencies or expertise have re-
ported that higher competencies or expertise are often related to higher 
instead of lower levels of brain activation (e.g., Kelly and Garavan, 
2005). These have been attributed either to a larger reliance on 
task-related brain regions or the application of more sophisticated 
strategies in problem-solving. The higher activation in the EM students 
of the present sample (compared to their NEM peers) may be indicative 
of these processes. Unfortunately, due to a lack of EEG studies on the 
neurophysiological correlates of processes involved in solving the 
function task, no conclusion can be drawn as to whether they only 
differed in the amount of activation in task-related regions or also in 
regions associated with problem-solving strategies. 
A related explanation considers the distinction between tasks 
focusing on short- or working-memory, on the one hand, and long-term 
memory, on the other hand. As elaborated in Neubauer and Fink (2009), 
positive relationships between alpha ERD and intelligence (i.e., con-
tradicting the neural efficiency hypothesis) have been observed in tasks 
that require access to (semantic) long-term memory, indicating that “the 
involvement of LTM [long-term memory] demands could be a possible 
moderator variable in the brain-IQ relationship” (p. 1015). Although 
there is not yet clear evidence for this moderating variable, the findings 
of the present study add to this notion in that the successful solution of 
the function problems is strongly dependent on the students’ prior 
knowledge stored in long-term memory. 
Another explanation is linked to the moderating influence of task 
complexity and difficulty (Neubauer and Fink, 2009). That is, neural 
efficiency mainly arises when individuals are faced with tasks of low to 
moderate complexity/difficulty, such as semantic letter matching 
(Neubauer et al., 1999) or easy intelligence problems (Doppelmayr 
et al., 2005a,b). However, when the task complexity or difficulty is high, 
more intelligent individuals seem to devote more cortical resources as 
compared to less intelligent individuals, and thus exhibit higher brain 
activation (Dunst et al., 2014; Nussbaumer et al., 2015). In other words, 
the negative association between intelligence and brain activation level 
arises only for tasks that do not place particularly high demands on the 
participants. The function task administered in the present study can be 
regarded as a task with high demands. Learning functions is part of the algebra curriculum, and algebra has long been assumed to be a more 
complex domain of mathematics than, for instance, arithmetic (Booth, 
1988; Eisenberg, 2002; Lee et al., 2017). In addition, translation be-
tween representations is thought to be difficult for learners (Adu-Gyamfi 
et al., 2017; Ainsworth, 1999; Janvier, 1987; Keig and Rubba, 1993). 
Thus, our findings for the higher ERDs in the upper alpha band in G-EM 
(compared to NG-NEM) students may reflect a larger amount of invested 
resources to solve the complex task accurately as fast quickly as possible. 
A limitation of this explanation, however, can be seen in the comparably 
high levels of accuracies (group averages between 71.4 and 82.6%), 
indicating that even though the task demands are complex, the task 
difficulty may not be very high. This raises the question of the distinctive 
effects of task complexity (in terms of processing demands) and task 
difficulty (in terms of solution rate) on neural efficiency, which appears 
to be a promising avenue for future research. 
An additional possible explanation for the lack of neural efficiency 
associated with the EM factor at S1 is linked to the visual (graphical) 
representation in which functions were depicted for students. A recent 
study demonstrated that visual abilities do not predict mathematical 
giftedness, with mathematical giftedness defined as a combination of G 
and EM as in the G-EM group (Paz-Baruch et al., 2022). It could be 
speculated that G-EM students proceed immediately to symbolic repre -
sentation at S1 without waiting until S2 due to their inclination to work 
with symbolic representations. This assumption is also in line with 
Clements (1984) who showed that mathematically gifted individuals are 
prone to deal with symbolic representations. On the other hand, since 
G-EM students showed significantly higher alpha ERD than the other 
three groups, we can assume that the latter groups did not translate the 
graphical representation to a symbolic representation at S1 but rather 
verified the correctness of the symbolic representation at S2. 
In addition to the alpha band, we exploratively analyzed potential 
effects of G and EM on the theta frequency band, as this band turned out 
to be sensitive to mathematical problem-solving processes in previous 
EEG studies (De Smedt et al., 2009; Grabner and De Smedt, 2011; 
Grabner et al., 2022). Neither in S1 nor in S2 were any effects of G and 
EM observed in this frequency. Even though this is in line with the re-
sults reported by Artemenko et al. (2019), who administered an arith-
metic task and failed to find a moderating effect of mathematical 
competence on theta (as well as alpha) ERD/ERS, effects of EM would 
have been plausible. Specifically, since higher theta ERS was found to be 
associated with a larger reliance on domain-specific knowledge (arith -
metic facts) during problem solving, EM students (possessing a larger 
knowledge base to draw on) could have displayed higher theta ERS than 
NEM students. The lack of this effect suggests that the automatic fact 
retrieval processes in arithmetic that are related to theta ERS cannot be 
generalized to the retrieval of more complex (less factual and more 
conceptual) mathematical knowledge needed to solve mathematical 
function tasks. 
Taken together, the present study is the first ERD/ERS study to 
investigate the neural correlates of the factors EM and G while solving a 
complex mathematical task representative of the high school curricu -
lum. We found that both EM and G positively affected task accuracy and 
that both factors interacted with each other in the speed of problem- 
solving. The level of brain activation was strongly dependent on stu-
dents’ EM in that students with higher mathematical excellence dis-
played stronger brain activation in both stages of solving function 
problems. At the first stage of problem-solving, EM had an impact on 
brain activity primarily among the G students. The pattern of results was 
opposite to the neural efficiency hypothesis, possibly due to the char-
acteristics of the function task (complex task drawing on domain- 
specific knowledge). 
