RESEARCH ARTICLE
Alpha and theta oscillations in mental addition for high and low 
performers
Sumyah Alnajashi1 
Received: 18 April 2020 / Accepted: 19 May 2021 / Published online: 2 June 2021 
© Marta Olivetti Belardinelli and Springer-Verlag GmbH Germany, part of Springer Nature 2021
Abstract
While many contemporary studies aim to explore the sources of notable individual differences in arithmetic skills, this study 
specifically aims to highlight cognitive differences between high and low math performers. Thirty-six undergraduate female 
students who were identified as either high or low math performers, according to an arithmetic fluency test, were recruited. 
In the main experiment, EEG recordings were taken, while the participants performed a mental addition task. The mental 
addition problems were classified as either easy or difficult, and were presented to participants in several forms. The results 
indicated that problem difficulty increases the gap in accuracy attainment between high and low math performers. Addition-
ally, high performers displayed larger alpha power during mental arithmetic in P7, corresponding to the left parietal lobe. 
This indicated that combining behavioral and neural data can improve our understanding of the differences between high 
and low math performers. Interpretations and implications are discussed.
Keywords Brain oscillation · Math abilities · Mental arithmetic · Solving strategy · Visuospatial working memory
Introduction
Math abilities are an essential element of IQ, predicting aca-
demic and professional achievement (see Neisser et al. 1996 
for a review). Research in numerical cognition is persistent 
in discovering the factors related to arithmetic skills, form-
ing basic math ability (Imbo and LeFevre 2009; 2010; Lee 
and Kang 2002; Logie et al. 1994; Otsuka and Osaka, 2015), 
and underlying neural correlated activities (Artemenko et al. 
2018; De Smedt et al. 2009; Grabner et al. 2007; 2009; 
Menon et al. 2000b; Micheloyannis et al. 2005; Proverbio 
and Carminati 2019).
Based on an extensive review of literature on math abili-
ties, Dowker (2005) concluded that individual differences 
in arithmetic abilities are largely attributed to flexibility 
and appropriate strategy choices in arithmetic performance. Suitable strategies vary according to task demands (Camp-
bell and Xue 2001; Otsuka and Osaka 2015) and other cog-
nitive abilities (Campbell and Xue 2001 ; Imbo and LeFevre 
2009; 2010; Otsuka and Osaka 2015). Several studies have 
aimed to examine the role of solving strategies (Camp-
bell and Xue 2001; Cragg et al. 2017; Hubber et al. 2013; 
Rosenberg-Lee et al. 2009; Tschentscher and Hauk 2014) 
and working memory components (Cavdaroglu and Knops 
2015; Clearman et al. 2017; Imbo and LeFevre 2010; Lee 
and Kang 2002; Logie et al. 1994; Otsuka and Osaka 2015; 
Seitz and Schumann-Hengsteler 2000) in variant settings 
of mental arithmetic. This study follows this approach by 
examining the differences between high and low math per -
formers in different settings of mental addition, by compar -
ing performance accuracy and oscillatory brain activities 
during mental addition.
Theoretical background
Early studies in neuroimaging have found an increase in 
activities in the left prefrontal, frontal, and specific pari-
etal regions, when performing arithmetic tasks (Micheloy -
annis et al. 2005 ; Rivera et al. 2005 ; Roland and Friberg 
1985; Rueckert et al. 1996; Stanescu-Cosson et al. 2000). Handling editor: Katsumi Watanabe (Waseda University); 
Reviewers: Christina Artemenko (University of Tübingen) and a 
second researcher who prefers to remain anonymous.
 * Sumyah Alnajashi 
 salnajashi@ksu.edu.sa
1 Department of Psychology, King Saud University, PO 
Box 85500, Riyadh 11691, Saudi Arabia 610 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626
1 3
The role of the parietal circuits includes general domain 
abilities, such as retrieving verbal information in the left 
angular region, attention in the posterior superior parietal 
region, and perceiving mental number representation in the 
intraparietal region (Dehaene et al. 2003). Some activities 
in the frontal lobe have been found to correspond to working 
memory function (Micheloyannis et al. 2005; Sammer et al. 
2007). Furthermore, the prefrontal region within the fron-
tal area has been found to be largely responsible for activi-
ties related to planning, imagination, and strategy selection 
organisation (Roland and Friberg 1985; Taillan et al. 2015).
Some studies show that an increase of arithmetic skills 
leads to a shift from prefrontal and more general frontal acti-
vation to activation in two areas in the parietal region: the 
right intraparietal sulcus and left angular gyrus. This reflects 
the shift from use of general cognitive abilities, including 
planning, selecting strategies, and working memory, which 
are related to the frontal areas, to representation of num -
bers during calculation and arithmetic fact retrieval. Rep -
resentation of numbers during calculation is related to the 
right intraparietal sulcus whereas arithmetic fact retrieval is 
related to the left angular gyrus (Delazer et al. 2005; Rivera 
et al. 2005).
Studies further specified the roles of certain parietal 
regions and revealed another shift within the parietal lobe 
from intraparietal sulcus to angular gyrus. Here, the shift 
occurs to be from representation and calculation of numbers 
to mere retrieval of arithmetic facts (Delazer et al. 2005; 
Prado et al. 2013).
However, conflicting results were found by methods of 
comparing studies investigating higher and lower math 
performers, showing inconsistencies in finding an increase 
of activity in angular gyrus during arithmetic performance 
in higher and in lower math performers. Grabner and col-
leagues (2007) showed larger angular gyrus activity in 
parietal area in higher math performers than that in lower 
performers, and suggested that this reflects different levels 
of dependence on retrieval strategies in mental arithmetic 
(Grabner et al. 2007). Menon and colleagues (2000a) found 
a different pattern of activation, whereby activities in the 
angular gyrus were lower during arithmetic performance in 
higher than in lower math performers. It should be noted that 
the participants in Menon’s study were all high performers, 
who were divided based on the experimental arithmetic task 
into perfect (100% correct answers) and imperfect (above 
90% correct answers). Additionally, the arithmetic tasks 
involved three operant addition and subtraction problems 
to encourage participants to engage in procedural strategies 
(e. g., deconstructing problems into smaller ones), rather 
than using retrieval strategies to find answers. Grabner and 
colleagues used single and double-digit multiplication prob-
lems, which are more likely to depend on answer retrieval, 
and the participants were intermediate in their math abilities (i.e., they were chosen based on a screening test from around 
the midpoint of normal distribution). This discrepancy 
between studies emphasizes the importance of consider -
ing task demands when comparing arithmetic accuracy and 
adopting strategies along with brain activities in high and 
low math performance.
In electrophysiological studies of mental arithmetic abili-
ties, studies either focus on synchrony of brain oscillation, 
or their power when performing mental arithmetic (Arte-
menko et al. 2018; De Smedt et al. 2009; Proverbio and 
Carminati 2019). Synchrony of brain oscillation reflects 
coherence between brain regions while EEG power reflects 
the amount of activity in each frequency band. These terms 
are linked, as alpha synchronization is related to the inhibi-
tion and reduction of cortical activities, while the absence 
of alpha synchronization (alpha desynchronization) indicates 
cortical arousal (an increase in wave amplitude correspond-
ing to the high demands of cognitive processes). In contrast, 
theta synchronization is a sign of cortical arousal, and the 
terms theta synchronization and theta power are positively 
related (Klimesch 1999; for an illustration see Soltanlou 
et al. 2019).
De Smedt and colleagues (2009) compared synchrony of 
alpha and theta when performing simple and complex addi -
tion and subtraction tasks. Simple tasks include problems 
without carrying or borrowing numbers, and the revealed 
answer is a small number, less than 10. Complex problems, 
in contrast, have integers with two digits and the answers 
are larger than 10, which can involve carrying or borrowing 
numbers. The results showed alpha desynchronization when 
participants solved complex problems, and theta synchroni-
sation when participants solved simple problems. Neverthe-
less, synchrony of brain oscillation was not consistent across 
EEG studies of mental arithmetic. A study comparing under -
graduate Chinese students who had demonstrated average 
performance in math achievement tests, with those desig-
nated as gifted students (i.e., had a high IQ, and had won an 
award in math), showed that theta synchronisation increases 
in the prefrontal lobe only when gifted undergraduates work 
on a verbal deductive reasoning task (Zhang et al. 2015).
Other studies comparing high and low math performers 
showed that brain activities when performing simple and 
complex tasks can vary according to participants’ profi-
ciency. Artemenko and colleagues (2018) compared perfor -
mance of high and low performers on simple addition and 
subtraction, where the problems are solved with no carry -
ing or borrowing, and complex problems, with carrying or 
borrowing. Their results showed that low performers were 
slower when responding to complex problems compared to 
when responding to simple problems, but their neural activi-
ties were not different between simple and complex prob-
lems. In contrast, high performers showed a larger increase 
in brain activities in the frontal region when solving complex  611 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626 
1 3
problems’) compared to with simple problems. They argued 
that high performers need to recruit additional brain regions 
to solve complex problems while low performers recruited 
large brain activities for both simple and complex problems. 
This indicates that low performers, compared to high per -
formers, are less efficient in performing both simple and 
complex tasks.
Proverbio and Carminati (2019) argued, based on similar 
findings, that high performers were more efficient in pro-
cessing mental arithmetic on behavioral and neural levels. 
They revealed larger activation in the prefrontal area for high 
performers accomplishing complex tasks, compared to when 
completing simple problems. In contrast, low performers 
showed the same level of increase in EEG activities with 
both simple, medium, and complex problems. As neural 
correlates are relatively unspecified, research on behavioral 
performance in arithmetic, and testing performance of high 
and low performers under several task demands, would fur -
ther disentangle the complex mechanisms related to math 
performance.
Explanations of brain activities during mental arithme-
tic are partially imported from working memory studies. 
Previous studies show that alpha power decreases with the 
increase of working memory load in several brain regions, 
including the prefrontal, frontocentral and posterior pari-
etal regions (Borghini et al. 2014; Foxe and Snyder 2011; 
Klimesch 1999; Micheloyannis et al. 2005). In contrast, 
theta power increases with both working memory load and 
fact retrieval (Borghini et al. 2014; Klimesch et al. 2005; 
Raghavachari et al. 2006; Sammer et al. 2007). An increase 
in theta power spreads across the brain cortex, and is unre-
lated to the specific process occurring; it arises when cog-
nitive processing takes place, regardless of which task is 
performed (Sammer et al. 2007). Alternatively, the spread of 
theta oscillations can be explained by the various strategies 
used to solve mental arithmetic tasks. Micheloyannis and 
colleagues (2005) showed the spread of brain activities when 
solving multi-digit multiplication tasks and explained their 
findings by suggesting the necessity of using a sequence 
of strategies to solve arithmetic problems. Moreover, using 
either retrieval or procedural strategies to perform mental 
arithmetic is related to specific parietal lobe regions (Grab-
ner et al. 2009). This emphasises the importance of com-
bining several parameters in one study to confirm previous 
findings on behavioral performance in mental arithmetic and 
its neural basis.
A precaution that should be taken when formulating any 
hypotheses regarding neural bases of mental arithmetic 
is that previous findings of the neural bases of arithmetic 
performance come either from fMRI studies (Ansari et al. 
2011; Menon et al. 2000b; Prado et al. 2011) that rely on 
BOLD signals, or from EEG studies that rely on event-
related or brain oscillatory components (De Smedt et al. 2009; Micheloyannis et al. 2005; Proverbio and Carminati 
2019). These are differently related to behavioral perfor -
mance (Winterer et al. 2007). Hence, it is not useful for the 
current study to adopt assumptions for EEG activities based 
solely on the results of fMRI studies.
Previous studies have employed several task demands to 
explore a participant’s use or choice of solving strategies 
(Campbell and Xue 2001; Cragg et al. 2017; Hubber et al. 
2013; Sidney et al. 2018). A common paradigm is the dual 
task paradigm, where participants perform mental arith-
metic concurrently with a secondary task (Cavdaroglu and 
Knops 2015; Clearman et al. 2017; Cragg et al. 2017; Imbo 
and LeFevre 2010; Lee and Kang 2002; Logie et al. 1994; 
Otsuka and Osaka 2015 ; Seitz and Schumann-Hengsteler 
2000). The rationale behind this paradigm is to load one 
component of working memory, including the phonologi-
cal loop for verbal information, the visuospatial sketchpad 
for visual and spatial information, and executive control for 
controlling high demanding tasks (Baddeley 2000). If the 
loaded component is essential for mental arithmetic, the par -
ticipant’s performance suffers under that loading condition.
In this intensive work on the role of working memory 
component in simple and complex arithmetic operations, 
few studies focused on the visuospatial working memory 
component (Cavdaroglu and Knops 2015; Clearman et al. 
2017; Cragg et al. 2017; Hubber et al. 2013). The role of 
visuospatial working memory component is controversial, as 
some studies found no interfering effect of visuospatial load-
ing on mental arithmetic (Imbo and Vandierendonck 2007; 
Logie 1994 ), while other studies showed an impairing effect 
(Clearman et al. 2017; Cragg et al. 2017; Imbo and LeFevre 
2010; Lee and Kang 2002). Another debate is related to the 
visuospatial component’s role. Imbo and LeFevre (2010) 
reveal that reliance on visuospatial working memory when 
solving complex arithmetic is moderated by several factors, 
including the performance level and the method of present-
ing the problem (i.e., horizontally or vertically). In their 
study, performance by Chinese adult participants in complex 
subtraction was impaired by visuospatial loading when the 
problems were presented vertically, compared to when they 
were presented horizontally. One plausible explanation by 
Imbo and LeFevre (2010) for this relationship between verti-
cal presentation and visuospatial working memory, is that 
vertical presentation encouraged decomposing the problems 
and numbers into smaller ones, and these procedures ben-
efit from visuospatial working memory (see also Foley et al. 
2016). This links the role of visuospatial working memory 
with how the problems are presented and suggest that the 
method of presentation might engage or exile the visuos-
patial working memory component when solving mental 
arithmetic.
Other findings support a view of equivalent interfering 
effect of visuospatial loading secondary tasks on mental  612 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626
1 3
arithmetic in different settings, denying the moderating role 
of task demands (Cragg et al. 2017). In addition, the role of 
visuospatial working memory in applying procedural strate-
gies to solve mental arithmetic was examined by Hoober and 
colleagues (2013), who compared the effect of a concurrent 
visuospatial secondary task on mental addition performed 
with one of three strategies, namely recall and two other 
procedural strategies: problem decomposition into smaller 
steps, or counting starting from one operant until the answer 
was revealed. Their results reveal the significant role of visu-
ospatial working memory when using procedural strategies 
to solve addition problems. Cragg and colleagues ( 2017 ) 
showed that concurrent working memory tasks, including 
visuospatial working memory, impair mental arithmetic 
performance regardless of used strategies. In this realm, 
exploring the differences between high and low perform-
ers in mental arithmetic in their strategy choice—with or 
without the presence of a secondary visuospatial working 
memory task would clarify part of the argument and is cru-
cial to understanding how high and low math performers 
differ in their mental arithmetic skills.
Overall, previous studies show visuospatial working 
memory to be an important resource in solving complex 
arithmetic problems (Imbo and LeFevre 2010; Zhou et al. 
2006). Additionally, visuospatial working memory is related 
to procedural strategies when performing mental arithmetic 
(Hubber et al. 2013). Furthermore, high and low perform-
ers differ in their flexibility and strategy choice (Dowker 
2005; Otsuka and Osaka 2015). Testing the effect of several 
task demands on participant accuracy and correlated EEG 
activities, including presentation method, loading of visuos-
patial working memory and complexity, and whether these 
changes in task demands have variant effects on higher and 
on lower math performance would be informative. Indeed, 
these implementations can partially attribute differences 
between high and low math performers in mental arithmetic 
to either differences in flexibility in strategy selection or in 
visuospatial working memory resources.
If high performers showed larger variation in strategies 
used, compared to low performers, according to the method 
of presentation, complexity or visuospatial loading, then 
the findings would give further evidence on the importance 
of flexibility in choosing a suitable strategy for a task. If 
low performers also showed flexibility in their use of solv -
ing strategies according to the method of presentation and 
complexity, but showed dampened performance and fixation 
to one strategy or mixed strategies within the same condi-
tion, then the argument would be about the limited working 
memory resources for low performers. If both strategies are 
fixed in all conditions, and visuospatial working memory 
loading dropped performance in all loaded conditions in low 
performers compared to high performers, then it could be 
argued that there would be differences between high and low math performers in both flexibility in choosing strategies and 
sources of working memory.
Aims and expectations
As the study aims to contribute to our understanding of the 
roots of differences between high and low math perform-
ers, it aims to compare accuracy and related alpha and theta 
activities when high and low math performers solve addition 
problems. It further aims to examine the role of visuospatial 
working memory in different task demands (i.e., simple vs. 
complex tasks and horizontal vs. vertical presentation). In 
all the above conditions, it examines to what extent high and 
low math performers depend on recall or procedural strate-
gies during the abovementioned task parameters.
Significant differences between high and low math per -
formers are expected in complex tasks but not in simple 
tasks. This is based on the findings of previous studies, 
where behavioral and neural differences between high and 
low math performers were shown in difficult problems (Pro-
verbio and Carminati 2019). Regarding brain oscillations in 
the frontal (De Smedt et al. 2009; Micheloyannis et al. 2005 ) 
and parietal lobes (De Smedt et al. 2009), a decrease in alpha 
power is expected when solving difficult problems versus 
easy problems. Based on the findings in previous studies, 
changes in oscillation powers are expected to occur in these 
regions, which show neural changes in activities related to 
difficult mental arithmetic in these regions (Stanescu-Cosson 
et al. 2000; Menonet al. 2000b). Additionally, the decrease 
in frontal lobe alpha power is expected to be larger for high 
math performers in difficult arithmetic problems than for low 
math performers. This is derived from the findings that alpha 
power decrease is related to visual attention (Klimesch 1999) 
and central executives (Sauseng et al. 2005), which function 
more in high performers (Dowker 2005). In contrast, build-
ing expectations for whether theta power differs between 
high and low math performers during mental arithmetic is 
difficult because theta power increase is related to work -
ing memory loading (Klimesch 1999; Klimesch et al. 2005; 
Raghavachari et al. 2006; Sammer et al. 2007). It is unclear 
whether low performers fail to recruit working memory 
resources to calculate difficult problems, or whether they 
load their working memory like high performers do but fail 
because they lack other cognitive resources.
No clear predictions can be made relating to the role of 
visuospatial working memory and task demands. Loading on 
visuospatial working memory has a negative effect on com-
plex arithmetic on participants from largely variant cultures 
(Western and Canadian) (Clearman et al. 2017; Cragg et al. 
2017; Imbo and LeFevre 2010). Only Chinese participants 
showed a selective effect of visuospatial load on presenta-
tion method, showing the interference of vertically presented  613 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626 
1 3
subtraction problems (Imbo and LeFevre 2010). It is hard to 
build assumptions based on speculations about the role of 
visuospatial working memory in mental arithmetic, involv -
ing imagery of calculus or any form of visual representation 
in mental sketchpad (Dehaene 1992). Visuospatial working 
memory is either reserved or disturbed when the problem is 
presented vertically to the participants. Finally, we expected 
approximately similar dependence levels on recall or proce-
dural strategies in several conditions in both high and low 
math performers. This is based on studies showing common 
procedural strategies for complex problems (De Smedt et al. 
2009; Zhou et al. 2006).
Method
Participants
Eighteen participants (mean age of 21 years and 3 months 
with a standard deviation of one year and 3 months; one left-
handed) were assigned as high math performers and eighteen 
(mean age of 20 years and 8 months and a standard deviation 
of one year and 11 months; 2 left-handed) were assigned as 
low math performers. The participants widely varied in their 
majors. For the high performers, 13 participants were in the 
medicine and natural science departments, 2 in management, 
2 in media and one in psychology. For the low performers, 6 
participants were in the medicine and natural science depart-
ments, 4 in art and literature, 3 in education, 3 in law, one 
in management and one in sport sciences. Participants were 
assigned in the high or low math performer groups based 
on a screening test for arithmetic abilities, using a sample 
of 49 undergraduate female students, aged 18–25 years 
(mean = 21, standard deviation = 1.6) from King Saud Uni-
versity, recruited via the convenient sampling method. All 
participants had normal or corrected-to-normal vision with 
no neurological or sensory disability affecting their task abil -
ity. They signed a consent form prior to the experiment and 
did not receive a reward. The average screening test score 
was 53.081, with a standard deviation of 18.987. The eight-
een participants from each extreme end were assigned as 
high and low math performers. High math performers scored 
54 or above and low math performers scored 45 and below.
Materials
Screening test of arithmetic abilities
This test was a paper-based task of four sections. Each 
section included one basic arithmetic task type (addition, 
subtraction, multiplication, and division). The internal con-
sistency, validity and reliability of the test were verified 
on the current study sample. The correlations between the subsections and the total score ranged between 0.813 and 
0.91, p < 0.001, and reliability revealed Cronbach’s alpha 
of 0.968. Each section was presented in a single page and 
included 42 problems. The task time was limited to two 
minutes for each section (see Online Resource 1 for the 
detailed description of the task and the included arithmetic 
problems).
Demography questionnaire
At the beginning of the arithmetic abilities screening test, 
the participants were asked about their age and major. They 
were also asked what and when was the last course they 
studied that involved considerable amount of arithmetic. 
They were also asked how much of mental arithmetic they 
use on a daily basis.
Updating task
The updating task was used to assess the participants’ abil-
ity to actively remove outdated specific information from 
working memory and substitute it with new incoming infor -
mation (Ecker et al. 2010; 2014; Kessler and Meiran 2008; 
Kessler and Oberauer 2014). The current updating task was 
a computer-based task, following the design of Sidney and 
colleagues (2018), where participants were presented with a 
series of letters (12 sequences in total). The sequence length 
varied between 7 and 12 letters per sequence. Each letter was 
presented for 1500 ms. The task was to recall the last three 
letters of each sequence. For example, when a sequence like 
‘SYMVRKA’ appears, participants had to recall the letters 
‘RKA’. Participants viewed 12 sequences. The first sequence 
was the same for all participants, with the remaining 11 
sequences randomized. The task was corrected by giving 
one score to each correct item, excluding the first sequence 
(maximum = 33).
The n‑Back task
This computer-based task followed Kaladous and col-
leagues’ design (2015), with minor response method modi-
fications. It had three levels of difficulty (1-back, 2-back, 
and 3-back). Each level included 40 digits presented sequen-
tially, at the rate of 2,000 ms per stimulus. In the one-back 
condition, participants had to press the ‘ENTER’ button if 
the digit—always a single digit—was the same as the previ-
ously presented digits. In the two and three digits, partici-
pants had to press ‘ENTER’ button when the presented dig-
its were presented earlier with a lag of two or three positions, 
respectively. The n-back task is used to measure a combina-
tion of executive functions (Gajewski et al. 2018 ), including 
maintenance, updating, inhibiting irrelevant information and 
matching maintained and new items to initiate a response  614 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626
1 3
(Rac-Lubashevsky and Kessler 2016). The dependent vari-
able was calculated by the d prime equation: d  = z(h)–z(f). 
Z(p) is the reversed cumulative probability function of 
normal distribution, h is the hits and f is the false alarms 
(Kaladous et al. 2015).
Digit span
This is a subtest in Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale 
(WAIS-I) for adults (Malika 1996). The participants were 
required to listen to a series of digits and recall the digits 
in normal order in the first phase of the test and in reverse 
order in the second phase of the test. The number of items 
in a series was increased across trials, and participants 
were stopped after failing to recall the digits in order in 
two consecutive trials at one level. The serial digit recall 
assesses auditory verbal short-term memory (STM) span, 
and inversed recall was assumed to represent the auditory 
verbal working memory (WM) span.
Coding
This paper-based test is a subtest in WAIS-I for adults 
(Malika 1996) and required participants to copy symbols 
assigned to Arabic digits in several lines. It assesses visu-
ospatial short-term memory. The participants were given 
60 s instead of 90 s for this task. The score relied on how 
many symbols were correctly copied in the right boxes 
(maximum = 67).
Raven’s Progressive Matrices
This well-known paper-based test for nonverbal reasoning 
was administered individually. The version used was vali-
dated on the Arabic sample by Ali ( 2013 ) and included 36 
matrices. The raw score reflected the number of correctly 
solved matrices.
Right handedness questionnaire
This questionnaire was assembled by Abdul-Kawi (2004) 
and included 20 items representing daily activities. Partici-
pants were required to rate on a 5-point rating scale how 
much they depended on their right hand for each of the 
activity.
The mental addition task
A total of 120 addition problems, 60 easy and 60 difficult, 
were included in the computer-based mental arithmetic task. 
Generating the problems followed the rules by Tschentscher 
and Hauk (2015). Easy problems included two single-digit 
integers, while difficult problems included two two-digit integers. The same number of even and odd operants were 
used. The number of problems involving carrying were con-
trolled in both conditions. Zero and one were never used in 
integer units, and neat problems, which have the same units 
for both operants, were avoided. Restrictions were added so 
that no total exceeds 100, and the difficulty for all condi -
tions was controlled by controlling the size of totals. As the 
task was designed to require participants to choose the right 
answer from two alternatives, one distracter was generated 
for the solution to each problem. Solutions and distracters 
were between 1 and 10 units apart (see Online Resource 2 
for the addition problems).
Half of the problems were presented horizontally and half 
vertically. Half of the problems were interleaved between 
two (5 × 5) visual matrices, where participants had to indi-
cate whether they resembled the first matrix before choosing 
the right arithmetic problem total. This visuospatial loading 
task was taken from Cavdaroglu and Knops (2015), with 
presentation and number of highlighted square modifica-
tions. The matrices (5 × 5 cm) were drawn as white squares 
with green borders. Three squares from each visual matrix 
were highlighted with red. The location of the red squares 
was randomly generated for all target matrices. For the test 
matrices, in which the participants must indicate whether 
they resemble the target matrices or not, half of the test 
matrices were the same as targets and half were different.
Brain‑computer interface (BCI) for EEG recording
The EPOC  + Emotiv BCI is a 16-channel BCI, attached to 
a computer via Bluetooth. This device records the EEG sig-
nals for educational and research purposes. The EEG signals 
were obtained from the frontal, temporal, occipital regions 
and parts of the parietal regions of the brain. It included 16 
sensors, with two references above the ears, in CMS and 
DRL. The electrodes were named according to their loca-
tions, as adopted by the 10–20 electrode system (Jasper 
1958): AF3, F7, F3, FC5, T7, P7, O1, O2, P8, T8, FC6, F4, 
F8, and AF4. The sensors at the end of the electrodes were 
covered with disposable felt pads designed to be soaked 
with saline before recording and disposed after each use. 
This noninvasive device records and sends the EEG to the 
computer at the rate of 128 samples per second. The EEG 
signals were amplified via EPOC + Emotiv electrodes and 
transferred to the EmotivPro software for recording and data 
processing (Emotiv 2019).
Design and procedures
The design used was a 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 mixed design, with level 
of math performance (high vs. low math performers) as a 
between-group variable. Presentation method (horizontal 
vs. vertical), difficulty (easy vs. difficult) and visuospatial  615 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626 
1 3
loading (no load vs. visuospatial load) were within-group 
variables. The dependent variables were mental addition 
task accuracy, selected solving strategies and alpha and 
theta activities in mental addition. Measures of STM and 
WM (updating, n-back, digit span and coding) and Raven’s 
colored progressive matrices, assessing fluid intelligence, 
were implemented as controlling variables.
The experiment involved three sessions. In the first ses-
sion, participants completed the screening test for arithme-
tic abilities and the demographic questionnaire. This ses-
sion lasted around 12 min. Following the administration of 
screening test, 36 participants were chosen and classified as 
high and low math performers. These 36 participants were 
asked to attend the second and third sessions of the study.
The second session took place within one to four weeks 
of the first session and lasted approximately 45 min. The 
session included six tasks: updating, n-back, digit span, 
coding, Raven’s colored progressive matrices and the right 
handedness questionnaire. The tests were performed in an 
individual testing room in a quiet area of the psychology 
building, which has good lighting conditions and has no 
windows. All participants performed the tasks in the same 
order. Each participant first performed the computer-based 
updating task, then the n-back task on a Dell laptop running 
Windows 10 with a 15-inch screen and 1,360 × 768 resolu-
tion. The tasks ran on e-prime software (v2; Psychology 
Software Tools, Inc., 2016) and all stimuli were presented 
in 24 point white font on a black background. Before the 
n-back task, each participant was given a short practice trial 
including up to five items to practice the three conditions. 
After the computer-based tasks, participants performed the 
digit span test, where the experimenter gave the instructions 
and an example trial before each of the serial and reverse 
recall tasks. The experimenter read the participants the digits 
at the rate of one digit per second. This was followed by the 
coding test, where the participants were given 8 examples 
with 60 s to completely copy the codes for the aligned digits. 
Ultimately, the participants performed the Raven’s colored 
progressive matrices test with a time limit of 15 min. Finally, 
the participants were asked to complete the righthanded-
ness questionnaire. The participants could take 5-min breaks 
whenever they desired.
The third session took place two to five weeks after 
the second session and lasted up to 60 min. This session 
included the EEG recording while simultaneously per -
forming the computer-based arithmetic task. Participants 
were seated 60 cm from the laptop screen. At the begin-
ning of this session, each participant was given eight prac-
tice trials to practice the horizontal and vertical arithmetic 
tasks with and without visuospatial load. The BCI headset 
was connected with EmotivPro software (Emotiv 2019) on 
a Dell laptop running Windows 10 with a 15-inch screen 
and a screen resolution of 1,360 × 768. The felt pads were attached to the electrode sensors and put on a participant’s 
head. The time of setting the headset varied between par -
ticipants. When all electrodes were adjusted, the main 
mental addition task started on the e-prime software (v2; 
Psychology Software Tools, Inc., 2016) on the same laptop 
running EmotivPro.
The 120 addition tasks were presented in four blocks 
with 30 problems each. The participant was informed of 
the presentation method and loading conditions at the 
beginning of each block (horizontal with no load, hori -
zontal with load, vertical with no load, and vertical with 
load). The participant initiated each block by pressing the 
spacebar. Each block included 15 easy and 15 difficult 
problems. The easy and difficult problems were presented 
continuously in each block and were not mixed. The order 
of problems was presented differently in a random order 
for each participant, and the order of blocks was controlled 
across participants. Each trial was initiated with a fixation 
cross for 500 ms followed by the addition problem. The 
font was always 28 point white on a black background. 
Each arithmetic task was presented in the centre of the 
screen with an angle view of 4.77 degrees for 5000 ms 
and was followed by two alternative answers, presented 
adjacently on a horizontal line and remaining for 1750 ms 
or until the participant responded by pressing either the 
right or left arrow key. The right answer was presented 
on the right half the time and on the left the other half. 
The time of presentation for the addition task was chosen 
based on a preliminary study, where the addition task was 
performed on 16 female undergraduate students. The RT 
in the preliminary study was (M  = 3547 ms, SD = 1648 ms) 
for difficult problems and (M  = 2385, SD = 1311) for easy 
problems. Considering the average RTs and their standard 
deviations and to decrease the artifacts by finger move-
ment, the time was fixed as 5000 ms, which would be 
enough for both groups to perform the mental arithmetic 
tasks without feeling disappointed because of short avail -
able time. This did not allow for comparing the RTs, but 
it helped in selecting similar time windows for analysis 
of both groups, as will be explained in the results section. 
Each trial was followed by asking the participants to iden-
tify the strategy used to solve the task, either procedural or 
recall. Participants had to identify their adopted strategy 
by pressing the right and left arrow keys. For the visuos-
patial loading task, the 5 × 5 target matrix was presented 
for 2,000 ms before each addition problem. The test matrix 
was presented after a participant selected the answer for 
the arithmetic task and remained for 4000 ms or until the 
participant responded by pressing the right arrow when 
the test matrix was the same as the target or the left arrow 
when it was different. See Fig.  1 for an illustration of the 
mental addition task. Participants were debriefed after the 
experiment. 616 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626
1 3
Results
Behavioral data
Table  1 shows the scores and independent sample t  test 
values for the tests of STM, fluid intelligence, and WM 
span and processes. High performers significantly sur -
passed the low performers in STM span, updating, and 
the 1-back task (see Table  1). Including these variables as 
covariates in the to-be-presented mixed measures ANOVA on the data of the mental addition task did not reveal dif-
ferent results. Thus, they were not included.
The mental addition task
Performance in the mental addition task was scored by 
giving one (1) for each correct response and zero (0) 
for each incorrect response (maximum  = 120). Percent -
ages of correct responses were then calculated. A mixed 
measures ANOVA with level of performance (high vs. 
low performers) as a between group factor and presenta-
tion method (horizontal vs. vertical), loading (no load 
vs. with load), and difficulty (easy vs. difficult) was 
performed to examine said variables’ effects on men-
tal addition accuracy. The test revealed the main effect 
of performance level, F (1, 34) = 46.717,  p < 0.001,  η2
p 
= 0.579, showing the expected advantage among high 
math performers (M  = 90.323, SD = 3.106) over low math 
performers (M  = 75.971, SD = 8.409). It also showed a 
significant effect of difficulty, F (1, 34) = 147.271,  p 
< 0.001,  η2
p = 0.812, where mean performance in easy 
problems (M  = 92.222, SD = 7.4) is significantly higher 
than performance in difficult problems (M  = 74.073, 
SD = 13.768) across all settings and groups. There was 
also a significant interaction between difficulty and level 
of performance, F (1, 34) = 19.325,  p < 0.001,  η2
p = 0.36
2. To explore the significant interaction between perfor -
mance level and difficulty, two paired-sample t  tests com-
pared the effect of performance level on mental addition 
accuracy within each of easy and difficult problems. The 
p value, here and in all multiple comparisons, was cor -
rected using the Bonferroni correction method. There was 
found to be a significant difference between high and low 
performers in the easy problems, t(34) = 3.673, p = 0.003, 
and a significant difference in the difficult problems, 
t(34) = 7.052, p < 0.001. However, the mean of the dif-
