Solving strategies
It was aimed to examine whether high and low perform -
ers used different strategies based on task demands related 
to presentation method, loading of visuospatial memory, 
and task difficulty. Therefore, the number of trials where 
the participant selected the procedural strategies was 
counted for each participant in each condition (maximum 
was 15). Table  2 shows the means of the percentages of 
problems that recruited procedural strategies as well as the 
standard deviations for each condition. A mixed measures 
ANOVA was performed on the number of problems, with 
procedural strategies in each condition as the dependent 
variable, level of performance as a between group vari-
able, and presentation method, loading, and difficulty as 
within group variables. Paired-sample t  tests were used 
to follow up significant interactions. No significant differ -
ence was found between the two groups in terms of perfor -
mance level, F (1, 34)  = 1.686,  p = 0.203. The main effect 
of presentation method was likewise insignificant, F (1, 
34) = 1.178,  p = 0.285.
However, significant main effects were found for both 
loading, F(1, 34) = 37.204,  p < 0.001, η2p = 0.522, and dif-
ficulty, F(1, 34)  = 83.807,  p < 0.001, η2p = 0.711, showing 
a greater use of procedural strategies for non-loading con -
ditions and for difficult problems. There was a significant 
interaction between presentation method and level of per -
formance, F(1, 34) = 4.616,  p = 0.039, η2p = 0.120. High 
performers showed a greater use of procedural strategies in vertically than in horizontally presented problems, 
t(17) = 2.455, p = 0.025, while low performers showed a 
similar average use of procedural strategies in both verti-
cally and horizontally presented problems, t (17) = 0.706, 
p = 0.489. Additionally, a significant interaction was 
found between difficulty and level of performance, F (1, 
34) = 5.035,  p = 0.031, η2
p = 0.129. Low performers showed 
a significantly greater use of procedural strategies for easy 
problems (M  = 23.222, SD = 12.056) compared to high per -
formers (M  = 15.722, SD = 8.1), t(34) = 2.110, p = 0.042. In 
contrast, both low performers ( M = 32.888, SD = 12.915) and 
high performers (M  = 31.666, SD = 9.081) showed similar 
percentages in terms of use of procedural strategies for dif-
ficult problems, t(34) = 0.328, p = 0.745.
Electrophysiological data
As discussed in the method section, continuous EEG was 
recorded using EPOC + BCI (Emotiv, US) with 14 elec-
trodes positioned according to the 10–20 system (Jasper 
1958) on the participants’ scalp. The 14 electrodes were 
AF3, F7, F3, FC5, T7, P7, O1, O2, P8, T8, FC6, F4, F8, and 
AF4. Analyses were performed offline using 2019b version 
of MATLAB. During pre-processing, the EEG was band-
pass filtered from 0.5 to 45, digitized at a sampling rate of 
128 Hz. To eliminate power line interferences, 50 Hz and 
60 Hz notch filters were implemented. Epochs from 500 ms 
pre-stimulus to 2500 ms post-stimulus were extracted from 
continuous EEG signals. This time window was chosen 
because the average participant RT in the preliminary study 
indicated that this period was occupied by arithmetic prob-
lem mental processing. Epochs were visually inspected, and 
artifact rejection based on the mean signal amplitude during 
the epoch period was separately performed for each epoch. 
To reduce the possibility of edge artifacts, modified peri-
odogram was applied to the signal tapered by a rectangular 
window. Spectral power was computed for every frequency 
band. This procedure was performed for each epoch, elec-
trode, and participant. Participants with less than 80 intact 
epochs were removed from further analysis; data from five 
participants (four low and one high math performers) were 
removed due to this criterion. Finally, frequency bands cor -
responding to alpha (8–12 Hz) and theta (4–7.5 Hz) bands 
were extracted. The mean power for each band was calcu-
lated, and the alpha and theta band signals were extracted 
by applying discrete wavelet transform.
Group analysis included the channels related to the pre-
frontal areas (AF3 and AF4), frontal and central frontal areas 
(F3, F4, FC5, FC6), parietal lobe (P7 and P8), and occipital 
lobe (O1 and O2). Further analysis excluded the temporal 
lobe, since previous literature contains no evidence of the 
temporal lobe’s involvement in mental arithmetic.Table 2  Means and standard deviations of percentages of addition 
