An analysis was first performed across all channels in 
each hemisphere to inspect the main activities. A mixed 
measures ANOVA with level of performance as a between 
group variable, and channels, presentation method, loading, 
and difficulty as within group variables was performed for 
each alpha and theta in each hemisphere. For alpha band 
activities in the left hemisphere, the results showed a sig-
nificant main channel effect, F(4, 116)  = 5.118,  p = 0.001, 
η2
p = 0.150. For theta band activities, analysis across all 
channels in the left hemisphere showed a significant inter -
action effect between channel, loading, and difficulty, F (4, 116) = 3.123,  p = 0.018, η2
p = 0.097, and a significant main 
channel effect, F(4, 116) = 5.782,  p < 0.001, η2
p = 0.166.
Based on the above analysis and considering that data of 
mental addition only showed main effects for performance 
level and difficulty, the analysis of EEG data focused on 
these two variables. The remaining variables (method of 
presentation and loading) were collapsed together (i.e., 
epoch signals belonging to the same condition: level of per -
formance (high vs. low performers) x difficulty (easy vs. dif-
ficult) were averaged). Figures  4 and 5  show the topographi-
cal images of alpha and theta activities when grand means 
