p values were corrected via Bonferroni correction method. 
This analysis was performed for each of the alpha and theta 
activities. Tables  3 and 4  show the results of mixed measures 
ANOVA for each channel for alpha and theta, respectively. 
Alpha power significantly differed between individuals with 
high and low math performance at the left parietal site (P7), indicating a larger decrease in alpha power for individu-
als with low as compared to high math performance, F (4, 
116) = 14.139,  p < 0.001, η2
p = 0.329.
Discussion
This study explored the individual differences in mental 
arithmetic by comparing the accuracy of high and low math 
performers when performing mental addition in different set -
tings. The related brain oscillations during mental addition, 
Fig. 5  Topographical images of theta power in the cortex. Values of 
theta powers are the grand means for all epochs in each condition, 
depicted for each image. As indicated by the labels of each image, 
the grand means are generated after collapsing all easy conditions in 
one grand mean and all difficult conditions in another grand mean for each of the low and high math performers groups. The right bar for 
each image indicates the values of the color codes in the topographi-
cal image. Changes in theta activities according to math performance 
and difficulty was not significant 621 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626 
1 3
specifically alpha and theta oscillations, were recorded and 
analyzed. The results demonstrate an interaction between 
the participants’ mental addition performance level and the 
problem difficulty levels. The gap between high and low 
performers increased with difficult problems. Both groups 
of participants seemed to use procedural strategies more 
frequently when faced with difficult addition problems and 
when no visuospatial load interrupted their visuospatial working memory. Regarding the electrophysiological data, 
the effect of problem difficulty on alpha and theta power 
was examined for each channel. In the left posterior parietal 
region, recorded by the P7 electrode, alpha power showed 
a larger decrease for the low than the high math performer 
group. These findings support the view that differences in 
performance can be detected using behavioral and neural-
based measures (Núñez-Peña et al. 2011).
The most significant finding is the difference between 
high and low math performers in P7, whereby alpha power 
showed a significant decrease for low math performers, in 
contrast to high math performers. Although the behavioral 
data showed greater mental addition accuracy differences 
between high and low performers in difficult compared to 
easy conditions, low performers’ alpha showed an overall 
decrease for both easy and difficult conditions. The decrease Table 3  Alpha activities during mental addition, calculated by mixed-
