in alpha in the parietooccipital area was found to be related 
to the use of procedural strategies in mental arithmetic (De 
Smedt et al. 2009). Furthermore, working memory, which 
is required for procedural strategies, is related to a decrease 
in alpha in several regions, including the posterior parietal 
region (Borghini et al. 2014; Foxe and Snyder 2011; Kli-
mesch 1999).
The current study showed an interaction between the level 
of performance and the effect of difficulty on using pro-
cedural strategies, whereby the post hoc analysis indicated 
a greater use of procedural strategies by low performers 
compared to high performers under easy conditions. This is 
consistent with the finding of decreased alpha power under 
easy conditions for low performers. For the difficult condi-
tions, not only did both high and low performers show a 
similar level of dependence on procedural strategies under 
difficult conditions, but also the high performers showed a 
larger dependence on procedural strategies in the vertical 
condition. It might be surprising, at first glance, that low 
performers, rather than high performers, showed a decrease 
in alpha power under the difficult condition. Nevertheless, 
despite the reliance on procedural strategies, high performers 
automatically retrieve intermediate answers, and this abil-
ity is not available for low performers (Jackson and Coney 
2007). Low performers depend on procedural strategies to a 
larger extent, even for many easy problems and intermediate 
answers. Therefore, the decrease in alpha in low performers 
emerges under both easy and difficult conditions.
In contrast, high performers depend heavily on the 
retrieval of answers in easy problems and use retrieval in 
conjunction with procedural strategies as a tool to retrieve 
intermediate answers. This claim receives support from 
previous studies. High activation in the left angular gyrus, 
responsible for arithmetic fact retrieval, was found in high 
math performers regardless of the task (Grabner et al. 2007). 
High math performers were also previously found to depend 
more on retrieval strategies in mental arithmetic (Grabner 
et al. 2007, 2009; Thevenot 2007).
Another possible explanation for the decrease in alpha 
activities in low math performers in both easy and difficult 
problems relates to the effect of math anxiety. A previous 
study found that cortical activities increased in participants 
with high math anxiety when they were given arithmetic 
problems, regardless of the difficulty of the task (Klados 
et al. 2015). Math anxiety is related to a reduction in math 
performance (Sidney et al. 2018; Trezise and Reeve 2014) as 
it consumes working memory resources (Ashkenazi and Naj-
jar 2018; Trezise and Reeve 2014) or causes the avoidance 
of math problems (Ashcraft and Kirk 2001). For a review of 
the disrupting effect of math anxiety on math performance, 
see Ashcraft and Kirk (2001).
It is interesting to note that the decrease in alpha power 
occurs only in the left posterior parietal lobe. According to the triple-code model of Dehaene (1992), the posterior 
parietal lobe is related to spatial and non-spatial attention, 
the left angular gyrus is related to the recall of verbal infor -
mation, and the intraparietal sulcus is related to number 
magnitudes and the representation of the number line. As 
discussed, the triple-code model has provided evidence 
that attention is required for procedural strategies as they 
involve multiple processes to reach the final answer to each 
problem. Procedural strategies in mental addition seem to 
exhibit a large use of visuospatial attention, which is related 
to the left posterior parietal lobe (Zago et al. 2001); hence, 
the decrease of alpha is significant only in the left posterior 
parietal region.
This interpretation is consistent with findings from pre-
vious studies that showed a left-side dominance in mental 
arithmetic in both high and low performers (Proverbio et al. 
2019) and for procedural strategies (Kong et al. 2005). In 
previous studies, the left and right regions in the parietal 
lobes showed different patterns of activity during mental 
arithmetic (Delazer et al. 2005; Prado et al. 2013).
However, it should also be mentioned that in previous 
studies, bilateral posterior parietal regions were found to 
show a decrease in alpha power with difficult mental arith-
metic (De Smedt et al. 2009). Additionally, fMRI findings 
showed more activities in biparietoccipital areas with com-
plex tasks (Menon et al. 2000b) and procedural strategies 
(Grabner et al. 2009). The role of the left posterior parietal 
lobe is related to visuospatial attention in procedural strate-
gies, and further studies can explore the specific roles of the 
right posterior parietal lobe in procedural strategies.
The findings of this study show that in the left hemi-
sphere, problem difficulty and the loading of visuospatial 
working memory have different effects on theta power in 
different areas. However, the post hoc analysis failed to show 
any significant results. Theta is responsible for memory 
encoding (Klimesch 1999) and executive processing (Saus-
ing et al. 2005), and it has been found in anterior frontopa-
rietal regions in deductive reasoning tasks, which are highly 
demanding tasks. Additionally, an increase in theta power 
is related to the retrieval of arithmetic facts (De Smedt et al. 
2009). However, as the study found no significant findings 
in relation to this, the role of theta will not be further dis-
cussed here.
With regard to solving strategies, participants’ more 
frequent use of procedural strategies with no visuospatial 
load illustrates that the visuospatial sketchpad is critical for 
procedural strategies. This is consistent with previous find-
ings, where visuospatial loading disrupted performance in 
procedural strategies (Hubber et al. 2013).
Another interesting finding is that visuospatial loading 
impaired performance in horizontally presented arithme-
tic problems, yet it had no significant effect on vertically 
presented problems. This interfering effect of loading  623 Cognitive Processing (2021) 22:609–626 
1 3
visuospatial working memory on horizontally presented 
arithmetic problems is complicated by the finding that the 
performance in the secondary visuospatial working memory 
task was higher when performed concurrently with difficult, 
instead of easy, horizontally presented arithmetic problems. 
This indicates that the participants either focus on the visu-
ospatial working memory task or the mental addition task. 
Furthermore, this emphasizes the role of visuospatial work -
ing memory in mental arithmetic and shows that both high 
and low performers might rely less on visuospatial work -
ing memory when arithmetic problems are arranged in a 
vertical order. Dowker (2005) concluded that flexibility in 
strategy usage is required for accurate mental arithmetic per -
formance. In this study, the high math performers tended 
to use procedural strategies more with vertically, than with 
horizontally, presented problems, meaning they were more 
flexible in changing their strategy according to how the addi-
tion problems were presented.
A previous study on Chinese students found that visuos-
patial loading impairs vertically presented problems, but not 
horizontal ones (Imbo and LeFevre 2010). However, in this 
study, visuospatial loading impairment was found on hori-
zontal, and not vertical, problems. Future studies can explore 
the role of the visuospatial sketchpad and related occipital 
lobe activities in arithmetic in connection with cultural and 
individual differences.
A final note is related to the differences between high and 
low math performers in the current study. As stated in the 
results, high and low math performers, categorized based 
on their performance in an arithmetic fluency test, also dif-
fer in their verbal STM and updating abilities, which were 
assessed by the digit span task and 1-back task, respectively. 
N-back measures a combination of executive functions, 
including updating (Gajewski et al. 2018). The 1-back task 
is less demanding than the 2- and 3-back versions. High and 
low math performers only differ in their performance on the 
least demanding task. This was previously explained by the 
activation of spatial representation (Fischer et al. 2003) or 
number semantic representation via number stimuli (Knops 
et al. 2006). These semantic representations of numbers 
are activated and enhance performance when faced with 
simple tasks. When the load on working memory increases 
(e.g., under 2- and 3-back conditions), the effect of number 
semantic representations interferes with working memory. 
The difference between high and low performers in num-
ber representation might be the reason for the differences 
between the two groups in the 1-back task and in digit serial 
recall.
It could be argued that using number stimuli to assess 
working memory activates other semantic and spatial rep-
resentations of numbers, which are components of mental 
arithmetic (Knops et al. 2006). Nevertheless, low math 
performers are behind in both their digit-serial recall and n-back, which use number stimuli, and working memory 
updating, which uses letters. Therefore, the differences in 
working memory are not solely attributable to differences 
in number representation. Furthermore, it is hard to disas-
sociate working memory efficiency from mental arithmetic 
skills. The order of items in working memory activates mag -
nitude representations that are similar to number representa-
tions (Marshuetz et al. 2000). Updating involves multiple 
component processes: retrieval, transformation, and substi-
tution (Ecker et al. 2010, 2014; Kessler and Meiran 2008). 
In mental arithmetic, updating seems to be particularly nec-
essary when carrying one and two-digit integers, whereby 
participants update decades alongside retrieving the unit 
total. Updating processes are the core processes in working 
memory (Kessler and Oberauer 2014), which, in turn, is the 
executor of arithmetic calculations that do not depend on 
mere solution retrieval (Dowker 2005).
Given the small number of participants in this study, 
caution must be exercised in generalizing the findings and 
interpretations. Another limitation is that the study included 
only female participants. Evidence from previous findings 
suggests a different utilization of solving strategies based on 
gender (Pletzer 2016). Hence, replications and extensions of 
the current findings to both males and females are required.
Conclusion
High vs. low math performers respond differently to arith-
metic problems in both behavioral and neural measures. 
They use different strategies in easy problems and their 
accuracies in mental addition are significantly different. 
Furthermore, while they tend to use similar strategies for 
difficult problems, the efficiency of low performers is not 
at the same level as that of high performers, which leads to 
significantly lower accuracy. The current study showed that 
a decrease in alpha, which indicates cortical arousal, in the 
posterior parietal region is related to lower mental arithme-
tic skills. Combining behavioral and neural measures is a 
promising approach for understanding differences in math 
performance.
