Discovering optimal brain states for problem solving with EEG* 
Ying Choon Wu, Member, IEEE, Melody Jung, Derrick Lock, Eric Chao, and Tzyy-Ping Jung 
ABSTRACT— To characterize neuro-cognitive dynamics during 
problem solving, high-density electroencephalography (EEG) 
(128 channels) was recorded as healthy adults engaged in math 
puzzles and rated the degree of insight that they experienced 
during the solution process. Higher levels of insight were 
typically associated with longer solution latencies. Time-
frequency transforms of artifact-corrected EEG time series data 
from six pilot subjects revealed distinct left and right 
hemisphere contributions during the problem-solving phase 
irrespective of participants' subjective insight experience. 
However, while few topographic differences as a function of 
insight rating were discerned, insight solutions tended to involve 
more sustained and stronger desynchronization of scalp-
recorded activities in the alpha, beta, and gamma ranges 
relative to non-insight trials. These findings may help to 
uncover ""cortical signatures"" associated with successful 
problem solving in math and other domains. 
I. INTRODUCTION 
With the advent of cutting-edge electroencephalography 
(EEG) measurement systems using wireless and dry 
electrodes [1], a wide range of applications centered around 
neuro feedback or other types of brain-computer interfaces is 
emerging. The focus of the present study is problem solving. 
Researchers have drawn a distinction between search- and 
insight-based problem-solving approaches. On the one 
hand, in search-based strategies, a solution is achieved 
through systematic evaluation of the known space of 
possible solutions. On the other hand, problems can be 
solved through enlarging and/or restructuring the problem 
space, allowing an unexpected solution to emerge that often 
yields a feeling of sudden insight, known as 
""Aha!""experience. In some such cases, the problem solver 
may have little awareness or memory of the logical steps 
that led to the solution. 
Existing EEG research on insight has frequently assessed 
problem solving through verbal puzzles, such as anagrams, 
riddles, or so-called remote associates, in which a word must 
be discovered that can be combined with three other 
unrelated words to create a phrase or compound (e.g., 
sauce, pine, crab: apple ). Importantly, this work has 
revealed that EEG signals during problem solving can 
