Eric Chao is with University City High School, San Diego, CA 
(eychaos@gmail.com). 
Tzyy Ping Jung is with the Swartz Center for Computational 
Neuroscience, UCSD, as well as the Brain Research Center, National 
Chiao-Tung University, Hsinchu, Taiwan (jung@sccn.ucsd.edu). differentiate between solutions involving insight versus 
other strategies, particularly in the alpha and gamma 
frequency ranges [2-4]. Our long-term goal centers around 
developing tools and resources that may ultimately help 
individuals overcome impasses and achieve solutions more 
readily in day-to-day problem solving, as well as in specific 
educational arenas, such as math. Examples of such possible 
resources include biofeedback training or behavioral 
interventions designed to promote incubation - the 
unconscious mental processes thought to follow active, 
conscious problem solving efforts, precipitating the 
restructuring of a problem space at some later time. 
A prerequisite for this mission is the characterization of 
neuro-cognitive dynamics during engagement with different 
types of problems. To this end, we recorded EEG as healthy 
adults played a game known as Math24, which involves 
combining, as quickly as possible, four single-digit numbers 
(using each only once) with basic arithmetic operators 
(addition, subtraction, division, multiplication, grouping) to 
form an arithmetic expression whose value is 24. This task 
was chosen because insight during math problem solving has 
received relatively less attention than verbal problems. 
Further, due to the formal nature of this task, problem 
solving can be evaluated at different levels of difficulty. 
After completing each puzzle, participants rated on a five-
point scale whether their solution was achieved through an 
Aha! experience. By comparing estimates of event-related 
spectral power derived from correct trials involving insight-
versus search-based solution strategies (versus trials 
involving time-outs), our goal is to uncover optimal 
neurodynamic states for successful problem solving. 
II. METHODS 
A. Participants 
The Institutional Review Board of UC San Diego 
approved the experiment protocol. Six volunteers (3 male) 
were recompensed for their participation at a rate of $15.00 
per hour. All were neurologically healthy university students 
(no history of seizures, concussion, or neuropsychiatric 
disorder) who gave informed consent. 
B. Materials 
Math24 is a popular commercial game found in many 
schools. Each problem consists of four single-digit numbers 
that must be combined through addition, subtraction, 
division, or multiplication to reach a final solution that equals 
twenty-four. For example, a puzzle consisting of 1, 7, 1, and 
2, could be correctly resolved through the following steps: 
1+7=8; 2+1=3; 3×8=24. Problems vary along three levels of 
difficulty, with harder items characterized by longer solution 
978-1-4673-1969-0/13/$31.00 ©2013 IEEE 774 
Authorized licensed use limited to: UNIVERSIDADE FEDERAL DO RIO GRANDE DO SUL. Downloaded on July 20,2025 at 03:13:01 UTC from IEEE Xplore.  Restrictions apply.  latencies [5,6] and more frequent recruitment of 
multiplication and division versus simple addition. 
In the present study, participants were presented with all 
three trial types in a randomized, interleaved fashion. After 
each trial, they were asked to rate how they reached their 
solution on a scale of 1 (no insight whatsoever) to 5 (distinct 
feeling of Aha!). In this way, it was possible to differentiate 
solutions that individuals saw immediately or simply 
stumbled upon from those that involved restructuring of the 
problem space. Care was taken during the instruction phase 
of each experimental session to ensure that participants 
understood the definition of insight and how to use the five 
point scale. 
C. Procedure 
Participants received oral and written instructions 
regarding the Math24 task and insight scale. They were 
given the opportunity to ask questions and completed a 
practice set. During the EEG recording session, puzzles were 
completed in a self-paced fashion. After two minutes, the 
opportunity was given to go on to the next trial if a particular 
problem was proving difficult. After three minutes, the trial 
""timed out,"" and a new puzzle was presented when the 
participant signaled readiness with a mouse click. 
Immediately upon arriving at a solution, participants 
clicked the mouse and shared their answer via intercom with 
an experimenter in the adjacent control room. The 
experimenter evaluated responses online and registered their 
accuracy with a mouse click. Solutions were only stated 
verbally by participants, and both their solution readiness 
mouse clicks, as well as the experimenter's evaluations of 
accuracy were recorded and synchronized with EEG. 
The entire Math24 session lasted one hour. Afterwards, 
participants completed a basic addition task. Either the same 
or similar puzzles were presented over again with the 
requirement that participants simply sum the four numbers. 
Importantly, this task involved perceptual and arithmetic 
features that closely resembled the experimental task for 
baseline subtraction purposes. 
D. Data Acquisition and Analysis 
128-channel EEG data were amplified (BioSemi ActiveTwo 
EEG system), referenced to the CMS-DRL ground, and 
sampled at 512 Hz. The onset of puzzles, as well as 
participants' and experimenters' behavioral responses were 
recorded and synchronized using Lab Streaming Layer 
(https://code.google.com/p/labstreaminglayer/). 
1) Behavioral Data: For correct trials, solution latencies 
(SLs) were determined by measuring the time between the 
stimulus onset and the mouse click indicating solution 
readiness. Data were then sorted into three categories, 
depending on the insight rating of their associated trial: low 
insight (rated as one or two), medium insight (three), high 
insight (four or five). For each individual participant, SLs 
were averaged within each category. All incorrectly solved 
trials were removed from further analysis. 
2) EEG data: The acquired EEG signals were first inspected to remove poor-quality EEG channels and trials that were 
heavily contaminated by movement and other non-brain 
artifacts. The remaining raw, time-series EEG underwent 
Independent Component Analysis (ICA, [7,8]) for the 
purpose of artifact correction. ICA is now a widely-used 
statistical technique to find linear projections of the EEG 
data that maximize the mutual independences of estimated 
components, and has been proven as an effective technique 
to remove EEG artifacts arising from eye blinks, eye 
movement and muscle activities [9]. EEG signals were 
analyzed using MATLAB (The Mathworks, Inc.) and the 
open source toolbox, EEGLAB (Swartz Center for 
Computational Neuroscience, University of California San 
Diego, La Jolla, CA; http://www.sccn.ucsd.edu/eeglab). 
Single trial data epochs were extracted from artifact-
corrected time series EEG within a time window extending 
from seven seconds to approximately 500 ms before the 
mouse click signaling solution readiness. To examine 
temporal brain dynamics in spectral changes during problem 
solving, this study applied a visualization tool known as 
Event-Related Spectral Perturbation (ERSP) [10] . The high 
dimensionality of results from this technique precluded 
analysis of data from all electrode sites. As a preliminary 
step, ERSPs were computed from data associated with twelve 
representative channels distributed over the right, left, and 
midline axes along four evenly spaced points extending from 
the front to the back of the scalp (F3, F4, C3, C4, P3, P4, O3, 
O4, Fz, Cz, Pz, Oz). Data epochs were transformed into 
spectrographic images by computing power spectral density 
estimates across a range of frequencies implicated in 
cognitive processing, including theta (6: 4-7 Hz), alpha (a: 8-
13 Hz), beta ((3: 14-30 Hz), and gamma (y: 30-50 Hz). 
Estimates were derived at 200 equally spaced time points 
within the 6.5 second window comprising each epoch. For 
all participants, mean ERSP plots were derived from single-
trial spectrographic images associated with either high or low 
levels of insight by converting to log power, averaging across 
trials, and subtracting the mean log power derived from the 
baseline addition task. Non-parametric, permutation-based 
signficance tests were conducted at each time/frequency 
point (a = 0.03), and non-signficant points were zeroed [11]. 
Individual mean ERSPs were then averaged across 
participants. 
III. RESULTS 
A. Solution Latencies 
Fig. 1 shows solution latencies for high, medium, and low 
insight trials. Notably, puzzles reported to involve little 
insight were solved substantially more quickly (less than one 
minute) than puzzles involving high levels of insight. 
Response times on medium-level items reflected more 
variability. In all but one case, participants obtained 
solutions involving medium-level insight more quickly than 
high-insight solutions. In some cases, medium insight 
solution times were visibly differentiated from those 
involving low insight, as well. Importantly, participants' 
ratings of insight were only weakly correlated with task 
