insight trials over representative frontal (F3/F4) and occipital 
(O3/O4) recording sites. Over the front of the head, the 6.5 
second interval preceding solution readiness is characterized 
in part by progressively decreasing power around 13 Hz. In 
four out of the total six participants, we found that this 
reduction in alpha power was stronger during the early 
portion of high insight trials as compared with low ones, in 
keeping with the pattern illustrated in the grand averaged 
ERSPs below. Intermittent bursts of event-related 
synchronization (ERS) in the theta range (3 to 7 Hz) are also 
visible for both solution types, though activities associated 
with high insight trials appeared more reliable (occurring in 
five out of six participants) than those associated with low 
insight ones (found only in half of the total participants). 
Notably, these activities appear greater over the right versus 
the left hemisphere. 
Over the back of the head, ERSP plots are predominated 
by a broad, sustained desynchronization of activities in the 
alpha, beta, and gamma range that is more discernible over 
the left versus right hemisphere. A trend can be discerned 
toward greater desynchronization associated with high versus 
low insight. Over the right hemisphere, both types of 
solutions elicit an alpha burst around 4.5 seconds before 
solution readiness. IV. DISCUSSION 
This study examines insight versus non-insight based 
problem solving while holding task constant. Preliminary 
analysis of solution latencies indicates a positive linear 
relationship between the length of time required to reach a 
solution and subjective experience of insight. Distinct Aha! 
experiences typically occurred only after an individual had 
been working on a problem for over a minute. 
Preliminary EEG results are consistent with some aspects 
of existing insight research. For instance, Sandkühler and 
Bhattacharya [12] also reported greater suppression of frontal 
alpha power during the resolution of remote association 
problems that involved overcoming a mental impasse versus 
not (though their findings were restricted to right hemisphere 
recording sites only, whereas current results reveal bilateral 
desynchronization). Further, analogous to the alpha burst 
around 2000 ms over O4 in both high and low insight trials, 
Beeman et al. [2] described a right parietal alpha burst 
preceding remote association solutions that recruited insight 
versus other strategies. This finding was proposed to reflect 
gating of visual attention that can allow restructuring to 
occur. 
A number of studies have implicated the right 
hemisphere in in diffuse attention [3], unconscious 
processing [12] and broad semantic representation [2,13], all 
of which are thought to contribute to the restructuring 
necessary to connect problem elements in such a way that an 
""Aha!"" solution is suddenly achieved. Our preliminary 
results likewise suggest a distinctive role of the right 
hemisphere in insight solutions, particularly in the theta 
frequency range. However, this study also revealed stronger 
contributions in the gamma range from the left hemisphere 
relative to the right over the back of the head - possibly due 
to the quantitative rather than verbal nature of the problems 
used in this study. 
In summary, the preliminary analysis presented here 
suggests that in the domain of math, insight solutions differ 
from search-based or other analytical approaches primarily in 
the intensity and time course of cortical activities detected 
over the scalp. Our future goal is to compare whether EEG 
early in the problem solving phase (or before the problem is 
even presented) can predict aspects of solvers' performance, 
such as likelihood of success (versus giving up) or time to 
achieve a solution. 
