1In order to further examine the possibility of di ﬀerent alpha power de-
pending on the conditions, an ANOVA also considering the side of the headJ. Bagnoud et al. Acta Psychologica 190 (2018) 116–121
118 4. Discussion
In this experiment, we examined the possibility that the mental
representation constructed in order to solve arithmetic word problems
might di ﬀer depending on the nature of the object described in the text.
To explore this issue, university students were asked to solve a set ofproblems describing either continuous or discrete quantities and we
measured the level of alpha power in the parieto-occipital area of their
brain. This measure allowed a quanti ﬁcation of the mental imagery
level during problem solving. As we expected, the level of alpha powerwas lower when discrete rather than continuous quantities were used in
the texts, which, as explained in our Introduction, re ﬂects a higher level
of mental imagery. This result is coherent with the situation modelframework, which hypothesizes that the context in which the mathe-
matical situation is embedded in ﬂuences the solving process. On the
contrary, our results are di ﬃcult to reconcile with the schema theory,
which cannot predict a di ﬀerence in mental processing between pro-
blems describing continuous and discrete quantities. Indeed, accordingto this theory, empty slots in a ﬁxed frame convoked from long-term
memory are ﬁlled with quantities and objects described in the text of
the problem as soon as they are encountered. Because the nature of the
objects cannot have an impact on the problem solving process, they
should be represented as abstract elements, or at the very least, they
should rapidly lose their inherent characteristics during the course of
the process. Thus, within the schema theory, since only the quantities
and the procedures to be applied to those quantities (i.e., add or sub-
tract them) are relevant for problem solving, the characteristics of the
objects associated with the quantities and, speci ﬁcally, their level of
visualizability should not be mentally represented.
Therefore, the present study reinforces previous claims in the lit-
erature that the schema theory by itself cannot account for arithmeticword problem solving (e.g., Coquin-Viennot & Moreau, 2003; Staub &
Reusser, 1995; Thevenot & Oakhill, 2006). Instead, an internal re-
presentation that is closer to the content of the problem seems to beconstructed by individuals. Nevertheless, it should be noted that con-
tent eﬀects have sometimes been interpreted within the schema fra-
mework. Indeed, Blessing and Ross (1996) argued that content e ﬀects
could stem from the high correlation between the surface character-
istics of the problems (e.g., type of objects) and their semantic struc-
ture. For example, problems in which a distance travelled has to be
determined often involve trains. Hence, the nature of the objects used in
the text could help individuals to correctly categorize the problem and
mobilize the correct schema. However, in our experiment, only com-
pare problems were used and, therefore, our participants had to solve
almost 100 problems of the same semantic structure. Thus, within the
context of this study, the categorization phase was of no relevance after
a few problems had been solved. Therefore, we maintain our rationale
that the schema theory leads to the assumption that the nature of the
objects should have been neglected by our participants during the
solving process. Still, our conclusion that the situation model theory
better explains our results than the schema theory does not mean that
schemata are never used when individuals solve arithmetic word pro-
blems. In fact, it has been shown that when the problems are or seem
typical, individuals sometimes apply ready-made procedures, which
can be triggered by problem schemata, without prior mental modelling
of the situation (e.g., Lewis & Mayer, 1987 ;Verscha ﬀel, De Corte, &
Lasure, 1994 ). Such schemata activations can lead to errors due to
misrepresentations of non-standard problems (see Jimėnez and
Verscha ﬀel (2014) for a literature review). Furthermore, we cannot
exclude the possibility that, in our experiment, participants sometimes
activated schemata from long-term memory in order to solve some ofthe
problems. Still, our results show that situation models are, at least
sometimes, constructed by individuals to solve familiar comparisonproblems.
A last point deserving discussion is related to the results we ob-
tained at a behavioural level. Because we expected di ﬀerent processing
