(footnote continued)
(left, right, center) as a within measure was conducted on our data The analysisshows an eﬀ ect of quantity type, F(1, 17) = 4.68, p= .045, η
2p = 0.22, but no
eﬀect depending on the side of the brain, F(2, 34) = 1.08, p= .35 and no in-
teraction between quantity type and side of the head, F < 1. Details on thelevel of the alpha rhythm can be found in the Appendix.J. Bagnoud et al. Acta Psychologica 190 (2018) 116–121
119 depending on the nature of the objects used in the text of the problems,
we could have predicted di ﬀerences in performance between problems
involving continuous or discrete quantities. However, we chose toconduct our experiments in adults in order to ensure that they already
had the possibility to extract abstract schemata from their numerous
previous encounters with similar problems. The drawback in testing
experts on simple problems, as attested by our results, is that they
perform at ceiling levels and that variations in performance cannot
really be expected. Yet, an analysis of reading times revealed that
problems describing discrete quantities were read more slowly than
problems describing continuous quantities. This result could re ﬂect the
time needed by participants to create an image of the discrete quan-tities. Interestingly, similar results were obtained by Knauﬀand
Johnson-Laird (2002) who showed that reading the premises of a rea-
soning problem takes longer when the contents are easy to visualize
(e.g., The dog is cleaner than the cat) rather than less visualisable (e.g.,
The dog is worse than the cat). Moreover, the authors showed that
visualisable material slowed the processing of reasoning compared to
less visualisable material. More precisely, inference problems such as
“The dog is cleaner than the cat. The ape is dirtier than the cat. Does it
follow: The dog is cleaner than the ape?” are solved more slowly than
problems such as “The dog is better than the cat. The ape is worse than
the cat. Does it follow: The dog is better than the ape? ”. Knau ﬀand
Johnson-Laird logically concluded that mental imagery impedes rea-
soning. According to the authors, the visual details contained in mental
images are far less relevant for the reasoning process than more abstract
mental representations, which can represent any possible situations.
Therefore, our results could echo Hegarty and Kozhevnikov's results
(1999) showing that imagery generated by sixth-graders is detrimental
to their performance or, more generally, conclusions that providing
children with pictorial representations does not always help them to
solve the problems (e.g., Dewolf, Van Dooren, & Verscha ﬀel, 2017 ;Van
Lieshout & Xenidou-Dervou, 2018 ). Nevertheless, as noted by Van
Garderen and Montague (2003) , it might not be the visual image per se
that is responsible for the decrease in performance but rather the fact
that an image is generated instead of the correct structural re-
presentation. As a matter of fact, several studies have shown that eli-
citing accurate visual-schematic representations (or mathematical
drawings) rather than pictorial representations (or situation drawings)
facilitates problem comprehension ( Boonen, Van Wesel, Jolles, & Van
der Schoot, 2014 ;Vicente, Orrantia, & Verscha ﬀel, 2008 ). Un-
fortunately, it is di ﬃcult to determine whether the manipulations we
made in the present research impacted individuals' mentalrepresentations of the objects or of the relationships between the ob-
jects. In either case, our results could have positive implications from a
pedagogical point of view and further studies in children using our
paradigm, even at a simple behavioural level, could be informative
about the precise role of mental imagery in word problem solving
performance. Another way to answer the question about the impact of
manipulating the nature of the quantities described in the text could be
to expand our analyses to additional frequency bands. For example,
examining theta activity could be informative because it is sometimes
viewed as re ﬂecting cognitive load ( Jensen & Tesche, 2002 ; see Hinault
& Lemaire, 2016 for a review about cognitive interpretations of
rhythmic activities in numerical cognition). Another alternative ap-
proach in order to address our question would have been to conduct an
event-related potential (ERP) analysis, which could have allowed us to
contrast the EEG signal patterns for problems with continuous and
discrete quantities. Nevertheless, ERP analysis is generally used for
more homogeneous tasks (e.g., Burra & Kerzel, 2014 for
 a visual per-
ception task or Hinault, Lemaire, & Phillips, 2016 for a computational
estimation task) than arithmetic word problem solving tasks in which
text reading comprehension and calculations are required. In fact, we
have to acknowledge that studying such a complex cognitive process
required a few comprises in order to maintain an acceptable ecological
validity of the task while collecting meaningful EEG data. For example,
we decided to present the text of the problem in two di ﬀerent segments,
which is not usual, but allowed us to better identify the di ﬀerent pro-
cessing steps in problem solving. In the same way, we decided to record
brain activity during 1 sec at the beginning of the question presentation
but this choice can be debated. Still, this pioneering study reveals that
brain activity recording technics can be applied in addition to more
classical behavioural methods in the domain of arithmetic word pro-
blem solving and can provide new theoretical knowledge within this
ﬁeld.
Compliance with ethical standards
The local ethics committee approved our study, which was therefore
conducted in accordance with the ethical standards laid down in the
1964 Declaration of Helsinki. All our participants gave their informed
consent prior to their inclusion in the study.
Declaration of interest
None.
