1 Introduction
The mammalian brain is made up of multiple neu-
rons that are responsible for controlling the activity 
of the human body in response to intrinsic/extrinsic 
motor/sensory excitation. These nerve cells will trans -
mit data from the human body to the brain. 
Analyzing signals or images from the brain can be 
used to better understand cognitive behavior. Eye 
motion, lip movement, recollection, attentiveness, 
hand grasping, and other motor and sensory states 
can be used to picture human behavior. These states 
are linked to a certain signal frequency, which aids in 
the comprehension of the functional activity of a 
complicated brain structure. EEG is a useful tool for 
obtaining brain waves from the scalp surface area that 
are correlated to different states. These signals are 
classed as n, s, k, l, and m!depending on signal fre-
quencies in the range from 0.1Hz to more than 
100Hz. The brain is an important part of the human 
body since it governs all of the body’s functions. The 
brain can be thought of as a network of intercon -
nected neurons that controls human behavior. Medical researchers are interested in learning more 
about the functional and cognitive activity of the 
human brain to develop better solutions to various 
brain-related ailments (Kumar and Bhuvaneswari 
2012 ). According to medical physicians and 
radiologists, the left side of the brain controls the 
right side of the human body and vice versa. 
Electroencephalogram (EEG) uses the frequency of a 
signal to evaluate the brain and its actions. The brain 
is perhaps the most key functional organ in human 
body, as it commands and regulates all the muscles 
and nerves. The left half of the brain is known as left 
hemisphere and the other half on the right is known 
as a right hemisphere. There are four lobes in each 
hemisphere: frontal, temporal, parietal, and occipital. 
Each lobe controls and regulates various functions.
Arithmetical is a discipline of mathematics that 
deals with question-solving and numerical operations. 
Mathematical problem-solving involves a variety of 
cognitive processes and methods. To solve arithmetic 
problems, some mental operations are required: Data 
retention, information arrangement, and control on 
