https://doi.org/10.1080/10255842.2023.2298362  decision making. The diverse functions performed 
during arithmetic problem-solving are controlled by 
separate brain areas. The intraparietal sulcus partici -
pates consistently during numerical calculations 
(Peters and De Smedt 2018 ). Working memory is a 
general term for a brain function that is responsible 
for temporarily processing and storing information. It 
is critical for a variety of cognitive tasks. Several func -
tional magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) investiga -
tions have discovered that executive function and 
working memory tasks engage the frontal lobe areas 
(Sarter et al. 1996 ). Working memory demand is 
thought to be supported by frontal lobe areas during 
mathematical activities. Varying types of task presen -
tation result in different frontal hemisphere domin -
ance. Visually presented activities tend to activate 
both the left and right frontal regions, but auditorily 
presented tasks activate the right frontal regions 
more.
In the recent studies conducted functional MRI 
(fMRI) data was used to study brain-behaviour correl -
ation (Cheng et al. 2022 ). A study was conducted 
using brain scanning technique to analyze the arith -
metic and metacognition (MC) of children. The study 
revealed the fact that prefrontal regions actively par-
ticipated in the MC through empirical studies. EEG 
over other imaging modalities furnishes direct neural 
activity. The dependence of fMRI on blood oxygen -
ation levels leads to indirect cognizant analysis 
(Gogna et al. 2021 ). Researchers from a range of 
domains, spanning from biophysical and connectom -
ics to systems development and digital signal process -
ing, have indicated an interest in investigating human 
cognitive function. An individual’s brain activity pat-
terns are influenced by emotional responses (Baars 
2005 ). Cognitive processing emphasizes on the predic -
tion of brain functioning during excited mental abil-
ity, sequential dynamic characteristics of the cortex, 
and interaction between neural centers.
EEG signals capture the electrical activity of the 
brain using electrodes attached to the scalp. The 
acquired signals are noisy, have artifacts. Doctors, 
neuroscientists, and biomedical engineers typically 
undergo years of training to comprehend and extract 
useful information from EEG data. Even in these cir-
cumstances, the raw collected data must be processed 
before being examined by specialists. Even if the per-
son is stationary during recording, temporal and spa-
tial filtering, as well as artifact rejection methods, are 
frequently used (Gemein et al. 2020 ). Clinical EEG 
analysis could be automated using machine learning 
(ML) techniques (Sharma et al. 2022 ). The data was separated into two categories: feature-based (custom 
elements) and end-to-end (with learned attributes). 
Visual inspection is a time-consuming, costly, and 
inconvenient technique. Therefore, does not scale 
well, and it cannot be used in brain-computer inter -
face (BCI) applications. To automate, extend, and 
improve EEG data processing, low intricate AI and 
ML techniques are the ideal companions. To accom -
plish this a simple mathematical approach is proposed 
in this article to study the cognizance of human 
beings. Indeed, BCI (Roy 2022a , 2022b ) systems like 
spellers and brain-controlled devices are built on 
decoding pipelines that employ a variety of machine- 
learning methods which can utilize the proposed 
model. The article primarily focuses on comparing 
traditional classification methods with deep learning- 
based techniques, specifically the Multi-Layered 
Perceptron (MLP) model. Support Vector Machine 
(SVM) showed the shortest training time and predic -
tion speed with comparable accuracy among trad-
itional ML-based algorithms. The subject-independent 
generalized MLP model successfully classified signals 
with approximately 90% accuracy and half the classifi -
cation time compared to traditional ML-based mod -
els. This suggests that the MLP model can serve as a 
framework for advanced subject-independent BCI 
with optimization. The paper also mentions continu -
ous efforts to improve deep learning-based BCI, such 
as the use of Deep Neural Autoencoders with sparsity 
constraints to extract hidden features from EEG data 
for subject-independent noninvasive BCI (Sharma 
et al. 2022 ). The article proposes an efficient multi- 
scale convolutional neural network (MS-CNN) for 
motor imagery (MI) classification in brain-machine 
interfaces using EEG signals. The MS-CNN model 
extracts distinguishable features from non-overlapping 
canonical frequency bands of EEG signals at multiple 
scales. Discriminant user-specific features are 
extracted and integrated into the CNN classifier to 
improve accuracy and performance. Data augmenta -
tion methods are implemented to further enhance the 
accuracy and robustness of the model. The proposed 
MS-CNN model achieves an average classification 
accuracy of 93.74% and Cohen’s kappa-coefficient of 
0.92 on the BCI competition IV2b dataset, outper -
forming several baseline and state-of-the-art EEG- 
based MI classification models. The MS-CNN model 
can be utilized in medical and healthcare applications, 
particularly for the detection and diagnosis of mental 
diseases and neurodegenerative diseases such as 
Parkinson’s disease (Roy 2022b ). The article proposes 
an efficient transfer learning-based multi-scale feature COMPUTER METHODS IN BIOMECHANICS AND BIOMEDICAL ENGINEERING
 559 fused CNN (MSFFCNN) for MI classification using 
electroencephalogram (EEG) signals. The MSFFCNN 
captures distinguishable features of various non-over -
lapping canonical frequency bands of EEG signals 
from different convolutional scales for multi-class MI 
classification. The article presents four different model 
variants, including subject-independent and subject- 
adaptive classification models, to account for inter- 
subject variability. Each adaptation configuration has 
been fine-tuned in an extensively trained pretrained 
model, and the performance of the classifier has been 
studied for a vast range of learning rates and degrees 
of adaptation. The proposed MSFFCNN achieves an 
average classification accuracy of 94.06% and outper -
forms several baseline and current state-of-the-art 
EEG-based MI classification models with fewer train -
ing samples. The article provides an effective and effi-
cient transfer learning-based end-to-end MI 
classification framework for designing a high-per -
formance robust MI-BCI system (Roy 2022a ).
2. Materials and METHODS
2.1. Data acquisition, retrieval, and pre- 
processing
PhysioNet is a growing resource of well-characterized 
digital formats of physiological data and associated 
data for biomedical researchers to use. A web-based 
resource intended to supplement current research and 
drive future explorations into intricate physiologic 
and clinical data. The MIT Laboratory for 
Computational Physiology manages openly available 
medical research data. It is user-friendly. Using this 
repository, data from the database “EEG during men -
tal arithmetic tasks” has been extracted in “edf” 
format.
The Neurocom EEG 23-channel equipment was 
used to capture the EEGs monopolarly. As shown in 
Figure 1, the surface electrodes were applied to the 
scalp with International 10/20 electrode reference. 
The interconnected ear reference electrodes were used 
to reference all electrodes.
