2.2. Data analysis
The data downloaded from PhysioNet is analyzed 
using an EDF analyzer in MATLAB. Various features 
of a signal like physical dimension, min max value, 
prefilter, number of samples are analyzed. Specific sig-
nal channel is visualized among 21 channels. The 
EEG data has to be differentiated based on relevant 
amplitude variations (Varshney et al. 2021 ). The tem-
poral lobe performance significantly contributes for 
the above-mentioned parametric changes. From the 
above it is noted that Fz channels contributes more to 
arithmetic task and it has higher classification accur -
acy. Based on this analysis channels from frontal 
regions of brain Fp1, Fp2, F3, F4, F7, F8 were 
selected. These signals were specifically analyzed for 
each subject based on the active and inactive state. 
Figure 2shows the EEG signal of subject_1 under rest 
state and active state of the same subject is given in 
Figure 3while performing mental arithmetic task. 
Those signals are recorded at a single stretch and the acquired signals can be separated by two different 
bounded boxes as shown in Figure 4.
2.3. Statistical feature extraction from EEG
The extracted raw EEG signals for a subject at rest 
state and active state are shown in Figures 5–10 are 
converted into a numerical feature. EEG is a stochas -
tic signal, so to deal with the random signal (Ma 
et al. 2021 ) statistical features like mean, variance, 
and standard deviation (SD) have been selected. A set 
of 72 observations were obtained for mean, variance, 
and SD which comprises active and inactive regions 
(Gurumurthy et al. 2013 ).
To select the optimum feature set Correlation coef-
ficient and Fisher’s score are used. Correlation coeffi -
cient is a statistical factor used to determine how 
close two variants are having a linear relation. 
Features with a high correlation are more linearly 
dependent and vice versa.
