1. Introduction
The importance of mathematical competence for effective function-
ing in today's society has led to intensi ﬁed research efforts to identify
the behavioral and neurocognitive processes and factors that in ﬂuence
the development and expression of mathematical skills. This research
has revealed that the foundations for numerical representation are
evident in infants [1,2] and develop further through exposure to
mathematical information embedded in the everyday environment
prior to the introduction of structured mathematical education [3–5].
Critical factors in this development are basic mathematics-related skills,
such as number sense, size or quantity discrimination, and ability to add
and subtract simple whole numbers, as well as cognitive abilities
involving memory functions and processing speed (reviewed in [6]).
There is a general consensus that in children and adults a network of
frontal and parietal brain regions are activated during calculation tasks
and that with increasing mathematical expertise there is a shift in
emphasis from frontal to parietal processes [7–9].This development is also in ﬂuenced by environmental variables and
individual capability as re ﬂected by SES and IQ [6,10] .H o w e v e r ,a
fundamental factor not generally considered in studies involving
healthy participants is their nutritional status at the time of assessment.
This is surprising in view of the undisputed fact that brain function is
dependent on adequate nutrition, and that short-term variations in the
amount and composition of nutrient intake in healthy individuals
inﬂuence measures of cognitive function [see [11–13]for reviews]. For
example, cognitive functions, including those involved in mental
arithmetic [12], have been shown to be sensitive to variations in
nutrient intake, levels of glucose in the blood, interactions of glucose
with other nutrients, e.g., proteins and fats [14,15] and hormones
involved in glucose regulation, e.g., cortisol [16].
Cognitive functioning is likely to be more susceptible to short-term
variations of nutrition in children because of their high metabolic rates
and increased energy demands [17,18] . On a daily basis the greatest
nutritional variation occurs during overnight fasting, which may last
more than 9 –10 h in children because of their extended sleep time [19].
Nutrients provided by breakfast are therefore particularly important for
meeting the physiological and cognitive demands children face in the
morning. Immediate cognitive bene ﬁts of eating breakfast that have
been reported in children include improved memory, attention, andPhysiology & Behavior 106 (2012) 548 –555
