journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/phb visual discrimination [20–23]. Studies regulating breakfast eating over
longer time periods (days or weeks) have reported improved academic
performance on complex mental tasks such as arithmetic [24,25] .
However, the neural correlates of these nutrition-related effects remain
largely unde ﬁned, and there are no studies comparing measures of
brain activity recorded during the performance of mental arithmetic in
school-aged children who had eaten or skipped breakfast.
In the present study we used time –frequency analysis to docu-
ment covariations among low frequency EEG activities occurring
while children who were fasting or had eaten breakfast performed
time-regulated mental computations of simple addition problems.
Recordings from placements over frontal and parietal brain areas
involved in mathematical cognition [26–28]were analyzed with a
focus on activity from 2 to 12 Hz. These frequencies were selected
because of the demonstrated relevance of EEG activities in this range
to attentional and memory processes involved in mathematical
thinking [29–31]. The 2 –12 Hz frequency range includes traditionally
deﬁned delta (2 –4 Hz), theta (4 –8 Hz) and alpha (8 –12 Hz) bands of
activity. Although the cognitive and behavioral correlates of these
activities are often based on these broadband de ﬁnitions, it is clear
that sub-bands within each frequency grouping may have different
functional correlates. In this regard, lower and upper frequencies in
the theta and alpha bands have received the greatest attention. Theta
activities have been most consistently associated with memory-
related functions, with increased lower frequency activity (4 –6 Hz)
associated with attention, encoding, retrieval, memory load, and
semantic memory processes [32–35], and increased upper frequency
activity (6 –8 Hz) re ﬂecting site-speci ﬁc memory maintenance and
memory load in ﬂuences [36,37] .
Differential effects associated with low (8 –10 Hz) and high
(10–12 Hz) alpha frequencies have been more extensively documented.
Low alpha effects are topographically diffuse and considered to re ﬂect
general, non-speci ﬁc variations in attention and arousal and high alpha
effects more topographically restricted and task-speci ﬁc and semantic
memory processes [38]. Lower and upper alpha bands are also
differentially sensitive to memory load and task dif ﬁculty [37,39] .T h e s e
sub-band correlates are generally associated with condition-related
alpha suppression (desynchronization) which is considered to re ﬂect
excitatory processes [40].
Recently it has been proposed that stimulus-related increases
(synchronization) in alpha activity enable the processing of task-
relevant information by inhibiting task-irrelevant neuronal activity
[40,41] . Importantly, these formulations of theta and alpha functions
are considered to represent processing modes ﬂexibly tailored to meet
task-speci ﬁc requirements and demands, rather than mechanisms that
are domain distinct. Given these considerations it is not surprising to
ﬁnd overlaps in the functional correlates of these bands and sub-bands
since these correlates result from interactions among frequency bands,
task-relevant sites, and task-related determinants [42–48].
Slower memory recall in children who skip breakfast [22,49]
indicates that working memory is sensitive to fasting, and working
memory is considered pivotal to mathematical learning and perfor-
mance in children [50,51] . In view of the association of EEG theta activity
with working memory and ﬁndings of increases in this activity with
increased mental effort or memory load, we expect fasting children will
s h o wg r e a t e rt h e t ap o w e rt h a n fedchildren. Furthermore, since the
ability to inhibit task-irrelevant information from gaining access to
working memory is critical to working memory function and ef ﬁcient
mathematical performance [50] and such inhibitory in ﬂuences have
been associated with increases in delta [29] and alpha activity, we
hypothesize that power in these bands will be greater in fasting than fed
children. It is expected that in children who eat breakfast these relatively
reduced levels of 2 –12 Hz brain activity will be associated with
improved task performance. The requirement of lower brain activity to
successfully meet task demands is consistent with the concept of neural
efﬁciency as proposed by Haier et al. [52] to characterize the reducedbrain energy consumption (glucose metabolism) required by good
relative to poor performers on a complex task. Evidence in support of
this concept has been provided by studies measuring brain electrical
activity and metabolism (see [53–55]). The overarching hypothesis,
then, is that morning nutrition will increase the ef ﬁciency of brain
processes involved in a complex mental function.
2. Methods
2.1. Participants
Study participants were recruited from the local community.
Participants were 8 –11 years old, above the 25th percentile in
weight-for-age and height-for-age, between the 25th and 95th
percentiles in BMI, and scored at least 80 on IQ evaluations (Wechsler
Abbreviated Scale of Intelligence; Table 1 ). Children having medical
conditions or taking medications that would prevent the administra-
tion of the study protocol or that were known to in ﬂuence study
variables were excluded from participation. Of 116 children who met
these criteria and completed the study protocol, eighty-one healthy,
right-handed children (44 females) are included for this report. The
remaining 35 were excluded for the following reasons: 16 were lefthanded (only right-handed children were included in this report to
avoid confounds in hemispheric analyses; handedness was deter-
mined from parental and children's self-reports and the preferred
hand was used for motor responses on study tasks); 17 showed
excessive artifact in their recordings resulting from movement orblinking; and 2 failed to follow testing instructions.
Three day food records and information about children's breakfast
eating habits (e.g., frequency and composition) were provided by
parents. Assessments of general math skills and performance were
made using the Wide Range Achievement Test-3 (Arithmetic subtest
standard scores) and a Math Fluency Task (20 simple addition and
subtraction problems to be completed in ≤10 min [56]) (see Table 1 ).
The study protocol was approved by the University IRB Committee.
Informed consent was obtained from parents and assent from the
children.
2.2. Procedures
Participants and one of their parents stayed at the research facility
the night prior to morning assessments, reporting to the facility at
