BMI (body mass index); IQ (intelligence quotient —based on Wechsler Abbreviated
Scale of Intelligence); SES (social economic status —based on [92]Four-Factor Index of
Social Positions); WRAT (Wide Range Achievement Test-3).549 R.T. Pivik et al. / Physiology & Behavior 106 (2012) 548 –555 approximately 5:00 p.m. for orientation to the laboratory and
assessment procedures. Orientation included the administration of a
shortened version of the math paradigm to familiarize participants
with the problem presentation rate and response demands of the
paradigm. Problems used in this practice session were similar to
those in the experimental paradigm but did not include the speci ﬁc
problems in that paradigm. After these procedures children atedinner and relaxed until going to bed no later than 9:00 p.m. Only
water was allowed after bedtime. A nurse monitored the children
during the overnight stay and ensured that fasting and bedtime
requirements were observed. Children wore a wrist actigraph over-
night (Mini-Motionlogger, Ambulatory Monitoring, Inc.) to provide
information regarding the amount and quality of sleep. Since those
assigned to the fasting condition would not be eating until lunch time
on the testing day, blood glucose levels were assessed via ﬁnger stick
(Glucometer Elite XL®, Bayer Corporation) as a safety precaution
upon awakening in the morning and again following the mid-
morning break and just prior to lunch.
Shortly after participants were awakened at 6:45 a.m., electrodes
were attached for recordings of EEG [tin electrodes in an elastic cap
(Electro-Cap International, Inc.); F3, F4, C3, C4, P3, P4, O1, O2 and
right mastoid all referenced to left mastoid placement] and eye
movements (bipolar EOG from placements at the outer canthi and
above and below one eye for recording horizontal and vertical eye
movements, respectively). The ground electrode was located on the
shoulder. Impedances were maintained at b10 KΩ. Physiological
signals were ﬁltered (0.1 Hz high pass, 100 Hz low pass), ampli ﬁed
(EEG: gain 20,000; EOG: gain 1000), and stored for of ﬂine analysis.
Beginning at 8:00 a.m. while still fasting and seated comfortably in a
dimly lighted room, the children began performing a battery of tasks
which included the mental arithmetic paradigm. With scheduled rest
periods, this initial testing session lasted until 9:30 a.m. At the end of
this session a 40 min break occurred during which children were taken
to another area of the research center and randomly assigned to fedor
fasting treatment groups. Participants then either ate breakfast ( n=40,
18 males) or continued fasting ( n=41, 19 males) and rested until the
end of the break period.
The standardized breakfast, based on USDA School Breakfast
Program minimum requirements, consisted of dry cereal (3/4 cup
unsweetened), milk (2% fat, 8 ﬂuid ounces), toast (1 slice made from
enriched white bread, plain), and applesauce (1/2 cup, unsweetened).
This breakfast contained 14 g protein, 6 g fat, and 57 g carbohydrate
(340 cal: 17, 16, and 67% from protein, fat and carbohydrate,
respectively) [57]. For sedentary preadolescents in the 8 –11 years age
range, the daily estimated energy requirement (EER; averaged across
age and gender) is ~1485 kcal [58]. This breakfast serving therefore
provided ~23% of the daily EER for these subjects, and age-speci ﬁc
values were similar for 8, 9, 10, and 11 year-old children, i.e., 24%, 23%,
23% and 21%, respectively.
Following the break, the children returned to the laboratory and
repeated the test battery. Order of tasks within each session was
randomized across subjects, but within subjects the same order was
maintained across sessions. Those conducting the recordings were
unaware of the children's treatment conditions. In this report the two
testing sessions will be referred to as Phase 1 (all children fasting)
and Phase 2 (either continuing to fast or having eaten breakfast).
The mental arithmetic task was time-regulated and involved
computations of 150 simple problems (75 addition, 75 subtraction,
randomized). The current report is focused on outcome measures
(number correct and response time) and EEG correlates associated
with correctly answered addition problems only. These problems
used single and double digit numbers and none of the computations
required a carry operation. Each problem was presented for 200 ms
on a monitor positioned 1.5 m from the child followed 1 s later by the
simultaneous display of three answers (200 ms; labeled a, b, and c),
one of which was correct. Children sat with their index, middle andringﬁngers of their right hand each resting on a response button.
They were required to press the response button corresponding to
their choice of the correct answer within 1.75 s of answer presenta-
tion offset and earned 2 cents for each correct response. Feedbackwas provided at the end of the response window (a smiling face if
correct and a frowning face if incorrect). The interval from the onset
of one problem to the onset of the next was 5.2 s. Including onescheduled 2 min break, the paradigm required 15 min to complete.
2.3. Data processing and quanti ﬁcation
EEG recordings were digitized at 1024 Hz. All channels were re-
referenced of ﬂine to the mean value of the mastoids and then screened
for blinks (250 μV threshold applied to the fast running average of the
vertical EOG recording) and other high amplitude artifact ( ≥30μVo n
EEG channels). The data were then segmented into 1200 ms trials
beginning 200 ms before, and ending 1000 ms after, stimulus onset.
Data were then down-sampled to 200 samples per/s prior to further
analysis. A continuous wavelet transform (Morlet) [Matlab (Version
R2009b) Signal Processing Toolbox (The Mathworks, Inc.)] was then
applied to single artifact-free trials from bilateral frontal (F3, F4) and
parietal (P3, P4) sites. The wavelet transformation was performed on
the 1200 ms EEG segments in 0.25 Hz steps. The results, expressed as
dB relative to 1 μV
2, were then averaged into 2 Hz bands. Data from the
initial and ﬁnal 200 ms were eliminated to reduce edge effects leaving
wavelet data for the 800 ms following problem presentation onset.
Wavelet analysis was used since it permits examination of changes
in spectral content of EEG signals over time, and therefore might reveal
group differences in mental arithmetic that unfolded across time.
Inspection of the curves of activity for each frequency band across the
800 ms showed that group differentiation was primarily re ﬂected in
sustained level differences across time. Therefore, to simplify data
analysis and presentation, statistical analyses were based on wavelet
data averaged across this 800 ms interval for each of the frequency
bands of interest, i.e., delta (2 –4H z ) ;l o w e r( 4 –6H z )a n du p p e r( 6 –8H z )
theta; and lower (8 –10 Hz) and upper (10 –12 Hz) alpha bands.
2.4. Statistical analyses
Analysis of variance (ANOVA) and t-tests were performed to com-
pare groups on each background variable. Time –frequency data were
analyzed using multivariate and repeated measures ANOVAs and post-
hoc t-tests. Greenhouse –Geisser corrections were made for violations of
sphericity. Covariates were also included to evaluate the in ﬂuence of
variables relevant to mathematical competence (i.e., age, WRAT-3
Arithmetic Scores, Math ﬂuency scores) on brain activity measures.
Data were analyzed using SPSS Statistics 17.0. A value of p≤.05 was
considered statistically signi ﬁcant. Comparisons where .05 bpb.10 are
reported to indicate possible trends.
3. Results
3.1. Background measures
Study groups were well-matched on inclusion criteria, i.e., there
were no signi ﬁcant between-group differences on age, IQ, or BMI
percentile ( Table 1 ). However, children assigned to the fasting group
did have higher WRAT-3 Arithmetic subtest scores than those in the
fedgroup ( p=.01).
As determined from food records and information regarding daily
eating habits, all but one child in each group typically ate breakfast. In
the laboratory 90% (36/40) of the children in the fedgroup consumed
all of the standardized meal, and the remaining 4 children consumed
68%, 81%, 92%, and 97% of the meal. Protocol procedures and testing
schedules were maintained as planned throughout the investigation.550 R.T. Pivik et al. / Physiology & Behavior 106 (2012) 548 –555 Overnight actigraph recordings were not obtained for eight
children (four in each group) because of technical problems. Group
comparisons for the remaining children showed similar amounts of
total sleep time, with both groups averaging more than 8 h of sleep.
Sleep ef ﬁciency (time asleep/total bed time) was greater in fed
children (fasting: 90.9%; fed: 94.8%; p=.005), but since sleep data
were not obtained for all children this measure was not included as acovariate. However, because of the potential impact of this behavior
on daytime performance —especially in children where sleep re-
quirements are greater —analyses were conducted which included
sleep ef ﬁciency among covariates by inserting group averages for
missing sleep data. The results did not alter group-related effects
observed when this measure was not considered, and no group
effects related to sleep ef ﬁciency emerged.
Blood glucose levels upon awakening were in the normal range
and similar across groups. Blood glucose increased signi ﬁcantly within
30 min of eating in fedchildren relative to their initial fasting levels
(pb.001) and compared to those who continued to fast ( pb.001).
Levels remained higher in fedthan fasting children when measured at
lunch time about 2 h after eating breakfast ( pb.001; Table 1 ).
3.2. Performance: correct responses and response time
Within testing phases groups did not differ signi ﬁcantly in the
number of or latency to (response time) correct responses. Across test
phases, children in the fedgroup showed an improvement in the
number of correct responses ( p=.001), and children in the fasting
group showed a decrease in response time ( p=.01; Fig. 1 ).
3.3. Time –frequency analyses
Group averages of frequency speci ﬁc power responses during the
performance of mental addition are presented as a function of scalp
region and test phase in Fig. 2 . Effects common to both groups across
test periods included: greater power in the right than the lefthemisphere; greater power in frontal than parietal regions for 2 –8H z
activity; and greater power in parietal than frontal regions for8–12 Hz activity. With the exceptions of hemispheric comparisons
for delta and broad band theta activity (4 –8 Hz) and frontal –parietal
comparisons for upper theta (6 –8 Hz), these power differences were
statistically signi ﬁcant [F (1, 79) values ranging from 9.88 to 258.72,
allpb.01]. Across bands and sites, power increased signi ﬁ
cantly from
Phase1 to Phase 2 [F (1, 79) values of 7.66 to 97.68, all pb.01].
Signiﬁcant interactions involving group and phase variables included
complex four-way interactions (hemisphere by frontal –parietal by
phase by group) for delta [F (1, 79)=5.71, p=.019] and lower theta
[F (1,79)=5.07, p=.027], as well as phase by group interactions for
upper theta [F (1,79)=10.64, p=.002] and lower alpha [F (1,79)=
9.96, p=.002]. When covariates were considered, statistical signi ﬁ-
cance was maintained for ﬁndings of greater frontal than parietal
delta power across groups and phases [F (1,76)=6.75, p=.011], and
for all the treatment-related interactions noted above, i.e., four-way
interactions for delta [F (1,76)=10.55, p=.002] and lower theta
[F (1, 76)=6.20, p=.02] and phase by group interactions for upper
theta [F (1,76)=9.85, p=.002] and lower alpha [F (1, 76)=8.10,
p=.006].
To focus on within-group treatment effects, analyses with ad-
justments for covariates were performed on the difference between
Phase 2 and Phase 1 power values. These data are presented in Fig. 3 .
In the lower frequency bands signi ﬁcant group-related effects were
found for hemisphere by frontal –parietal by group interactions [delta:
F (1, 76)=11.84, p=.001; lower theta: F (1, 76)=5.57, p=.02]. For
