4. Discussion4.1. General
This study evaluated the effects of a morning meal on complex
mental functions involved in solving arithmetic problems in 8 –11 year
old children. To make this determination EEG activity was recorded
from placements over frontal and parietal regions important for
mathematical functions while children performed mental calculations
of simple addition problems, ﬁrst after overnight fasting and again after
they had either eaten or continued fasting. Frequency-speci ﬁc EEG
measures were adjusted for variables that in ﬂuence or re ﬂect the
development of mathematical skills, i.e., age and measures of mathe-
matical pro ﬁciency. As hypothesized, the ﬁndings indicate that the
efﬁciency of neural networks engaged during mathematical processing
was enhanced in children who had eaten breakfast compared with
those who continued fasting. Furthermore, these effects were asso-
ciated with group-related variations in performance measures, i.e., anincrease in number of correct responses in fedchildren and faster
response times in fasting children. These ﬁndings are discussed below.
4.2. Variations in regional EEG during mental arithmetic
This is the ﬁrst study to apply wavelet analyses to brain activity
generated during mental arithmetic in children, and the ﬁrst to consider
how variations in nutrition may modulate these correlates of mathe-
matical thinking. The few studies of mental calculations in adults using
this method of analysis have involved more complicated mathematical
operations, i.e., two-digit multiplication [59], continuous mental arith-
metic [60], or multiple operators involving addition and subtraction
[61], and have not included measures of nutritional status. However,
comparisons of brain activity during mental arithmetic in children and
adults using various measures [e.g., EEG [31], event-related potentials
[62], and imaging [7]] indicate that neural networks underlying mathe-
matical thinking are similar in children and adults, and that the
development of mathematical skills with experience is re ﬂected by
changes in problem-solving strategies associated with differences in
levels of activation within these networks [7,63] .
Results of the current study are in general agreement with these
developmental observations. For example, given the reported inhib-itory in ﬂuences associated with delta and alpha activity [29,62]
, the
observed greater right hemisphere power for these bands would
promote the left hemisphere emphasis reported for processing of
mathematical information [7,28,64] by reducing neuronal activity in
areas that are not necessary for, or that might interfere with, task
demands. The ﬁnding of greater power at frontal than parietal sites in
lower theta is consistent with the recognized role of theta activity in
frontal processes activated in tasks like mental arithmetic that are
dependent on working memory [45,64,65] , and with the greater
reliance of children on frontal than parietal functions while mathe-
matical skills are developing [8,9,28,51] . It is important to note that
these nutrition-related in ﬂuences are considered to be mediated by
effects on processes fundamental to information processing and
behavior, e.g., attention and working memory, which are tailored to
meet task-demands and in this regard are not speci ﬁc to mental
arithmetic. For example, both common nutrition-related effects and
task-speci ﬁc differences are evident between the ﬁndings of the
present study and those of Pivik and Dykman [21]who used ERS/ERD
methodology to study the effects of morning nutrition on cued visual
continuous task performance (CPT) in fasting andfedchildren. In both
studies fedchildren showed less low alpha synchronization than
fasting children, but interestingly faster response times were observed
infedchildren in the CPT study, but in fasting children in the current
study. The different group response time effects across studies may
reﬂect both task-speci ﬁc and methodological factors.
4.3. Nutritional status, regional EEG and performance
Evaluating the effects of eating or skipping breakfast on mental
arithmetic using frequency band and brain region related difference
scores between Phase 1 and Phase 2 provided a normalized index of
treatment in ﬂuences on EEG measures. These results, adjusted further
for age and measures of math ability, showed that power levels in Phase
2 were either maintained or increased relative to those in Phase 1 for
both groups. These group-common effects may re ﬂect a combination of
factors, including circadian variations in 2 –12 Hz activity across the
morning related to increasing arousal and alertness [66]and increased
attention and effort required by extended testing [67] and mental
fatigue [68]. Similar in ﬂuences were advanced to explain increases in
alpha activity across the morning noted in fasting andfedchildren [21].
Group differences in these between-phase comparisons identify
brain regions and indicate frequency-related neural networks involved
in mathematical thinking that are sensitive to transient variations in
nutritional status in children. The group differences –fasting relative toFig. 3. Treatment effects based on between-phase changes in power. Group means of
Phase 2 relative to Phase 1 values (800 ms averages+SE) are presented for individualfrequency bands for left hemisphere frontal (FL) and parietal (PL) sites and righthemisphere frontal (FR) and parietal (PR) sites. Signi ﬁcant within- and between-group
effects are indicated by brackets with associated probability values. Probability valuesfor Theta 2 and Alpha 1 indicate group main effects.552 R.T. Pivik et al. / Physiology & Behavior 106 (2012) 548 –555 fedchildren –included greater increases in power for upper theta and
both alpha bands across sites and for delta and lower theta at the left
frontal site. Power increases in the higher frequency bands (6 –12 Hz)
have been related to increased working memory [theta: [31,32,36] ]a n d
to the facilitation of task-essential activity by decreasing activity in
regions not necessary for task performance [alpha bands: [44,69] ].
The presence of group differences in the left frontal recordings is
consistent both with the involvement of this region in attention,
working memory, and executive function processes important for
mental arithmetic [8,70] and with reports that increased activation of
frontal processes in children performing mental calculations is
particularly prominent while mathematical skills are still developing
[28,71] .
Studies in adults suggest that the greater left frontal delta and lower
theta power in the fasting group would work to amplify the higher
frequency (6 –12 Hz) effects noted above. These studies indicate that
the increased delta activity may re ﬂect greater activation of processes
that promote attention to internal processing during performance by
suppressing interfering activity [29,30] . The increased theta activity
may represent greater demands on working memory for this mental
function [57,72,73] .
These results are also relevant to strategy-related modulation of EEG
activity during mental arithmetic. Although children in this study were
not questioned regarding strategies used in problem solving, the
consensus is that procedural methods (e.g., counting and transforma-
tion) are used during the development of mathematical skills and direct
memory retrieval becomes more prevalent with greater development
of these skills and working memory capabilities [74,75] . Studies based
on ERS/ERD methods in adults showing increased theta activity in
association with computation of simple addition problems have
attributed this to memory retrieval processes [72,76] . Since children
do not rely heavily on direct retrieval of rote knowledge for problem
solving, the observed theta increases likely indicate greater mental
effort associated with working memory processes as opposed to in-
creases associated with direct memory retrieval.
Studies in adults [72,76] have also reported reduced alpha activity
during computation of simple mathematical problems —unlike the
increased alpha activity observed in the present study. While these
age-related effects may in part re ﬂect differences in methods of
analysis (ERS/ERD vs. treatment-related differences), it may also bethat with development the ef ﬁciency of neural systems involved in
processing mathematical information decreases the extent to which
alpha-related suppressive effects are required. It remains unclear,
however, whether similar dietary variations in adults would provoke
the frequency-related processing relationships observed in children
in this study.
Considered together, the observed general and region-speci ﬁc
ﬁndings suggest that brain processes involved in mathematical thinking
are facilitated in children who eat breakfast compared with those who
skip breakfast. The fasting-related effects did indicate increases in
functions that serve to enhance information processing, i.e., attention
(upper alpha), working memory (theta), and suppression of non-
essential or potentially interfering neural activity (delta and lower
alpha). However, since these effects were not associated with improved
performance they may represent compensatory responses required to
maintain performance at baseline (pre-treatment) levels in response to
fasting. Although response times to the selection of answers were
improved in fasting children —an effect that could have been in ﬂuenced
by increased arousal associated with fasting
[77] —this performance
measure involves processes subsequent to those involved in mental
calculation, such as long-term memory and visual search [78].
The emphasis on memory-related functions for theta and
inhibitory functions for delta and alpha in the interpretation of the
results provides a plausible, parsimonious integration of treatment-
related EEG and behavioral ﬁndings. However, these frequency bands
have other functional correlates that could be meaningfully related toprocesses underlying mathematical thinking. For example, theta
activity has been shown to increase during the processing of semantic
information [35] and, since mathematical thinking also relies on
semantic processes [79], the observed treatment-related increases in
theta bands may in part re ﬂect semantic information processing
correlates of this activity. Both delta and alpha synchronization have
also been related to processes other than inhibition that could becontributing to the increases in these frequency bands across test
phases. Increased delta activity has been associated with the ac-
tivation of working memory processes [30,73] , and increased alpha
with high internal processing demands [80], with working memory
[81], and access to memory traces [48]. Although it is not possible to
disentangle the contributions these various correlates may make to
theﬁndings, the conclusion remains: children who continue fasting
require greater activation of processes associated with these EEG
frequencies than those who have eaten breakfast to maintain
performance accuracy at the Phase 1 level.
In terms of the contribution of speci ﬁc meal nutrients to the study
results, an in ﬂuential role for carbohydrates is suggested by the sig-
niﬁcant group difference in blood glucose at the start of Phase 2
testing. Blood-borne glucose is considered to be the most important
energy source for the central nervous system [82–84] and is
fundamental to cognitive activity [14,49] including mental arithmetic
[12]. Administration of the math paradigm occurred within a post-
meal time window when bene ﬁcial behavioral effects of increased
blood glucose levels are likely to be present since levels had not
signiﬁcantly declined at the time the third sample was taken 2 h after
the breakfast meal.
4.4. Other dietary factors
Other dietary factors that may have in ﬂuenced the results include
nutrient –nutrient interactions (e.g., carbohydrate to protein balance)
and their effects on synthesis of brain neurotransmitters. Meals rich in
carbohydrates increase serotonin synthesis while those rich in protein
increase dopamine and norepinephrine synthesis [85]. These neuro-
transmitter systems are involved in the regulation of functions im-
portant for mental arithmetic such as attention and memory processes
[86,87] , often, however, with oppositional effects. For example, alert-
ness is facilitated by greater levels of dopamine but may be decreased
by increased levels of serotonin [88]. Furthermore, small amounts of
protein in a meal can attenuate the serotonin-promoting effects of
carbohydrates [89]. In the present study facilitating effects on mathe-
matical cognition were observed following a breakfast meal that
contained proportionately more carbohydrates than proteins (~4:1
ratio). In a study in adults, Fischer and colleagues [90]
reported
improved attention and decision times within the ﬁrst hour after
eating a breakfast meal containing a similar balance of carbohydrates-
to-proteins. These effects were not accompanied by increases in blood
levels of the serotonin precursor tryptophan which was presumably
blocked by the protein content of the meal. This would serve to
promote the cognitive enhancing effects of food-induced glucose on
brain function. It is plausible that a similar effect contributed to the
positive neurocognitive effects observed in this study.
5. Caveats and conclusions
The results indicate a coherent set of effects on neural networks
involved in mental arithmetic related to the presence or absence of
morning nutrition in children, but there are aspects of the study design
that may have served to attenuate treatment differences. For example,
greater differences between fedand fasting children might have been
observed if the breakfast meal (340 cal) had been more substantial. The
USDA School Breakfast Program recommends a minimum 554 cal meal
for 8 –11 year old children. Furthermore, the in ﬂuence of meal size
may have been compounded by having children eat at mid-morning —553 R.T. Pivik et al. / Physiology & Behavior 106 (2012) 548 –555 thereby increasing pre-breakfast fasting in ﬂuences. It could also be that
the addition problems presented may not have been challenging
enough to reveal greater treatment-related performance differences.
In this regard, it is not possible to determine the extent to which the
observed error rates that averaged 23% across groups and test phases
reﬂected dif ﬁculties with calculation independent of the in ﬂuence of
the demanding time-related features of the task, i.e., brief time periodsfor viewing problems and answers (200 ms each) and for selecting
answers (1.75 s after offset of answer options).
The above considerations point out aspects of the study design that
might have been modi ﬁed to more effectively demonstrate the effects
of morning nutrition on a complex cognitive function in children.
However, the study design was strengthened by features that, if left
uncontrolled, could signi ﬁcantly impact brain function and perfor-
mance independent of nutritional status. These include: documenting
sleep amount and quality the night before morning testing to ensure
study measures were not compromised by the effects of sleep
deprivation [91]; conducting morning sessions according to a prescribed
schedule that controlled for time-of-day in ﬂuences and intervals
between dietary manipulations and assessments; and maintaining
dietary and physical activity control the evening and morning before
assessments.
In summary, the results suggest that eating breakfast facilitates
brain processes involved in mathematical thinking in children. This
conclusion is supported by ﬁndings showing that during mental
calculation neural network activity involved in processing numerical
information is functionally enhanced and related to improved per-
formance in children who have eaten breakfast, and that greater
mental effort is required for this mathematical thinking in children
who skip breakfast. However, the time window used in these anal-
yses encompassed multiple processes involved in mathematical cal-
culations, e.g., the perception and recognition of digits, the retrieval
or calculation of the answer, and the storage of this answer in
memory in preparation of selecting the correct answer from among
those presented. It will be important for future studies to determine
the extent to which these different stages of mathematical informa-
tion processing may be selectively in ﬂuenced by morning nutrition in
children.
