Evaluating the effect of mathematical anxiety in healthy subjects on brain signal using swLORETA analysis.pdf,2025,2,1,Evaluating the effect of mathematical anxiety in healthy subjects on brain signal using swLORETA analysis.pdf,"Evaluating the effect of mathematical anxiety in healthy subjects 
on brain signal using swLORETA analysis
Parisa Ghafourian , Majid Ghoshuni*,1, Iraj Vosough
Department of Biomedical Engineering, Ma.C., Islamic Azad University, Mashhad, Iran
ARTICLE INFO
Keywords:
Math anxiety
Electroencephalography
SwLORETA analysis
Theta/Beta ratioABSTRACT
Recent studies indicate that high test anxiety lowers students ’ exam grades, making its diagnosis 
crucial for academic progress. 22 volunteers consisting of 9 men and 13 women with an average 
age of 24.195 years old and a standard deviation of 2.25 were randomly put in two “test” and 
“control ” groups. An electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded in 19 channels from all partici -
pants while they had their eyes open and were simultaneously taking the mental math test. Theta 
to beta power ratio for all Brodmann areas in relaxing and anxiety states was extracted and 
examined by employing the non-parametric statistics of the Wilcoxon signed-rank test. The 
swLORETA analysis revealed a significant difference (p D0.05) in the temporal, insular, and 
parietal lobes between the resting state and the math task in the test group. The temporal lobe 
processes language and auditory information, the parietal lobe manages awareness and sensory 
processing, and the insular cortex aids in decision-making. Therefore, understanding auditory and 
environmental information can play an influential role in people ’s performance during a math 
test.
1.Introduction
Recent research has shown that anxiety disorders have the largest share of frequency among people worldwide (Arghavanian, 
Khanjani, & Poursharifi, 2010 ). Anxiety is defined as being worried and apprehensive about a potential future threat (Atabek et al., 
2022 ). One underlying ground of anxiety is intolerance of uncertainty among human beings. In fact, anyone has faced anxiety in their 
lifetime, and it goes hand in hand with some physical symptoms caused by the autonomic nervous system, such as headache, 
perspiration, heart palpitations, chest tightness, and slightly upset stomach, which may differ from one person to another( Sadock, 
2015 ).
Exam anxiety is a subcategory of anxiety (Cassady & Johnson, 2002; Hong, 1999; King, Ollendick, & Gullone, 1990; Morris & 
Mather, 2008 ) and is a specific type of trait anxiety (Zeidner, 1998 ). Trait anxiety is described as people ’s tendency to experience 
anxiety. People with high trait anxiety perceive events as more frightening to themselves than others (Morales, 2012 ). A low amount of 
anxiety in students is beneficial and makes them stay more alert, but it causes students to lose concentration if this amount exceeds. As 
Yerkes-Dodson (Nickerson, 2021 ) puts it, stimulation boosts individuals ’ performance to a degree. In other words, learners who go 
through small doses of anxiety before the exam are more focused and recall the information better in their courses. Nonetheless, if the 
anxiety transcends, it distracts them from grasping what they are studying (Buchwald & Schwarzer, 2010 ). Based on numerous studies 
