0023-9690/©  2025  Elsevier  Inc. All rights  are reserved,  including  those  for text and data mining,  AI training,  and similar  technologies.   (Putwain & Daly, 2014 ; Thomas, Cassady, & Finch, 2018 ), 15–22 percent of the student population has undergone high levels of test 
anxiety. High-level amounts of test anxiety are significantly associated with low grades in students ’ academic performance( Cassady & 
Johnson, 2002 ; Hong, 1999 ; King et al., 1990 ; Von der Embse, Jester, Roy, & Post, 2018 ). Future uncertainties and fear of failure 
among students trigger anxiety, for students usually tend to succeed in education (Atabek et al., 2022 ). Studies have shown that 
anxiety impedes learning( ¯Simi˘c & Manenica, 2012 ) and reasoning skills in students( Atabek et al., 2022 ), and it may bring about school 
leavers (King et al., 1990; Morris & Mather, 2008 ). In addition, it heightens anxiety disorders and depression (Leadbeater, Thompson, 
& Gruppuso, 2012 ), so timely diagnosis is crucial to put a stop to the struggles of students with anxiety in their learning and academic 
progress (Klados, Paraskevopoulos, Pandria, & Bamidis, 2019 ). The outcome of studies showed that when teenagers took arithmetic 
exams with a high level of math anxiety, it took them more time to examine math questions than those with lower math anxiety 
(Atabek et al., 2022 ), which indicates that these students have attentional control deficits (Huang, Hou, Zhang, & Zhou, 2022; 
Su˘arez-Pellicioni, Nú~nez-Pe ~na, & Colom ˘e, 2013 ). As a result, they paid more heed to answering the questions (Eysenck & Calvo, 1992 ). 
Moreover, Individuals with high math anxiety have deficiencies in the top-down goal-oriented attention system (Eysenck, Derakshan, 
Santos, & Calvo, 2007 ). An analysis depicted an inverse correlation between state anxiety and mathematics progress at all core ex-
ecutive functions and cognitive processes levels. Children with higher inhibitory control and cognitive flexibility were more prone to 
math anxiety( Orbach, Herzog, & Fritz, 2020 ). Ultimately, math anxiety and math performance have a considerable influence on one 
another, especially in tasks that require more attention resources such as calculation accuracy and speed, to name but a few 
(Commodari & La Rosa, 2021 ).
The electroencephalogram (EEG) is one of the non-invasive electromagnetic methods that directly measure the activities inside the 
brain. In fact, it measures the activity of neurons using the electrical potential produced by them (Hamalainen, Hari, Ilmoniemi, 
Knuutila, & Lounasmaa, 1993; Wierenga, 1993 ). EEG has been used as an accurate and reliable method to evaluate the level of anxiety 
and attention of people taking a test (Batashvili, Staples, Baker, & Sheffield, 2019; Demerdzieva & Pop-Jordanova, 2015; Klados et al., 
2019; Putman, Verkuil, Arias-Garcia, Pantazi, & van Schie, 2014 ). The beta band plays a key role in increasing the neural repre -
sentation of sensory input, processing stimuli, and controlling attention from top to bottom (Buschman & Miller, 2007, 2009 ). In the 
study of Huawei (Wei, Chang, Huang, & Zhou, 2020 ), a meaningful correlation between the parietal theta to the beta ratio test scores 
and anxiety was shown before the test. There was a significant difference between the theta-to-beta ratio in the parietal lobe of people 
with high test anxiety compared to those with low test anxiety in both test phases. Also, people with high test anxiety tend to have 
adverse cognitive impairments, and people with a high theta-to-beta ratio suffer from lower attention control (Putman, van Peer, 
Maimari, & van der Werff, 2010 ). In addition, a high ratio of theta to beta or an increase in it while performing a mental task causes a 
decrease in cognitive performance and attention (Putman et al., 2010; Putman et al., 2014 ). Moreover, Putman proved that (Putman 
et al., 2014 ) people with increased theta-to-beta ratio who were doing the math test had committed more mistakes. Furthermore, a rise 
in the alpha band indicates a drop in accuracy, and a decrease in alpha signals an increase in alertness (Demerdzieva & Pop-Jordanova, 
2015; Field, Diego, & Hernandez-Reif, 2010; Field et al., 1996 ). Additionally, people with high math anxiety have more beta band 
fluctuations. In other words, these people are more focused when solving mathematical questions (Liu, Li, Peng, Feng, & Luo, 2019 ).
On top of that, several studies show the activity of the gamma band of brain waves related to math anxiety (Oathes et al., 2008; 
Schneider et al., 2018 ). People with high math anxiety have more gamma band activity than those with low math anxiety. These 
people had more training in the gamma band in the face of mathematical stimuli (Batashvili et al., 2019 ), possibly due to negative 
emotional incitements (Schneider et al., 2018; Wei et al., 2020 ). It has been proposed in an article (Batashvili et al., 2019 ) that in terms 
of math anxiety, anxious people who were exposed to numerical stimuli showed more gamma activity, which is apparently due to the 
prediction of mathematical stimulants during the test (Liu et al., 2019; Oathes et al., 2008; Schneider et al., 2018 ).
EEG provides high temporal resolution; however, it lacks the spatial resolution necessary to identify deep brain areas accurately 
(Palmero Soler, 2016 ). In contrast, methods like fMRI and MRI provide good spatial resolution but have limitations in temporal 
resolution. They are also costly and not always readily accessible (Lin et al., 2021 ). LORETA is a low-resolution electromagnetic to-
mography for brain source localization that creates a 3D image of the brain and is a functional imaging technique based on electro -
physiological and neuroanatomical constraints. LORETA can be used for many cognitive neuroscience applications, such as data 
analysis of epilepsy (Pascual-Marqui, Esslen, Kochi, & Lehmann, 2002 ), in which localization inference is based on current density 
images. LORETA provides the localization of electrical activity in the brain based on multi-channel surface EEG that records shifts. 
Instead of estimating point dipoles, it calculates a current distribution in the entire brain volume (Pascual-Marqui, Michel, & Lehmann, 
1994 ). The measurement of EEG signals from the scalp area does not directly show the location of the sources of electrical activity 
inside the cerebral cortex. Therefore, it is necessary to use mathematical tools to determine the location of the neural generators of 
those activities. To solve this problem, Standardized LORETA (sLORETA), which is a newer version (Ocklenburg, Güntürkün, & Beste, 
2012 ) of LORETA, was used. It can accurately locate point sources and provide important information about the time course and 
location of brain activity, and it contains 6430 voxels (Pascual-Marqui, 2002 ). sLORETA validation was performed independently with 
fMRI, MRI, and PET (Jaworska, Blier, Fusee, & Knott, 2012 ). sLORETA can also be used in various neuroscience, cognitive, and 
behavioral applications, encompassing the diagnosis of various brain disorders (epilepsy, depression, stress, sleep disorders, etc.) 
(Pascual-Marqui, 2002; Pizzagalli et al., 2002 ).
Based on our knowledge, the standardized weighted LORETA (swLORETA) technique is the best solution to the inverse EEG 
problem that incorporates a singular value decomposition (SVD)-based lead field-weighting method (Proverbio, De Benedetto, & 
Guazzone, 2020 ). The advantage of swLORETA over traditional sLORETA or LORETA lies in its ability to provide accurate re-
constructions of both surface and deep sources, even under noisy conditions or when multiple brain areas are simultaneously activated 
(Brevers et al., 2020; Palmero-Soler, Dolan, Hadamschek, & Tass, 2007 ). This capability is particularly essential for our study, as it 
allows for the identification of brain regions involved in mathematical anxiety, contributing to a deeper understanding of the neural P. Ghafourian et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                   Learning  and Motivation  90 (2025)  102130  
2  correlates associated with this condition. Specifically, the accuracy of swLORETA results in deep brain regions is highly consistent with 
fMRI and PET (Oakes et al., 2004; Seeck et al., 1998 ). This technology measures surface EEG and uses fMRI templates to identify brain 
regions (Palmero-Soler, Dolan, Hadamschek, & Tass, 2007 ). To solve the inverse problem in swLORETA, a weighting matrix is used to 
adjust the influence of each dipole on the potential measurements. This matrix is adjusted based on the characteristics of the data and 
the desired resources (Palmero-Soler, Dolan, Hadamschek, & Tass, 2007 ). Consequently, our use of swLORETA aims to uncover im-
mediate changes in brain activity linked to mathematical anxiety, facilitating a better comprehension of how the brain reacts during 
anxiety-inducing situations. This understanding is necessary for developing targeted interventions. In summary, swLORETA is an 
appropriate and effective method for estimating the neural activity related to anxiety in brief periods, which aligns with the objectives 
of our study.
In Knyazev’s study, in a non-clinical sample, the effect of trait anxiety symptoms along with the perception of facial emotional 
expressions was investigated, and the results of swLORETA showed an increase in the alpha band in the Premotor Cortex Brodmann 
area 6 (BA. 6), which is essential to planning and movement preparation. The results showed that anxiety is related to the Hyper- 
reactive attention system, so it is reduced by increased event-related alpha desynchronization and reduced theta synchronization 
(Knyazev, Savostyanov, Bocharov, & Rimareva, 2016 ).
By considering previous research efforts mentioned in the literature review, this study aims to investigate the effect of anxiety on 
people’s performance and then the functional difference of the deep brain areas between the two test and control groups during the 
implementation of the mental math test using the swLORETA. Considering the impact of test anxiety on cognitive efficiency and the 
importance of understanding its neural mechanisms, this method will be employed to assess brain activity.
Our first hypothesis is that while anxiety may not significantly impact test performance, it can induce significant changes in brain 
activity across different regions. Additionally, this study hypothesizes that inducing anxiety in test group will lead to a decrease in the 
theta to beta ratio, thereby enhancing attention levels, as analyzed through swLORETA.
2.Materials and methods
2.1. Participants
First, 100 undergraduate and graduate students of the Islamic Azad University of Mashhad engineering faculty were given the 
Speilberger State–Trait Anxiety Inventory (Spielberger, Gonzalez-Reigosa, Martinez-Urrutia, Natalicio, & Natalicio, 1971 ). Among 
them, those whose Spielberger anxiety score was in the range of 30–50 were selected to participate in this study. Finally, 22 subjects (9 
men and 13 women) with an average age of 24.195 and a standard deviation of 2.25 years participated in the mental math test and EEG 
signal recording. This study assumes that individuals do not exhibit significant differences in their anxiety and ASRS questionnaire 
results, meaning all participants have a similar baseline level of anxiety. Subsequently, they were randomly assigned to either the test 
group or the control group.
2.2. EEG recording
Data was collected using a nineteen-channel brainwave recording device, Mitsar-202 (Mitsar Co. Ltd. Saint Petersburg, Russia). The 
placement of the electrodes on the head was in accordance with the international standard 10–20 system. The recording was unipolar 
compared to the average reference of the two ears model by filtering between 0.5 and 75 Hz. The data acquisition channels include 
Fp1-Fp2-F3-F4-C3-C4-P3-P4-O1-O2-F7-F8-T3-T4-T5-T6-Fz-Pz-Cz. In this research, the Electrocap and the injection of Elecreo_Gel 
have been used to reduce the impedance of the scalp to 5 kOhms to record the EEG signal. Electrodes were applied using caps 
manufactured by Electro-cap International, Inc (http://www.electro-cap.com/caps.htm ). The signals are sampled at a rate of 250 Hz. 
The data collection was accomplished in a designated room for recording signals in the medical engineering laboratory of the engi-
neering faculty of the Islamic Azad University of Mashhad, a quiet place away from all outside noises.
It should be noted that all participants were right-handed, and all participants were asked to refrain from smoking and consuming 
caffeinated beverages or sedatives that affect brain activity 12 hours before the test. Also, before starting the EEG recording, the 
participants were asked to remove any jewelry, communication devices, and watches and avoid talking, sleeping, or excessive body 
movements that cause noise during the recording. In addition, they were encouraged to put their body in a relaxed and tension-free 
position in the first minutes. All people were given explanations about the test process and how to record brain waves before starting 
the test.
At first, the person was asked to keep their eyes open for 2 minutes in a resting state without performing any specific tasks, ensuring 
they refrained from any mental activity or cognitive engagement. In this state, the EEG baseline was recorded, allowing for a com-
parison of brain activity between the resting state and the anxiety-inducing task. In the next step, a mental math test was taken from the 
individual simultaneously with the brain signal. In this test, whenever a person wrongly answers a question, the proctor warns them to 
increase accuracy and concentrate on answering the questions correctly, and the answer is considered incorrect.
2.3. Spielberger and adult ADHD self-report scale (ASRS) questionnaire
Before initiating the experiment, the Spielberger anxiety questionnaire was given to the participants. This questionnaire consisted 
of 40 questions, the first twenty of which were related to measuring people’s state anxiety, and the 20 following questions were about 
their trait anxiety. A special effort has been put into having acceptable results by designing a questionnaire based on standards such as P. Ghafourian et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                   Learning  and Motivation  90 (2025)  102130  
3  clarity of questions, comprehensibility, facile interpretation, and research. According to Mahram (Mahram, 1994 ), the reliability of 
this test was validated through Cronbach’s alpha formula, which is equal to 0.94. Comparing the average anxieties of the norm and 
reference groups (the group of anxious people visiting psychiatric offices and clinics) in all age groups proves that the coefficient is 
significant at two levels of 0.05 and 0.01, indicating the validity of the test in measuring anxiety. In the scoring scale for evaluating 
state and trait anxiety, scores between 20 and 30 are equivalent to no anxiety or minimal anxiety, 30–40 are mild anxiety, 40–50 are 
moderate anxiety, and more than 50 define severe anxiety (Fathi-Ashtiani & Dastani, 2009 ). After completing the questionnaire ac-
cording to the selected options and evaluating the participants’ answers, they were asked to participate in the brain signal recording 
test if the questionnaire score was 30–50 (mild to moderate anxiety).
In the next step, the preparation forms for participation in the test, written consent form, demographic information, and Adult 
ADHD Self-Report Scale (ASRS) forms are completed by them. ASRS scale questions are consistent with the Diagnostic and Statistical 
Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM-V) criteria, and this scale includes two categories and 18 questions. There are nine questions for the 
category of inattention and nine questions for hyperactivity/impulsivity (Kessler et al., 2005 ). In Mokhtari et al.’s research (Mokhtari, 
Rabiei, & Salimi, 2015 ), the reliability of the questionnaire using Cronbach’s alpha method was 0.87. Its sensitivity, with a cut-off point 
of 50 for diagnosing attention deficit and hyperactivity in adults was 70 %, and the specificity of the questionnaire was 99 % (Moezzi, 
Ghoshuni, & Amiri, 2023 ).
2.4. Performing mental math test
This test lasted 13 minutes, and at first, math questions were read to the participants. Then, they were given 6 seconds to think, and 
two options were available to them, and the participant must choose one of them as the correct answer. Meanwhile, the participant is 
told that it is impossible to calculate the answer to the question using hand, paper, or a calculator. The math test used in this research 
was similar to that used by Putman (Putman et al., 2014 ). A total of 30 math questions were designed, including 15 easy and 15 
challenging questions. The order of test questions was designed to maintain the participants’ attention. The test began with five easy 
questions, followed by five difficult ones, and this pattern was repeated, alternating between five easy and five difficult questions. This 
sequence was repeated for three trials.
However, in the test group, the conditions were more frightful: the participants were only allowed to read the questions once. 
During the test, they were tricked into being filmed by a fake camera and told that their video would be evaluated. They were also 
reminded to be careful not to answer the questions incorrectly. In addition, if the test group could not answer the question within the 
given time, they would not receive any score for that question, whereas there was no such restriction in the control group. Indeed, 
anxiety was further induced in the test group through questioning interventions by a stern observer, fake videotaping, and strict time 
constraints, none of which were imposed on the control group.
2.5. EEG signal processing
WinEEG software has been utilized for noise and motion artifact removal from the EEG signal. The effect of eye blinking in the EEG 
signal has been removed using the independent component analysis (ICA) method. To remove the motion artifact noises, bands pass 
digital filters with a low frequency of 0.3 Hz and a high frequency of 70 Hz have been employed. Also, a Notch filter at 45–55 Hz 
removes line interference noise. Then, Parts of the signal that had artifacts were removed manually.
Neuroguide software, a quantitative EEG (QEEG) analysis system that utilizes the Talairach MRI Atlas, is designed for brain 
mapping techniques such as LORETA and swLORETA. It can also calculate time and frequency details (Applied Neuroscience, Inc., St. 
Petersburg, FL, USA). EEG signals without artifacts are transformed in Neuroguide 3.0.8.1 software and subsequently processed with 
Neuronavigator software for swLORETA (http://appliedneuroscience.com ) and converting them to current source density (CSD) 
across the theta (4–8 Hz) and beta (12–25 Hz) frequency bands. In Neuroguide’s Neuronavigator software, the swLORETA utilizes a 
grid comprising 12470 voxels. This represents a significant enhancement over the earlier Key Institute sLORETA viewer, which 
employed only 6430 voxels. The increased voxel count in swLORETA allows for higher spatial resolution, enabling more precise 
localization of electrical activity sources within the brain.
For signal processing, an interval of 60–120 seconds is selected, as it provides a balance between capturing stable neural activity 
and minimizing the effects of non-stationarity in EEG signals. This duration ensures sufficient data for reliable source localization while 
avoiding excessive artifacts or signal drift (Pascual-Marqui, 2002; Babiloni et al., 2004 ).
Then the activity of EEG frequency bands in different Brodmann Areas (BA) was obtained for each subject. Finally, the data was 
exported to MATLAB software to determine each BA’s theta (4–8 Hz) to the beta (12–25 Hz) band ratio. The significant BAs between 
the control and test groups were extracted in the state of the mental math test and resting mode using Statistical Package for the Social 
Sciences (SPSS)-software (SPSS 18.0 for Windows; SPSS inc).
2.6. swLORETA method
The swLORETA calculation is fully described in the Palmero-Soler study (Palmero Soler, 2016 ). However, a brief explanation of the 
calculation is given in this section.
Different neurons can generate a similar electric field in the brain (Helmholtz, 1853 ), that is very difficult to determine which area 
is activated, so the inverse solution should be used (Palmero-Soler et al., 2007 ). SwLORETA is used to compensate for the various 
sensitivity of sensors in different depths.P. Ghafourian et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                   Learning  and Motivation  90 (2025)  102130  
