3.Results
3.1. The results of the ASRS and Spielberger questionnaire
As seen in Table 1, after employing independent sample t-test, there was no significant difference in the Spielberger anxiety and the 
ASRS questionnaire between the test and control groups.
3.2. Mental math test results
According to the results of the mental math test in Table 2, no significant difference has been observed between the two test and 
control groups, and the average correct answers are not substantial.
3.3. Statistical results
In this study, the Shapiro-Wilk test was used to evaluate the normality of the distribution of variables. According to the obtained 
results, pD0.05 has been attained. Therefore, the assumption of the normal distribution is rejected. As a result, the non-parametric 
Wilcoxon test was deployed to analyze the data. According to the outcome, in Table 3, a significant difference was obtained between 
the resting and the math test state in the test group in the following BAs. Still, no significant difference was observed between the 
control group ’s resting and the math test state.
3.4. swLORETA analysis results
The results of the swLORETA analysis are divided into three categories based on the obtained BA regions. Fig. 1compares the 
median of theta to the beta ratio in the post-central gyrus region between the test and control groups in the resting and the math test 
modes. Fig. 1-a is related to BA 1 on the left side of the head. Fig. 1-b is shown BA 1 on the right side of the head. Fig. 1-c is BA 2 on the 
left side of the head. Fig. 1-d is related to BA 2 region on the right side of the head. Fig. 1-e is BA 3 region on the left side of the head. In 
the test group, a significant
difference (pD0.05) was observed between resting and math conditions in BA 1, as well as in the left BA 2 and BA 3, whereas no 
significant difference was found in the control group. However, in the right BA 2, a highly significant difference (pD0.01) was 
observed in the test group. Fig. 2compares the median of theta to the beta ratio in the insular cortex between the test and control group 
