4.Discussion
This study investigates one of the anxiety disorders called test anxiety. The aim of this study was to explore the effect of test anxiety 
on the performance of healthy subjects while performing a mental math test. The theta to the beta ratio was examined as an indicator of 
attention deficit (Putman et al., 2014 ). It should be noted that this index may undergo some changes under test anxiety conditions. It 
can also be said that test anxiety is related to irrational cognitive statements and emotional impulses (Hou, Zhang, Huang, & Zhou, 
2022 ). Presuming that the ratio of theta to beta is high, it causes a decline in cognitive performance and people ’s attention (Putman 
et al., 2010; Putman et al., 2014 ). Another study also mentioned a significant difference in the ratio of theta to beta among people who 
had high test anxiety compared to subjects with low test anxiety was observed in the parietal region (Wei et al., 2020 ).
Hence in this study, the average ratio of theta to beta is used to determine the attention level at rest and performing mental math 
tests for two test and control groups for all BAs. Subsequently, the functional difference of the deep brain regions was scrutinized by 
swLORETA, and the non-parametric Wilcoxon method was used for data analysis in SPSS software. Consequently, BAs were identified 
as significant between the two groups in the mental math test and resting state.
The results of several studies showed that the brains of the person with high math anxiety had scattered and unstructured brain 
networks (Büchel et al., 2002; Klados et al., 2019; Zeidan et al., 2011 ). Also, the results of this study indicate that by triggering a small 
amount of anxiety in the subject in the test group, the theta-to-beta ratio dropped, so attention level surged, which is consistent with 
the Yerkes-Dodson law (Nickerson, 2021 ). The outcome of the swLORETA approach has shown that there is a significant difference in 
the ratio of theta to beta in resting and math test mode in the math anxiety group in the areas related to sensory perception (BA1: 
z-2.312, p.021, BA2: z-2.401 p.016, BA3 z-2.312, p.021- Post Central Gyrus); areas related to emotion processing (B. 
A 13: z-2.223, p.026- Posterior Insula); areas involved with the processing of language, hearing and vision (B.A 22:z-2.312, 
p.021 - Temporal Lobe); and the areas related to the processing of neural information of Parahippocampal Gyrus - Uncus and Medial 
Temporal Lobe (B.A 28: z-1.956, p0.050- ventral entorhinal cortex).
In this study, it is shown that test anxiety caused a change in brain activity in the parietal lobe, insular cortex, and temporal areas. 
As shown in the study (Toazza et al., 2022 ), emotions are related to the temporal region, consistent with the results achieved in this 
study, and subjects with anxiety disorders have problems in this region. However, the temporal lobe has an important role in the 
anxiety disorders (Montag, Reuter, Weber, Markett, & Schoene-Bake, 2012 ), auditory information (Shao et al., 2021 ), and under -
standing language (Boles, 1991; Ivanova & Dronkers, 2022 ). In addition, the function of the parietal lobe is to regulate attention (Bian 
et al., 2014 ) and understand sensory information (Santhosh et al., 2020 ). In another study (Fales et al., 2008 ), it was shown that trait 
anxiety brought about a reduction in activity in the prefrontal cortex and parietal regions.
Similar to the survey (Schrammen et al., 2022 ) of subjects who had anxiety disorders after psychotherapy sessions, a decrease in the 
area Posterior insular showed that if they performed computational tasks like study (Arsalidou & Taylor, 2011 ), an increase in this area 
could be seen. Like our study, evidence in several studies suggest that the insula plays a key role in decision-making under conditions of 
uncertainty (Bian et al., 2014; Fales et al., 2008; Santhosh et al., 2020; Schrammen et al., 2022 ). Another study showed that Table 2 
