8  progress, they will increase physical health in students (Atabek et al., 2022; Zhang, Su, Peng, Yang, & Cheng, 2011 ).
5.Conclusion
The results of swLORETA analysis confirm that in all the temporal, insular, and parietal lobes in the test group between the resting 
and the math test state, there was a significant difference (pD0.05) between theta to beta ratio showing attention level. According to 
the study, the temporal lobe is responsible for understanding language and perception and processing auditory information. The 
parietal lobe processes attentional awareness of the environment and understanding of sensory information. Ultimately, the insular 
cortex is vital to process surrounding information and decision-making. So, understanding auditory and environmental information 
can play an influential role in people ’s performance during math tests. From a broader perspective, brain functions result from complex 
interactions among multiple regions, so the specific areas identified in this study through swLORETA analysis should not be assumed to 
correspond directly to distinct functions. Instead, they may serve as potential indicators for future research exploring the neural 
mechanisms underlying mathematical ability.
One limitation of this study is the low number of participants and the limited age range to look into the effect of test anxiety in 
different ages. Furthermore, due to the limited number of candidates, it is impossible to compare the brain patterns between anxious 
men and women since there was no separate test in this research to do so. Therefore, it is suggested to progress this effort in another 
study for people with medium or high anxiety levels. The effect of anxiety during the test should be compared with this study and 
evaluated using brain indicators. Further studies in the fMRI field are necessary to examine gender and age differences in Brodmann ’s 
areas during test anxiety.
