155processing EEGsignals because relevant features helpaccurately classify
mental tasks. Besides improving accuracy, handcrafted features canhelp
explain mental tasks thathave yettobeexplored considerably. These
features canbeextracted inthetime domain, frequency domain, orboth
time –frequency domain. Theprominent features extracted inthetime
domain arestatistical [19],fourrhombuses lattice pattern (FRLP) [13],
sample entropy (SE)[14],approximate entropy (AE) [20] fusion-based
autoregressive model [21],magnitude squared coherence (MSC) [22],
graph variational auto-encoder (GVAE) [23],andBayesian structural
learning (BSL) [24].Similarly, various features areextracted inthe
frequency domain, such aspower spectral density [PSD] [25],circulant
singular spectrum analysis (C-SSA) [26],3-Dspectral [27],Fourier
decomposition method (FDM) [28],and spectral power (SP) [29].
Moreover, time –frequency features arealsoused formental arithmetic
taskclassification, such aswavelet transform (WT) [30,31] ,robust local
mean decomposition (R-LMD) [32],discrete wavelet transform [DWT]
[3334] ,andshort wavelet transform (SWT) [15].These handcrafted
features have provided considerable classification accuracy using
different classifiers. However, these studies could passively orbarely
represent aclear relationship between theselected features forthe
classification ofmental tasks with thebrain functionality thatinvolves
different regions ofbrain rhythms.
Despite thepronounced success ofexisting techniques onthebrain
state, notable issues anddifficulties stillexist, predominantly theinter-
subject/cross-subject variability, which isthemain hurdle ingeneral-
izing theBCIsystems. Thesolution tointer-subject variability issues
could besubject-dependent models with calibration androbust features-
based subject-independent models. Recently, subject-independent
models have performed better insome studies, such as[35] intro-
ducing meta-learning frameworks toreduce inter-subject variability.
Similarly, [36] discussed thefeasibility ofatransfer learning approach
toreduce subject-dependent calibration [37],butduetotheblack box
nature ofthemodels, itfaces deficiencies ininterpretability. Recently,
transformers have alsobeen combined with deep learning CNN models
toclassify mental arithmetic tasks, and91.23 %classification accuracy
hasbeen achieved [38].However, transformers canbechallenging to
interpret because they aretrained end-to-end anddonothave apparent
intermediate interpretations. Hence, exploring meaningful and
explainable machine learning models thatcanoffer insight isrequired to
deal with inter-subject variability. Machine learning includes trans-
parent models, such asrule-based learners, decision trees, andlinear
regression, andopaque models include random forests, support vector
machines, ormulti-layer neural networks [39].Opaque models achieve
higher accuracy byutilizing complex decision boundaries butatthe
expense ofexplainability. This lackofexplanation could beovercome
using post-ad-hoc explanations, including text,visual, local, byexample,
simplification, andfeature relevance [40].
Thiswork analyzes mental arithmetic tasks using publicly available
datasets [41].Thefeatures ofcognitive tasks areextracted from the
average signals ofallthetrials oftheresting vscalculation andgood vs
bad calculation states ofthebrain. Empirical mode decomposition
(EMD) isused toobtain four intrinsic mode functions (IMFs) ofthe
average signals, andpseudo-inverse isapplied later togettheEMD
features. Redundancy inthefeatures isremoved using arandom forest-
based recursive feature elimination (RF-RFE) feature selection method.
Finally, theclassification ofmental arithmetic tasks isdone byfour
machine learning methods: random forest (RF), support vector machine
(SVM), linear discriminant analysis (LDA), andk-nearest neighbors
(kNN). Ourexplainable feature-based proposed method achieved the
highest generic andinter-subject classification accuracy. Itshowed the
relevance offeatures tothebrain areas andrhythms involved inmental
arithmetic calculation. Thiswork hasmade thefollowing contributions
andfindings:≡Theproposed method introduced theexplainability ofthemachine
learning model ’spredictions formental arithmetic tasks from EEG
signals forthefirsttime intheliterature.
≡Themethod successfully classified themental arithmetic tasks from
EEG, achieving animpressive 99.30 %and98.33 %better classifi-
cation accuracies forresting vscalculation andgood vsbadcalcu-
lation states, respectively, after asystematic comparison with
existing techniques andstate oftheart.
≡Inter-subject variability isafundamental issue faced byBCI; this
study performs exceptionally wellonunseen subjects duetorobust
interpretable features, achieving 98.17±0.47 %and97.19±0.95
%accuracy forresting vscalculation andgood vsbadcalculations,
respectively.
≡EMD features have shown their direct relevance tothebrain regions
involved inmental arithmetic tasks, which have never been
explored.
≡Wealso associated changes inthevarious brain rhythms from
intrinsic mode functions ofEEGsignals totheresting, good, andbad
calculation brain states.
≡Thisstudy alsosuccessfully describes theinvolvement ofmemory in
mental arithmetic andthatwrong calculations cancause frustration,
stress, andanxiety, andgood calculations reveal arelaxed state of
mind.
2.Materialandmethods
Thissection describes data acquisition andmethods used toclassify
resting vscalculation andgood vsbadcalculation mental arithmetic
tasks. Each stepisdescribed asfollows.
2.1.Material
Apublicly available Mental Arithmetic Tasks EEGdataset isused in
thiswork. Thisdataset contains EEGsignals from 36subjects using the
23-channel Neurocom EEGsystem inresting andduring serial subtrac-
tionof4-digit (minuend) and2-digit (subtrahend) numbers ofmental
arithmetic tasks [41].Allthesubjects aredivided into twogroups:
Group “G”(24subjects) performing good-quality calculations and
Group “B”(12subjects) performing bad-quality calculations. Inthis
study, data ofallthesubjects isdivided into 2groups: resting vs
calculation andgood vsbadcalculations. Thedataset consists ofartifact-
freeEEGsignals thatare60sinduration, each recorded from 19elec-
trodes: FP1,FP2,F3,F4,Fz,F7,F8,C3,C4,Cz,P3,P4,Pz,O1,O2,T3,T4,
T5,andT6asshown inFig.1ata500Hzsampling frequency. Thirty
trials arerecorded persubject forboth tasks, i.e.,resting vscalculation,
2160 trials, andgood vsbadcalculation, 1080 trials. Thedataset used
here ispreprocessed using independent component analysis toremove
artifacts such aseyes, muscles, andcardiac pulsations, whereas the
power linenoise isremoved using the50-Hz notch filter.
2.2.Methods
Inthiswork, feature extraction, feature selection, andsupervised
machine-learning classification methods aredeveloped fortheEEG
dataset. Theblock diagram ofthetechniques used here isshown in
Fig.1.Before feature extraction, theaverage ofallthetrials ’signals is
obtained forresting vscalculation andgood vsbadcalculation states.
Extended EMD features oftheaverage signals against each task are
extracted from IMFs. After removing redundancy inthefeatures, mental
tasks areclassified using supervised machine learning algorithms. These
methods arediscussed below.
2.2.1. Feature extraction
