2.2.2.2. Recursive feature elimination using RF.Inthisphase, features
with lowimportance areremoved after obtaining thefeature setwith
high importance. Theremoval offeatures isdone recursively, andthe
importance ofthefeature isupdated ineach iteration. Features with the
highest average importance score based onclassification accuracy are
selected using cross-validation. Thefeature ’simportance value directly
quantifies theinfluences ofeach feature input onthemodel predictions
after ranking. Although these alone cannot beexplained thoroughly,
they canprovide abasis forgaining insight intothemodel ’sreasoning.
Aflow chart ofthealgorithm isshown inFig.1,andthesteps are
given below:
i.Train anRFmodel with kconstituent decision trees.
ii.Assess theclassification accuracy oftheensemble using 5-fold
cross-validation.
iii.Usemean decrease inimpurity (MDI) torank theimportance
IMPaofeach feature ainthefeature set.
iv.Delete thefeature with thelowest importance using backward
sequence selection andrepeat steps itoiiiuntil thefeature setis
empty. Thesubset ofthefeatures with thehighest classification
accuracy isdetermined from cross-validation results.
2.2.3. Classification
Mental arithmetic tasks areclassified using extracted features fedto
supervise traditional machine learning algorithms LDA, SVM, kNN, and
RF.TheSVM isanopaque model, ahigh-level version ofthenon-ruled-
based transparent discriminator. RFistheadvanced form ofthedecision
tree, which isatransparent, rule-based model. Thedecisions ofthese
opaque models areexplained with high-ranked features obtained from
RF-RFE thatarerelated tooneofthemental tasks [39].Thedetails of
each classifier areasfollows.
2.2.3.1. kNN. kNN isanonlinear butsimple classifier that uses
Euclidean distance-based decision boundaries todivide thefeatures into
resting andarithmetic classes. InkNN, atestdata sample iscategorized
byamajority vote ofitsneighbors. Thebestchoice ofkdepends upon
thedata; here, intheproposed work, itischosen 5;generally, larger k
values reduce thenoise ’seffect ontheclassification butmake bound-
aries between classes lessdistinct [25].
2.2.3.2. RF.RFisanensemble nonlinear learning algorithm used in
various studies because itismore precise androbust tonoise than single
classifiers. Itruns efficiently onbigdatasets, canhandle many input
variables, gives estimates ofessential features intheclassification, andis
computationally lessexpensive than other ensemble methods [44].In
RF,each decision ismade using therecursive division ofthetraining set.
Every node tofadecision treeisassociated with asetofntdatasamples
from thetraining set;inthiswork, thechosen node sizeis50,andthe
number oftrees issetto100.
2.2.3.3. SVM. Inmachine learning, SVM isthefamous supervised max-
margin model. Itcreates hyper-planes inhigher dimensions, which are
called decision boundaries. Various kernel tricks have been used inSVM
models tooptimize themargins ofthehyperplane forgood classification
accuracy [46].Intheproposed work, theoriginal linear SVM isused
first. Afterward, theradial basis function (RBF) kernel isalsoused with
thescale kernel coefficient gamma, which canhandle nonlinear decision
boundaries andsimplify classification [47].Besides, thevalue ofregu-
larization parameter Cissetas70,which significantly minimizes the
training error andmaximizes themargin toachieve high classification
accuracy.2.2.3.4. LDA. Finally, asimple linear classifier isalsoused inthiswork.
Using variance andwithin-class variance, LDAusesFisher ’scriterion to
determine theratios between theresting andcalculation andgood and
badmental arithmetic classes [48].Since theclass orlabel infoisused in
thetraining, LDA tries todivide thedata into separate classes. The
hyperparameters, such asgamma issetto0forLDA, tolerance issetto
0.0001, andsingular value decomposition isused asasolver tocompute
theproject matrix.
3.Results
Inthiswork, ananalysis ofmental arithmetic tasks isdone using
publicly available datasets. EMD feature-based explainable machine
learning isused toanalyze theEEGpattern, andthemost relevant fea-
tures with higher feature scores areselected using RF-RFE. Thefeatures
from twosetsofclasses arefedtoSVM, kNN, RF,andLDA machine-
learning algorithms. Detailed performance ofclassifiers, explainable
feature ranking, andinter-subject variability arediscussed inthissec-
tion. Formaximum classification accuracy, 44and54features with high
feature scores have been selected outof152(channels19,features per
channel4,features perclass19x476,total152) using RF-RFE
forresting vscalculation andgood vsbadcalculation tasks, respectively.
