sensory-motor area.4.Discussion
Understanding theconnection between brain rhythms, regions, and
functionalities iscrucial indeveloping EEG-based BCIapplications. In
machine learning, thisunderstanding canonly beachieved iftherele-
vance ofsignificant features tomental tasks forclassification canbe
successfully determined. Inourresearch, wehave extracted explainable
features from EEG signals, directly mapped these features tobrain re-
gions, andidentified changes inbrain rhythms. Asystematic comparison
ofourmethod ’sperformance with existing studies thatused thesame
datasets [41] andsupervised machine learning fortheclassification of
brain resting vscalculation andgood vsbadcalculation states hasbeen
made andsummarized inTable 7.Various performance parameters such
assensitivity, specificity, precision, andF-score ofalltheexisting studies
onmental arithmetic data arereported inTable 7.Ourmethod stands
outforitsunique accurate approach ofdirectly mapping features to
brain regions, ananalysis notfound inexisting studies. Ourmethod
achieved remarkable accuracy, specificity, sensitivity, precision, andF-
score of99.30 %,100%,98.61 %,100%,and99.30 %,respectively.
Itcanbeobserved from Table 7that various studies have been
conducted inthelastfewyears fortheclassification ofresting vs
calculation. Compared tothestate oftheart[27],theproposed method
achieved better generic classification accuracy of99.30 %vs98.81 %,
whereas other performance parameters arenotreported inthestudy.
They used 3Dspectral features andCNN-LSTM models forclassification,
which arecomputationally complex andlessefficient than theproposed
method. Besides, [27] didnotreport thecross-subject variability test
results, andmapping ofthemachine learning model, tothebrain regions
formental arithmetic tasks hasnotbeen discussed. However, they
provided avisual presentation addressing thechange inthepower of
frequency bands inthebrain ’sfrontal andprefrontal [69],occipital, and
parietal lobes, consistent with theresults summarized inTable 5and
demonstrated inFig.7.Similarly, [28,33] ,and[15] have alsoreported
accuracies of98.60 %,98.10 %,and98%,using FDM, DWT, andSWT
features, respectively. [33] and[15] have shown thesensitivity and
precision of80.56 %,80.86 %,97%,and97%,respectively, besides,
[15] hasshown theF-score value of98%.These features extraction
methods, likeEMD, decompose signals intovarying frequency compo-
nents over time butusefixed basis functions. Whereas EMD isdata-
driven, creating itsbasis functions byadapting complex signal struc-
tures andgenerating amore relevant feature setthatcancapture the
changes insignal against mental arithmetic tasks [70].Nevertheless,
these methods didnotdiscuss andpresent theinter-subject variability
results, andnorelationship between theobtained features andthebrain
regions andrhythms hasbeen shown. Also, [14,23,26] ,and[21] haveTable5
