Afewother studies thatclassified resting vscalculation have also
discussed theactivity ofthebrain regions. These include [25,19,29] ,and
[24],which achieved 75%,92.5 %,84 –100%,and91%generic clas-
sification accuracy, respectively. Only [19] from thissetofstudies have
reported 82.2 %,92.5 %,75.7 %,and83.2 %ofspecificity, sensitivity,
precision, and F-score values, respectively. Moreover, these studies
could notreport inter-subject variability, except [25],which reported an
accuracy of72%,significantly lessthan 98.17 %ofourproposed
method. Inaddition, theauthors showed thatPSDfeatures have higher
values inthebrain ’sleftfrontal, center, andparietal areas against
mental arithmetic tasks. Thisisconsistent with thefindings inthepro-
posed work, especially inthefrontal lobe channels F4andFP1, which
played acrucial roleinincreasing theclassification accuracy ofthe
resting vscalculation state ofthebrain, asshown inTable 5.Similarly,
[19] hasalsodemonstrated thatfrontal regions F1andF8areinvolved
inmental arithmetic using statistical features, which iscoherent with
theoutcomes ofourproposed method. Moreover, [29] associated the
spectral power oftheta, beta, andgamma bands forresting vscalcula-
tion, which showed asignificant difference, consistent with ourpro-
posed method fortheta andgamma bands shown inFig.7.Similarly,
[24] hasalsoconfirmed thattheta andbetahave aprominent difference
between resting andmental arithmetic states ofthebrain using BSL
features, which aligns with thefindings oftheproposed method.
Another study [20] reported amaximum testclassification accuracy of99%using approximate entropy (AEN) with anensemble classifier (EC).
Other performance metrics reported inTable 7alsohave thesame value
of99%.These arecloser toourresults reported foraccuracy, specificity,
sensitivity, andprecision, andtheF-score, which are99.30 %,100%,
98.61 %,100%,and99.30 %,respectively. [20] Thestudy didnotbuild
therelationship ofobtained features tothebrain areas andrhythms, and
inter-subject variability isalsonotreported. Lastly, arecent work [32]
hasused R-LMD features toclassify themental arithmetic task using
binary arithmetic optimization (BAO) feature selection methods with
optimum ensemble learning (OEL) classifiers. This study achieved a
classification accuracy of97.4 %with 97%sensitivity and98%spec-
ificity. R-LMD used product functions with amplitude andfrequency,
whereas EMD used IMFs from thefrequency oscillations. Theproposed
feature selection method worked better inachieving thehighest classi-
fication accuracy. Furthermore, [32] didnotreport thecross-subject
accuracy; however, itmentioned thefrontal lobe area asakeypartici-
pant inmental arithmetic tasks, consistent with ourobservations onthe
frontal lobe discussed intheresults sections.
Ourwork alsoincludes classifying good andbadmental arithmetic
tasks, which wecompared with existing techniques andthestate ofthe
art,assummarized inthesecond halfofTable 7.Ourmethod achieved
remarkable accuracy, specificity, sensitivity, precision, andF-score of
98.33 %,100%,96.66 %,100%,and98.30 %,respectively. Amongst
existing methods, [34] achieved thebest classification accuracy of
98.10 %using CNN deep learning models forfeature selection and
BLSTM forclassification. Theauthors alsoreported other performance
metrics likespecificity, sensitivity, precision, andF-score, which are
99.40 %,98.50 %,98.40 %,and98.40 %,respectively. Incontrast, the
proposed method achieved aslightly higher generic classification ac-
curacy of98.33 %,demonstrating theefficiency ofourapproach. More
importantly, theproposed method achieved 97.19 %inter-subject
average accuracy, which isnotreported forthegood vsbadcalcula-
tion arithmetic tasks byanyofthestudies summarized inTable 7.
