5.Conclusion
EEGcould beoneofthebestsources forunderstanding brain func-
tionalities andtheir complexity, specifically inmental arithmetic skills.
Some ofthemost common issues inarithmetic skills arelearning dis-
abilities atanearly ageandtherecent spread ofADHD andautism in
children. While assessing mental arithmetic skills, theproposed method
explored various factors, such asstress asanoutcome ofincorrect cal-
culations andtherole ofworking memory. Weused anexplainable
feature setobtained from acombination ofEMD feature extraction and
RF-REF feature selection methods toclassify thecalculation from resting
andgood from thebadcalculation states ofthebrain. Theobtained
feature sethasshown itsunique anddirect relevance tothebrain regions
andrhythms during mental tasks. Asystematic comparison ofthepro-
posed method andthestate ofthearthasbeen made. Theperformance
metrics andin-depth anddirect association oftheproposed method with
thebrain showed thatourmethod performed outstandingly inalldo-
mains. Thegeneralization oftheproposed method isverified with high
inter-subject classification accuracy, which isnotdone inexisting
literature. Extension ofthework could bemade intomore data collec-
tion, especially forchildren with disabilities inmental arithmetic skills,
sothatageneralized diagnostic toolcould bedeveloped.
