1 | INTRODUCTION
Neuroimaging studies have investigated how interindividual 
math abilities differentially affect the neural representation of arithmetic processing. Differences in the activation of the left angular gyrus (Grabner, Reishofer, Koschutnig, & Ebner, 2011; Menon et al., 2000), connectivity of the intraparietal 
sulcus (IPS; Park, Park, & Polk, 2012; Prado et al., 2011), 
activation of right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (Ansari, Grabner, Koschutnig, Reishofer, & Ebner, 2011; Menon, Mackenzie, Rivera, & Reiss, 2002; Pesenti et al., 2001) and the left angular gyrus (Grabner et al., 2007) have been found 
across high and low math skill individuals. Consistently, rTMS stimulation of the left angular gyrus has been shown to disrupt numeric processing (Rusconi, Walsh, & Butterworth, 2005) that independent studies have shown to be involved in arithmetic processing (see Arsalidou and Taylor (2011) for a review). Again, Evans, Flowers, Napoliello, Olulade, and Eden (2014) observed hypo‐activation of the left supram-arginal gyrus in children with dyslexia during addition and subtraction operations. A role of the right angular gyrus/intraparietal sulcus (rIPS, supporting number representa-tion, e.g., Proverbio, Bianco, & de Benedetto, 2018) in acal-culia and arithmetic deficits has also been demonstrated in right‐damaged patients (e.g., Benavides‐Varela et al., 2017). 
Dyscalculia is very frequent in Turner syndrome (Bruandet, Molko, Cohen, & Dehaene, 2004; Mazzocco, 1998; Temple & Marriott, 1998). A deficit in mathematics, and particu-larly in arithmetic, has been documented in association with a bilateral parieto‐occipital dysfunction (Reiss, Mazzocco, Greenlaw, Freund, & Ross, 1995).
While there are a few studies investigating ERP indices 
of arithmetic processing (e.g., Núñez‐Peña, Cortiñas, & Escera, 2006; Núñez‐Peña, Honrubia‐Serrano, & Escera, 2005; Pauli, Lutzenberger, Birbaumer, Rickard, & Bourne, 1996; Pauli et al., 1994; Zhou et al., 2006, 2009), individual 
differences in mathematical skills reflected in event‐related brain potentials have been seldom explored. The only excep-tion is (as far as we know) Núñez‐Peña, Gracia‐Bafalluy, and Tubau's (2011) investigation, in which they compared brain potentials recorded in individuals with high and low math skill engaged in arithmetic tasks involving small (e.g., 3 + 4), 
medium (e.g., 7 + 8) and large numerical sets (e.g., 16 + 29). 
The authors found a late positivity (LP) that increased as task difficulty increased; but while LP did not change in ampli-tude when solving small versus medium problems in high skill individuals, it was greater to medium than to small prob-lems in low‐skill individuals, thus showing that the workload of medium problems was more challenging for them because of their reduced arithmetic skills.
Apart from these studies, mainly observing the effect 
of workload on numerical ability, the literature on neural markers or ERP indicants of math abilities in healthy adults is very scarce. In fact often subjects are tested not on arith-metic abilities per se, but on number related processes such as digit memory retrieval (Wang, Du, & Ma, 2017), mag-nitude representation/estimation abilities (e.g., deciding: whether visually presented digits (1–4, 6–9) are smaller or larger than 5 (Soltész, Szucs, Dékány, Márkus, & Csépe, 2007; also Dehaene, 1996); mental number line representa-tion (e.g., indicating the magnitude or direction of numeric stimuli, from 11 to 99; Jastrzebski, Crewther, & Crewther, 2015). In a very recent study, the neural correlates of math abilities were explored through a combined fNIRS and ERP study (Artemenko, Soltanlou, Dresler, Ehlis, & Nuerk, 2018). Subjects of this study were recruited and assigned to high and low math ability groups based on an online screening of arithmetic abilities. The screening consisted of speeded addi-tions, subtractions, multiplications and divisions with simple and difficult items, and the task for each operation was to solve as many items as possible within 2 min. The arithme-
tic task consisted of two‐digit addition and subtraction prob-lems with two operands. High performers showed increased frontal activation especially in the left inferior frontal gyrus associated with differences in slow waves at 1,000–1,500 ms 
at frontal sites.
To study individual differences in math abilities, we used 
the event‐related potential (ERP) technique, providing useful indices of cognitive processes, including arithmetic calcu-lations. Several studies have found an arithmetic N400 that behaves very similarly to the N400 evoked by words, as op-posed to the P300 component, associated instead with cor -
rect and congruent math solutions. The N400 component is a large negative deflection peaking at about 400 ms over cen-
tro‐parietal scalp areas. It has been related to the detection of an incongruence in semantic, lexical or conceptual process-ing, including arithmetic computing (Kutas & Iragui, 1998; Lau, Phillips, & Poeppel, 2008).
Niedeggen and Rösler (1999) investigated whether incon-
gruent solutions of simple multiplication problems would elicit similar event‐related brain potentials as inappropriate words in sentences and found larger N400s (as opposed to P300s) to incorrect than correct arithmetic solutions. Single‐digit multiplication problems were used to construct correct and incorrect arithmetic equations for a verification task. The operands were presented one after another and completed with either the correct or an incorrect solution. A compa-rable event‐related brain potential (ERP) effect was elicited by incongruous solutions in simple multiplication problems (Niedeggen, Rösler, & Jost, 2007). Correct solutions elicited a large P300 response, while incorrect solutions evoked a negativity between 300 and 500 ms with a maximum over 
the centro‐parietal scalp, followed by a late positive com-ponent which was interpreted as a “positive syntactic shift” or P600 (Hagoort, Brown, & Groothusen, 1993), also found  1880 |   
PROVERBIO and CaRMIna TI
in response to syntactic and musical violations (Osterhout, 
Holcomb, & Swinney, 1994; Patel, Gibson, Ratner, Besson, & Holcomb, 1998). A similar P600 was found by Núñez‐Peña and Honrubia‐Serrano (2004) in response to rule viola-tions in arithmetic tasks.
The aim of the present study was to investigate the elec-
trophysiological correlates of math abilities in the healthy population. Participants were required to quickly solve hun-dreds of operations (additions, subtractions, divisions, mul-tiplications) of varying difficulty, in a verification task. The participants recruited for the EEG recordings were selected from a sample of 41 graduate students tested for their arith-metic performance: They were asked to solve or correct as many operations as possible in 2 min. The fastest and slowest 
individuals were attributed to the group of skilled and poor calculators, respectively.
On the basis of previous literature, we hypothesized that 
arithmetic incongruities (i.e., math operations paired to an incorrect result) would considerably reduce the amplitude of P300 responses, whose amplitude would be increased by correct solutions. P300 component (or P3b) is one of the most studied brain potentials linked to categorization and decisional processes (e.g., Johnson, 1988; Kirschner, Cruse, Chennu, Owen, & Hampshire, 2015; Polich, 2007) in ad-dition to other functions, and it is always larger to congru-ent than incongruent pairs (e.g., Bach, Gunter, Knoblich, Prinz, & Friederici, 2009; Farwell, Richardson, Richardson, & Furedy, 2014; Kałamała, Szewczyk, Senderecka, & Wodniecka, 2018; Proverbio, Calbi, Manfredi, & Zani, 2014). It also reflects response certainty and subjective confidence in making a decision (e.g., Dröge, Fleischer, Schlesewsky, & Bornkessel‐Schlesewsky, 2016). With these premises, we ex-pected to find a poorer performance, both in terms of speed of response and percentage of correct responses in poor cal-culators, possibly associated with a later P300 component latency in this group. Indeed, individual differences for P300 latency are correlated with mental functionspeed, such that shorter latencies are related to superior cognitive skills (e.g., Amin, Malik, Kamel, Chooi, & Hussain, 2015; Emmerson, Dustman, Shearer, & Turner, 1989; Johnson, Pfefferbaum, & Kopell, 1985; Pelosi et al., 1992; Polich, 2007).
Furthermore, we hypothesized that, due to task difficulty, 
N400 response (reflecting expectancies’ violation) would not be much pronounced, especially in poor calculators. On the other hand, since the task consisted in evaluating solution accuracy, we expected that P300 (supposedly indexing cog-nitive updating) might be larger than N400 in this study, es-pecially in poor calculators who because of their inability to quickly access arithmetic facts might rely more on the verifi-cation of solutions provided, than forming specific expectan-cies about the solution. For this reason, the P300 component was identified and measured in the two groups as a possible marker of math abilities in this study.2 | METHODS
2.1 | Participants
Volunteers were recruited among B.A. students graduated at the University of Milano‐Bicocca. They earned academic credits for their participation. Forty‐one students (28 males, 13 females, mean age = 24.49 ± 3.12) took part in the pretest 
selection. They were all right‐handed as assessed through the administration of the Edinburg Inventory (Oldfield, 1971). Laterality scores were 85 for the skilled group and 83 for the poor group (scale = −100 to 100).
They studied in humanistic, statistical, economical or 
scientific fields (in the end, they were equally distributed across the two subgroups). Participants were administered a shortened version of N section of Kit of Factor‐Referenced Cognitive Tests (Ekstrom, French, Harman, & Derman, 1976) relative to arithmetical abilities including the four fun-damental operations: division, multiplication, subtraction and addition (in this order). The pretest was divided into four parts; for each of these four parts, candidates were required to resolve or correct as many operations as possible in 2 min. 
The pretest was administered in paper format in the pres-ence of the investigator who controlled and timed the can-didates. This task was chosen to gain empirical measure of the candidate's arithmetic abilities and to be able to select the (worst and best) students on the basis of their ability to quickly solve arithmetical operations. The mean number of operations correctly solved by the group within the allowed period of time was then computed. The mean score was 70.73. The individuals showing the best (N = 13) and worst performance (N = 13) were identified and subdivided into two groups (above and below the mean). The first subgroup was deemed “skilled calculators,” the second “poor calcula-tors.” See Figure 1 for a distribution of scores across people 
belonging to the two subgroups. In order to avoid including subjects with potentially undiagnosed calculation disorders, it was preliminarily established to exclude participants with a performance below 2 SDs (29.76 or less), but no such case was found.
The EEG data of two males for each of the two groups 
were not included in the final grand average, for excessive ocular and muscular artifacts. The final sample had a mean age of 24.02 years (skilled group = 24.17 year [seven males, 
four females]; poor group 23.88 years [four males, seven 
females]).
It was assessed (through self‐report) that subjects had 
never suffered brain damage, had no previous history of epilepsy and were under no current medications that could affect the electrical activity of the brain. None of the par -
ticipants had been diagnosed as dyscalculic, dyslexic or had any learning or attentional disorder (e.g., ADHD; acal-culia). The experiment was conducted with the approval of     | 1881
