the Ethical Committee of the University of Milano‐Bicocca 
(Prot. 0000273/14) and in compliance with APA ethical stan-dards for the treatment of human volunteers (1992, American Psychological Association). Informed written consent was obtained from all subjects. All experiments were performed in accordance with relevant guidelines and regulations.
2.2 | Procedure
Participants were seated comfortably in a dark, acoustically and electrically shielded cubicle facing a screen located 114 cm from their eyes. They were instructed to gaze at the 
center of the screen, where a small red circle served as a fixa-tion point, and to avoid any eye or body movements during the recording session. Participants rested their head against the back of their armchair and had to stay relaxed and per-fectly still (while fixating the foveal point). No chin rest was used. Stimuli were presented in random order at the center of the screen in 10 experimental runs of 35–37 trials. Each run lasted about 165 s each. The experimental session was preceded by a training session that included two runs, one for each response hand, and containing stimuli discarded during the validation phase. The sequence presentation order var-ied across subjects. Each run featured a balanced number of correct and incorrect operations, presented in a randomized manner, and each session began with three warning stimuli (“READY,” “SET” and “GO”) lasting 700 ms. Each opera-
tion was presented for 1,500 ms and was followed by a ran-
dom ISI of 100–150 ms. Results were flashed for 1,500 ms, 
and intertrial interval (ITI) was of 1,000 ms. Responses should be provided immediately after result presentation, within 1.5 s.
The task (a verification paradigm) required participants 
to decide as accurately and quickly as possible about the correctness or incorrectness of the operation's solutions by pressing a response key with their index finger (of the left or right hand), to signal that a solution appeared correct, and another key with their middle finger (of the left or right hand) to signal that it was incorrect. Previous literature has shown no significant difference in response speed between the two fingers (index vs. middle) in button press tasks (Lachnit & Pieper, 1990). The hand used was alternated during the re-cording session. Hand order and experimental runs were counterbalanced across subjects. At the beginning of each session, participants were reminded which response hand would be used.
2.3 | Stimuli and materials
Four hundred and forty arithmetic operations (divisions and subtractions) along with their results were selected as experi-mental stimuli. More (44 additions and multiplications) were added for a total of 484 arithmetic operations (242 correct and 242 incorrect) of various difficulty, but mentally solvable (at least by approximation) by anyone who had completed compulsory schooling.
Arithmetic operations were created according to the fol-
lowing criteria: They included integers between 0 and 2,000; contained a maximum of eight characters including the oper -
ator; each operation had to be followed by a whole solution FIGURE 1 Average number of solved 
