between 0 and 10. For this reason, an asymmetrical number 
of arithmetic operations was used (mostly divisions and sub-tractions), and arithmetic operation type could not be there-fore a factor of observed variability.
• Half of the operations had to be followed by a correct solu-
tion, the other half by an incorrect solution. This was true for each of the four operations.
• Incorrect solutions had to be diversified and clearly dif-ferent from the correct result to allow approximate calcu-lations, given the fast rate of stimulation and the temporal length of the test requiring mental concentration for a pro-longed period of time (half an hour of EEG recording, in-cluding pauses). Indeed, it has been shown that the more two numerals are farther apart (e.g., 2 vs. 8) the easier is to compare them, as opposed to when they have a similar numerical value (e.g., 2 vs. 3) than closer ones. This effect is known as distance effect (Dehaene, Dupoux, & Mehler, 1990; Henik & Tzelgov, 1982; Tzelgov, Meyer, & Henik, 1992). For this reason, the distances of the incorrect solu-tions were matched across operation types.
By observing no operation in particular, we wished to annul 
the effect of a specific operation, thus gaining information about arithmetic abilities per se. Furthermore, since the exper -
imental purpose was not to discriminate between different op-erations, numerical codes were not associated differently with stimuli linked to different operations, so that EEG trials relative to different operations were average together.
Stimuli were typed in Times New Roman font and yel-
low (FFFF00) color on a gray (424246) background (to avoid after effects) and were presented at the center of the screen. Overall stimulus size depended on the number of ciphers but did not exceed 2.5° of visual angle.
2.4 | Stimuli validation
For stimulus validation, a sample of 12 judges (five women and seven men) was recruited. Judges had a mean age of 34.08 years (SD = 11.5) and had 15 years of schooling on 
average (SD = 3.33). In order to balance all the operations 
per difficulty (across the correct and incorrect conditions), judges were presented with all the stimuli, organized in pseu-dorandom sequences, with each operation followed by a cor-rect (or incorrect solution), and were asked to evaluate the stimuli for subjective difficulty. They were required to first solve and afterward rate each problem by using a three‐point Likert scale. In particular, they had to answer:
• 0 for all solutions that appeared to be clearly correct or 
clearly incorrect;
• 1 for all solutions that they had recognized with difficulty to be correct or incorrect, or that had left them in doubt about the answer to be given;
• 2 for all operations that appeared to be unsolvable or too confusing.
On the basis of this procedure, operations that were desig-
nated by at least ¼ of the judges as too difficult to be mentally solved (score 2) were eliminated. Furthermore, operations that were considered as clearly solvable by 100% were elim-inated as too simple (score 0), except for additions and mul-tiplications (only 10% of all operations). The final group of operations consisted of 352 stimuli, 176 followed by correct results and 176 by an incorrect result. An ANOVA proved that the degree of difficulty was perfectly balanced across the two classes: correct versus incorrect (p = 0.97). Example of stimuli is provided in Table 1.
2.5 | EEG recording and data analyses
The EEG was continuously recorded using the software pack-age EEvoke (ANT, Enschede) from 128 scalp sites arranged according to the international 10–5 system (Oostenveld & Praamstra, 2001) at a sampling rate of 512 Hz. Horizontal 
and vertical eye movements were also recorded. Average mastoids served as the reference lead. The EEG and TABLE 1 Examples of operations followed by a correct (left 
