electrooculogram (EOG) were amplified with a half‐ampli-
tude bandpass of 0.016–100 Hz. Electrode impedance was 
maintained below 5 kΩ. EEG epochs were synchronized 
with the onset of the operation result. A computerized ar-tifact rejection criterion was applied before averaging to discard epochs in which eye movements, blinks, excessive muscle potential or amplifier blocking occurred. The artifact rejection criterion was a peak‐to‐peak amplitude exceeding 30 μV, and the rejection rate was ~5%. ERPs were averaged 
off‐line from −100 to 1,500 ms after stimulus onset and ana-
lyzed via software EEProbe (ANT, Enschede).
Event‐related potential components were identified and 
measured with reference to the average baseline voltage over the interval of −100 to 0 ms at the sites and latencies at which they 
reached their maximum amplitudes. EEG epochs associated with an incorrect or rejected behavioral response were excluded. The mean area amplitude of P300 component was measured at Fz, FCz and Cz sites within the 280–430 ms time window.
Event‐related potential data were subjected to a 3‐
way multifactorial repeated‐measures ANOVA with 1 between‐subject factor (Group: Skilled vs. Poor) and 2 within‐subjects factors: correctness (correct, incorrect) and electrode (3 levels: Fz, FCz and Cz). Multiple comparisons of means were performed with Tukey's post hoc test.
Spearman ρ correlations were performed between individual 
P300 latency values and response times, individual P300 ampli-tude values and response times, and individual P300 amplitude values and percentage of correct responses (Hits), regardless of group and electrode sites. These correlations were planned on the basis of the known relationship between P300 latency and response speed, as well as that of P300 amplitude and accuracy in performance (e.g., Duncan‐Johnson & Donchin, 1980; Houlihan, Campbell, & Stelmack, 1994). The correlation between P300 amplitude and response speed (not theoretically justified) was performed to test the reliability of the statistical method, and a lack of significance was indeed predicted for this analysis.
Reaction times (RTs) that exceeded the mean value ±2 
SD were discarded, which resulted in a rejection rate of 2%. Hit rate percentages were converted to arcsine values and used for analysis of variance. Because percentage values do 
