not exhibit homoscedasticity (e.g., Snedecor & Cochran, 
1989), which is necessary for ANOVA, the data were con-verted into arcsine values. In fact, the distribution of per -
centages is binomial, whereas the arcsine transformation of the data makes the distribution normal. Both RTs and hit percentages were subjected to separate multifactorial re-peated‐measures ANOVA analyses with 1 between‐subject factor (group: skilled vs. poor) and 2 within‐subjects factors: correctness (correct, incorrect); response hand (left, right).
The Greenhouse–Geisser correction was applied to com-
pensate for possible violations of the sphericity assumption associated with factors which had more than two levels. The epsilon (ε ) values and the corrected probability levels 
(in the case of epsilon <1) are reported. Partial eta‐squared values were systematically provided to estimate effect sizes.
