4 | DISCUSSION
The aim of this study was to investigate whether ERP po-
tentials, and in particular P300 response linked to decisional processes, might reflect interindividual differences in the math abilities of a representative sample of healthy graduate students.
Overall, response times were faster when the right hand 
was used, which suggests a prevalent left‐hemispheric in-volvement in arithmetic calculations (Altenmüller, Jung, Winker, & Landwehrmeyer, 1989), although the crucial role of the right hemisphere in number processing has also been demonstrated. For example, Proverbio, Bianco et al. 
(2018) found no hand asymmetry when subjects compared Arabic stimuli (for equality) but a right hand (left hemi-spheric) advantage when they compared numbers in ver -
bal format. In this study, both skilled and poor calculators showed a right‐hand advantage with no group difference in lateralization.
Behavioral results showed that individuals with high 
math abilities provided faster responses compared to indi-viduals with low math abilities, similar to that found by Artemenko et al. (2018). This was associated with better 
accuracy (higher hit percentages) and to an overall earlier fronto‐central P300 latency in the group of skilled calcula-tors. Interestingly, having high math skills was also asso-ciated with smaller P300s to incorrect solutions, and, vice versa. Having poor math skills led to larger P300s to in-correct solutions, as demonstrated by significant Spearman correlations. Since in match/mismatch paradigms P3/N400 potentials reflect correct/congruent versus incorrect/incon-gruent categorizations (e.g., Farwell et al., 2014; Kałamała 
et al., 2018; Proverbio & Zani, 2003), it might be argued 
that low math skilled individuals had reduced abilities to reject incorrect solutions. This hypothesis is supported by Spearman correlations showing an inverse relationship be-tween performance and P300 amplitude to incorrect solu-tions. The finding of a larger P300 to correct than incorrect arithmetic solutions is in accordance with previous electro-physiological literature (El Yagoubi, Lemaire, & Besson, 2003; Niedeggen & Rösler, 1999; Núñez‐Peña & Escera, 2007; Núñez‐Peña & Suárez‐Pellicioni, 2012; Szűcs & Csépe, 2005). The reduced P300 amplitude in response to incorrect solutions corroborates many findings report-ing enhanced negativities to incorrect solutions (Szűcs & Csépe, 2005; Wang, Kong, Tang, Zhuang, & Li, 2000). Niedeggen and Rösler (1999) found that incorrect solutions of multiplications elicited a negativity (named arithmetic N400) starting at about 300 ms poststimulus, which was 
followed by a centro‐parietal late positivity. They inter -
preted these biphasic responses as indicating a conflict be-tween the operation presented and the solution offered (see also Núñez‐Peña et al., 2011).Our hypothesis is that the low math ability individuals 
mainly relied on a strategy based on a plausibility check of the results, while the most capable individuals more often relied on certain calculations or on the re‐evocation of arithmetic facts (for example, results of simple multiplication problems (e.g., 6 × 8) are retrieved from declarative memory as well‐
established facts, i.e., Niedeggen and Rösler (1999). The sec-ond strategy would have led to a clearer representation of the numerical result, and to a more distinguishable bioelectrical effect between correct and incorrect trials, which was actually found for skilled calculators. At this regard, it has been found that recruitment of the left angular gyrus during arithmetic problem solving underlies individual differences in math abilities: Its activation would index a stronger reliance on automatic, language‐mediated processes in more competent individuals. Grabner et al. (2007) investigated through fMRI 
whether brain activation was modulated by individual differ -
ences in math abilities during mental calculation. Two groups of students were selected from a larger pool based on their performance on arithmetic (quite similar to the present study) and divided into groups of skilled versus poor calculators. The task required them to verify the correctness of provided multiplication solutions. The results showed that individuals with higher mathematical competence displayed stronger ac-tivation of the left angular gyrus (lAG), which has a crucial role in the retrieval of arithmetic facts (Grabner et al., 2009). 
Therefore, the hypothesis can be advanced that P300 response elicited to correct solutions in the present study might reflect the activity of lAG during retrieval of arithmetic facts, differ -
ently in skilled versus poor calculators. Indeed, several neu-roimaging studies have provided evidence of a contribution of AG in generating P300 responses to targets. A correlation between white matter underneath the angular gyrus and P300 amplitude to targets has been demonstrated by Fusar‐Poli et al. (2011), while significant increases in fMRI signal for 
both auditory and visual targets were observed in the supra-marginal gyrus by Linden et al. (1999). Again Sabeti, Katebi, 
Rastgar, and Azimifar (2016) found that the angular gyrus (BA39) was one of the most prominent sources of P300 in memory processes.
In an interesting study, Luo, Liu, He, Tao, and Luo (2009) 
explored the electrophysiological markers of shortcut calcu-lation strategy (i.e., rounding) and non‐shortcut calculation strategy (i.e., exact calculation) in performing addition using mental arithmetic. It can be assumed that approximate versus exact calculations are associated with a smaller and greater degree of response/output certainty, that were linked to larger P220 and N400 responses in that study. Other evidence sug-gests that mental calculation is based on a dual process involv -
ing, on one hand, a visual mental imagery resolution strategy, and, on the other hand, a number‐specific working memory (Zago et al., 2001), but their involvement might depend on 
the specific math operation to be solved (e.g., 20 + 20 vs.  1888 |   
PROVERBIO and CaRMIna TI
6 × 8). In the end, further research is needed to understand 
their relevance in explaining individual math skills.
In our study, the overall reduced negativity to incorrect 
solutions found in poor calculators suggests that, because 
of the task's difficulty, low math ability individuals mainly relied on a strategy based on a plausibility check of the solutions, rather than forming an expectation. This result is different from that found in other studies using much simpler arithmetic operations based, for example, on the well‐known multiplication table (e.g., Niedeggen & Rösler, 1999), and in which incorrect solutions elicited N400 responses.
In conclusion, the present findings indicate that the 
latency and amplitude of P300 component evoked by the solution of a mathematical operation can be considered as reliable electrophysiological markers of superior versus poor math abilities in healthy individuals. Furthermore, data analysis suggests that the P300 component might be efficaciously used to assess mathematical comprehension and understanding in individuals unable to provide a writ-ten or vocal response (e.g., locked‐in or brain‐damaged patients). Furthermore, it can be universally used regard-less of the native language spoken, or of language profi-ciency because it does not require the access to number phonological representation, being a YES/NO verification paradigm.
One limit of this study is that no other measure (such 
as brain connectivity, I.Q., verbal fluency, introversion–extroversion trait, etc.) was performed or correlated with the performance of individual subjects. Therefore, we ig-nore whether skilled calculators were more introverted (as shown for example by Proverbio, De Benedetto, Ferrari, & Ferrarini, 2018) or had thicker white matter. For example, children with superior math abilities have been shown to possess a higher degree of intrinsic functional connectiv -
ity of the hippocampus with dorsolateral and ventrolateral prefrontal cortices and the basal ganglia (Supekar et al., 
2013). In our study, poor and skilled calculators had the same age and cultural status and had a degree in human-istic, scientific or technical fields (without differences be-tween groups). The only mild difference concerned female individuals who were overrepresented in the poor math skills group. However, the study aim was to identify elec-trophysiological markers of math skills in healthy individ-uals regardless of other variables, such as the contributing factors to explain low mathskills.
