By extracting the cognitive microstates of ma th-gifted and non-gifted adolescents during
a reasoning task, our study discovers the signiﬁ cant association of four microstate classes
with the math-gifted brain in mean duration and occurrence. Moreover, the topologicaldiﬀerences between the two groups varied across classes, suggesting the functional
disassociation of diﬀerent microstate classes for reﬂecting individual diﬀerences incognitive processing of reasoning problems. Speciﬁcally, microstate class C with topo‐logical diﬀerence in the right hemisphere shows more characteristics related to speciﬁcability in mathematics. Functional network research on diﬀerent microstate classes ofmath-gifted brain, especially on class C, is worthy to be systematically explored further.
