Abstract —Problem solving is regarded as one of the 
important skills required at the workplace and especially demanded by the industry. However, an individual’s problem 
solving skills might differ from one another due to several 
factors, such as their genetic background and experiences. 
Hence, this preliminary study used electroencephalography (EEG) signal to investigate the differences in problem solving 
skills among the Malaysian undergraduates based on their 
gender differences. A total of 29 undergraduate students from the 
Faculty of Electrical Engineering, Universiti Teknologi Malaysia (UTM) participated in several experiments to complete this 
research. Specifically, 16 female and 13 male subjects were given 
two main tasks: mental arithmetic task and Tower of Hanoi 
(TOH) task. The EEG data were analyzed using partial directed coherence (PDC) and power spectrum estimation (PSE). Based 
on the results, female subjects achieved only 1% higher 
performance in mental arithmetic task while male subjects 
achieved about 13% higher performance in TOH task. The differences in terms of the functional connectivity between brain 
regions (in PDC) as well as the power distribution of 6 EEG 
waveforms, i.e. delta, theta, alpha, beta, gamma and high gamma 
bands are also highlighted and represented graphically in this paper. 
 
Keywords—problem solving, EEG, gender differences, 
Partial Directed Coherence (PDC), power spectrum estimation 
(PSE). 
I. INTRODUCTION  
Problem solving is a cognitive process of the brain 
that searches or infers a solution for a given problem in the 
form of a set of paths to reach a set of expected goals [1]. 
Individuals face problems in their everyday life. For instance, an employee has to solve problems related to their job and a student has to answer questions given by the 
lecturers during the class or examinations. Many surveys 
have been conducted on employers to find out the criteria 
demanded by the industry when hiring a worker. For example, the Association of American Colleges and Universities (AAC&U) has conducted a national survey on 
business and non-profit leaders in Washington, DC. They 
concluded that nearly all employers surveyed (93%) agreed that the ability to solve complex problems is more 
important than a candidate’s undergraduate major” [2].  
 
It is a fact that men and women differ genetically or 
physically. For example, a scientific finding states that the 
average male human brain weighs about 10% more than the 
female human brain, while some areas in the female human brain contain more neurons than men’s [3]. Besides, some 
researcher claims that women have a denser corpus 
callosum than men which causes women being typically 
more emotional compare to men [4]. When relating to the 
brain cognitive processes, however, it is believed that the physical factor of the brain of these different sexes is not much an effector.  
 
Consequently, in terms of the gender thinking ability, 
male and female might have the same performance but mentally going through different information processing path [3,4]. Moreover, through numerous experiments, it is found out that female could perform better in some tasks 
compared to male. For instance, women are more 
multitasking, good in autobiographical memory and verbal 
fluency [4,5]. Men on the other hand can outperform women in mathematical reasoning and visuospatial task [4,5]. 
Furthermore, the differences of male and female can also be 
accessed through their creativity [6].  
 EEG is one of technique used to measure the electrical 
activity of the brain at different sites of the head. This is typically using electrodes placed on the scalp, i.e. by using 
cap electrode. One of its main benefits over other brain 
signal recording techniques are its high temporal resolution 
and the fact that it can be recorded noninvasively [7]. EEG 
is a very accessible and useful tool for the analysis of high level brain processes since it is relatively low cost and widely used both in clinical settings and research 
laboratories [7]. Therefore, this study intends to overlook 
the gender differences focusing on problem solving task as 
it is one of demanded aspect in nowadays life and should be 
paid more focus in order to improve one performance in this aspect. 
