A. Population and Sample 
A number of experiments have been conducted with a 
total of 29 participants. In general, subjects were 1st and 4th year undergraduate students with 16 female and 13 
male subjects from Faculty of Electrical Engineering, 
Universiti Teknologi Malaysia. 
 
B. Problem Solving Task  
A problem can be classified into three types: puzzle 
problem, well-structured problems and ill-structured 
problems [8,9]. Tower of Hanoi (TOH) is in the category 
of puzzle problem which used to be the traditional task in 
cognitive science [10]. It is also a well-structured problem with close ended solution, and hence require the use of logical thinking [9]. TOH is a puzzle of basically three rods with rings. In TOH problem, one is required to move all the 
rings from the left-most rod to the right-most rod. The rules 
state that the ring could only be taken one a time and a bigger ring cannot be put on a smaller ring. Although TOH 
is a classic puzzle, some people nowadays might still be 
considered a novice in this puzzle if they never solve this 
kind of puzzle before. 
C. Measurement  
The experiment measurement can be illustrated as in 
Figure 1 below.  
 
 
Fig. 1.  Experimental measurement procedure. 
First of all, subjects were given a brief explanation of the 
experimental procedure. The gender and year of study of the subjects were noted and recorded. Next, the scalp EEG 
electrode was put on the subject head and EEG signals were 
recorded using the NeuroFax EEG 9000 signal acquisition software. For the control task, subjects were required to be at rest and relax, and if possible with emptied mind. The 
subjects were asked to open their eyes during this task since the following tasks will also be recorded with open eyes. 
The control task was recorded for 30s for one to three times 
depending on a subject’ mental condition (like nervousness) before they proceed with the problem solving task  
Next, the problem solving task consists of two sub tasks: 
the arithmetic task and Tower of Hanoi task. In the arithmetic task, subjects were asked to mentally subtract 7 from 1000 continuously within 30s time. The final answer for each trial was noted and then the process was repeated for 
three trials after resting for about 30s per trial. EEG signals were recorded when the subjects were thinking. 
Finally, the TOH task was divided into three difficulty 
levels: easy, medium and hard. The levels were chosen based on the feedback from subjects of preliminary experiment. EEG signals were recorded when subjects were thinking (30s) and answering (maximum two minutes) the puzzle. The rest time interval for each level was also 30s. Overall, 10 EEG data (.csv) were recorded for each subject and the recorded EEG data were named using short form of the tasks name as shown in Figure 2. 
 
Fig. 2.  Code for recorded EEG data. 
III. FINDINGS  
In this study, analyses of data were done based on two 
outputs from the experiment, i.e. the tabulated answer and performance of subjects and the recorded EEG data (.csv) during the tasks. The tabulated answer and performance of 
subjects refer to the subjects’ ability to answer the given 
arithmetic questions with accurate final value for each trial, and also their ability to complete the TOH task within maximum 2 minutes’ time provided for each level. Based on this, comparison for gender factors can be made by calculating the statistic of high performance versus low performance subjects as shown in Table 1 and further represented in graphical form as in Figure 3. 
