In contrast, the recorded EEG data were analyzed using two 
methods, namely power spectrum estimation (PSE) and 
partial directed coherence (PDC) methods. The power spectrum estimation method analyse the change in power distribution of the EEG waveforms whereas the PDC analysis provides a more visual comparison based on the information pathway between the channels or brain regions 
of subjects when doing the given tasks. In this project, both 
the PSE and PDC outputs were obtained on C-program running on a Linux platform. Finally, the outputs were further analyzed using Microsoft Excel (for t-test) and Paint (for drawing). 
 
IV. D
ISCUSSIONS  
A. PDC Analysis  
The PDC output was plotted in the form a 19x19 matrix 
layouts of all the 19 channels used during EEG data recording. By referring to the matrix layouts as well as the three PDC values given out, the results were transformed into drawing of the information pathways for better visualization as in Figure 4. 
 
 
Fig. 4.  Functional connectivity diagram for respondent 1 of task a1 and a2 
Gender differences were determined by comparing the 
female and male subjects’ task performance with the source of information pathway they used for the task with high performance. For each high task performance result, the source of information flow of EEG signals was identified, 
tabulated and can be summarized tables are shown in Table 
II. 
 
Basically, the information pathway of problem solving 
should be originated mainly from the frontal lobe [18]. The 
tabulated PDC results have also shown that most of the high performance information flow sources for both the male and 
female are from the frontal (F) regions. Moreover, female subjects outperformed the male subjects in arithmetic task while in opposite, male subjects outperformed female subjects in TOH task. The summarized PDC source of 
information flow as shown in Table II (b) especially proved 
that the female subjects used more frontal regions in arithmetic task, while the male subjects used more frontal regions during TOH task. This is as if the utilization of the frontal regions as the source of EEG information flow during a task is proportional to the performance result of the subjects. 
