B. PSE  
 
An example of the power spectrum measured at Fp1 is 
shown in Fig 5 where the distribution of signal power is 
segregated as follows bands: delta (0-4 Hz), theta (4-8 Hz), 
alpha (8-13 Hz), beta (13-31 Hz), gamma (31-51) and high 
gamma (51-120 Hz). In this example, it is observed that there is significant power at frequency less than 31 Hz indicating brain activities in the delta, theta, gamma and 
beta bands. 
 
 
Fig. 5. Example of a power spectrum at Fp1 for a subject while 
performing a task. 
 
The power spectrum for all the subjects, bands and 
electrodes are compared between the male and female 
subjects for all the tasks. Example for Fp1 and Fp2 is shown 
in Fig. 6 for the delta band. The horizontal axis represents the tasks defined in Fig. 2 while the blue and red bars represent the power measured for the male and female subjects respectively. The Student t-test is used to determine if there is significant difference between the male and 
female subjects for all task, electrodes and bands. 
 
 
 
Fig. 6. Comparison between the power in the delta band for Fp1 and Fp2 
at state of rest with the various tasks. 
 
The gender differences results based on PSE show 
changes in control task to problem solving tasks ratio for each of the EEG waveform mentioned. For both male and female subjects, the labelled significant difference can be 
observed mostly at the frontal regions.   
During arithmetic task, the power of delta and theta 
waves (especially in frontal region) for both gender 
increased, while the alpha, beta, gamma and high gamma 
power were decreased. The major waveband used by female 
subjects was the theta wave while male subjects used theta and beta wavebands majorly during mental arithmetic task.  
 
In contrast, during TOH task, the high gamma wave 
power for female was increased, while the male subjects 
showed increased in both the gamma and high gamma 
power. Moreover, female subjects used their alpha and theta waves majorly, while male subjects used alpha, theta, gamma and high gamma waves majorly.  
 
The different in the change of the wave power as well as 
the major wavebands involved during the problem solving task were directly related to the subjects’ performance. For instance, male subjects who showed best performance in TOH task had correspondingly higher gamma and high gamma power compared to the female subjects 
V. C
ONCLUSION  
On the whole, the term ‘differences in problem solving’ 
not only refers to the ability of one to solve a problem, but also refers to an individual way of thinking or thinking 
pattern or strategy (in a given time) to solve an encountered 
problem to reach the wanted goal. Especially when dealing 
with a close-ended solution problem, often people will reach the same solution for the problem regardless of their gender or background. However, the way they solve it or the time taken for someone to solve the same problem may differ from one to another.  
 
Hence, the study of gender differences in problem 
solving in this study has been done by comparing the 
performance of subjects based on the gender group (male and female. The EEG data analysis, like PDC and PSE is 
useful to see the relation between the subjects’ performance and the different part of brain regions involves (as shown in 
PDC results) and wave power distribution (as shown in PSE 
results). 
