Oscillatory EEG correlates of arit hmetic strategy use in addition 
and subtraction
Bert De Smedt · Roland H. Grabner · Bettina Studer 
Received: 18 February 2009 / Accepted: 30 April 2009 / Published online: 19 May 2009
© Springer-Verlag 2009
Abstract Adults use diVerent strategies in mental arith-
metic. For example, they directly retrieve the answer from
memory or calculate by means of procedural strategies.
Despite growing insight into the hemodynamic and electro-
physiological correlates of these strategies, the functional
changes in the oscillatory brain dynamics during the use of
these strategies remain unknown. In the present high-reso-
lution electroencephalography (EEG) study, we analysed
event-related synchronisation (ERS) and desynchronisation
(ERD) in the theta and alph a bands while participants
solved addition and subtraction problems, which displayed
a high probability of retrieval or procedural strategy use.
Findings revealed that arithmetic fact retrieval is re Xected
in left-hemispheric ERS in the theta band, whereas the
application of procedural strategies is accompanied by
bilateral parietooccipital ERD in the alpha band. The topo-
graphical and frequency speci Wcity of the strategy e Vects
provides a start for the development of electrophysiological
indices of strategy use in arithmetic.Keywords Arithmetic · Strategy use · Oscillatory EEG · 
ERD · ERS · Fact retrieval
Introduction
It is well established that educated adults use di Verent strat-
egies in mental arithmetic (e.g., Campbell and Xue 2001 ;
LeFevre et al. 1996 ): they directly retrieve the answer from
long-term memory or they cal culate the answer by means
of procedural strategies (e.g., decomposition of a problem
into smaller facts). While retrieval is fast, requires minimal
cognitive load and involves little or no magnitude process-
ing, procedural strategies are more time-consuming and
rely stronger on magnitude processing and working mem-
ory resources. Neuroimaging studies have recently started
to unravel the brain correlates  of these solution strategies.
Functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) studies
have revealed that small single-digit arithmetic problems,
which are likely to be solved by fact retrieval (see, e.g.,
Campbell and Xue 2001 ), elicited stronger activation in
left-hemispheric language regions, including the supramar-
ginal and angular gyri. In contrast, large problems, which
are assumed to rely more on procedural strategies, were
associated with stronger bilateral activation in frontal and
parietal cortices, the latter being associated with magnitude
processing (e.g., Dehaene et al. 2003 ; Grabner et al. 2007a ;
Stanescu-Cosson et al. 2000 ). Similarly, Grabner et al.
(2009 ) recently showed that the application of retrieval
strategies elicited stronger left angular gyrus activation,
while procedural strategies evoked bilateral widespread
fronto-parietal activation. The involvement of left-hemi-
spheric language-related brain regions in calculation has
been interpreted to re Xect the demand on verbal coding of
numbers or on the retrieval of verbally stored arithmeticB. De Smedt and R. H. Grabner equally contributed to this study and 
should be regarded as joint Wrst authors.
