123knowledge from memory (Dehaene et al. 2003 ). In addition
to fMRI, event-related potential (ERP) studies have shed
light on the time-course of brain activity during the applica-
tion of diVerent arithmetic strategies, pointing to an ampli-
tude modulation of the late positive slow wave during
procedural calculation but not during retrieval (Jost et al.
2004 ; Nunez-Pena et al. 2006 ).
Despite growing insight into the hemodynamic and elec-
trophysiological correlates of arithmetic strategies, little is
known about how the involved neuronal networks are
formed and interact with each other during arithmetic.
Therefore, we analysed induced EEG activity, which is a
well-established way to investigate the dynamics of func-
tional network formation during cognitive information pro-
cessing (Bastiaansen and Hagoort 2003 ; Klimesch 1999 ;
Pfurtscheller and Lopes da Silva 2005 ). In contrast to ERPs
which reXect a time- and phase-locked response of the
brain to a single event (time- locked) induced activity refers
to functional changes in the oscillatory brain activity elic-
ited by an event or task. Basically, the pattern of synchroni-
sation and desynchronisation (ERD) of neuronal activity in
diVerent frequency bands is related to the coupling and
uncoupling of functional networks in the brain (Bastiaansen
et al. 2006 ; Klimesch et al. 2005 ; Neuper and Pfurtscheller
2001 ). The quantiWcation of event-related synchronisation
(ERS) and desynchronisation (ERD) has proved to be a
useful method to determine functional changes in the oscil-
latory brain dynamics during cognitive information pro-
cessing (for an overview, cf. Neuper and Klimesch 2006 ).
This method calculates the percentage amount of band
power increases (ERS) or decreases (ERD) in any fre-
quency band from a pre-stimulus reference interval to an
activation interval (Pfurtscheller and Lopes da Silva 2005 ).
Studies applying the ERS/ERD methodology have accu-
mulated a large basis of empirical evidence suggesting a
diVerential functional signi Wcance of diVerent frequency
bands depending on the scalp topography. Global and pos-
terior increases in theta activity (ERS) have repeatedly been
associated with tasks demanding memory encoding and
retrieval (Burgess and Gruzelier 2000 ; Klimesch et al.
1997 ) and with retrieval of lexical-semantic information
from long-term memory in particular (Bastiaansen et al.
2006 ). Higher theta ERS was observed to be related to the
retrieval of lexical information while reading (Bastiaansen
et al. 2005 ) and translating words (Grabner et al. 2007b ).
The functional speci Wcity of alpha oscillations (around 8–
12 Hz) is less clear as alpha ERD has been reported in
response to various cognitive task demands (Neubauer
et al. 2006 ). As the amount of alpha ERD has turned out to
generally increase with task di Yculty, it has been inter-
preted as an index of general cortical activation or invested
cognitive resources (Pfurtscheller and Lopes da Silva
1999 ).Studies focusing on oscillatory EEG activity during
arithmetic are scarce. Earle et al. ( 1996 ) found higher left-
hemispheric theta band power when participants solved
arithmetic problems involving symbolic and verbal opera-
tors compared to a task in which they had to supply the cor-
rect arithmetic sign into an equation. This Wnding was
interpreted to re Xect fact retrieval. Harmony et al. ( 1999 )
reported, compared to a physical baseline, larger task-
related activation changes during a complex arithmetic task
[e.g., (24 + 39)/9] in the theta frequency range (around 3–
4 Hz) in left parietooccipital regions (band power
increases) and in the alpha frequency range (around 12 Hz)
in the left parietal regions (band power decreases). Theta
eVects were interpreted to re Xect sustained attention,
whereas the alpha e Vect was associated with long-term
retrieval. Recently, Micheloyannis et al. ( 2005 ) observed
frontal theta power increases and parietal alpha power
decreases during multiplication relative to viewing num-
bers.
Although the aforementioned studies have provided
important Wrst insights into the oscillatory correlates of
arithmetic, their signi Wcance with respect to strategy use
remains limited. First, the selection of the arithmetic prob-
lems was not designed to di Verentiate between retrieval
versus procedural strategies, making it unclear which strat-
egies were likely applied in the administered conditions.
Second, these studies did not always distinguish between
diVerent operations, which may involve di Verent strategies.
Finally, these studies analysed Wxed time periods (activa-
tion intervals) for all individuals and all task conditions.
This may not capture the individual and task-speci Wc oscil-
latory changes related to cognitive strategies appropriately.
For example, when a constant activation interval of several
seconds after stimulus onset is used, the activation interval
in faster individuals or easier task conditions may cover not
only problem solving but also other task-irrelevant cogni-
tive processes.
The present study is the Wrst to explore the ERS/ERD
correlates of retrieval and procedural strategies in arithme-
tic taking into account the aforementioned limitations. We
recorded a 64-channel EEG a nd analysed the topographical
ERS/ERD patterns in the alpha and theta frequency range
using individually and trial-wise de Wned activation periods
(cf. Grabner et al. 2004 , 2006 ; Neubauer et al. 2004 ). To
distinguish retrieval and procedural strategies, we presented
additions and subtractions that have been shown to display
a high probability of retrieval or procedural strategy use.
Retrieval problems had a sum or minuend below or equal to
10, which showed high frequencies of retrieval use in edu-
cated adults (95% in addi tion and 86% in subtraction;
Campbell and Xue 2001 ). Problems with a high probability
of procedural strategies invo lved two-digit calculations, to
which the answer is unlikely to be directly retrieved from Exp Brain Res (2009) 195:635–642 637
123memory. We expected the topographical ERS/ERD pat-
terns in the alpha and theta band to di Ver between retrieval
and procedural problems. Based on Wndings from previous
EEG studies linking theta power increases with memory
retrieval, we hypothesised that the solution of retrieval
problems would be associated with higher theta ERS than
the solution of procedural problems. The strong association
between alpha ERD and task di Yculty suggests that proce-
dural problems would elicit more alpha ERD than retrieval
problems.
In addition to the ERS/ERD correlates of di Verent strate-
gies, we also investigated potential neurophysiological
diVerences between addition and subtraction. This goal is
motivated by neuroimaging and neuropsychological Wnd-
ings suggesting that di Verent operations draw on di Verent
codes and require the recruitment of both shared and sepa-
rate neural resources (Dehaene and Cohen 1997 ; Fehr et al.
2007 ; Kong et al. 2005 ). The triple-code model (Dehaene
and Cohen 1997 ) predicts that single-digit addition relies
on a verbal code while subtraction involves more on a visu-
ospatial quantity code. This stronger reliance on quantity
processing in subtraction may be re Xected in the alpha fre-
quency range.
Method
Participants
Participants were 25 right-handed healthy university stu-
dents without known calculation di Yculties. Four partici-
pants were excluded because their performance accuracy
was below 50%; one participant was excluded due to tech-
nical problems during EEG acquisition. The remaining
sample of 20 adults comprised 11 males and 9 females
(mean age = 22.60, SD = 3.10). The study was approved by
the local ethics committee (Swiss Federal Institute of Tech-
nology Zurich, Switzerland). All participants gave written
informed consent.
Materials and apparatus
Participants solved additions and subtractions that di Veren-
tially drew on retrieval and procedural strategies. No zero-,
one-, or tie problems (e.g., 6 + 6) were included. Retrieval
problems had a sum or minuend between 2 and 10 (e.g.,
4 + 2). All procedural problems comprised two-digit num-
bers with a sum or minuend between 11 and 60. Two types
of procedural complexity were presented: complex proce-
dural problems, which required carrying/borrowing (e.g.,
53–26), and simple procedural problems, without carrying/
borrowing (e.g., 24 + 31). Each problem type involved 48
additions and 48 subtractions, yielding a total of 288 trials.The position of the largest addend and the size of the sub-
trahend were counterbalanced.
Each EEG trial started with the presentation of a Wxation
point for 3,000 ms, followed by the arithmetic problem.
The participant was instructed to solve the problem as cor-
rectly and quickly as possible and to speak the solution into
a voice-activated device (voice- key) that was connected to
the computer. The experimenter  recorded the participants
answer to the problem. The next trial followed after an
inter-trial interval of 2,000 ms.
EEG was acquired through the BioSemi ActiveTwo sys-
tem (BioSemi, Amsterdam, The Netherlands) from 64 scalp
electrodes placed according to the extended 10–20 systems.
An electrooculogram (EOG) was recorded from four addi-
tional electrodes; two placed horizontally at the outer canthi
of both eyes, and two placed vertically below and above the
inner canthus of the left eye. EEG and EOG signals were
sampled at 256 Hz and Wltered between DC and 128 Hz.
Procedure
The EEG recording started with a 3 min rest EEG during
which the participant was instructed to open the eyes, close
them, or to deliberately blink, roll and move the eyes. This
sequence was required for the automatic reduction of eye
movement artefacts. Next, participants solved the arithme-
tic problems which were presented in four runs. Runs were
separated by short breaks in order to avoid participants los-
ing their concentra tion. Within each run of 72 additions or
72 subtractions, all problem types (retrieval, simple proce-
dural, complex procedural) were presented intermixed in
pseudo-randomised sequence. The order of the runs was
counterbalanced across participants. The EEG session took
about 2 h.
Data analysis
EEG data were band-pass Wltered between 0.5 and 45 Hz to
eliminate slow-frequency a nd power-line contamination
artefacts. EOG artefacts we re automatically reduced by
employing a regression method (Schlogl et al. 2007 ) based
on the resting EEG sequence. Afterwards, all EEG trials
were visually inspected for ar tefacts. The spatial informa-
tion of the artefact-free EEG data was enhanced by apply-
ing a 3D spline surface Lapl acian estimation (Babiloni
et al. 1998 ). This procedure has turned out to signi Wcantly
improve the spatial resolution of EEG potential distribu-
tions by reducing head volume conductor e Vects and can-
celling the inXuence of the electrical reference.
ERS/ERD was computed for correctly solved trials in
the theta (4–7 Hz) and alpha (8–12 Hz) frequency band. We
selected the broad alpha frequency range because an analy-
sis with separate lower (8–10 Hz) and upper (10–12 Hz) 638 Exp Brain Res (2009) 195:635–642
123alpha bands (cf. Klimesch 1999 ) did not reveal task-related
functional dissociations (similar to Bastiaansen et al. 2002 ;
Stipacek et al. 2003 ). For ERS/ERD computation, the data
from 500 to 2,500 ms after trial onset (during the Wxation
interval) served as reference interval. The activation inter-
val comprised the entire time period from problem presen-
tation (at 3,000 ms) until 125 ms before the onset of the
oral response as registered by the voice-key. Consequently,
the length of the activation interval varied between individ-
uals and across trials and captured the entire period of arith-
metic problem solving. The last 125 ms (i.e., 32 samples)
of the response time were discarded to account for the delay
of the voice-key trigger signal and to eliminate motor- and
speech-related artefacts. The band power of reference ( R)
and activation ( A) intervals were obtained by band-pass
Wltering, squaring the artefact-free EEG signal and
averaging over all trials separately for R and A. The amount
of ERS/ERD was calculated according to the formula:
%ERS/ERD = [( A¡R)/R]£100. Positive values indicate
increases in band power (ERS) and negative values indicate
decreases (ERD). For statistical analyses, the %ERS/ERD
values were topographically aggregated (by using the arith-
metic mean) to obtain eight cortical areas per hemisphere
(electrode positions given ex emplarily for the left hemi-
sphere): anteriofrontal (AF; Fp1, AF7, AF3), frontal (F; F7,
F5, F3, F1), frontocentral (FC; FC5, FC3, FC1), central (C;
C5, C3, C1), centroparietal (CP; CP5, CP3, CP1), parietal
(P; P7, P5, P3, P1); parietooccipital (PO; PO7, PO3, O1),
and temporal (T; FT7, T7, TP7).
In all statistical analyses, degrees of freedom were cor-
rected for violations of the sphericity assumption by means
of the Huynh–Feldt procedure; the probability of a type I
error was maintained at 0.05 . If applicable, uncorrected df
values together w ith the corrected P value and the Huynh–
Feldt epsilon ( /afii9830) are reported. Post hoc t tests were Bonfer-
roni corrected.
Results
Behavioural data
The mean error rates and r eaction times per problem type
and operation are displayed in Fig. 1. A repeated measures
ANOVA with problem type (retrieval, simple procedural,
complex procedural) and operation (addition, subtraction)
as within-subject factors was conducted on the error rates
and reaction times. With regard to error rate, there were
main eVects of problem type [ F(2,38) = 76.94, P< 0.001]
and operation [ F(1,19) = 10.44, P< 0.01], and a problem
type£operation interaction F(2,38) = 10.41, P<0 . 0 1 .
Post hoc t tests revealed that fewer errors were made on
retrieval than on the procedural problems ( Ps<0 . 0 1  c o r -rected). There were no di Verences between simple and
complex procedural problems in addition, while in subtrac-
tion more errors were made on the complex than on simple
procedural problems ( P< 0.001 corrected). No di Verences
in error rates between addition and subtraction for both
retrieval and simple procedural problems were found,
whereas for complex procedural problems more errors were
made on additions than on subtractions ( P<0 . 0 0 1  c o r -
rected).
Turning to reaction time, there was a main e Vect of prob-
lem type [ F(2,38) = 212.67, P< 0.0001], showing that
retrieval problems were solved faster than simple proce-
dural problems, which were solved faster than complex
procedural problems. There was a main e Vect of operation
[F(1,19) = 104.95, P< 0.001) and a problem
type£operation interaction [ F(2,38) = 29.82, P< 0.0001].
Post hoc t tests revealed that retrieval problems were solved
equally fast in addition and subtraction, while procedural
additions were solved faster than procedural subtractions
(Ps < 0.001 corrected).
Event-related (de-) synchronisation (ERS/ERD)
Repeated measures ANOVAs were computed for the theta
and alpha frequency band separately with problem type,
operation, hemisphere (left vs. right), and topographical
area (eight areas as described above) as within-subject
factors.
In the theta band, an interaction of problem type £
area£hemisphere [ F(14,266) = 2.28, P< 0.01] was found.
DiVerences between the three problem types mainly
emerged in the left hemisphere with the retrieval problems
showing the highest theta ERS (Fig. 2a). Post hoc compari-
sons revealed that the retrieval problems elicited signi WcantlyFig. 1 Mean error rates and reaction times as a function of problem
type and operation.  Bars  depict error rates ( left y -axis) and lines repre-
sent reaction times ( right y -axis). Error bars  depict 1 SE of the mean
 Exp Brain Res (2009) 195:635–642 639
123higher theta ERS than the co mplex procedural problems in
left frontocentral and parietooccipital areas ( Ps < 0.05 cor-
rected), and that the simple procedural problems showed
stronger theta ERS than the complex procedural problems
in the left parietooccipital cortex ( P< 0.05 corrected).
There were also main e Vects of problem type [ F(2,38) =
9.93, P< 0.001, /afii9830= 0.81] and area [ F(7,133) = 9.81,
P< 0.001, /afii9830= 0.44], and an area £hemisphere interaction
[F(7,133) = 3.51, P< 0.01, /afii9830= 0.61]. Overall, the highest
theta ERS was found for the retrieval problems (3.86%),
followed by simple (0.75%) and complex procedural prob-
lems ( ¡0.25%). Furthermore, theta ERS peaked in the pari-
etooccipital area, most prominently in the left hemisphere.
No operation e Vects emerged in the theta band.
In the alpha band, both problem- and operation-related
eVects were found. The problem type £area interaction
[F(14,266) = 9.09, P< 0.001, /afii9830= 0.49) revealed distinctive
alpha ERD for simple and complex procedural problems,
whereas the retrieval problems were accompanied by ERS/
ERD values around 0 (Fig. 2b). More speci Wcally, the ERD
of retrieval problems was signi Wcantly lower than that of
complex procedural problems in all topographical areas
(Ps < 0.05 corrected). This di Verence was especially pro-
nounced in the parietooccipital cortex bilaterally. The samepattern was found for main e Vects of problem type [ F(2,38)
= 36.05, P< 0.001), area [ F(7,133) = 9.48, P< 0.001,
/afii9830= 0.33], and hemisphere [ F(1,19) = 6.67, P<0 . 0 5 ) .
We also observed a signi Wcant operation £area interac-
tion [ F(7,133) = 3.86, P<0 . 0 5 ,  /afii9830= 0.45]. Subtractions dis-
played higher alpha ERD than additions, with the largest
diVerence in the parietoo ccipital cortex (Fig. 2c). These
diVerences, however, failed to reach signi Wcance in the post
hoc comparisons.
Discussion
The present high-resolution EEG study analysed the ERS
and ERD in the theta and alpha frequency bands while
solving diVerent types of additions and subtractions to
unravel the functional brain dynamics associated with the
application of retrieval and procedural arithmetic strate-
gies. To distinguish between these strategies, we presented
problems with a high probability of retrieval or procedural
strategy use. Retrieval problems had a sum or minuend
below or equal to 10, which showed high frequencies of
retrieval use in educated adults (e.g., Campbell and Xue
2001 ); procedural problems involved two-digit calculations,Fig. 2 Event-related (de-)syn-
