123to which the answer is unlikely to be directly retrieved
from memory. Behavioural data revealed that retrieval
problems were solved more accurate and faster than
procedural problems, con Wrming the distinction between
arithmetic fact recall and real calculation. The distinction
between retrieval and procedural problems was also evi-
dent in the ERS/ERD patterns in the theta and the alpha
frequency band.
As expected, the solution of retrieval problems elicited
stronger theta ERS than procedural problems with signi W-
cant diVerences in the frontocentr al and parietooccipital
brain areas of the left hemisphere, thereby extending previ-
ous EEG studies in arithmetic (Earle et al. 1996 ; Harmony
et al. 1999 ; Micheloyannis et al. 2005 ). Considerable evi-
dence indicates that oscillations in the theta frequency band
play an important role in me mory encoding and retrieval as
they are thought to be involved in functionally linking the
neocortex with the medial temp oral lobe, especially the hip-
pocampus (Bastiaansen and Hagoort 2003 ; Klimesch et al.
2005 ). Language studies have recently attributed theta ERS
to the retrieval of lexical information from long-term mem-
ory (Bastiaansen et al. 2006 ). For example, Bastiaansen
et al. ( 2005 ) found larger left temporal theta ERS while
reading semantically rich (e.g., nouns) compared to seman-
tically poor words (e.g., prepositions) which was inter-
preted to reXect the activation of a network involved in
retrieving the lexical-semantic properties in the Wrst class of
words (see also Hald et al. 2006 ). Our Wndings of higher
theta ERS in retrieval compar ed to procedural problems
may similarly re Xect the stronger reliance on retrieval of
lexical information from long-term memory. In line with
this, simple arithmetic problems are assumed to be stored
verbally in long-term memory and to engage left-hemi-
spheric language regions during retrieval (Dehaene et al.
2003 ; Grabner et al. 2009 ). The restriction of the theta
eVect to the left frontocentral  and parietooccipital brain
regions Wts with this and suggests that the theta frequency
band is sensitive not only to lexical-semantic retrieval dur-
ing language processing but also to the retrieval of verbally
represented arithmetic facts.
It should be noted that task-related increases in frontal
theta ERS have also been associated with working memory
load and attention demands (Gevins et al. 1997 ; Jensen and
Tesche 2002 ; Kahana et al. 2001 ). Our Wndings, however,
are not in line with this interpretation. If frontal theta ERS
would reXect working memory processes, then this e Vect
should be most prominent in the (complex) procedural
problems, who have the highest working memory load.
However, we found that theta ERS in left frontocentral and
parietooccipital areas was higher in retrieval than proce-
dural problems. Moreover, there was no e Vect of arithmetic
operation in the theta band, even though the procedural
subtraction problems were more di Ycult than the additionproblems (Fig. 1), the latter of which suggests more e Vort-
ful processing or working memory load in subtraction than
in addition. This all indicates  that the observed theta e Vects
likely reXect the diVerential demands on lexical retrieval
rather than on working memory resources.
EVects related to problem type were also found in the
alpha frequency range. As hypothesised, procedural
problems were accompanied by stronger alpha ERD than
retrieval problems in all cortical areas, with the largest
diVerence emerging in parietooccipital regions, bilaterally.
Variations in parietal alpha ERD between di Verent types of
arithmetic problems have not been reported so far. Alpha
oscillations are assumed to be modulated by thalamo-corti-
cal and cortico-cortical loops (Klimesch et al. 2007 ) and
have been observed to desynchronise while processing var-
ious cognitive tasks (Neubauer et al. 2006 ). It is assumed in
current neurophysiological models that the alpha amplitude
is inversely related to the activated cortical neuronal popu-
lations, and alpha ERD can be regarded as a correlate of
cortical activation (Pfurtsc heller and Lopes da Silva 1999 ,
2005 ). Several studies have corroborated this by showing
higher alpha ERD over task-rel ated areas in conditions with
increasing diYculty or cognitive demands (e.g., Gevins
et al. 1997 ; Stipacek et al. 2003 ). Thus, the present alpha
ERD result may re Xect higher cortical activation in the
more demanding procedural compared to the simple
retrieval problems. The largest activation di Verence over
parietooccipital regions converges with previous fMRI
studies showing stronger bilateral parietal activation in
complex (vs. simple) arithmetic problems (Kong et al.
2005 ; Menon et al. 2000 ) and procedural (vs. retrieval)
problems (Grabner et al. 2009 ).
The diVerential sensitivity of the theta and alpha band to
arithmetic problem solving strategies is striking. Solving
complex procedural problems is accompanied by clear-cut
alpha ERD (most strongly at parietooccipital areas bilater-
ally) while no theta ERS was observed in any of the ana-
lysed brain areas. Conversely, the retrieval problems elicit
strong theta ERS (at left frontocentral and parietooccipital
areas) but no alpha ERD. This frequency-related distinction
between retrieval and procedural strategies in arithmetic
highlight the ERS/ERD method as an interesting tool to
validate the often controversial use of verbal self-report
measures to study arithmetic strategies (Kirk and Ashcraft
2001 ).
Our study also aimed to investigate neurophysiological
diVerences between addition and subtraction problems. The
triple-code model (Dehaene and Cohen 1997 ) assumes
diVerences between simple addition, which should rely on a
verbal representation, and simple subtraction, which should
rely on a nonverbal quantity code. Our Wndings are not
entirely in line with this assumption. There were no perfor-
mance diVerences for the retrieval problems and no operation Exp Brain Res (2009) 195:635–642 641
123eVects in the theta band, suggesting similar underlying
cognitive processes. Some evidence for stronger alpha ERD
while solving subtraction compared to addition problems
was found, but this di Verence failed to reach signi Wcance in
the post hoc tests. Subtractions displayed higher ERD than
additions at parietooccipital br ain areas. This higher alpha
ERD in subtraction may re Xect the higher engagement of
task-related cortical resources. These Wndings echo the
fMRI data of Kong et al. ( 2005 ) who showed that both sub-
traction and procedural complex ity activated left intraparie-
tal sulcus and hypothesised that their common activation
represents a general network that supports more di Ycult
calculation.
To conclude, the present high-resolution EEG study
shows a high sensitivity of the ERS/ERD measure to cap-
ture diVerent strategies involved in solving addition and
subtraction problems. The Wndings suggest that arithmetic
fact retrieval is re Xected in power increases (ERS) in the
theta frequency band, whereas the application of more
demanding procedural strategi es is accompanied by power
decreases (ERD) in the alpha band. The surprisingly strong
frequency speci Wcity of the strategy-related e Vects provides
a potential starting point for the development of electro-
physiological indices of di Verent problem solving strategies
in mental arithmetic.
