/C2232020 Taylor & Francis Group, LLCAPPLIED NEUROPSYCHOLOGY: CHILD
2022, VOL. 11, NO. 3, 328 –338
https://doi.org/10.1080/21622965.2020.1830403 determine if brain coherence at rest is predictive of general
math skills. This information will help to shed light on theunderlying neurocognitive mechanisms fundamental to
mathematical ability and thus, guide future research on per-
formance-based math assessment batteries as well as mathinterventions for struggling children.
Electroencephalography (EEG) approaches are one such
method to investigate a person ’s neurocognitive processes
that underly specific behaviors and abilities since theseapproaches have the potential to highlight the neurological
underpinnings of cognition. Additionally, findings from
EEG research help to inform specific interventions andtherapeutic applications such as neurofeedback therapy.Consequently, there is a growing interest for the use EEG inboth the research and practical domains of healthcare, as
this imaging modality offers up the potential for growth in
many spheres of psychological clinical practice. One suchEEG analysis technique involves the investigation of coher-ence, a type of quantitative EEG (qEEG) analysis that is
often used when examining continuous EEG data
(Gonz /C19alez-Garrido et al., 2018; John et al., 1988 ; Thatcher
et al., 1989 ,2001 ,2005 ). Specifically, EEG coherence refers
to the degree of brain activity synchrony between specifiedlocations throughout the brain (Gasser et al., 1987 ); it can
therefore be used to determine which brain networks are “in
sync ”with one another during the EEG recording and
which general brain regions are involved in those particularnetworks (Dumermuth, 1973; Gonz /C19alez-Garrido et al., 2018 ).
One exploratory research technique involves the investi-
gation of an individual ’s coherence while they are not per-
forming a task. A coherence recording at rest (subject not
performing a task) implies a recording of the individual ’s
basal electrophysiological brain functions, which has beentermed the “EEG-Default Mode Network ”by Chen et al.
(2008 ). Examining an individual ’s default EEG brain activity
can provide information about their neurocognitive apti-
tudes or, in some cases, incapacities (Margolis et al., 2019 ;
Rocca et al., 2010; Savini et al., 2019).
Neuroimaging and math
In 1992, Dehaene proposed a theoretical neurocognitive
model to outline mental arithmetic and numerical process-
ing entitled “the triple-code model. ”Three years later —with
the advent of fMRI research and its corresponding studiesthoroughly underway —Dehaene and Cohen ( 1995 )
expanded upon this model by reviewing the available fMRI
case studies exploring this topic. Through their review of
the relevant fMRI research, the triple-code model wasexpanded to create a cohesive functional-anatomical modelof number and arithmetic mental processing. This updated
model hypothesized the anatomical correlates of mathemat-
ical ability and number processing. Specifically, the updatedtriple-code model posits that numbers are processed bythree distinct brain areas: (1) visual number processingoccurs in the ventral occipito-temporal areas, (2) quantity
and magnitude judgements occur in the inferior parietal
areas (Brodmann area 40), and (3) the mathematical verbalcode is processed in the left perisylvian areas in the inferior
parietal lobules. The model has since been empirically vali-dated (Schmithorst & Brown, 2004 ) and further expanded
upon with the availability of additional fMRI data
(Arsalidou & Taylor, 2011).
Arsalidou and Taylor ( 2011) updated Dehaene and
Cohen ( 1995 ) model by reviewing the extant fMRI research
exploring cognition as it relates to math ability and creatingan atlas of the functional anatomical correlates for mentalarithmetic operations. The atlas indicates that both the left
and right inferior parietal lobules (Brodmann area 40: BA
40) are the most likely brain regions to show activation dur-ing general numerical processing and calculation tasks.Additionally, their review revealed that BA 40 showed arelatively high likelihood of activation during addition tasks,a moderate activation likelihood during subtraction tasks,and a relatively low likelihood for activation during multipli-cation tasks (Arsalidou & Taylor, 2011 ). These findings sug-
gest that the cognitive processes specialized to BA 40 play a
crucial role in a child ’s basic processing of numbers and
performance of simple mental calculations; a finding thatfurther supports the theories first presented in Dehaene ’s
Dehaene ( 1992 ) functional-anatomical triple-code model.
Quantitative EEG has a history of being used to assess
underlying brain functions for various neuropsychological
disorders (e.g., Thatcher et al., 1989 ,2001 ). Numerous stud-
ies have also utilized qEEG to examine its relationship withmeasures of intelligence, several of them reporting signifi-cant relationships between coherence and standardized intel-ligence measures (Mart /C19ın-loeches et al., 2001; Neubauer &
Fink, 2009; Thatcher et al., 2005 ). Additional studies have
cemented the utility of qEEG to study neuropsychologicaldifferences in individuals with ADHD, demonstrating its
utility in this domain with several decades worth of litera-
ture (Barry et al., 2009; Clarke et al., 1998 ,2001 ; Janzen
et al., 1995; Satterfield et al., 1972 ).
Despite an extensive history of utilizing qEEG for study-
ing various neurocognitive phenomena, a relatively smallbase of literature exists outlining its utility for examining
children ’s academic skills and abilities. While recent EEG
studies have begun to focus on children ’s reading abilities
and disorders (e.g., dyslexia; Bosch-Bayard et al., 2020), very
few EEG studies have examined the underlying neurocogni-tive mechanisms involved in general mathematics skills.
Although arithmetic abilities have been studied for many
years within the frame of an educational context, neurocog-
nitive research on mathematics abilities is a relatively recentfield of study (Plerou & Vlamos, 2016). One of the most
recent research studies on this topic by Gonz /C19
alez-Garrido
et al. ( 2018 ) explores mathematical achievement as it relates
to qEEG measures of coherence. Specifically, this studyaimed to evaluate the coherence levels in children with dif-fering math skill abilities as they performed math tasks and
examine coherence differences between children who per-
formed particularly well in math tasks against those whoperformed poorly. Findings from this study suggest thatthere are no specific math brain networks in children andfurther posit that a child ’s mathematical abilities rely upon aAPPLIED NEUROPSYCHOLOGY: CHILD 329 complex integration of several connected brain regions and
networks (Gonz /C19alez-Garrido et al., 2018). This theory is in
support of findings from prior research depicting EEG dif-
ferences during mental calculation tasks (Fern /C19andez et al.,
1995 ). Additionally, Gonz /C19alez-Garrido et al. ( 2018 ) posit
that higher math achieving children display more localizedcoherence over parietal areas —particularly in the beta
band —than low achieving children, which is in alignment
with prior fMRI research (e.g., Zhang et al., 2017 ). Thus, we
expect children with greater coherence around BA 40 (a BAin the parietal brain region) to display greater math abilitiesthan those with lower coherence values around this region.
A significant number of studies have implicated
Brodmann area 40, synonymously referred to as the inferiorparietal lobule (IPL), as having an important connection
with math ability (Anderson et al., 2011; Cohen et al., 2000 ;
Kroger et al., 2008), though many of its theorized functions
remain contested. Experts propose that this brain regionplays crucial roles in spatial perception, visual motor inte-
gration (Andersen, 2011), tactile perception, manual con-
struction (J €ancke et al., 2001), working memory (Baldo &
Dronkers, 2006 ), decision making (Vickery & Jiang, 2009 ),
sustained attention (Singh-Curry & Husain, 2009 ), and men-
tal mathematical operations (Anderson et al., 2011 ; Cohen
et al., 2000; Kroger et al., 2008 ).
Several techniques have been used to study the function-
ality of this brain region. Lesion studies indicate that
patients who have suffered damage to the IPL often sufferfrom multiple syndromes including aphasia, dyslexia, visual-spatial neglect, and dyscalculia (Cohen et al., 2000 ; Singh-
Curry & Husain, 2009 ). Neuroimaging research on this
region further supports the results from lesion studies,
showing that the IPL plays a critical role in language andcalculation abilities (Cohen et al., 2000 ; Rivera et al., 2005 ).
Interestingly, further findings show that children who are
more adept in mathematics have greater activation in the
IPL with less activation in other regions, and therefore con-clude that this brain region has a functional specializationfor mental arithmetic processes (Rivera et al., 2005 ).
Current study
Although progress has been made in improving our under-
standing of the neurocognitive mechanisms underlyingmathematical abilities (e.g., Arsalidou & Taylor, 2011 ;
Gonz /C19alez-Garrido et al., 2018 ), experts in the field still strug-
gle to translate this basic neurocognitive research into prac-
tical outcomes (Plerou & Vlamos, 2016 ). Recent
translational research has begun investigating the utility ofneurophysiological resting-state paradigms to evaluate bio-markers of various clinical and neurological disorders
(Takamura & Hanakawa, 2017). The current study utilizes a
qEEG resting-state paradigm to explore children ’s basal elec-
trophysiological brain activity to determine if coherence val-ues among brain regions at rest are predictive of generalmath skills. Although task-based EEG and fMRI research on
math disabilities elucidates key brain areas actively involved
in completing specific math tasks, there are severaladvantages to resting-state paradigms, which were taken
advantage of in the current study to uncover associations
between brain networks and later math performance.
By using a resting-state paradigm, we gathered continu-
ous sets of EEG data from child participants and extractedcoherence values between BA 40 in each hemisphere and
their connectivity with the rest of their respective hemi-
spheres. Using EEG resting-state coherence to investigateBAs that are significantly coherent with BA 40 allowed for
the identification of specific basal electrophysiological brain
activity that is linked to standardized math achievementscores, and therefore, general sets of math abilities(Anderson et al., 2011 ; Cohen et al., 2000 ; Kroger
et al., 2008).
Methods
Participants
Data used in the current study was derived from a larger
parent study aimed at examining the relationships betweenbrain function, math performance, and anxiety. Participantsfor the current study included 60 school-aged children (ages
7–12 years), including typically developing children, children
with low math achievement (LA), and children with a sus-pected and/or confirmed math learning disability (MLD).This sample was utilized to ensure the full range of mathem-
atical achievement scores was obtained for the study sample.
Children were excluded from the study if they were deemedto have an intellectual disability, as determined by their
Broad Cognitive Ability score from the Woodcock-Johnson
Tests of Cognitive Ability —3rd Edition (WJ-III Cog;
Woodcock et al., 2001 ) falling below the score of 70.
Demographic characteristics of the sample are reported
inTable 1 .
Measures
The current study used the WJ-III Ach to determine math-
ematical abilities. This battery is designed to measure an
individual ’s academic skills whom are aged two to 90 or
more years, and it has been validated for its reliability andconsistency in research studies. Its core subtests have
median reliability coefficients of r
11¼.81–.94 (Note, the
Broad Cognitive Ability score on the WJ-III Cog was usedas an estimate of IQ, to rule-out general cognitiveTable 1. Demographic characteristics.
