in the inclusion criteria). The three core math subtests wereused for the current study and include the MathCalculation, Applied Problems, and Math Fluency subtests.
The Math Calculation subtest requires students to write
down the answers to increasingly difficult mathematicsproblems (ranging from counting problems to algebra). TheApplied Problems subtest includes math problems verballyread to the student by the examiner. Students answer ver-bally on the Applied Problems subtest but are allowed a
paper and pencil if needed. Lastly, the Math Fluency subtest
requires students to answer as many simple math problemsas they can in a specified timeframe.
EEG data were collected to examine whether specific fre-
quency bands (i.e., delta, theta, alpha 1, alpha 2, beta 1, beta2, beta 3, and high-beta) and the coherence patterns amongthem were able to predict the degree of a child ’s mathemat-
ical abilities. EEG data were recorded from 19 channel elec-
trodes distributed across the scalp via Electro-cap using the
10/20 placement system. Data were sampled at 1026 Hzusing a BrainMaster Discovery 24E amplifier. This devicewas selected due to its FDA approval classification as well asits compatibility with the Neuroguide program 6.6.4(Thatcher, 2011 ). A 60 Hz notch filter was used to remove
noise caused by electronics from the surrounding environ-
ment and the bandwidth range was set to record frequenciesbetween 1.0 and 30 Hz. The frequency bands used in thecurrent study are defined as follows: delta (1.0 –4.0 Hz), theta
(4.0–8.0 Hz), alpha 1 (8.0 –10.0 Hz), alpha 2 (10.0 –12.0 Hz),
beta 1 (12.0 –15.0 Hz), beta 2 (15.0 –18.0 Hz), beta 3
(18.0 –25.0 Hz), and high-beta (25.0 –30.0 Hz). Impedance
values for the A1 and A2 ear reference electrodes were keptbelow 5K X, and all other electrode impedance values were
kept below 10K Xfor all subjects. Neuroguide 6.6.4
(Thatcher, 2011) was used for removing EEG artifact in the
data and to obtain normative values of qEEG spectral coher-
ence and MATLAB ( 2018 ) was used for data transformation
and organization.
Procedures
Prior to conducting the study, approval to perform the
research procedures was granted from the University ofSouth Carolina ’s institutional review board. Participants
were provided child assent and parental consent forms and
signatures were obtained. Preliminary measures of mathem-atical skills and cognitive abilities were obtained from partic-ipants who agreed to partake in the study. Data fromparticipants who met the study eligibility criteria wereretained and EEG data were recorded. EEG recordings were
obtained by fitting the participants with their appropriately
sized Electro-Cap and ground leads. The recordings werecollected over three-minute intervals while the participantswere awake, at rest, with their eyes were closed. Thismethod of collecting resting-state data was used due to theadvantages it offers for young participants, specifically, three
minutes is a relatively short amount of time for a child to
remain still and calm, but still allows for the adequatecollection of qEEG data to for coherence analyses.
Furthermore, having participants close their eyes does notsignificantly impact brain activity in brain regions unrelatedto visual processing (e.g., math regions), and having eyes
closed during an EEG recording provides a method to
reduce common EEG artifact associated with eye musclemovements (Barry et al., 2007). All data used for the current
study were collected over the course of one to two study ses-sions dependent on participant availability.
Data analysis
Prior to conducting analyses, the first minute of each partic-
ipant ’s qEEG data was manually inspected to identify a min-
imum of ten seconds of artifact-free data. The visualinspection process involves a review of the raw EEG data,where the reviewer aims to identify points in time with
abnormal spikes in amplitude across multiple channels at
the same time. Artifacts of this type are typically related toscalp and/or facial muscle movement and are thereforeremoved from the dataset individually for each participant.Following visual inspection, an automated program withinthe Neuroguide software was used to identify and flag EEG
patterns consistent with artifacts related to drowsiness (e.g.,
slow rolling eye movements, specific changes in alpharhythm, specific changes in theta and beta ratios, etc.) andeye muscle movement. These flagged patterns were subse-quently reviewed for accuracy and manually removed by thereviewer if necessary. The Neuroguide software then uses
the artifact-free data from the now “cleaned ”10 s sample as
a reference. With this artifact-free reference, the automatedsoftware program identifies and selects artifact-free datafrom the rest of the three-minute dataset and discards allportions of the data with artifacts; thus, yielding an entirelyartifact-free EEG sample. This procedure was repeated for
each participant. By using the automated artifact flagging
and rejections programs housed within the software severalunique advantages are offered compared to other methods.These methods are reliant upon objective quantitative valueswithin each participant ’s dataset, as such, this more objective
method of data cleaning removes the potential for con-
founding inconsistencies when rejecting EEG artifact for
each participant.
Coherence measures between electrodes were obtained
through an automated Neuroguide program. Neuroguide
software contains a proprietary database with informationfrom 625 individuals, covering the age range of two monthsto 82.6 years (Johnstone & Gunkelman, 2003 , pp. 42 –43). By
sourcing this database, Neuroguide yields reports which pro-vide coherence values in raw Z-score units. Utilizing stand-
ardized coherence values allows for the reduction of
discrepancies in coherence due to age-related/developmental
differences. A subsequent automated Neuroguide program,utilizing Low Resolution Electromagnetic Tomography(LORETA), was performed to convert the standardizedcoherence values between electrodes into a format that
yields standardized coherence values between each of the 52
Brodmann areas in either hemisphere.APPLIED NEUROPSYCHOLOGY: CHILD 331 LORETA is one of the most extensively used algorithms
for localizing the source of EEG signal detected on the scalp
(Grech et al., 2008). It accomplishes this by attributing elec-
trode activity to specific regions under the scalp, indexingthose regions through a standardized MRI atlas, and assign-ing BAs to the regions based on the MRI atlas. By running
the EEG dataset through the LORETA program 3-dimen-
sional statistical maps were generated to model the distribu-tion of brain coherence values. The obtained values ofcoherence between scalp electrodes were converted into
coherence values between each of the 52 BAs within their
respective hemispheres. By obtaining models of EEG activitybased on an MRI atlas, the current study utilized the find-ings by Arsalidou and Taylor ( 2011 ), which suggest that BA
40 is heavily implicated in mathematical cognitive processes,
to provide a framework for which the analyses would be
based off. As such, MATLAB ( 2018 ) was utilized to extract
intrahemispheric coherence data between BA 40 and allother BAs from each respective brain hemisphere. This data
was then exported to Microsoft Excel and IBM SPSS (ver-
sion 24; IBM SPSS Statistics for Windows, 2017 ) for
final analyses.
Using IBM SPSS ( IBM SPSS Statistics for Windows ,
2017 ), principle component analyses (PCA) with varimax
rotation were applied individually to coherence values acrosseach frequency band of interest (delta, theta, alpha 1, alpha
2, beta 1, beta 2, beta 3, and high-beta) for BA 40 in the left
hemisphere then separately for each frequency for BA 40 inthe right hemisphere to the rest of the BAs in their respect-ive hemispheres. PCA was used to reduce the number ofEEG coherence variables and extract the essential features
from the data, thus facilitating a more accurate interpret-
ation of the coherence properties between brain regions ineither hemisphere. PCA is a traditional method that hasbeen used in EEG analysis due to the high number of varia-
bles that are acquired and the necessity to reduce that num-
ber for studies with smaller sample sizes. PCA has beenused in previous research to achieve similar analytic goals(Vig/C19ario et al., 2000 ). Only components whose
Kaiser –Meyer –Olkin (KMO) measure of sampling adequacy
was at or above the recommended value (KMO ¼.60;
Dziuban & Shirkey, 1974 ), had eigenvalues greater than 1.0
(Gorsuch, 1990), and that passed the scree test (Bro &
Smilde, 2014 ) were considered for ensuing analyses.
PCA revealed that BA 40 was involved in components
across various frequencies in both hemispheres. Subsequent
bivariate Pearson ’s correlation coefficients were computed to
quantify associations between EEG coherence componentsand math performance The components whose correlationswere significant with at least two of the three WJ-III Achmath subtests ( p’s<.05) were used in subsequent multiple
regression analyses to assess their utility in predicting each
math subtest scores individually. The large number of cor-relation tests run and the relatively small sample size (i.e.,45 components correlated with each of the three math subt-
ests, yielding 135 correlations on 60 participants) introduced
the issue of random false positive results due to the highlikelihood family-wise type 1 errors. To minimize thechances of Type I error across such a large number of tests,
we required a coherence component to correlate with atleast two out of the three math subtests to meet criteria forinclusion in the subsequent regression analyses. These crite-ria assumed it is unlikely that a component would correlatewith two (or all three) math subtests by chance and enabledus to focus on brain activity related to broad, rather thanspecific, math skills. Thus, despite not correcting for mul-tiple comparisons in a traditional fashion (e.g., Bonferroni
correction), this strategy does account for and effectively
reduce the occurrence of random false positive results. Thelast step of the analyses used each of the significantly corre-lated coherence components to predict both broad math abl-ity and broad reading ability scores to determine if theextracted coherence components were specifically associatedwith math, or academic ability more generally (i.e., discrim-inant validity).
Results
Descriptive statistics for all participants ’scores on the WJ-
III Ach math subtests including means, standard deviations,minimum scores, and maximum scores are reported inTable 2 . Examination of the descriptive statistics indicates
that the current study included a sample of participants
whose math achievement scores are generally representative
of the range of scores observed in the population.
Eligible components (eigenvalues greater than 1.0, passed
the scree test, had a KMO value greater that .60) wereextracted separately for each frequency band in both brainhemispheres using varimax rotation. Table 3 lists all compo-
nents that were extracted meeting these criteria for each
wavelength by hemisphere with the percent of variance
explained by the Eigenvalue of that component.
Associations with broad math ability
Pearson ’s correlations were used to examine the linear rela-
tionships between the extracted EEG components ( Table 3 )
and the WJ-III Ach math scores. A total of three coherence
components were significantly correlated with all three math
subtest scores and one component that was correlated withtwo out of the three scores. It was assumed that if a compo-nent correlated with at least two out of three math subtestsit was indicative of brain activity related to broad, ratherthan specific, math skills. The four extracted componentsindicative of broad math abilities included: right hemispherealpha 1 component one, right hemisphere theta componentfour, left hemisphere delta component one, and left hemi-
sphere theta component one.
