Multiple regression
A multiple regression model including all four components
was used to characterize their utility for predicting children ’s
broad math abilities ( Table 5 ). The model explains 30% of
the variance and significantly predicts the Broad Math WJ-
ACH score, which is a composite of all three math subtests(F(4, 55) ¼5.88, p<.01, R
2¼0.33). Variance inflation
factors (VIFs) for each variable are below two, suggesting
low multicollinearity within the model.
Discriminant validity
The predictive utility of the identified components was
examined for the broad reading composite score to identifywhether these coherence circuits were related to math-spe-
cific abilities, or to general academic abilities ( Table 6 ). The
right first alpha 1 component, the left first and right fourththeta components, and the left first delta component wereeach examined to determine their correlations with broadreading ability using broad cluster scores provided by the
WJ-III Ach.
Three of the four components, (excluding the left first
theta component (D)) are correlated to reading ability ( p>
.05). The components are positively related to math andreading ability, except for the right fourth theta component(B), which is negatively related to both. Overall, these results
suggest that, despite including BA 40, components A, B, andC may be tied to general academic ability and/or neurocog-
nitive systems that are foundational to academic perform-
ance, rather than mathematics processing specifically.Notably, the left first theta (D) component is related exclu-
sively to math scores, and not reading scores, suggesting a
domain-specific component for mathematics.
Further, a multiple regression model including all four
components was examined to determine if the model signifi-cantly predicts the Broad Reading score. The model explains26% of the variance and does, in fact, significantly predict
Broad Reading scores, F(4,55) ¼4.79, p<.01, indicating a
domain general model. Interestingly, if the right alpha com-ponent (A) is removed from the model (predicting BroadMath and Broad Reading), then the model significantly pre-
dicts Broad Math scores ( F(3,56) ¼6.63, p¼.001, R
2¼
0.26), but not Broad Reading, ( F(3,56) ¼3.88, p>.01,R2
¼0.17). This suggests that the alpha component (A) may be
related to domain general cognitive processes, but once that
component is removed, the model is more indicative of
domain specific cognitive processes for mathematics.
Discussion
The present study investigated BA 40 and its qEEG coher-
ence patterns in school-aged children with a wide range of
math abilities. Currently, there is a dearth of research exam-ining neurocognitive underpinnings of brain functions thatare implicated in mathematical abilities. This is the first
study to examine associations of BA 40 qEEG coherence
and math performance. Importantly, the current study addsto cognition literature on mathematics performance by pro-
viding empirical support for a unique method to examine
brain activity as it relates to academic performance. Thismethod provides evidence of specific brain activity patternsthat are implicated in math ability. QEEG measures, such as
coherence, provide bio-signatures associated with a child ’s
aptitude for math, and these bio-signatures can be used toenhance the theoretical understanding of the cognitive proc-esses that underly MLD. Additionally, the accumulation of
findings from studies utilizing resting-state qEEG paradigms
to assess academic ability can one day provide practitionerswith the necessary information to improve SLD identifica-tion practices and guide intervention techniques.
As mathematics skills are important for a child ’s future
academic and vocational success (Garnett, 1998 ; Ritchie &
Bates, 2013), improving the ability to quickly and accurately
determine a child ’s aptitude for mathematics is particularly
important. Improving the theoretical understanding of how
a child ’s brain performs math tasks can be achieved through
the examination of neuro-electrophysiological activity that iscorrelated with math performance. Understanding theunderlying neural processes is a crucial step toward address-
ing the need for improved mathematics assessment and
intervention practices.
