processes implicated in children ’s broad mathematical abil-
ities. Despite the utility of more common neuroimagingmethods for studying brain activity related to math perform-
ance (e.g., event-related potential or functional magnetic res-
onance imaging research), qEEG resting-state researchparadigms offer several advantages that are particularly use-ful in the context of the current study ’s aims and goals.
As noted in fMRI research, collecting resting-state data is
easier than task-related data, particularly for clinical popula-
tions (Heine et al., 2012). Additionally, resting-state qEEG
paradigms eliminate researcher bias in picking an appropri-ate math task to examine broad mathematics abilities. Lastly,using resting-state data allows for examination of connectiv-ity circuits broadly related to math abilities, rather thanobserving activity only related to the demands of specificmathematics tasks. As such, studies that use resting-state
paradigms are more generalizable and comparable to each
other given that there is no reliance on stimuli or having tocontrol for behavior.
Research has long supported the notion that BA 40 (IPL)
plays a major role in the cognitive processes surroundingmath performance (Anderson et al., 2011; Cohen et al., 2000 ;
Kroger et al., 2008), the current study adds to this knowledge-
base by elucidating the associations between children ’s math
abilities and intrahemispheric brain connectivity levels withBA 40. Results of the present study indicate that there are twosignificant coherence networks in each hemisphere that areassociated with broad math ability as determined by standar-dized WJ-III Ach math test scores (see Figure 1 ).
In the right hemisphere a coherence network in the alpha 1
frequency band (8 –10 Hz) significantly predicts standard
scores across the Calculation, Applied Problems, and MathFluency subtests, thus indicating its involvement in mathem-atics more globally. This network is comprised of BA 40 andvarious BAs situated across the temporal lobe. The alpha fre-
quency is generally associated with a relaxed state (Milner,
1968 ) while the function of the right temporal lobe is generally
associated with the organization and memory encoding ofsensory input (Zulkurnaini et al., 2012 ), thus this component
may highlight the importance of a child ’s ability to suppress
or“relax ”the functions of the right temporal lobe in order to
perform well in math tasks. Children who exhibit higher levelsof suppression, may have a propensity for greater math capa-
bilities due to their ability to block out competing demands
on cognitive processes. Similarly, in the right hemisphere, anadditional coherence network in the theta frequency band(4–8 Hz) was predictive of global math skills. This network
includes BA 40 and various BAs situated in the frontoparietallobe. The theta frequency band is associated with concentra-tion, where too much can result in impulsivity and difficulty
attending (Milner, 1968 ); the function of the frontoparietal
lobes is generally associated with executive control and prob-lem solving (Stuss et al., 1985 ). Thus, a child ’s reduced in theta
activity in this region compared to other children likely indi-cates an improved ability to attend and therefore, exhibit thenecessary levels of concentration to solve math problems.In the left hemisphere, a coherence network in the delta fre-
quency band (1 –4 Hz) predictive of global math skills included
BA 40 and various BAs in the medial prefrontal cortex. The
delta frequency band is largely implicated in sleep, attention
and decision-making processes (N /C19acher et al., 2013), while the
medial prefrontal cortex is associated with decision-making andmemory retrieval processes (Euston et al., 2012). Therefore, this
component suggests that children with increased decision-mak-
ing abilities may also have an increased ability to perform well
in math related tasks. This hypothesis is consistent with long-standing evidence suggesting mathematics ability is associatedwith executive functioning and cognitive control in early child-hood (Bull et al., 2011; Mazzocco & Kover, 2007).
The final component identified was a left hemisphere theta
(4–8 Hz) component. This was predictive of global math abil-
ity (but not Applied Problems) and included BA 40 and vari-ous BAs in the superior region of the temporal lobe. Thiscomponent is likely related to the attenuation of working
memory functions as theta is related to concentration and the
left temporal lobe is associated with receptive and expressivelanguage as well as the phonological rehearsal processes impli-cit in working memory systems (Deschamps et al., 2020 ;
Milner, 1968; Zulkurnaini et al., 2012). The lack of association
between this component and the Applied Problems subtest
may be explained given relations between the left temporal
lobe and phonological processes used in working memory.The Applied Problem subtest involves listening to verbal mathproblems, thus intruding on one ’s ability to engage in the
phonological rehearsal strategies that are crucial for some
children to remember and perform the steps to complete basic
math problems (Swanson, 2004 ; Swanson & Kim, 2007 ).
Overall, results demonstrate that in the right hemisphere
increased alpha 1 coherence between BA 40 and the tem-poral lobe and reduced theta coherence between BA 40 and
the frontoparietal region are associated with increased math
abilities in children. Likewise, in the left hemisphere,increased delta coherence between BA 40 and the medialprefrontal cortex and increased theta coherence between BA40 and the superior temporal lobe is associated with
increased math abilities in children.
Notably, many of the components for predicting math
abilities discovered in this study were also predictive ofreading, except for a theta coherence network linking BA40 to other BAs in the superior region of the temporal
lobe. These results lend support to the domain-specific
and domain-general hypotheses that surround neuroscien-tific research on learning disabilities (see J €ancke et al.,
2019 ). Specifically, components related to deficits can be
classified as domain-general, indicating that individuals
with any type of learning disability can have underactive
network connectivity in specified areas. However, somenetworks may represent specific deficits only present inindividuals with a specific type of disability (i.e., math,reading, writing). The noted theta coherence componentincorporating the left parietal and temporal lobes presents
as a specific math-related network that is associated with
diminished coherence in children with lower mathemat-ics abilities.APPLIED NEUROPSYCHOLOGY: CHILD 335 When exploring the data further, a model containing
three of the components (excluding the right alpha compo-nent) significantly predicts Broad Math scores, but not
Broad Reading. This is suggestive of a cohesive domain-
specific model of brain activity that underlies mathematicalabilities more exclusively. Future studies should compareidentified connectivity networks for both reading andmathematics ability to determine whether these networks
are representative of specific or general academic abilities.
Future directions
Future studies may wish to utilize a larger sample size to
examine cognition and math ability. Due to the relatively
small sample size used in the current study, several steps were
taken to reduce the number of variables within the dataset.The major consequences of this are two-fold; the first conse-quence results from performing PCA, which was performedto combine variables with redundancy. By combining multiple
coherence variables into one component variable, spatial reso-
lution of the anatomical structures involved in the coherencevariables was sacrificed and the interpretability of brainregions represented by the variables was limited only to gen-eral brain regions rather than distinct BAs or brain structures.
With a larger sample size, PCA may not be necessary since
the large sample would not necessitate the reduction of varia-bles, thus allowing researchers to examine coherence variablesindividually rather than in clusters of components. Though
beyond the scope of the current study, eliminating PCA from
the methods used would allow for the examination of varia-bles that are related to specific math skills rather than globalmath ability. Furthermore, a large sample would allow add-itional analyses to examine differences between high achieving
and low achieving mathematics students. Interestingly, inter-
hemispheric coherence may be an especially important area toresearch as individuals who are gifted in math exhibit height-ened interhemispheric connectivity compared to individuals
who do not have exceptional math skills (O ’Boyle, 2005 ).
Future neuroimaging research should aim to identify the
function of the four coherence networks outlined in the cur-
rent study. This can be achieved through functional neuroi-
maging techniques such as ERP, fNIRS, fMRI, MEG, etc.Since prior research suggests that mathematics skills rely onseveral key cognitive abilities, such as planning skills, atten-
tion, processing speed, working memory, and number sense
(Van Luit & Toll, 2018 ), future studies may also aim to
empirically determine which aspects of cognition each of theidentified coherence networks are implicated in.
Lastly, more translational research is needed to increase
the practical utility of qEEG research. To expand the prac-tical utility of the current study ’s findings, future studies
should pursue methods to address neural connectivity pat-
terns that are consistent with poor academic performance;interventions such as neurofeedback therapy and appliedbehavior analysis have been used to address disconnectionsyndromes (e.g., Schummer, 2008) and should therefore be
investigated as potential interventions aiming to mitigate the
symptoms of MLD.Conclusion
The current study is the first qEEG study to highlight empir-
ical associations between BA 40 coherence and math ability.
While the results presented in the current study offer novel
information regarding cognition and math performance, their
interpretation relies upon the assumption that a qEEG coher-
ence network at rest correlating with a math score is indicative
of a network that is directly involved in the performance of
that math task. It is important to point out that, in fact, the
four networks identified in the current study represent basal
electrophysiological activity at rest and this resting-state brain
activity does not imply that these networks are involved with
the math tasks they are correlated with, nor that they become
active during the performance of them. Despite this, the net-
works identified herein arepredictive of math performance
and therefore have utility in furthering the MLD knowledge-
base, though interpretations warrant caution until further
research validates these findings.
Despite this limitation, utilizing the method of EEG imple-
mentation and analysis outlined in this study can improve the
understanding of how a developing brain performs math. By
determining the degree of brain activity synchrony between
specified locations throughout the brain at rest we can examine
how these measures relate to broad academic skills and abilities.
Our study provides a foundation of knowledge and unique
research methodology upon which future studies examining the
neurocognitive processes associated with academic ability may
build upon. Additionally, we provide theoretical interpretations
of the coherence networks with regards to how they relate to
the underlying cognitive skills that are implicated in broad
math ability. This information offers practical utility for MLD
assessment and remediation by offering suggestions upon
which interventions may target. For example, rather than focus-
ing interventions for a student with MLD toward building basic
math skills (e.g., addition and subtraction), our results provide
additional support for interventions that target improving con-centration and/or memory abilities along with basic math skills
(e.g., Kroesbergen & Van Luit, 2003; Naglieri & Gottling, 1997).
Developing a research base within the areas of study that
combine functional neurocognitive data and academic per-
formance in children is lacking, but paramount if we hope
to gain a better understanding of MLDs at a cognitive level.
Exploring the neurocognitive underpinnings of academic
performance is a major dearth in current neuropsychology
and school psychology research. Investigation and research
incorporating these practices lends promise for providing
much needed improvements to our current learning disabil-
ity assessment, identification, intervention, and remediation
practices. The current study implicates general brain regions
of interest for math ability, which include frontal, temporal
and parietal regions in both hemispheres. The activity asso-
ciated with these regions is related to specific cognitive abil-
ities (i.e., concentration, attention, memory) that may also
be important targets for math intervention, alongside typical
academic interventions. Due to the exploratory nature of
this research, findings warrant continued examination, yet
provide a foundation for understanding some of the336 C. ANZALONE ET AL. neurological and cognitive underpinnings of math ability
and/or performance in children.
