1. Introduction
In the current era of information saturation, prob-
lem solving — rather than rote knowledge accumula-tion — has become an increasingly important educa-
tional goal.
1Cognitive neuroscience can oﬀer timely
insight into the neurodynamics supporting success-ful problem solving. Recent work in our labs, for
instance, has explored brain activities during engage-
ment in ill-structured problems with open solutionsrequiring specialized knowledge of optics.
2Intrigu-
ingly, the magnitude of spectral power in a range
of frequencies important for cognitive processing —
including theta, alpha and beta — was found toincrease as solvers came on their own to develop
progressively more optimal, elegant solutions. This
ﬁnding distinguishes problem solving from otherdomains of human endeavor, such as skill learn-ing, which tends to be characterized by an overall
decrease in task-related co rtical activity as perfor-
mance improves with practice.
3,4
The present study extends our exploration of
the relationship between EEG dynamics and perfor-
mance on intellectually challenging problems. Pre-viously, we uncovered an intriguing relationshipbetween frontal theta activities and solution time.
5
Whereas slow solvers exhibited greater frontal thetaover frontal right hemis phere recording sites, the
opposite pattern was exhibited by fast solvers. Build-
ing upon this discovery, the present study explores
this question: How are the magnitude and topo-graphic distribution of EEG spectral dynamics mod-ulated as a function of the amount of time required
to solve a problem? On the one hand, problems
that are solved quickly and easily might be associ-ated with greater short -term mental eﬀort — and
hence, stronger cortical engagement — resulting in
speedier performance, wher eas problems involving
long solution latencies (SLs) might be character-ized by relatively diminished measurable spectral
activities. On the other hand, however, paralleling
our previous work, the opposite pattern could befound — that is, relative to their easier counterparts,
diﬃcult problems could lead to greater, and even
topographically distinct, forms of engagement. Thislatter possibility is consistent with the idea thatwhen faced with challenges — whether in the form
of mental impasse or other internally generated con-
straints, or in the form of particularly challeng-ing problem parameters — solvers “redouble theireﬀorts” so to speak, recruiting additional and quali-
tatively diﬀerent resources relative to problems thatoﬀer more straightforward paths to solution.
To examine these possibilities, we recorded EEG
as healthy adults worked on math puzzles derivedfrom a popular commercial game known as Math24.Each problem consisted of four single-digit numbersthat were to be combined through addition, subtrac-tion, division, or multiplication to reach a ﬁnal solu-
tion that equaled 24. For example, a puzzle consisting
of 1, 7, 1, and 2, could be correctly resolved throughthe following steps: 1 + 7 = 8; 2 + 1 = 3; 3 ×8 = 24.
The use of math puzzles contrasts signiﬁcantly withprevious studies of problem solving, which have typ-ically involved language-based stimuli, such as ana-grams, riddles, and remote associates.
6–8There are
a number of motivations for this approach. First,while mental arithmetic has received extensive atten-tion from a neurocognitive perspective, fairly littleis known about problem solving per se in the mathdomain. Secondly, the abundance of Math24 puz-zles — which all involve the same range of num-bers (1 through 9), and the same number of steps
to solution — aﬀords the opportunity to compare
EEG activities over multiple well-controlled trials.
In the present study, participants worked on math
puzzles for one hour at their own pace. We expecteda wide range of solution times within each individual,allowing for the detailed study of spatio-temporalbrain dynamics during both challenging and rela-tively easy solution search es. Spectral modulations
of EEG power were analyzed using event-relatedspectral perturbation (ERSP) and other commontime–frequency-based approaches.
9,10The relation-
ship between hemispheric and anterior–posteriorasymmetries of EEG activation and solution timeswas also explored. Given previous research indicat-
ing that asymmetric patterns of brain activation are
related to participants’ mathematics ability,
11we
explore the relationship between sustained mentalmath problem solving and the asymmetric modu-lation of EEG power over anterior versus posteriorrecording sites.
2. Methods
2.1. Subjects
Eleven healthy adults (nine males, two females,
age: 15–49 years) with normal or corrected-to-normal vision participated in the experiment. The
