Institutional Review Board of University of Cali-
fornia San Diego approved the experimental pro-tocol used in this study. Subjects were required toabstain from alcoholic, caﬀeinated or tobacco drinksfor 24h before the recordin g session. Sessions took
place either in the morning (9–12 am) or afternoon(2–5 pm). Participants were instructed regarding theexperimental procedures and engaged in practiceblocks until they felt conﬁdent in their understand-
ing of the task. None of the volunteers was aware of
the hypotheses being tested. All participants deliv-ered their informed consent prior to any experimen-tation.
2.2. Materials and Procedures
Math24 is an intellectually challenging game that is
commercially available and widely used in schoolswith the aim of sharpening problem solving and men-
tal math skills (http: //www.24game.com/). While a
number of variants of the game exist, each puzzle inthe present experiment involved four numbers to becombined through basic operations (addition, sub-traction, division, multiplication) to reach a ﬁnalsolution equal to 24. For example, a trial with 2,2, 4, 7, could yield the following solution: 2 + 2 = 4,4∗7 = 28 and 28 −4 = 24. Note that each of the four
numbers is used only once and yields three equationsas the ﬁnal solution.
An ideal feature of Math24 puzzles is that dif-
ﬁculty level can be varied while holding all othertask parameters constant. Harder problems typicallyinvolve fewer possible and more atypical solutions
(i.e. they are not readily reduced to a variant of 8 ×3
or 6×4, and may be solvable by only one approach).
In the present study, puzzles representing three lev-els of diﬃculty, as ranked by the manufacturer, werepresented in a randomly i nterleaved fashion.
During the experimental session, participants
were allotted 120s to solve each puzzle. They sat ina comfortable chair in front of a 27
/prime/primecomputer mon-
itor, and silently worked on puzzles in a self-pacedfashion. Upon reaching a solution, participants wereinstructed to press a button immediately withouttaking any time to mentally verify their solutions.Next, they verbally described their solutions to a co-present experimenter seated behind them.
Each trial began with a black background on the
computer monitor for 2 s (a baseline period), followedby the numbers that comprised the puzzle, which
remained visible on the screen during the entire solu-tion phase (120s maximum). Problems that were notsolved within 120s “timed-out,” and the next trialwas presented. Experimental sessions lasted 1 h.
2.3. Data acquisition
128-channel EEG data were ampliﬁed (BioSemi
ActiveTwo EEG system), referenced to CMS-DRLground, sampled at 512Hz, and notch ﬁltered at60Hz. The contact impedance between the scalp and
the electrode was calibrated to be less than 5 kΩ
using conductive gel. Electrode locations were dig-itized using a 3D digitizer (Zebris Medical GmbH).
2.4. Analysis of behavioral data
Trials resulting in incorrect solutions or solution
times exceeding 120s were excluded from furtheranalysis. For each correctly solved trial, the solutionlatency (SL) was computed from the time betweenstimulus onset and the button press to indicate solu-tion readiness. Each participant’s performance wasdeﬁned as their mean SL, averaging SLs across tri-als. Repeated-measures one-way ANOVA tests wereused to compare groups’ m ean SLs across the three
levels of task diﬃculty.
2.5. EEG preprocessing
MATLAB (The Mathworks, Inc.) and an open source
toolbox, EEGLAB (Swartz Center for Computa-
tional Neuroscience, La Jolla, CA; http: //www.sccn.
ucsd.edu/eeglab), were used for all preprocessing andanalysis. Figure 1 is a schematic illustration of theanalysis pipeline for a single subject. EEG channelswere re-referenced oﬄine to an average of the leftand right mastoids. A band-pass ﬁlter between 2 and30Hz was applied to raw, time-series EEG to elim-inate line noise (60Hz and its harmonic) and DCdrifts. Subsequently, data were compressed by down-sampling to 256Hz (Fig. 1(A), Step
➀)a n dv i s u -
ally inspected to remove channels and data segmentsheavily contaminated by nonphysiological artifacts,such as momentary spikes in electrode impedance,or high amplitude voltage ﬂuctuations across all
channels introduced by postural shifts (Fig. 1(A),
Step
➁).
