Independent component analysis (ICA) was
applied to continuous EEG for the purpose of arti-fact correction
12–16(Fig. 1(A), Step ➂). ICA is a
family of algorithms that learns optimal ﬁlters toestimate the activities of spatially coherent corti-cal sources, as well as nonbrain artifacts, from thestatistics of scal p-recorded EEG.
9,17Resultant inde-
pendent components (ICs) accounting for numer-ous kinds of artifacts, including blinks, eye moment,
EKG, muscle activity, and line noise can be dis-
cerned on the basis of their mean power spectra,time-series activations, and topography of their pro-jections to scalp electrodes. In the artifact correc-tion procedure implemented here, the contributionsof such nonbrain sources were removed by zeroingtheir projection weights to each scalp channel andthen re-computing estimations of the original data asa weighted linear sum of the remaining source activ-ities (Fig. 1(A), Step
➃).2.6. Time–frequency analysis
2.6.1. EEG dynamics during mathematical
problem solving
As illustrated in Fig. 2, mean SLs diﬀered substan-
tially across the three levels of task diﬃculty. Thediﬀerences in SLs to easy problems (level 1) acrossparticipants were small (mean ±SD: 5 .3±4.8s),
whereas on the challenge l evel (level 3), substan-
tially more variance was observed (mean ±SD:
22.3±30.3s). Further at level 3, the number of
available trials was much fewer than at level 1 andlevel 2. For this reason, the time–frequency analysiswas performed only on intermediate level problems(mean ±SD: 10 .3±13.5s).
For each participant, 23 to 88 (mean ±SD: 47 ±
22) correctly solved, artifact-free trials were avail-able for time–frequency analysis at the intermediatelevel. Single-trial data epochs were extracted from
