2.6.2. Performance-sorted single trial EEG
spectra
To investigate the relationship between EEG spec-
tral activities and solution times across individuals,the mean power spectrum (2–30Hz) was computedfor trials of intermediate diﬃculty as follows: esti-mates of spectral power for each frequency step were
derived from puzzle onset to the button press sig-
naling solution readiness (Fig. 1(B), Step
➀). Mean
power spectra of each trial were obtained by aver-aging estimates across the time dimension and thensubtracting the base of power spectrum, which wascomprised of mean power sp ectral densities averaged
across trials in which participants responded veryquickly (within 5s or fewer). Mean power spectrawere pooled across subject s and sorted by their SLs.
Subsequently, the performance-sorted EEG spec-tra were smoothed through an equal-weight movingaverage method,
22with a window of 9s and a step
of 0.5s.
2.6.3. Topographic distribution of EEG
spectral modulations as a function oftask performance
To assess the relationship b etween task performance
and the topographic distribution of EEG spectralactivities, all trials of intermediate diﬃculty weredivided into three groups according to SL — Group I(SLs≤20s, 31 trials), Group II (20s <SLs≤40s,
40 trials) and Group III (SLs >40s, 40 trials).
