4. Discussion
Problem solving continues to be of high impor-
tance in education and a pivotal ability for stu-
dents.
26–28Quantitative problem solving has been a
long withstanding diﬃculty faced by students andhas received extensive atte ntion in the ﬁeld of math-
ematical development and education.
29In this study,
EEG was recorded as healthy adults solved mentalmath problems with three levels of diﬃculty. ERSP,a time–frequency analytical method, were used toevaluate averaged dynamic changes of the broadbandEEG spectrum from the onset of math problemsto the button press indicating solution readiness.ERSP images revealed alpha- and beta-power sup-pression and theta-power augmentation during thecourse of problem solving, consistent with previousEEG studies in mental calculation and working mem-
ory (WM) tasks.
30–32However, the present analysis
extends existing knowledge by oﬀering new insightinto the detailed spatio-temporal dynamics of spec-tral changes during problem solving, indicating theengagement of a broadly distributed fronto-parietalbrain network whose activities exhibit overlapping,but discrete time courses.
Two topographically and temporally distinct pat-
terns of alpha and beta event-related desynchroniza-tion (ERD) were discovered. First, over the posteriorregions, ERSP plots revealed tonic, sustained sup-pression of activities in the alpha and beta ranges (10to 30Hz) from puzzle onset to completion. Because it
is typically detected over areas of task relevant cortexduring active engagement, alpha ERD is generally
thought to reﬂect a release of cortical inhibition,
33
and has been found to increase in magnitude when
parameters of task diﬃculty, such as WM load, aremade more challenging.
34We propose that the sus-
tained ERD in the alpha and beta ranges reﬂectsbackground processes — likely linked to attentionalcontrol — supporting the solution search. This ideais consistent with existing research revealing mod-
ulations of alpha and beta ERD
35as a function of
attentional load.
While continuous cortical engagement from select
brain regions is clearly n ecessary for this task, it is
also the case that some processes make graded orincremental contributions, as evidenced by the sup-pression of power above 8Hz over primarily ante-rior electrodes (but also P4). In these cases, ERDis typically most apparent in the ﬁnal few secondsof the problem-solving phase, and weakly discernibleat earlier intervals. This p attern suggests that cer-
tain cortical systems become increasingly active as a
solution is about to be reached.
ERS in the theta range was found predominantly
over the frontal midline (Fz) and right parietal (Pz)
channels. This pattern of spectral activity is consis-tent with a number of studies reporting either theengagement of a broadly distributed fronto-parietaltheta network
36–38or primarily frontal theta power
augmentation39,40during mental arithmetic. It is
also consistent with neuroimaging work reportingactivation of frontal and parietal cortices, includingthe right and left inferior frontal gyri, along with theright and left angular gyri and intraparietal sulci, bymental math tasks.
41,42
Notably, frontal and frontal midline theta has
been extensively implicated in tasks requiring atten-
tional control, such as error monitoring43or main-
tenance of verbal and visuo-spatial information in
immediate memory.34,44–52Whereas the frontal mid-
line theta ERS observed in this study is likely toreﬂect the engagement of attention-related, domaingeneral executive function, the parietal ERS mayreﬂect more task-speciﬁc processes. For instance,Mizuhara and Yamaguchi
37report long-range theta
phase synchronization between clusters of frontalmidline and left and right parietal recording sites —and on the basis of simultaneously recorded func-tional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), theauthors propose that theta oscillations dynamically
