utive or other controlled processing with more distalcortical regions, such as the intraparietal sulcus orangular gyrus, which are important for quantitativereasoning.
42,53
A novel and important contribution of the
present work is the snapshot that it aﬀords of thetime course of theta activities during solution search.In particular, right parietal theta ERS is visible
by approximately 1s aft er puzzles appear on the
screen and precedes the onset of frontal midline thetaERS by about 1.5 s. However, over both record-ing sites, discernable pow er augmentation declines
approximately 3s before participants signal solu-tion readiness. In other words, whereas continuousfrontal-parietal theta act ivities characterize a sub-
stantial portion of the problem-solving phase, theyare not engaged during the ﬁnal moments whenpresumably, participants are formulating a solution.Rather, in the ﬁnal seconds, ERD in the alpha andbeta ranges is the predominant form of spectralmodulation.
Overall, on the basis of ERSP outcomes, we pro-
pose a three-stage model of problem solving. An
initial orienting phase is characterized primarily bytonic alpha and beta ERD visible over most of thescalp and sustained throughout the trial. A subse-quent stage that likely reﬂ ects exploration of the
solution space involves fronto-parietal theta ERSconcurrently with the tonic, broadband alpha andbeta ERD. Lastly, in the ﬁnal few seconds before thebutton press, theta ERS attenuates, while alpha andbeta ERD become stronger over electrode sites wherethey had previously been on ly weakly detectable.
Future work using individually derived, rather thanﬁxed, frequency windows
54may allow for more ﬁne-
grained examination of these processes.
A second important ﬁnding of the present work
is the positive relationship between the magnitude oftheta ERS and SL. As can be seen in Fig. 4, trialsinvolving latencies shorter than 20s tended to involveless theta ERS over Fz and P4 than those incurringlonger latencies. This outcome parallels the ﬁndingthat mean theta power incr eases parametrically with
increasing WM load,
48,50and is consistent with the
idea that the magnitude of oscillatory activities inthe theta range reﬂects men t a le ﬀ o r t .I n t r i g u i n g l y ,
in the present case, diﬃcult problems are charac-terized not only by longer solution searches, butalso increased engagement of mental resources dur-
ing those search periods.
Our previous work
5has revealed that fast prob-
lem solvers exhibited greater left frontal theta activ-ity, whereas slow solvers sh owed greater right frontal
theta activity. In other words, depending upondegree of math puzzle proﬁciency, solvers appearto have engaged frontal cortical systems diﬀerently.One interpretation of thi s topographic diﬀerence is
that the left versus right hemispheric dominance
may reﬂect preferences for d istinct problem solving
styles. Research on insight problems, for instance,has implicated the right hemisphere in diﬀuse atten-tion,
55unconscious processing,56and broad semantic
representation.57,58These aspects of cognition may
contribute to the restruct uring necessary to connect
problem elements in such a way that insight can besuddenly achieved. In the present case, it is possiblethat slow solvers may have relied more on insight-based approaches than fast solvers, who likely devel-oped eﬃcient search-based strategies.
Support for this idea can be found in the analy-
sis by trials revealing that r ight parietal theta activ-
ities were greater than those over the contralateral
left recording site, particularly for trials involvingthe longest solution times (Fig. 5). In other words,irrespective of subject grouping, both slow and fastsolvers tended to recruit the right hemisphere morethan the left when problems proved diﬃcult andengendered extended solution searches. While it isnot known whether solutions on these trials wereultimately derived through insight, we have recentlydemonstrated that when pa rticipants subjectively
rate their experience of insight on each puzzle, highinsight ratings tended to be associated with longersolution times.
19
The analyses by trials also revealed a strong rela-
tionship between fronto-parietal asymmetry and task
performance (Fig. 6). Fronto-parietal asymmetries inthe theta and beta range over LH electrodes, thealpha range over midline electrodes, and theta andalpha range over RH sites all increased linearly acrossthe three groups of trials — that is, with longer solu-tion times the magnitude of the asymmetry becamemore pronounced. For contrasts involving left andright lateralized recording s ites, spectral activities
were greater over the front versus the back of thehead, whereas the opposite was found for midlinechannels. An important conclusion that we can infer
