from this pattern of outcomes is that fronto-parietal
networks are increasingly engaged as greater obsta-cles to problem resolution ( reﬂected in solution time)
are experienced.
This idea is consistent with previous research
implicating fronto-parietal connectivity and acti-vation in the development of abstract numericalconcepts,
59–61in mathematical processing,11and
problem solving in children and adults.62In partic-
ular, the right fronto-parietal asymmetry observed
here (Fig. 6) coincides with neuroimaging studiesdemonstrating an analogous right lateralized asym-metry during the mental manipulation of numbersand orienting of attention along the mental num-ber line.
41Further, in keeping with Micheloyannis
et al.,63who report that neuronal populations in
both hemispheres become increasingly engaged dur-ing complex arithmetic, we found that when longeramounts of time were required to solve Math24 puz-zles, widespread desynchro nization occurred within
fronto-parietal systems (Fig. 4) — likely due to theprolonged cognitive demands associated with main-taining information in WM, retrieving learned arith-
metic facts (e.g. the product of 4 ×4), and searching
for the correct solution path (e.g. discovering that akey to a given problem lies in combining the integersto reach a ﬁnal equation of 6 ×4, as opposed to other
possible approaches, such as 48 ÷2).
Finally, the present study supports and extends
our own earlier work. We previously reported thatwithin participants, progressively more optimal solu-tions to open-ended physics problems are character-ized by a broadband increa se in spectral power across
the theta, alpha and beta ranges.
2Analogously, here
we ﬁnd that diﬃcult solutions are associated withincreased theta activities — and intriguingly, withan increasingly asymmetric distribution of spectral
activity along the anterior–posterior dimension. In
other words, diﬃcult problems elicit not only greatercortical engagement — but also topographically dis-tinct brain areas diﬀerently. This ﬁnding is partic-ularly important with respect to the prospect ofmonitoring learners in real time through wearablebiosensors, as it suggests that the topography ofEEG activities can diﬀerenti ate brain states associ-
ated with diﬃcult and easy problem solving. Futurework centered on the co-modulation of EEG spec-tral power or coherence may yield further insight intounderlying mechanisms mediating this eﬀect.5. Conclusion
Problem solving is an increasingly important edu-
cational goal. This study expands upon previ-
ous research examining brain processes involved inarithmetic-based problem solving. Over the full timecourse of the problem-solving phase (from puzzleonset to resolution), spectral modulations of EEGwere characterized by augmentation of power in thetheta range over the front of the head and P4, as wellas a broadly distributed suppression of power in thealpha and beta ranges. These results are consistentwith existing research suggesting a fronto-parietalcortical network supporting arithmetic abilities. Fur-ther, our work oﬀers the novel ﬁnding that longersolution times were linked to the magnitude of spec-tral modulation. Additionally, the length of solution
times was associated with increasingly asymmetric
broadband activities along the fronto-parietal axis.This work is important for understanding the neuro-dynamic foundation of both mathematical cognitionand problem solving.
