neuroimage.usc.edu/brainstorm )(Tadel et al., 2011 ).
In the forward process of the source estimation, the
EEG signals were assumed to be primarily determined
by a block of electric dipoles located at the surface of
the cortex. An averaged realistic head model constitutedby scalp, outer skull, inner skull, and cortex was used
as the common brain for group analysis, and the
symmetric Boundary Element Method (BEM) in theopen-source software ( http://www-sop.inria.fr/athena/
software/OpenMEEG/ )(Gramfort et al., 2010 ) was
applied to the EEG electrode locations of the head modelto obtain the volume conductor modeling of the subjects
(i.e., the forward model matrix). The noise of the sensors
was removed by computing the noise covariance matrixfrom the pre-stimulation time interval. In the inverse pro-cess, an inverse kernel matrix was produced by the for-
ward model and the standardized Low Resolution Brain
Electromagnetic Tomography (sLORETA), by which theEEG signals could be transformed into the cortical current
sources. After further downsampling the original sources,
248 cortical vertices were selected to serve as the nodesin the following network analysis ( Fig. 2 B, C).
Graph-theoretical analysis of the phase
synchronization network
