ANOVA statistical test
The group diﬀerences in the RAPM score and the
behavioral performances on the deductive reasoning
task were tested by the one-way analysis of variance(ANOVA). The ANOVA was also performed to test the
group diﬀerence in the fm theta that was derived from
the averaged theta-band spectral responses ofelectrodes FZ and FCZ. In order to discover the
signiﬁcant topological changes occurred in the functional
reorganization process of the network, the results ofgraph-theoretical analysis were statistically tested by theANOVA between the task and baseline periods. Similar
tests were also conducted between the two groups in
the task period to ﬁnd the group diﬀerences in thereasoning-related network topology.
Correlation analysis and between-groups
discrimination
It has previously been shown that fm theta oscillation
emerges in various mental tasks, with the amplitudecorresponding to individual eﬀortful cognitive processing
(Turken et al., 1999; Onton et al., 2005; Doppelmayr
et al., 2008 ), such as attention concentration, working
memory load, self-control, internal timing, and assess-ment of reward ( Nakashima and Sato, 1992; Asada
et al., 1999; Jensen and Tesche, 2002; Mizuhara et al.,
2004 ). Importantly, the appearance of event-related fm
theta might be a reﬂection of alternative activities in the
medial PFC and AC ( Asada et al., 1999 ). In a nonstation-
ary functional network, individual cognitive eﬀort is alsoassociated with the execution of topological reorganiza-
tion and even related to the intension of workspace con-ﬁguration, that is, stronger integration would be drivenby higher eﬀortful executive processing and thus morechanges in complex network metrics might be measured
(Kitzbichler et al., 2011 ).
According to the above assumption, single-trial
correlation analyses were performed to estimate the
coordination relationship between mental eﬀort and
topological shift related to workspace formation of thetheta network. Firstly, the association between the fm
theta activated in the reasoning process and the
intension of task-related workspace conﬁguration wasestimated by the correlation analyses, in which the
averaged PSDs from electrodes FZ and FCZ and each
global network parameter (i.e., modularity, characteristicpath length and global eﬃciency) in the task periodwere used as analytical variables. Secondly, by
removing the relevant activities in the baseline resting
state, the variables used in the correlation analyseswere the absolute change rate of averaged PSDs in the
two electrodes and the task-related change rate of each
global network parameter, which is quantiﬁed by
