RESULTS
Behavioral performance and group diﬀerence
In the RAPM psychometric test, the math-gifted subjects
have obtained signiﬁcantly higher scores than the
control subjects ( p= 0.0000). In performing the
deductive reasoning task, signiﬁcant group diﬀerence
can be observed in the reaction time of correct
responses, in which the math-gifted group hassigniﬁcantly shorter reaction time than the control group
(p= 0.0036). Meanwhile, the math-gifted adolescents
have outperformed the control subjects in averageresponse accuracy ( Table 1 ).
Temporal coordination between fm theta response
and long-distance coherence
As shown in the ERSP diagrams of electrode FZ
(Fig. 3 A), the deductive reasoning task has elicited the
staged spectral response in the theta frequency band.
Corresponding to the time interval of ERSP, the theta-
band phase synchronizations between distantelectrodes increase in the three stages of the reasoning
task, including the enhanced intrahemispheric ERPCOHbetween frontal-occipitoparietal electrodes ( Fig. 3 B) and
interhemispheric ERPCOH between bilaterally frontalinferior electrodes ( Fig. 3 C). As compared with the
control group, the math-gifted subjects show higher
response strength of ERSP in electrode FZ and moresigniﬁcant long-distance intrahemispheric ERPCOH and
interhemispheric ERPCOH in the theta frequency band
(Fig. 3 ).
In the global distribution of the theta-band response
activated by the three stages of the deduction task,
more coherent theta-band power change in frontal-sensorimotor-parietal cortical regions is presented at the
stages of premise integration and conclusion validation
(Fig. 4 ), which can be associated with the higher
synchronized activity in the fronto-parietal network.Particularly, the brain maps from the math-gifted group
present higher global theta oscillations, especially at the
frontal midline locations.
In the ANOVA tests for the group diﬀerences in the fm
theta, signiﬁcantly higher average PSDs in frontal midline
electrodes are found in the math-gifted group in bothresting and cognitive states ( p= 0.0000). From the
resting state to task period, the math-gifted subjects
also show greater task-related change rate of fm thetathan the control group ( p= 0.0327) ( Table 2 ).
Reasoning-related workspace conﬁguration of the
theta network
Signiﬁcant network reorganization related to workspace
formation . By the Louvain method of functional
community detection ( Blondel et al., 2008 ), the basic
architecture of the resting-state theta network is primarily
divided into prefrontal, bilateral frontal/frontotemporal,
parietal, occipital and frontoparietal modules. EspeciallyTable 1. Behavioral performance and group diﬀerence: mean ±
