from 4 to 50 Hz.340 L. Zhang et al. / Neuroscience 289 (2015) 334–348 in the time intervals of premise integration and conclusion
validation, more intensive synchronizations across ana-tomically separated brain areas have increased from theresting state ( Fig. 5 A). After task-related reconﬁguration
of connections, the major changes in functional partition
of the theta network architecture are found in the integra-tion of some nodes in prefrontal, right frontal and temporal
cortical regions, and in the integration of some nodes in
parietal and occipital cortical regions, which can be asso-ciated with the integrative functions of temporo-frontal
and occipito-parietal systems in cognitive processing.
Importantly, the reasoning task also induces the integra-tion of some nodes in frontal and parietal regions through
the increased long-distance fronto-parietal connections,
which leads to an expanded fronto-parietal module inthe theta network.
Based on the functional integration by the long-range
synchronizations, the network measures of the two
groups show signiﬁcantly decreased modularity andcharacteristic path length, and signiﬁcantly increased
global eﬃciency from the resting state to the task period
(p= 0.0000) ( Fig. 6 ), which indicate that a less modular
but more globally synchronized and parallel transferred
network conﬁguration pattern has been formed in the
reasoning process.
The statistical tests for the individual nodes in the
network present the changes of local conﬁgurations in
the topological reorganization process ( Fig. 7 ). The
increase of the node degree is primarily focused on thefrontal–sensorimotor–superior parietal cortical regions,
accompanied with simultaneously decreased node
degree distributed in temporal and inferior parietal andoccipital regions ( Fig. 7 A). Because of the adjustment of
node degree distribution, the simultaneously increased
within-module degree z-score also emerges in the
fronto-parietal cortical area, which correlates with theincreased interconnectivity of fronto-parietal network in
the cognitive process ( Fig. 7 B). Corresponding to the
analytical results of the global network topology, theindividual nodes with diminished clustering coeﬃcient
and local eﬃciency are extensively distributed in the
multiple cortical regions ( Fig. 7 C, D), which
demonstrates that the local modularity of the network
has been greatly weakened in the reasoning process,
following the globally synchronized and less modularnetwork conﬁguration. According to these changes ofthe key graph-theoretical parameters related to
workspace formation in the complex network
organization, the global neuronal workspace in thetafrequency of the brain activity has been driven by the
subjects for supporting higher cognitive functions of the
reasoning task, by means of long-range recruitment oforiginal loosely connected functional modules.
Group diﬀerence in network reorganization and
workspace conﬁguration . In the math-gifted group, it can
be found that more node pairs with increased
synchronizations in the fronto-parietal network have
been formed in the reasoning task ( Fig. 5 A). Thus, the
math-gifted group shows greater topological shift of thetheta network from the resting state to the reasoning
process than the control group, which is demonstrated
by higher absolute change rates of characteristic pathlength (mean ± SD: /C00.15 ± 0.08 vs. /C00.13 ± 0.09;
p= 0.0179), modularity (mean ± SD: /C00.16 ± 0.06 vs.
/C00.14 ± 0.07; p= 0.0020) and global eﬃciency
(mean ± SD: 0.09 ± 0.07 vs. 0.07 ± 0.11; p= 0.0287)
(Fig. 8 B). Meanwhile, corresponding to the changes in
global network measures, the math-gifted subjects showmore signiﬁcant changes in nodal measures, andquantitatively more cortical vertices signiﬁcantly involved
in the network reorganization process ( Fig. 7 A–D). From
the above comparisons at both global and nodal levelsof the theta network, the analytical results suggest the
highly adaptive functional self-organization of neuronal
assemblies and greater transition capacity from locally
