In the reasoning process, the ANOVA tests indicate
that the theta network of the math-gifted subjects works
in a topological pattern with stronger workspaceconﬁgurations than the control subjects, through lessmodularity (mean ± SD: 0.47 ± 0.05 vs. 0.49 ± 0.05;
p= 0.0000), shorter path length (mean ± SD:
2.65 ± 0.20 vs. 2.77 ± 0.29; p= 0.0000) and higher
global eﬃciency of parallel information transfer
(mean ± SD: 0.35 ± 0.02 vs. 0.33 ± 0.04; p= 0.0000)
(Fig. 8 C). At the nodal level of the reasoning-related
theta network, the nodes with increased local
conﬁguration measures in the math-gifted group are
mainly distributed on the fronto-parietal brain regions(Fig. 9 ). Especially in the anterior cortical vertices in
medial and right frontal modules, the math-gifted group
has signiﬁcantly higher node degree, within-module
degree z-score, clustering coeﬃcient and eﬃciency than
the control subjects ( Table 3 ).
Although the increased global integration in the task-
related theta network of the math-gifted brain wouldweaken the local cluster of nodes, the relatively higher
clustering coeﬃcient and local eﬃciency in the medial
and right frontal modules indicate that the math-giftedadolescents still have maintained the local cliques andthe local information transfers better than the control
subjects in the right-lateral anterior brain area ( Fig. 9 C,
D). The good performance can be attributed to the
higher node degree distribution (i.e., higher connection
density) and better interconnectivity of the nodes in theiranterior sub-network ( Fig. 9 A, B).
Correlationship between fm theta and workspace
conﬁguration of theta network
During the reasoning process, there are correlationships
between the task-related fm theta activation and the
workspace conﬁgurations of the theta network. Asshown in the scattergrams composed of all the trial
samples, the PSD of the fm theta shows slight negative
correlation with the modularity and the characteristicpath length, and slight positive correlation with the
global eﬃciency of the theta network, respectively
(correlation coeﬃcient jr
PWj>0:3). In the single-trial
discrimination for group-based samples, the math-giftedadolescents can be indentiﬁed as having higher fm theta
activation and stronger workspace pattern of the
reasoning-related theta network (the accuracies arehigher than 0.74) ( Fig. 10 A).
Besides, the change rates of the global network
measures toward workspace conﬁguration can be
