In addition, the between-group comparisons ﬁnd that
the math-gifted adolescents have increased local
measures in the nodes of the medial and right frontal
modules. The previous studies have emphasized theimportance of the right frontal lobe in mathematical
problem-solving, as it is dominant for geometric and
visual space analyses and also highly involved inmathematical creativity ( O’Boyle et al., 2005; Prescott
et al., 2010 ). The better local conﬁgurations of the right-
lateral frontal nodes in the math-gifted brain could supportmore eﬃcient local information exchange and even facili-
tate the unity of various thoughts arising from mathemat-
ical reasoning and creative thinking processes.
Coordination relationship between mental eﬀort and
workspace formation. In the time–frequency diagrams,
the emergence of long-range synchronizations can be
coordinated in the time interval of fm theta responsewhile executing diﬀerent stages of the reasoning task,
which is in good agreement with the results reported by
the study using simultaneously recorded EEG andfunctional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI)
(Mizuhara et al., 2004 ). Our study discovers that there
are slight correlations between fm theta power and globalnetwork measures in terms of workspace conﬁguration, inwhich the math-gifted group can be characterized by an
enhanced state of eﬀort-driven topological shift toward
workspace formation. The ﬁndings can supportKitzbichler et al.’s (2011) research conclusion that higher
cognitive load (mental eﬀort) can drive greater functional
reorganization and thus facilitate stronger workspace for-mation of human brain functional network.
The global neuronal workspace theory suggests that,
through integrative function of the neural system, themessages from the global workspace are broadcast to all
the unconscious processors to recruit their participation
for solving novel problems ( Baars, 2005 ). From the ﬁnd-
ings in our study, with the well-developed anterior neuralsystem ( O’Boyle et al., 2005 ;Desco et al., 2011 ), the
math-gifted brain could be assumed to have a superior
central executive processor that can facilitate/mobilizegreater recruitment of the originally competing processors
distributed in discrete brain regions to cooperatively partic-
ipate in the complex cognitive process.
It should be noted that previous neuroimaging studies
have suggested diﬀerent neurobiological substrates
unique to giftedness in mathematics or common tointelligence. In cognitive processing, the highly activatedanterior brain areas including the PFC, frontal lobe and
AC can be connected to general ﬂuid intelligence of
math-gifted adolescents ( O’Boyle et al., 2005 ). In our
study, the greater eﬀort-driven network reorganization
seems to be attributed to the nature of high intelligence
of the math-gifted adolescents irrespective of their spe-ciﬁc aptitude in mathematics. This suggestion is rather
consistent with the previous research ﬁndings on intelli-
gent brains that bright individuals often devote moreeﬀortful cortical resources while there are quite strong
cognitive requirements ( Neubauer and Fink, 2009 ).Additionally, there are original group diﬀerences in the
resting-state theta cortical network organization.
Compared with the control group, the math-giftedadolescents have shorter characteristic path length(mean ± SD: 3.18 ± 0.24 vs. 3.25 ± 0.38; p= 0.0193)
and higher global eﬃciency (mean ± SD: 0.32 ± 0.02
vs. 0.31 ± 0.03; p= 0.0106) ( Fig. 8 A), which indicates
higher global synchronization activity under resting
condition without any task information processing. From
the between-groups comparison in the resting-statenetwork ( Fig. 5 B), it can be found that the diﬀerences in
the global network measures are primarily resulted from
the increased fronto-parietal synchronizations in themath-gifted brain. Complex brain network research has
suggested that resting-state functional connectivity on
multiple time scales is shaped by underlying anatomicalarchitecture of the cerebral cortex ( Honey et al., 2007 ). A
recent diﬀusion tensor imaging (DTI) study has
demonstrated the increased anatomical connectivity in
fronto-parietal association tracts in the math-gifted brain,and further found it underlies subjects’ speciﬁc mathemat-
ical ability independent of their intelligence scores ( Navas-
Sanchez et al., 2013 ). In conjunction with the dynamic
reconﬁguration of the functional network, the topological
basis of the resting-state cortical network probably underly-
ing greater mathematical ability should also be an impor-tant part of the stronger emergence of workspaceconﬁgurations in the reasoning-related functional network.
CONCLUSIONS
By constructing the theta-band cortical source networks
under resting and task conditions, our EEG study hasconﬁrmed the greater topological reorganization of the
brain functional network in the math-gifted adolescents
in response to the cognitive demands from a deductivereasoning task. Coordinated with stronger cognitiveeﬀort invested in the reasoning process, the math-gifted
adolescents exhibited an enhanced task-related global
workspace at the level of global network organizationthan the average-ability control subjects. With a better-
integrated resting-state cortical network, the higher
capacity of the math-gifted brain in the dynamictransition of topological organization from modular
subsystems to global workspace can further promote
the level of timely information processing of the fronto-parietal network. Additionally, our complex networkanalysis indicates that the dynamically reconﬁgured
network architecture in the math-gifted brain enhances
both global and local information processing inreasoning processes, which can be viewed as the
neural correlations with the superior problem-solving
ability of the math-gifted adolescents in logical reasoning.
