Multi-aspect data analysis for investigating human computation mechanism.pdf,2009,6,3,Multi-aspect data analysis for investigating human computation mechanism.pdf,"Multi-aspect data analysis for investigating human
computation mechanism
Action editor: Jiming Liu
Shinichi Motomura*, Ning Zhong
Department of Life Science and Informatics, Maebashi Institute of Technology, 460-1 Kamisadori-Cho, Maebashi-City 371-0816, Japan
Received 25 February 2008; accepted 4 August 2008
Available online 29 October 2008
Abstract
In the paper, we present a multi-aspect data analysis approach for investigating human computation mechanism. Multi-aspect anal-
ysis in multiple human brain data sources is an important methodology in Brain Informatics, which emphasizes on a systematic way for
investigating human information processing mechanisms, including measuring, collecting, modeling, transforming, managing, and min-
ing multiple human brain data obtained from various cognitive experiments by using powerful equipments, such as fMRI and EEG.
After giving an outline of Brain Informatics methodology, we describe how to design cognitive experiments of mental arithmetic taskwith multiple diﬃculty levels for obtaining multiple EEG and fMRI data sources, and how to analyze such data for investigating the
spatiotemporal characteristics and ﬂow of human computation processing. Such an investigation can be regarded as a case study using
Brain Informatics methodology. Experimental results show the usefulness of our approach./C2112008 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.
Keywords: Multi-aspect data analysis; Brain informatics methodology; Human computation mechanism; EEG and fMRI
1. Introduction
Multi-aspect analysis in multiple human brain data
sources is an important methodology in Brain Informatics.
Brain Informatics (BI) attempts to understand human
intelligence in depth, towards a long-term, holistic viewto uncover the principles and mechanisms underlyinghuman information processing system (HIPS). BI empha-sizes on a systematic approach for investigating human
information processing mechanisms, including measuring,collecting, modeling, transforming, managing, and miningmultiple human brain data obtained from various cognitive
experiments. The future of BI will be shaped by our ability
to do large-scale analysis and simulation of human braindata. The key issues are how to design the psychologicaland physiological experiments for systematically obtainingvarious data from HIPS, as well as how to manage andanalyze such data from multiple aspects for discoveringnew models of HIPS. Although several human-expert cen-
tric tools such as SPM (MEDx) have been developed for
cleaning, normalizing and visualizing the fMRI images,researchers have also been studying how the fMRI imagescan be automatically analyzed and understood by usingdata mining and statistical learning techniques ( Megalooik-
onomou & Herskovits, 2001; Mitchell et al., 2004; Sommer& Wichert, 2003; Zhong, Wu, Nakamaru, Ohshima, &Mizuhara, 2004 ). We are concerned with how to extract
signiﬁcant features from multiple brain data measured byusing fMRI and EEG in preparation for multi-aspect anal-ysis and simulation.
In the paper, we present a multi-aspect data analysis
approach for investigating human computation mecha-nism with multiple diﬃculty levels. Such an investigationcan be regarded as a case study using Brain Informatics
