 methodology. We show that discovering new knowledge and
models of human computation mechanism requires not onlyindividual data obtained from a single measuring method,but also methods for multiple data sources measuring andmulti-aspect data analysis. In this work, we focus on investi-gating the spatiotemporal characteristics and ﬂow of human
computation processing. More speciﬁcally, at the current
stage, we want to understand: how a speciﬁc part of the brainoperates in a speciﬁc time, how the operations change overtime, and how the activated areas work cooperatively toimplement a whole human computation mechanism.
The rest of the paper is organized as follows. Section 2
provides an outline of the BI Methodology. Section 3
explains how to design the experiments of ERP/fMRI men-
tal arithmetic tasks with multiple diﬃculty levels standing
on BI Methodology. Section 4describes multi-aspect data
analysis in ERP and fMRI based multiple data sourcesfor investigating human computation mechanism. Section5discusses how to combine the results obtained by each
analysis method separately, stated in Section 4, towards a
more whole explanation and understanding. Finally, Sec-tion6gives concluding remarks.
2. Brain informatics methodology
As an interdisciplinary study, Brain Informatics (BI)
combines results from experimental, computational, cogni-tive neuroscience and advanced Web intelligence (WI) cen-tric information technologies. BI can be regarded as brainsciences in the WI centric IT age ( Zhong, 2005, 2007;
Zhong et al., 2007 ), which is proposing to study human
brain from the viewpoint of informatics (i.e., human brainis an information processing system) and use informatics(i.e., WI centric information technologies) to support brainscience studies. BI pursues a holistic understanding ofhuman intelligence through a systematic approach to brainresearch. BI regards the human brain as an informationprocessing system and emphasizes cognitive experiments
to understand its mechanisms for managing and analyzing
data. Such systematic study includes the following fourmain research issues:
/C15Systematic investigation of human thinking centricmechanisms;
/C15systematic design of cognitive experiments;
/C15systematic human brain data management; and,
/C15systematic human brain data analysis.
The capabilities of human intelligence can be broadly
divided into two main aspects: perception and thinking.In cognitive neuroscience, although many advanced resultswith respect to ‘‘perception oriented ”study have been
obtained, only a few of preliminary, separated studies withrespect to ‘‘thinking oriented ”and/or a more whole infor-
mation process have been reported ( Gazzaniga, 2004 ). Sys-
tematic investigation of human thinking centricmechanisms is based on the observation for Web intelli-gence research needs and the state-of-the-art cognitive neu-roscience ( Zhong, 2006; Zhong et al., 2007 ).
Systematic design of cognitive experiments is with
respect to how to design the psychological and physiologi-cal experiments for obtaining various data from HIPS, in asystematic way. In order to discover new knowledge and
models of human information processing activities, not
only single data source obtained from a single measuringmethod, but also multiple data sources from various prac-tical measuring methods, such as fMRI and EEG, arerequired. Furthermore, by systematical design of cognitiveexperiments in BI methodology, the data obtained from acognitive experiment and/or a set of cognitive experimentsexpect to be used for multi-purpose.
Systematic human brain data management is based on a
conceptual brain data model, which represents functionalrelationships among multiple human brain data sources,with respect to all major aspects and capabilities of HIPSfor systematic investigation and understanding of humanintelligence. This kind of data representation is withmulti-level by modeling, abstracting and transforming formulti-aspect analysis and simulation.
Systematic human brain data analysis is concerned with
how to extract signiﬁcant patterns/features from multiplebrain data sourcesmeasured by using fMRI and EEG in prep-aration for multi-aspect data analysis by combining variousdata mining methods with reasoning ( Megalooikonomou &
Herskovits, 2001; Mitchell et al., 2004; Sommer & Wichert,2003; Sternberg, Lautrey, & Lubart, 2003; Zhong, 2007 ).
Multi-aspect data analysis can mine several kinds of hypoth-
eses from diﬀerent data sources. Furthermore, ACT-R, the
cognitive architecture, is used to simulate/predict human cog-nitive behavior and the structure of brain to achieve the func-tion of adaptive cognition in a system level ( Anderson et al.,
2004, Anderson,Qin,Yung,& Carter, 2007 ).Thus, the frame-
work provides a combination of analysis and simulation tounderstand human intelligence in depth.
Fig. 1 shows an investigation ﬂow based on BI method-
ology, in which various tools can be cooperatively used inthe multi-step process for experimental design, pre-processing(data extraction, modeling and transformation), multi-aspect data mining and post-processing. In the experimen-tal design part, various tasks of experiments with multiplediﬃculty levels are designed by a systematic way for multi-purpose investigation of human thinking and/or perceptioncentric cognitive functions. In the data mining part, various
methods for data processing, mining, reasoning, and simu-
lation are deployed on a multi-phase process for perform-ing multi-aspect analysis as well as multi-level conceptualabstraction and learning, which aims at discovering usefulknowledge to understand human intelligence in depth.
3. The experiment of mental arithmetic task with multiple
diﬃculty levels
Fig. 2 gives a computation processing from the macro
viewpoint, which consists of several component functions4 S. Motomura, N. Zhong / Cognitive Systems Research 11 (2010) 3–15 of human computation mechanism, such as attention,
interpretation, short-term memory, understanding of work,
computation, and checking. As mentioned above, based onthe BI methodology, the data obtained from a cognitiveexperiment and/or a set of cognitive experiments expectto be used for multi-purpose. For example, it is possiblethat our experiments meet the following requirements:investigating the mechanisms of human visual and auditorysystems, computation, problem-solving (i.e. the computa-
tion processing is regarded as an example of problem-solv-
ing processes), and spatiotemporal characteristics and ﬂowof HIPS in general. Furthermore, we set multiple diﬃcultylevels with respect to a series of computation tasks in a setof experiments.
3.1. Outline of experiments
The task of our cognitive experiments is to show a
numerical calculation problem to a human subject, andto ask the subject to solve it in mental arithmetic. More
speciﬁcally, the numerical calculation used in the experi-
ments is the addition problem with the following forms:‘‘augend þaddend ¼sum”or ‘‘augend, summand 1, sum-
mand 2, summand 3, summand 4, summand 5 ¼sum”.W e
can see that the former is a general addition problem, andthe latter is a continuous addition problem. As for the con-tinuous addition problem, the ‘‘þ ”symbol is not displayed,
and the human subject adds up the numbers continuously.
In the experiments, four states (tasks), namely, on-task ,
oﬀ-task ,no-task ,a n d memory-task are addressed by the dif-
ference in the stimulus given to a human subject. Here on-
taskis the state on which the human subject is calculating
by looking at a number; oﬀ-task is the state on which the
human subject is looking at the number that appears atrandom; no-task is the relaxed state on which the human
subject does not work at all; memory-task is the state on
which the human subject is remembering six randomnumbers.
We set two presentation types, namely Type A and Type
B, with six diﬃculty levels. Type A remains the ﬁgure onthe screen, but Type B does not remain. Furthermore,the six diﬃculty levels are described as follows: Levels 1and 2 use single digit addition tasks (with carry or no carry,respectively); Levels 3 and 4 use double digits addition
tasks (with carry or no carry, respectively); Levels 5 and
6 use the tasks of 6 ﬁgures continuous addition. The diﬀer-ence between Level 5 and Level 6 is that the number ofaddition is 3 or less, and an answer is 11 or less in Level5, however, carrying is caused two times in Level 6. Figs.
3 and 4 give examples of the screen state transition of the
tasks, and show the relationship between tasks with respectto diﬀerent types and diﬃculty levels. By such a design, it is
possible to analyze the inﬂuence in the diﬀerent diﬃculty
levels, with the same on-task andoﬀ-task , and to make a
Fig. 1. An investigation ﬂow based on BI methodology.
Fig. 2. Human computation processing.S. Motomura, N. Zhong / Cognitive Systems Research 11 (2010) 3–15 5 comparison between on-task andoﬀ-task in the same diﬃ-
culty level.
3.2. Trigger signal and timing diagram
It is necessary to measure EEG/fMRI relevant to a cer-
tain event to the regular timing in measurement of ERP/fMRI repeatedly. In this research, since the attention was
paid to each event of augend, ‘‘ þ”, addend, and ‘‘ ¼”pre-
sentations in computation activities. Pre-trigger was set to200 ms, and addition between two digits is recorded in
2000 ms, respectively. Fig. 5 gives an example of the timing
diagram, in which ‘‘Au ”denotes an augend, ‘‘Ad ”denotes
an addend, ‘‘Sm ”denotes a summand, and ‘‘Rn ”denotes a
random number. Hence ‘‘Au 1” is the most signiﬁcant digit
(MSD) of augend, and ‘‘Au 2 ”is the least signiﬁcant digit
(LSD) of augend. In this research, all tasks were executed
in the EEG experiments. While only on-task in Level 4
was executed to conﬁrm the eﬀectiveness of the experiment
design in the fMRI experiment. Subjects need to perform
25 experimental trials in EEG and 40 experimental trialsin fMRI, respectively.
3.3. Experimental devices and measurement conditions
We ﬁrst describe the EEG measurement conditions. The
stimulus presentations were created using Presentation ver-
sion 9.9 (Neurobehavioral) and the subjects were shown
with the LCD. It was made to synchronize with PC forFig. 3. Experimental design.
Fig. 4. An overview of experimental tasks with multiple diﬃculty levels
and inter-relationships.6 S. Motomura, N. Zhong / Cognitive Systems Research 11 (2010) 3–15 EEG data measurement with the trigger signal from PC for
stimulus presentation control. The EEG activity wasrecorded using a 128 channel BrainAmp ampliﬁer (Brain
Products, Munich, Germany) with an 128 electrode cap
as shown in Fig. 6 . The impedance of the electrode is all
8kXor less. The electrode cap is based on an extended
international 10–20 system. Furthermore, the eye move-ment measurement (2 ch) is also used. The sampling fre-quency is 1000 Hz to be processed.The ERP (event-related potential) data obtained from
10 subjects are analyzed using Brain Vision Analyzer(BRAIN PRODUCTS, Inc.) as the pre-processing and
data analysis software of EEG. We used several functions
provided in Brain Vision Analyzer, such as ocular correc-tion, ﬁlter (BPF: 0.5–80 Hz), baseline correction, artifactrejection, and ERP derivation.
The fMRI measurement conditions are as follows. The
stimulus presentations were also created using PresentationFig. 5. Timing diagram of experimental tasks.
Fig. 6. Electrode cap.S. Motomura, N. Zhong / Cognitive Systems Research 11 (2010) 3–15 7 version 9 (Neurobehavioral) and the subjects were shown
with the LCD (viewed through a mirror). Scanning wasperformed on a 3 T Siemens system using a standardwhole-head coil. Functional data were acquired using agradient echo planar pulse sequence (TR ¼2s ,T E ¼31 ms,
30 axial slices, 4 mm
3voxels, 0.8 mm inter-slice gap, 200
volumes per run, 90/C14ﬂip angle, 64 /C264 matrix size in
240/C2240 mm2ﬁeld of view). The imaging sequence is opti-
mized to detect the BOLD eﬀect including local shimmingand 10 s of scanning prior to data collection to allow theMR signal to reach equilibrium.
The fMRI data obtained from 11 subjects are analyzed
using Statistical Parametric Mapping (SPM2). We usedseveral functions provided in SPM2, such as slice timing
correction, realignment, coregistration, normalization,
smoothing. A permissible threshold value of head move-ment is 2 mm, and data with a small movement is adopted.For normalization, the fMRI data are standardized withstructural image and MNI standard brain of T1, and theparameter is set to T2-EPI. For smoothing, the FWHMis set to 10, which becomes two or three times of the voxelsize. The activations reported survived an uncorrected
voxel-level intensity threshold of p<0:01.
4. Multi-aspect data analysis
It is possible that our experiments meet the following
requirements: investigating the mechanisms of human
visual and auditory systems, computation, problem-solving(Newell & Simon, 1972 ), and the spatiotemporal character-
istics and ﬂow of HIPS in general. Furthermore, multi-aspect data analysis can mine several kinds of interestingpatterns and hypotheses from diﬀerent data sources. In thisresearch, we used multiple data sources, such as frequencyspectrum data, ERP data, potential topography (2D and3D), and fMRI data, for multi-aspect data analysis, namelyfrequency analysis, ERP analysis, potential topography
analysis, and fMRI data analysis. Furthermore, a more
exact result can be obtained by integrating and explainingthe results of multi-aspect data analysis.
4.1. Frequency analysis
The objective of frequency analysis is to catch the fre-
quency element ﬂuctuation from the spatiotemporal view
by recognizing distribution and appearance of alpha wave
and beta wave. Hence, we can ﬁnd the diﬀerent features onfrequency elements with respect to a computation process-ing. And medical knowledge can be also used by analyzingfrequency elements.
Fig. 7 shows the results of frequency analysis with respect
to no-task, oﬀ-task, and on-task (Level 4), respectively. Weanalyzed the data (about 1 s) when the addend (Ad 2) was
presented in on-task. The time period is closely related to
a computation activity. Furthermore, we analyzed the data(about 1 s) when the Rn 5 was presented in oﬀ-task. In thiswork, we focus on analyzing the following channels: Fz(attentiveness and concentration), Oz (visual cortex), C5(left temporal lobe), and CPz (between Fz and Oz). In com-parison between on-task and oﬀ-task, we can see that thebrain wave has a high percentage of theta rhythm in Fz
and Oz in on-task. On the other hand, the alfa rhythm pre-
Fig. 7. Frequency band of brain waves.8 S. Motomura, N. Zhong / Cognitive Systems Research 11 (2010) 3–15 dominates in no-task, and decreases in on-task and oﬀ-task.
This phenomenon is called the Fm theta rhythm, which is aconventional knowledge conﬁrmed.
4.2. ERP data analysis
For the measured EEG data, a maximum of 40 addition
average processing was performed, and the ERP (event-
related potential) human brain waves were derived by usingBrain Vision Analyzer (Brain Products, Munich,Germany). ERP is a light, sound, and brain potential pro-duced with respect to the speciﬁc phenomenon of sponta-neous movement ( Handy, 2004; Nittono, Nageishi,
Nakajima, & Ullsperger, 1999; Picton et al., 2000 ). We
use the mental arithmetic task with visual stimuli, as anexample to investigate human computation processing.
Generally speaking, the Wernicke area of a left temporal
lobe and the prefrontal area are related to the computationprocessing ( Mizuhara, Wang, Kobayashi, & Yamaguchi,
2005). In this research, we pay attention to integrated pro-
cessing and short-term memory (AF3), recognition of thenumber (CP3), vision (Oz), as well as compare between
tasks by focusing on some important channels.
Fig. 8 a shows the ERP of Type A on-task in Level 4 and
oﬀ-task. In comparison between on-task and oﬀ-task in
Level 4, the latency of response is slow in on-task. Thisphenomenon is especially prominent in Oz during the‘‘þ”presented, AF3 and CP3 during an addend presented,
and Oz during the ‘‘ ¼”presented. The most interesting dif-
ference is about a latent time during the Ad 2 presented.
P250 appears in oﬀ-task and P300 appears in on-task on
AF3. Similarly, N150 and P300 appear in oﬀ-task, butP400 (long latency potential) appears in on-task on CP3.We can guess that the delay of AF3 and CP3 is relatedto the diﬀerence of digit number and computation activi-ties. This result suggests that the ﬁgures gaze and linguisticinterpretation possess a lower speed. On the other hand,the positive potential of on-task is higher than that of
oﬀ-task after an addend was presented. It is thought that
this result is related to a peculiar process of on-task likethe addition processing and the short-term memory.
Fig. 8 b shows the ERP of Type B on-task in Level 6,
memory-task and oﬀ-task. A common factor to the threetasks is that the ﬁgure (1 digit) is continuously displayedon the monitor. On the contrary, the diﬀerences amongthe three tasks are with respect to adding, memory, and
attention. In comparison between on-task and memory-
task, the potential change of on-task is bigger while the ﬁg-ure appears. On the other hand, the potential change ofmemory-task is very big while the question time. In partic-ular, the latent time of P250 is deeply in AF3. We can guessthat the potential change is related to the process of short-term matching ( Fletcher & Henson, 2001 ). As in Type A,
both on-task and memory-task latent times are slower than
that of oﬀ-task. The N300 and N400 can be explained as
language understanding and semantic process ( Curran,
Tucker, Kutas, & Posner, 1993 ). We need to discuss deeplyby analyzing the diﬀerence of the appearance of N400 inthe diﬀerent levels of computation diﬃculty.
4.3. Potential topography analysis
The advantage of potential topograph analysis is that it
catches the electrical ﬂuctuation and gives a rough visuali-
zation of the spatiotemporal characteristics, for recogniz-ing distribution and appearance of positive and negativepotentials. Hence, we can ﬁnd the diﬀerent features onpotentials with respect to each step of the computation pro-cessing. In this research, we use the 2D and 3D topogra-phies. In particular, activities around the brain becomeclear by using the 3D topography ( Kim, Kwon, Lee, &
Kim, 2007 ).
Fig. 9 a shows the 2D potential topography. This ﬁgure
shows the appearance of the potential change from begin-ning to the end of a computation processing. Each ﬁgure isa description between 300 ms and 400 ms from the stimula-tion presentation. In this research, we focus on on-task inLevel 4 (both Type A and Type B), oﬀ-task, and memory-task. In comparison between four tasks, it is found that the
appearance position and timing of positive potential are
greatly diﬀerent. In comparison between Type A and TypeB, the positive potential distribution of Ad 1 and Ad 2 isalmost symmetrical in Type A, but it is not symmetry (rightbrain-dominant) in Type B. >From the viewpoint of cerebrallocalization, this result is very important for logical or intu-itive computation processing. Furthermore, in comparisonbetween on-task and oﬀ-task, the potential distributions of
frontal cortex and parietal lobe are sharply diﬀerent. The
positive potential just appears in the frontal cortex fromthe parietal lobe in memory-task and on-task, but such phe-nomenon does not appear in the visual cortex in oﬀ-task.
Fig. 9b shows the 3D potential topography, in which we
