5. Integration and explanation of results
Based on the results stated above, this section provides a
comparative study by combining the results obtained by
each analysis method separately towards a more wholeexplanation and understanding. The common featuresand the diﬀerence points are investigated by comparingType A with tasks of Type B in Level 4, which are the
two digit addition problem. However, the repetition prob-
lem related tasks, such as oﬀ-task, continuous addition taskFig. 11. Integration and explanation of Type A and Type B.S. Motomura, N. Zhong / Cognitive Systems Research 11 (2010) 3–15 13 (Level 6), and memory-task, cannot be indiscriminately
discussed on the same axis as the two digit addition prob-lem. Hence, the comparison between these tasks is summa-rized by only discussing some interesting points.
We ﬁrst discuss the diﬀerence of the presentation meth-
ods between Type A and Type B at the same level (on-task
in Level 4). Fig. 11 shows the main features of Type A and
Type B on each event. >From the results of brain wave
analysis and fMRI data analysis, we can see that timingof ﬁgure recognition is diﬀerent from that of computation.Furthermore, since subjects must reassemble two digits ﬁg-ure based on two characters in Type B, we can conﬁrmfrom the result of fMRI data analysis in Type B that thebrain areas with respect to restructuring and working mem-
ory of the number are activated (BA 6, BA 37, BA 40). We
also ﬁnd the spatiotemporal diﬀerence that the positivepotential appears in Type A and Type B from the resultof topography. The positive potential in Type A standsout in each time zone, and this suggests the continuousnessof the computation processing. On the other hand, a com-mon feature of Type A and Type B is the spatial recogni-tion for the ﬁgure, which is obtained from both fMRI
data analysis (BA 7) and brain wave analysis (CP 3). An
interesting guess from the results is that human beingscan do an eﬃcient computation processing unconsciouslyand the diﬀerence of processing aﬀects the diﬀerence ofthe results. In order to understand the results deeply, notonly brain data analysis, but also the analyzes need to becombined with studies of psychology and pedagogy.
Next, we give a summary by discussing some interesting
points in comparison between tasks in Type B. It is clearfrom the results that both common potential change andpeculiar potential change existed. The results suggest thatthe computation processing consists of more componentfunctions, and both on-task and oﬀ-task use the same brainfunctions for ﬁgure recognition. A lot of common featureswere also conﬁrmed from the visual cortex to the left tem-poral lobe in this analysis. On the other hand, comparing
with a usual addition problem, it was found that the frontal
lobe was highly activated when subjects carried out thecontinuous addition problem that puts subjects a highload. Although the diﬀerence in the ﬁgure recognition isclear in the memory-task, it is not caught plainly that thereactive diﬀerence between the right and left brain whencarried out diﬀerent tasks For such a further investigation,it is necessary to compare the computation problem with
other higher cognitive functions such as reasoning ( Liang
et al., 2007 ), which is based on BI methodology for system-
atic experimental design and analysis.
6. Conclusion
In this paper, we investigated human computation
mechanism related functions by using mental arithmetic
as an example, which demonstrate what is BI methodology
and its usefulness. The proposed multi-aspect data analysisapproach based on BI methodology shifts the focus of cog-nitive science from a single type of experimental data anal-ysis towards a deep, holistic understanding of humaninformation processing principles, models and mecha-nisms. Based on the BI methodology, we designed cogni-tive experiments for investigating human computationmechanism with multiple diﬃculty levels on multi-task,
carried out the experiments by using fMRI and EEG,
and analyzed the data from multi-aspect. Experimentalresults showed the usefulness of our approach.
Our future work includes obtaining and analyzing more
subject data, and apply more data mining techniques torichen multi-aspect data analysis ( Motomura, Hara, Zhong,
& Lu, 2007;Zhong, 2007 ). In addition, the computation pro-
cessing can be regarded as an example of problem-solving
processes, and can be deeply investigated in the connection
between the ﬁgure processing and memory, as well as therelationship with other higher cognitive functions.
