Abstract— The mental effort needed to complete the 
activities is referred to as cognitive workload.  Mental arithmetic 
tasks  (MAT)  are engag ing in various cognitive processes, 
including decision -making, memory recall, problem solving, 
fact retrieval, etc. Solving a MAT  requires more than one brain 
activity and i s a crucial component in many fields, such as 
industrial applications, clinical medicine, and system design.  An 
EEG (electroencephalogram) is an effective tool for 
detecting  patterns and variations in the   brain's electrical 
activity.  Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)  have been 
widely applied for a utomatic feature extraction from raw EEG 
signals for different deep learning  (DL)  models . Due to the 
capability of temporal dependency representation, Recurrent 
Neural Networks  (RNN)  can be considered suitable for the time 
series analysis of EEG signals.  Considering the advantages of  
DL models, a hybrid CNN -LSTM  model  is developed  for the 
categorization of EEG signals obtained before and during  the 
MAT.  The proposed model is assessed by utilizing the open 
access  MAT  EEG database  and is obtained  during the 
performance of  serial subtraction of two numbers. The 
proposed approach is executed utilizing MATLAB R2023b  and 
the performance metrics such as accuracy (99.10%), sensitivity 
(96.05%), specificity (99.72%), precision (98.64%), MCC 
(96.80%), kappa (99.09%) and F1 -score (97.33%) are 
obtained  respectively  and are compared with the existing 
methodologies . 
Keywords — Cognitive workload, EEG, mental arithmetic task, 
deep  learning.  
I. INTRODUCTION  
Mental tasks, such as reality retrieval, memory, 
sequencing, and decision -making, are essential cognitive 
functions. Mental activities are essential for improving 
cognitive flexibility and critical thinking skills. Monitoring 
these activities through EEG signals helps to understand  how 
the brain responds to such tasks.  Research has highlighted the 
importance of analysing  brain activity  for early detection of 
various cognitive and mental disorders.  This includes syndromes  like autism , dyscalculia , attention deficit 
hyperactivity disorder [1]. The study of electrical brain activity 
during mental tasks helps in understanding and addressing 
these conditions.  
 The brain cortex comprises four major lobes frontal, 
parietal, temporal, and occipital [2]. These lobes coordinate 
and facilitate many cognitive operations, including numerical 
processing, memory retrieval, and construction of problem -
solving strategies. The frontal lobe involves in decision -
making, working memory, and problem -solving, while the 
parietal lobe deals with sensory processing and numerical 
calculations and retrieval of information from facts. The 
auditory system and verbal memory may be grouped  with the 
temporal lobe, whereas the occipital lobe is relate d to visual 
perception and the recognition of numerical symbols.  
The EEG is a non -invasive method  widely utilized for 
analysing cognitive performance across various brain 
states [3]. It is particularly effective in assessing brain activity 
during cognitive tasks. Electrode placements are determined 
utilizing the International 10/20 system, which aligns 
electrode positions with the cerebral cortex structure for 
accurate data acquisition.  EEG signals are beneficial for 
testing functional aspects of the human brain and refer to a 
change in powering patterns of brainwaves, of ten in a MAT . 
Its biggest advantage is speed, as it is able to detect complex 
brain activity within fractions of a second post -trigger. EEG is  
