settings. It is utilized  to monitor brain activity and to find 
abnormal brain wave activity that can assist in the assessment 
of neurological disorders such as epilepsy. EEG may also be 
used when monitoring multiple sleep stages in sleep studies to 
assess sleep disorders such as insomnia and obstructive sleep 
apnea. In cognitive research, EEG is used to measure brain 
activity for a variety of tasks such as learning, memory,  
problem -solving  and brain activity associated with attention.  
Several authors have examined EEG signals during MATs 
to study brain activity in both resting and active states. Binish 
Fatimah et. al.,[1] though Fourier decomposition method is 
used for decomposing the EEG into m ultiple  sub-bands  and 
features were extracted  from each sub -band. The MATs were 
categorized  using machine learning (ML) method based on the 
extracted features. Binish Fatimah et. al.,  presented a ML 
classifier methodology for the detection of MAT difficulty 
level  [2]. The digital filters were util ized and decomposed the 
raw data into various frequency rhythms and extracted the 
features. The extracted features were utilized and classified 
the data into rest and active states using various ML 
classifiers. Naqib Sad Pathan et.al., proposed a SVM class ifier 
to categorize  the MAT  [5]. The signals were divided into 
discrete frequency sub -bands utilizing the discrete wavelet 
transform in which the features were statistically assessed. 
Qiang Wang et.al.[6] performed multifractal analysis of EEG 
data using a  method known as Generalized Higuchi Fractal 
Dimension Spectrum. In MAT classification, the algorithms 
applied can be subject -dependent and may operate in either a 
single -channel or multi -channel configuration.  The proposed 
method demonstrated an accuracy of 84.15% using single -
channel algorithms, which further improved to 97.87% with 
multi -channel subject -dependent algorithms.  Biswarup 
Ganguly et.al., proposed a stacked LSTM  model [7] to 
recognize and categorize MATs with less number of 
electrodes. Window segmentation was implemented to 
enhance data augmentation, resulting an acc of 91.67%. Celia 
Shahnaz et.al.,  utilized Perceptual Wavelet Packet Transform  
[8] to separate  EEG signals into multiple frequency bands. 
Teager energy was computed for the wavelet packet 
coefficients and extracted the features. These features were 
utilized and c ategorized  using SVM. Rifai Chai et.al. 
suggested an artificial neural network for categorization that 
optimizes genetic algorithms  [9]. The data is collected from 
subjects u sing non -hair area electrodes on the prefrontal 
cortex. Hilbert -Huang Transform energy method were utilized 
for feature extraction  and achieved 73% of accuracy for 
mental tasks vs. baseline conditions. Hyeon Kyu Lee et.al. 
proposed a CNN to classify the motor imagery  [10]. Time -
frequency image s of EEG signals were generated using the 
Continuous Wavelet Transform  and achieved 97.61%  of 
accuracy . Abhishek Varshney et al. [11] investigated 
classification of good and bad MA calculation, and 
classification before and during MA calculation, using RNN 
classifiers. The RNN models achieved accuracy values 
exceeding 99% in all cases.  Author in [12] examines the 
mental workload in real time applications, such as driving 
under real traffic conditions. Classified mental workload 
levels in real -time using ML methods. Tahemineh Azizi [13] 
begins by outlining the algorithms used in signal p rocessing. 
Firstly divides the input signal into overlapping segments 
using the STFT, and then applies FT to each seg ment. Nan 
Ying Liang introduced in [14] a new classification algorithm 
called the Extreme Learning Machine that reduces training time with no regard for the loss of acc. In this model, feature 
extraction was made on raw data and then classifiers were 
trained based on feature vectors. Then, the classifiers were 
tested using the unseen data for classification acc evaluation. 
Abadi Hod a Edris[15] extracted geometric features such as 
short distance, length, angle and slope. The most relevant 
geometric features are selected for dimensionality reduction 
and improvement of the ML model's efficiency . The selected 
features are fed into a ML classifier to detect and classify 
MATs.    
Despite advancements, EEG -based mental arithmetic 
classification faces several limitations. Subject -dependent 
algorithms may not generalize well across individuals, and 
high-dimensional feature sets increase computational 
complexity. Many methods require e xtensive preprocessing, 
making real -time applications challenging. M L models 
demand large datasets for effective training, which are not 
always available [16]. Additionally, signal quality is affected 
by noise, artifacts, and electrode placement, reducing m odel 
reliability.  
This paper presents the following key contributions:  
(1) EEG signals are pre -processed with a band -pass 
Butterworth filter of order 2 followed by Z -score 
normalization to enhance the quality of data.  
(2) CNN and LSTM networks are combined to 
automatically extract spatial and temporal features 
from EEG signals.  
(3) he features extracted from the CNN -LSTM fusion 
model are used for classifying EEG data into two 
classes: before and during the task.  
(4) The model proposed by this method was evaluated 
using the MIT Physionet EEG database and 
achieved a much better performance than already -
existing methods.  
 With this paper going ahead, Section II serves as a brief 
introduction to the project that includes a block diagram, 
dataset details, and methodology. Section III presents a 
detailed analysis of the simulation results, evaluating the 
performance of the proposed method using various metrics 
and comparing it with existing methods.  Section IV 
summarizes the key outcomes of the study  and future work.  
II. PROPOSED METHODOLOGY  
MAT involve solving math problems in the mind without 
external tools engaging cognitive processes like attention, 
working memory, and problem solving. EEG can capture 
brainwave patterns which reflect cognitive engagement, focus 
and mental workload during thes e tasks [17]. The proposed 
 
