This Fig. 2. illustrates the process of analysing EEG data 
to classify brain activity before and during a MAT task. The 
raw data signals are recorded from individuals, which include 
the brainwave signals recorded under two conditions, before 
and during the task. The first stage is data preprocessing, 
which consis ts of two stages, filtering and normalization. The 
Butterworth bandpass filter removes noise and unwanted 
frequency components. Normalization rescales the data so that 
the comparison among the signa ls could easily be processed 
in a uniform way by deep -learning algorithms [18].  After pre -
processing, feature extraction takes place using the hybrid 
deep learning model that integrat es CNN  and LSTM  (Long 
Short -Term Memory) . While CNN acts on spatial 
features [19], LSTM works well for sequential data. This 
combination extracts the characteristics from EEG data by 
temporal and spatial segmentation, allowing the model to 
better distinguish brain states before and during the task. The 
extracted features are utilized to c ategorize  the EEG signals 
into two distinct groups: Before Task (BT) and During Task 
(DT). This performance classification is evaluated using 
metrics accuracy  (acc) , sensitivity  (sen) , specificity  (spe) , 
precision  (pre) , Matthews Correlation Coefficient  (MCC) , 
kappa  (ka) and F1 -score  (F1_s). The analysis helps in 
understanding the changes in mental states during task 
performance.  
A. Database  Description  
In this study, a n open  access  dataset from MIT PhysioNet 
was utilized [20]. EEG recordings were collected from 
individuals both before and during MAT and are included in 
the database. Silver or silver chloride electrodes were arranged  
symmetrically on the scalp and the Neurocom 23 -channel 
system (Ukraine, XAI -MEDICA) was utilized to record the 
EEG data.  
The impedance between electrodes was maintained less 
than 5 kΩ by referencing each electrode to the ear electrodes. 
EEG signals were filtered with a high -pass at 0.5 Hz and a 
low-pass at 45 Hz, and sampled at 500 Hz per channel. To 
eliminate power line noise , a 50 Hz notch filter was 
utilized .The amplification tract was lasted for  0.3 seconds.  
There are 36 subjects in total. These EEG recordings are 
artifact -free recordings of 180 sec before task and 60 sec 
during task. Two numbers were serially subtracted as the 
arithmetic task. Every trial began with an oral discussion of 
two-digit (subtrahend) and four -digit (minuend) integers, 
such as 3141  and 42. The before task data includes 36 subjects, however 33 subjects have 91000 samples but the 
remaining three subjects has 94000, 85000 and 40000 samples 
for 182s duration each, while the during task data has 31000 
samples for all the 36 subjects of 60s duration each . The EEG 
segments are separated into non -overlapping chunks to 
improve the  data available for traini ng and testing . A window 
size of 35s (35*500=17500 samples) was considered  to ensure 
that the signals are the same length before and during the task  
A total of 4452 frames are considered for analysis  (BT-3696 
frames and DT -756 frames) . Z-score normalization is utilized 
to standardize the data distribution effectively and expressed 
in equation (1) as 
(data - mean of the data)Z Score = std deviation of the data
                 (1) 
B. CNN -LSTM Model  
          Fig. 4. shows the proposed hybrid CNN -LSTM model's 
block diagram.  For the purpose of classifying mental 
arithmetic tasks with EEG, a hybrid Convolutional Neural 
Network -Long Short -Term Memory (CNN -LSTM) model 
was employed. This model was selected due to the advantage 
of combining both CNN and LSTM in the learning process  
of the spatial -temporal representations of EEG data.  The 
CNN model is well -suited for capturing spatial dependencies 
across EEG channels, while the LSTM model represents the 
tempo ral dynamics present in the EEG data due to sequential 
neural activity. The combination gives strength to the feature 
extraction and classification, especially in relation to brain 
signals associated with performing cognitive tasks.  The CNN  
architecture has several layers that work together to process 
input. The convolutional layer  (CL)  utilizes a filter to extract 
features, generating feature maps. The dimension of the 
feature maps is minimized by  utilizing a pooling layer (PL) 
to improve  the process more efficien tly. Pooling is 
categorised into two types. First, Max pooling selects the 
largest value while, average polling gives the average value 
from feature map. The neurons are connected between 
various layers through the use of a fully connected layer (FL).  
It includes the neurons, along with their associated weights 
and biases.  In pr oposed model, the CNN block includes three 
CL, each with a filter size of three. The number of filters is 
fixed to 128, 256, and 128, with padding set to ""same"" and a 
stride of 2 for all layers. A ReLU activation layer is utilized 
to add non -linearity and improves feature extraction after 
each CL. A global average PL is applied to minimize  the 
number of values  and further optimize the network. This 
pooling method computes the average of each feature map, 
providing a compact representation of the input data while 
retaining its essential features.  
          LSTM  architecture  consists of an input, hidden state, 
cell state, gates, and output. At each time step, it processes an 
input , updates the hidden state and maintains long -term 
memory via the cell state. Three gates regulate information 
flow,  the Forget Gate selectively erases past data, the Input 
Gate adds or discards new information, and the Output Gate 
decides which aspects of the cell state  to focus on or ignore 
when computing the output.  Here, LSTM block consists  of  
an LSTM  and a dropout lay ers. Two LSTM layers were 
considered with hidden units of 64 and 128. The output  mode 
for first layer is taken as sequence and for second layer i s 
considered  as last. After each LSTM layer, dropout layer of  
