IV. CONCLUSION  
      The classification of MAT  based on   EEG signals is much 
needed in cognitive neuroscience and BCI applications [24]. 
EEG signals  are non-invasive and high in temporal 
resolution, present challenges due to their complex and non -
stationary nature. To overcome the limitations, an integrated 
CNN -LSTM model built on CNNs and LSTMs has been 
proposed . The spatial features  are extracted by CNNs  and 
LSTMs for temporal sequence  modeling , thus enhancing the 
model's performance with regard to classification accuracy. 
The model achieved remarkable accuracy of 99.31, along 
with various performance metrics  such as  sensitivity (96.05), 
specificity (99. 72), precision (98.64), Matthews Correlation 
Coefficient (MCC) (96.80), recall (96.05), kappa (99.09) and 
F1-score (97.33). This indicates that the proposed m ethod  has 
been effective in accurately categorizing EEG signals  during 
MAT . For future research, efforts could focus on enhancing 
the model’s ability to generalize across diverse participants 
and varying conditions by improving its performance on 
larger and more complex EEG datasets. Additionally, the 
incorporation of transformer -based architectures an d 
attention mechanisms could be explored to further strengthen 
feature extraction and overall model capabilities.  
