Brain Vision ampli ﬁer and RecView software (Brain Products GmbH,
Munich, Germany). All recordings were monitored by a trained
investigator.
2.4. EEG data analysis
EEG signals were analyzed of ﬂine using Brain Vision Analyzer 2.0
(Brain Products, Munich, Germany). After the application of low and
high cut off ﬁlters, a frequency range between 5 and 30.0 Hz
remained for analyses (time constant 0.3183099 s; 48 dB/octave).
Any channels exceeding an impedance of 10 k Ωwere excluded
from further analysis. Following visual inspection, automatic artifact
rejection was applied (gradient b50μV; max/min amplitude −200
to 200 μV; lowest allowed activity in intervals 0.5 μV). From the 43
participants, EEG data of 34 participants was eligible for further ERP
analysis.
Event related potentials (ERP) usually consist of several components
that are assumed to be real-time correlates of speci ﬁcc o g n i t i v ep r o c e s s -
es. The relatively early components mainly re ﬂect automatic processes
such as stimulus detection, while the later components primarily re ﬂect
control processes.
As ERPs are time-locked to stimuli, we identi ﬁed the appearance of
the task (i.e. the display of numbers on the screen) as the relevant stim-
ulus. Following segmentation based on stimulus onset ( −100 to
800 ms), segmented data were baseline corrected ( −100 to 0 ms)
and averaged, using a minimum of 50 epochs for each participant for
the 0G and a minimum of 50 epochs for each participant for the 1G con-
dition over all electrodes. Signal to noise ratios (SNR) for each partici-
pant and each condition were calculated using the equation P signal/
Pnoise. Even in the worst case —the similarity between P signal and P noise
was still below 2%.
As recorded scalp potentials show different volumes based on the lo-
calization of the reference, all averaged ERP waveforms were trans-
formed into reference-free current source density (CSD) maps (order
of splines: 4; maximal degree of legendre polynomials: 10; Lambda
1e-5). This allows for the generation of topographies with more sharply
localized peaks than those of scalp potentials and eliminates volume-
conducted activity from distant sources.
It was expected that the presentation of a visual task would elicit a
visual evoked potential (VEP) which is characterized by a N1 –P2complex, where N1 is the ﬁrst negative-going component at around
150 to 200 milliseconds post-stimulus and detectable in centro-
frontal scalp areas. The visual N1 is a component evoked by any visual
stimulus, nevertheless its amplitude might serve as an indicator of task
complexity [16]. The visual P2 is a positive electrical potential that
peaks between 150 and 275 ms post-stimulus in centro-frontal and
centro-parietal regions and has been identi ﬁed to be related to
higher-order perceptual processing and to be in ﬂuenced by the com-
plexity of tasks [17]. Accordingly, amplitude ( μV) as well as latency
(ms) of these visual evoked potentials were exported for statistical
analysis of N1 and P2.
2.5. Localization of EEG activity —sLORETA analysis
A fundamental limitation of traditional EEG recording procedures is
the inverse solution. That is, there is a challenge in determining activat-
ed brain regions by extra cranial recordings. Standardized low resolu-
tion brain electromagnetic tomography (sLORETA) enables the spatial
identi ﬁcation and analysis of brain cortical activity via traditional EEG
recordings [18–21]. Extra cranial EEG activity is evoked by synchronized
postsynaptic potentials (PSPs), which are located in clusters of pyrami-
dal cells [22]. sLORETA allows for the determination of the three dimen-
sional orientation of these highly synchronized PSPs. Cortical regions
are created by allocating the raw LORETA values of individual voxels
to their corresponding Broadmann areas (BA) or cerebral gyri on the
basis of the coordinates of the digitized Talairach Atlas [23]. First, the co-
ordinates of the electrode positions were applied to a digitized MRI ver-
sion of the Talairach Atlas (McConnell Brain Imaging Centre, Montréal
Neurological Institute, McGill University). These Talairach coordinates
were then used to compute the sLORETA transformation matrix. Using
the sLORETA transformation matrix, averaged ERP signals of each indi-
vidual for the 0G and 1G condition were transformed to sLORETA ﬁles.
This resulted in the corresponding 3D cortical distribution of the electri-
cal neuronal generators for each subject. The computed sLORETA image
displayed the cortical neuronal oscillators in 6430 voxels, with a spatial
resolution of 5 mm.
2.6. Statistics
Statistical analyses were performed using STATISTICA version 7.1
(StatSoft, Tulsa, USA). Comparisons of reaction time, accuracy (percent-
age of errors) were performed using two-way repeated measures
ANOVA with the within-group factors of “level ”(1–4) and “gravity ”
(1G/0G), and the between-group factor complexity (EASY/DIFFICULT).
Further analysis of the effects of experience or medication were calcu-
lated using the factors “gravity ”(0G/1G), “level ”(1–4, RT only) and
“group ”(frequent ﬂyer,ﬁrst time ﬂyer –no medication, ﬁrst time ﬂyer
–with medication). Analysis of N1 and P2 amplitude and latency during
the EASY trial was performed using repeated measures ANOVA with the
within-group factor of “gravity ”(1G/0G).
Where appropriate, Fisher's least signi ﬁcance difference test (LSD)
was used for post-hoc analyses. The level of signi ﬁcance was set at
pb0.05. Data are presented as mean +/ −standard deviation (SD).
To localize differences in ERP activity between normal gravity and
weightlessness, paired sampled t-test were computed on Log trans-
formed data at each voxel. Statistical signi ﬁcance was assessed using a
nonparametric randomization test [24]. To correct for multiple compar-
isons, a nonparametric single-threshold test was assessed de ﬁning a
critical threshold (tcritical ). Voxels with statistic values exceeding this
threshold have their null hypothesis rejected. The omnibus hypothesis
(that all the voxel hypotheses are true) is rejected if a voxel value ex-
ceeds the critical threshold for p b.05 de ﬁned by 5000 randomizations.
Voxel-by-voxel t-values in Talairach space are displayed as statistical
parametric maps (SPMs).
