3.1. Reaction time
Results for group EASY showed no difference in reaction time be-
tween 0G and 1G (F (1, 14) = 2.63, p = .13) nor between levels (F (3,
42)= .53, p = .66). As expected, reaction time increased with increasing
levels of dif ﬁculty in group DIFFICULT (F (3, 78) = 97.12, p b.001), but in-
terestingly this increase in reaction time was longer (slower) during the
1G condition (F (1, 26) = 18.90, p b.001). Post-hoc analysis of the effects
of gravity at the different levels (F (3, 78) = 5.58, p b.01) in the DIFFICULT
group revealed shorter reaction times in 0G compared to 1G at the more
difﬁcult levels (levels 3 and 4; Fig. 1 ).
3.2. Accuracy
As i g n i ﬁcant increase in the frequency of incorrect answers was ob-
served in the 0G condition when combining both groups (main gravityeffect: F (1, 40) = 4.70, p b.05; Fig. 2 ). While there was a signi ﬁcant
level∗group interaction (F (3, 120) = 10.06, p b.001), associated with
an increased error rate in group DIFFICULT from level 1 to level 2
(pb.001) and level 2 to 3 (p b.001), no level ∗gravity ∗group interac-
tion was observed (F (3, 120) = 1.08, p = .36; Fig. 2 ).
3.3. ERP components/signal topography
As usual for visual stimuli [25], in both conditions (0G/1G) a clear N1
could be detected at around 140 –170 ms after stimulus onset over
centro-frontal scalp areas, followed by a P2 starting at around 180 ms
at parieto-occipital location and shifting towards centro-frontal scalp
areas until 250 ms after stimulus onset ( Fig. 3 ).
T-statistics comparing ERPs of the 0G and 1G conditions in between
200 and 300 ms after stimulus onset using the sLORETA software re-
vealed a signi ﬁcant difference (p b.05; t = −4.15; t critical (two-tailed) =
4.04) for the time point 238 ms after stimulus onset. Comparing the cal-
culated cortical distribution maps revealed a signi ﬁcantly lower activity
