3.4. Experience and medication
Further analysis within the DIFFICULT group of the possible effects of
medication and/or experience showed no differences between experi-
enced ﬂyers ( N100 parabolas) and ﬁrst time ﬂyers, with or without
medication, for reaction time (F
(2, 23) = .11, p = .89) but con ﬁrmed
the improved reaction performance at the higher dif ﬁculty levels during
0G (F (6, 69) = 2.40, p b.05;Fig. 5 ).
A differentiation between experienced ﬂyers and ﬁrst time ﬂyers
with/without medication on P2 amplitude on position Cz revealed no
effect of experience or medication (experienced ﬂyers (n = 12):
6.06μV+ /−2.72; no medication (n = 14): 8.08 μV+ /−5.57; medica-
tion (n = 8): 6.56 μV+ /−2.21; F (2, 31) = .67, p = .52).
4. Discussion
This study aimed to determine the effect of short term microgravity
on cognitive function and associated neurocognitive markers. Previous
studies have demonstrated no, or a slightly negative impact, of micro-
gravity on cognitive performance [1,2,26,27] . To further understand
these behavioral changes, we aimed to assess the related neurophysio-
logical markers. The present study showed an improvement in behav-
ioral markers (RT) during 0G, as well as a positive impact of
microgravity on neural processing quanti ﬁed by ERPs.
It is well known that stress levels increase during parabolic ﬂight, as
indicated by alterations in brain cortical activity and cortisol levels, as
well as negative effects on perceived physical and emotional state
[28–30]. To further investigate the effect of gravity per se, we attempted
to control for this ﬂight induced stress by ensuring that assessments of
reaction time and EEG activity were made during repetitive andconsecutive periods of normal gravity and microgravity, with each
being separated by no more than 30 s. It is unlikely that stress levels
changed signi ﬁcantly between these two short periods. Furthermore,
the microgravity induced changes were independent of the partici-
pants' previous parabolic ﬂight experience, as consistent trends were
seen in both ﬁrst time ﬂyers, who tend to have higher stress levels dur-
ingﬂight[30], as well as more experienced frequent ﬂyers. In addition,
the use of anti-nausea medication, which also minimizes the stress as-
sociated with parabolic ﬂights, had no in ﬂuence on the ﬁnding that mi-
crogravity lead to an improvement in reaction time.
As can be seen by the participants' performance during the more
advanced levels, the more dif ﬁcult the tasks becomes, the greater the
cognitive load that seems to be necessary, which is re ﬂected by an in-
crease in reaction time. Of particular importance here is the decrease
in reaction time during the microgravity condition while completing
the more complex problem solving tasks (levels three and four).
Whereas no difference was observed between micro- and normal grav-
ity during the initial “easy ”levels, there was a signi ﬁcant decrease in re-
action time during the completion of the more dif ﬁcult levels in
microgravity. Importantly, this decrease in reaction time is not
reﬂected in a decrease of accuracy as there was no loss of accuracy dur-
ing the 0G condition.
It is important to note that this improvement in RT during the more
difﬁcult levels is not re ﬂected by any changes in the initial central pro-
cessing. Although N1 seems to be a bit more blurred under 1G ( Fig. 3 ),
no signi ﬁcant effect could be obtained neither in N1 amplitude nor la-
tency. A large number of previous studies focused on factors modulating
the amplitude of the visual N1, suggesting that the N1 re ﬂects a bene ﬁt
of correctly allocated attentional resources and that it is a manifestation
of an important sensory gating mechanism of attention [31]. The results
obtained in this study let us assume that these processes were not af-
fected by changed gravity conditions. A missing effect in N1 amplitude
might be due to the fact that approximately 80% of the stimuli used in
this study could be characterized as single choice reaction time tasks
and previous results showed that amplitude effects on the N1 are absent
during simple reaction time tasks, which only requires participants to
make a rapid response to stimuli [32], A potential limitation of this
study is that the 22 s of microgravity during each parabola only allowed
for a maximum of nine assignments to be solved during dif ﬁculty levels
3 and 4 and therefore we are not able to differentiate the VEPs between
the different dif ﬁculty levels.
Fig. 5. Within each of the subgroups who performed the DIFFICULT protocol, reaction time performance tended to be improved at the higher levels of dif ﬁculty during the 0G condition
(solid line). *p b.05, **p b.01, ***p b.001 between 0G and 1G.14 P. Wollseiffen et al. / Physiology & Behavior 155 (2016) 9 –16 The P2 has traditionally been studied in the context of perception,
with speci ﬁc emphasis on how stimulus evaluation takes place. Using
different paradigms, the visual P2 amplitude is modulated by general vi-
sual features of stimuli as size, color and/or orientation of a presented
task [17,33] . When investigated using a visual search paradigm, an in-
crease in P2 amplitude has shown to be an indicator for attention, mem-
ory and response selection [34]. Studies showing that P2 seems to play a
major role in selective attention and even relates to the derivation of an
emotional percept [35]let us assume that P2, as a response, seems to be
multidimensional and re ﬂects a sensitivity to stimulus features. More-
over and most importantly for the present study, the N1 –P2 complex
has been shown to be in ﬂuenced by stimulus salience. When presented
in a multimodal way (visual andauditory) the N1 –P2 complex is more
expressed in comparison to the presentation in a single mode (visual
orauditory) [36]. As the visual features of the presented task in this ex-
periment did not differ between 0G and 1G, it might be argued that the
change in P2 amplitude is either caused by changes in selective atten-
tion (participants might have been more focused in 0G) or, as it has
been shown that P2 amplitude is dependent on the amount of sensory
input [36], the missing in ﬂuence of gravity might be responsible for
the suppressed N1 –P2 complex. Whether this is connected to the ﬁnd-
ing of a decreased reaction time cannot be fully answered with our data.
One might argue that less sensory input allows for a better attentional
focus and less discrimination between multisensory inputs (e.g. in 1G,
besides the mental arithmetic processing, information on body position
has to be integrated into preparing the tapping response). In particular,
the involvement of BA6, which is an important area related to the plan-
ning of coordinated movements, raises the question of whether the de-
scribed effect could be attributed to changes in (the processing of)
motor control. Although any effects of learning or adaptation can be
ruled out as those should be visible in both 0G and 1G conditions, one
might assume impairment of motor control in microgravity as existent
motor programs need to be adjusted, which would obviously impede
on central resources. However, this would likely result in an increase
not a decrease in reaction time. Moreover, motor control seems to be
less vulnerable in this experiment as there were no ﬁne motor skills
needed with the tablet providing a relatively large tapping area of ap-
proximately 15 ∗20 cm.
Although previous experiments have shown that there is an accu-
mulation of blood volume to the brain during microgravity [15], a sys-
temic in ﬂuence (e.g. changes in conduction) can be ruled out as such
an effect should have been present also in N1 amplitude.
It is important to mention that neither previous experience with mi-
crogravity nor anti-nausea medication had any in ﬂuence on the pre-
sented phenomenon. As there is a broad discussion about the effects
scopolamine, used as anti-nausea drug, on human performance, espe-
cially sensory perception, this study clearly demonstrates that this effect
can be neglected.
5. Conclusion and limitations
This study demonstrates that previous observations of a decrease in
cognitive performance during conditions of microgravity may not be di-
rectly related to microgravity itself. In the present study where the con-
founding in ﬂuence of stress was controlled, reaction time as well as the
underlying early neural processes seem to be enhanced in microgravity.
Whether this effect is limited to the initial sensation of weightlessness
remains to be determined and further experiments under permanent
microgravity would be needed.
With the data presented here, we are only able to identify an effect of
gravity levels (0G and 1G) on VEPs. Given the low number of repeated
stimuli within each level, a further differentiation between levels of dif-
ﬁculty is not possible but should be considered in future studies. Special
attention should be paid to the fact that the improvement in reaction
times is not mirrored in the temporal resolution of the ERPs but seems
to be connected only with the magnitude of the response. While theaim here was to use a more complex task, future studies should include
classical tasks like the oddball paradigm or the ﬂanker task, for which
ERPs have been clearly described.
