ARTICLE INFO
Keywords:
Numerical cognitionMath achievementMagnitude representation
EEG Coherence
ChildrenABSTRACT
Symbolic numerical magnitude processing is crucial to arithmetic development, and it is thought to be supported
by the functional activation of several brain-interconnected structures. In this context, EEG beta oscillations have
been recently associated with attention and working memory processing that underlie math achievement. Due to
that EEG coherence represents a useful measure of brain functional connectivity, we aimed to contrast the EEGcoherence in forty 8-to-9-year-old children with di ﬀerent math skill levels (High: HA, and Low achievement: LA)
according to their arithmetic scores in the Fourth Edition of the Wide Range Achievement Test (WRAT-4) whileperforming a symbolic magnitude comparison task (i.e. determining which of two numbers is numericallylarger). The analysis showed signi ﬁcantly greater coherence over the right hemisphere in the two groups, but
with a distinctive connectivity pattern. Whereas functional connectivity in the HA group was predominant inparietal areas, especially involving beta frequencies, the LA group showed more extensive frontoparietal re-lationships, with higher participation of delta, theta and alpha band frequencies, along with a distinct time –-
frequency domain expression. The results seem to re ﬂect that lower math achievements in children mainly
associate with cognitive processing steps beyond stimulus encoding, along with the need of further attentionalresources and cognitive control than their peers, suggesting a lower degree of numerical processing automation.
1. Introduction
In an increasingly competitive technological world, under-
achievement in mathematics can dramatically hinder children ’s op-
portunities to succeed, not only in the academic setting but also in
social and economic future endeavors ( Ritchie and Bates, 2013). There
is suﬃcient evidence supporting a strong relationship between mathe-
matical development and the skills required for symbolic numerical
magnitude processing ( Durand, Hulme, Larkin, & Snowling, 2005;
Holloway and Ansari, 2009; Lyons, Price, Vaessen, Blomert, & Ansari,
2014; Sasanguie, De Smedt, Defever, & Reynvoet, 2012; Vogel, Remark,
& Ansari, 2015 ).
The integration of multiple brain regions during early arithmetic
processing has been studied using functional magnetic resonance ima-
ging methods (fMRI: Anderson, 2007; Dehaene, Piazza, Pinel, & Cohen,
2003; Rosenberg-Lee, Lovett, & Anderson, 2009 ). In this regard, and aspart of children's cognitive development, arithmetic problem solvinghas been related to relevant changes in the hippocampal-neocortical
functional connectivity ( Cho et al., 2012; Qin et al., 2014).
A recent quantitative meta-analysis of fMRI studies in healthy
children below the age of 14 revealed that number tasks (those invol-
ving numbers without formal calculation) are mainly associated with
the signi ﬁcant participation of the inferior parietal lobule (Brodmann
area: BA 40), extending to regions of the inferior parietal sulcus,claustrum and insula (BA 13) in the right hemisphere, whereas calcu-lation tasks implicate structures from both hemispheres ( Arsalidou,
Pawliw-Levac, Sadeghi, & Pascual-Leone in press ). Children with math
diﬃculties though, have a reduced ability to process symbolic re-
presentations ( Iuculano, Tang, Hall, & Butterworth, 2008; Mussolin,
Mejias, & Noël, 2010 ), and they show an inappropriate task modulation
and brain hyperconnectivity ( Rosenberg-Lee et al., 2015 ) while per-
forming simple arithmetic operations.
