T Despite the fact that ﬂuency in processing magnitudes associated
with Arabic numerals may be a critical foundational skill for arithmetic,
few attempts have been made to assess the integrated cortical functions
underlying the earlier steps of this process, particularly through the use
of tools with high temporal resolution.
Cortical electrical ﬂuctuations can be measured at low cost and
noninvasively with electroencephalographic (EEG) sensors placed on
the scalp. EEG is a useful tool for functional connectivity analysis since
it provides a direct measure of cortical synaptic activity with high
temporal resolution. More speci ﬁcally, EEG coherence; a measure of the
degree of association or coupling of frequency spectra between twodiﬀerent time series, is considered a hallmark of integrated cortical
functions ( Moazami-Goudarizi, Sarnthein, Michels, Moukhtieva, &
Jeanmonod, 2008) that has been applied to evaluate functional con-
nectivity in the human cortex ( Gross et al., 2001; Srinivasan, Winter,
Ding, & Nunez, 2007 ). In fact, EEG coherence has been interpreted as a
reﬂection of the functional association between di ﬀerent brain regions
(Nunez et al., 1997; Sklar, Hanley, & Simmons, 1972 ; see Lowe et al.,
2016 for an extensive review).
In 2005, Mizuhara and colleagues combined simultaneous fMRI and
EEG methods to evaluate a group of young adults while performing a
simple arithmetic operation ( Mizuhara, Wang, Kobayashi, &
Yamaguchi, 2005 ). They found an increase in phase synchronization in
beta frequency across biparietal areas that probably represent a func-
tional link between the left angular gyrus and the right superior parietal
gyrus, including several other anterior –posterior regions (right dorso-
lateral prefrontal cortex, putamen, and right superior temporal gyrus).In brief, phase synchronization was interpreted as a possible function of
beta oscillations around parietal sites re ﬂecting attentional control for
spatial working memory, which has been associated with mathachievement ( Cirino, Tolar, Fuchs, & Huston-Warren, 2016; Toll,
Kroesbergen, & Van Luit, 2016 ).
Traditionally related with sensorimotor processing ( Hari and
Salmelin, 1997; Pfurtscheller and Lopez da Silva, 1999 ), oscillations in
the beta frequency have recently become more broadly interpreted asreﬂecting functional coupling across large distances ( Bibbig, Traub, &
Whittington, 2002; Kopell, Ermentrout, Whittington, & Traub, 2000 ),
“readiness ”, and maintenance of the current brain state ( Engel and
Fries, 2010), as well as implicated in top-down processing ( Spitzer and
Haegens, 2017).
Spitzer, Blankenburg (2014) examined the oscillatory signature of
abstract numerosity information in human working memory, within
and across sensory modalities. They found numerosity-dependent
modulations of right prefrontal upper beta (20 –30 Hz) that probably
reﬂected the extent to which numerosity was assessed by analog esti-
mation, both between and within presentation modalities, and inter-
preted their ﬁndings as an index of abstract numerosity integration, at a
supramodal processing stage in working memory.
Recently, Tschentscher and Hauk (2016) evaluated arithmetic pro-
blem-solving in adults and reported a strong beta desynchronization inright frontal, parietal, and temporal regions as a function of executive
demands interpreted by the authors as been related to the use of pro-cedural
strategies. These ﬁndings seem to be in line with those from
Gaillard et al. (2009) , and Trübutschek et al. (2017) , who interpreted
the alpha/beta desynchronization as a correlate of conscious percep-
tion, and a neural state common to conscious perception and conscious
working memory. Other studies have partially associated beta event-
related desynchronization (ERD) with cognitive processing ( Pesonen,
Björnberg, Hämäläinen, & Krause, 2006; Weiss and Rappelsberger,1998 ), or with the planning and/or preparation of the motor response
(Kaiser, Birbaumer, & Lutzenberger, 2001); while beta event-related
synchronization (ERS) has been interpreted as re ﬂecting memory pro-
cessing ( Pesonen et al., 2006; Wisniewski, Mercado, Church, Gramann,
& Makeig, 2014).
In light of these antecedents, the present study aimed to evaluate
the EEG coherence in children with di ﬀerent math skills levels, whileperforming a symbolic numerical magnitude comparison task, parti-
cularly focusing on changes in the beta frequency band. We hypothe-
sized that di ﬀerent level of arithmetic skills in children might associate
with distinct brain EEG coherence patterns, as a result of the degree ofspecialization that has been developed.
2. Methods2.1. Participants
The sample included forty 8-to-9-year-old children selected from a
pool of 441 third-graders from six public and three private elementary
schools. In order to assess their mathematical abilities, all children
completed the math sub-section of the Wide Range Achievement Test,
4th edition (WRAT-4; Wilkinson and Robertson, 2006 ). Participants
were equally divided into two groups according to their performance onthe WRAT-4: Low Achievement (LA; Mean age = 9.1, SD = 0.62; 10
females) having scores within the lower 15th percentile, and High
Achievement (HA; Mean age = 9.1, SD = 0.33; 6 females) belonging to
the upper 15th percentile. Children were matched according to their
educational environment, such that each LA subject was paired with an
HA child from the same school.
2.2. Procedure
A group administration of the WRAT-4 arithmetic sub-test was
performed in each elementary school halfway through the school year.
From 2-to-3 weeks later, on a separate session preceding the experi-
ment, several additional tests were applied: the abbreviated IQ version
of the Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children, WISC-IV (Block Design,
and Vocabulary), the Edinburgh Inventory of Handedness, and a
custom-designed questionnaire covering the children ’s neurodevelop-
ment which was answered by parents. They were all administered at theNeuroscience Institute Lab in a single session, lasting no more than
30 min.
All children were right-handed and had an estimated IQ of 90 or
higher [Mean (Standard Deviation): HA = 112.0(15.0);
LA = 99.4(7.7); F
(1,38) = 3.79, p= 0.027], according to the local
norms of the WISC-IV version. None of the participants had repeated aschool grade-level, nor had a history of psychiatric or behavioral dis-
orders. Parents provided written informed consent authorizing their
child ’s participation. The review and approval of the Ethics Committee
(ET122009-77) were obtained prior to conducting the study.Participants were then asked to perform a symbolic numerical com-
parison task with simultaneous EEG recording.
The quantities in the symbolic numerical comparison task were
presented in pairs of Arabic numerals with values ranging from 5 to 34.
The magnitude of the ratio between the number pairs was controlled in
the experimental design, so that half the pairs had a small ratio 1:2
(0.5): 5– 10, 7– 14, 10– 20, 11– 22, 13 –26, 14– 28, 17– 34, while the other
half, had a greater ratio 3:4 (0.75): 6– 8, 9 –12, 12– 16, 15– 20, 18 –24,
21–28, and 24– 32. The left and right presentation of the numerical
value with the greater magnitude was counterbalanced. Children wereinstructed to determine which of the two numbers represented a higher
quantity; and depending, on whether the higher magnitude number was
on the left, or on the right side of the screen, they had to respond by
pressing a key using the corresponding index ﬁnger. Children were
comfortably seated at a 60-cm distance of a 17-inch LCD monitor(screen resolution = 1280 × 1024) in which each number pair was
displayed. The task comprised a total of 2 blocks (56 stimuli each,lasting about 2 min) with a 3 min resting period between them. The
pairs were presented in pseudo-random order within each block, and
the order of the blocks was counterbalanced among participants.
Each trial began with the presentation of a ﬁxation cross (400 ms),
followed by a pair of numerical values (1000 ms), and then a gray
screen (400 ms). Participants were instructed to focus on the ﬁxationA.A. González-Garrido et al. Brain and Cognition 124 (2018) 57–63
58 cross to minimize ocular artifacts. The software package (MINDTRA-
CER, Neuronic Systems, Inc.) controlled stimuli presentation and au-
tomatically marked behavioral responses.
2.3. Stimuli
A total of 112 pairs of Arabic numerals were shown in 54-point Arial
font. These images were displayed on a gray background with yellow
and blue print for the right and left numerals, respectively.
2.4. Electrophysiological methods2.4.1. Recording
Electrophysiological (EEG) activity was recorded from 19 scalp
electrode sites (C3, C4, CZ, F3, F4, F7, F8, FZ, Fp1, Fp2, O1, O2, P3, P4,
PZ, T3, T4, T5, and T6) using an Electro-Cap (Electrocap Inc., Eaton,
Ohio). Electrooculograms (EOGs) were additionally recorded from the
outer canthus and infraocular orbital ridge of the right eye using 10-mm
diameter gold-disc electrodes. Electrode sites were referenced to linked-
earlobes. Inter-electrode impedances were < 5 kilo-ohms at 30 Hz. EEG
and EOG signals were ampli ﬁed at a band-pass of 0.5-to-30 Hz (3dB
cutoﬀpoints of 6 dB/octave roll-o ﬀcurves) with a sampling period of
5 ms in a MEDICID-04 system (Neuronic Systems, Inc.). Data was col-
lected in trials of 1000-ms intervals segmented into the ﬁrst 100 ms
–used for baseline correction –and the subsequent 900 ms, for all re-
corded channels. Single-trial data was stored o ﬀ-line for averaging and
analysis.
2.5. Data analysis2.5.1. Behavioral measures
Correct, incorrect and non -responses, as well as reaction times, were
automatically collected by the software and marked in the EEG as it was
being recorded. A mixed-design, repeated measures ANOVA with Group
(LA and HA) as the between-subject factor, and Ratio (small and large)
as the within-subject factor, was performed to examine correct re-
sponses and reaction times during experimental task performance.
2.5.2. Signal processing
EEG time windows lasting 1000 ms –from 100 ms before to 900 ms
after stimulus onset –corresponding to a correct behavioral response
were selected from each participant ’s EEG recording (i.e. 20 similar
epochs of 1000 ms EEG time windows from each LA and 20 from HA
participants). In addition to the visual inspection of the EEG, a Blind
Source Separation method was used for artifact and noise canceling
based on the methodology presented by Romo et al. (2012; see
Barthélemy et al., 2017 for review) . Afterward, a 3-layer realistic geo-
metry head model of volume conduction was built with the aim to
implement the Surface Laplacian solution through a realistic head
geometry model originally described for adults ( Deng, Winter, Thorpe,
& Srinivasan, 2012). Due to the age of our participants, we decided totailor the ﬁnal spatial sampling by adjusting our calculations to the
averaged coordinates of the sensor position ﬁles settled in the EGI 3-D
model for children aged 2 –9, and 9– 18 years, respectively, in each lo-
cation in which EEG was recorded in our sample. The realistic headgeometry model consisted of an innermost layer brain structure, sur-
rounded by two realistic-geometry structures for the skull and scalp.
The spatial ﬁlter was applied to all the EEG recordings prior to co-
herence estimation. Subsequently, the brain connectivity ’s dynamic was
estimated from a connectivity matrix calculated using the magnitude-
squared coherence from surface Laplacian EEG ( Chorlian,
Rangaswamy, & Porjesz, 2009; Nunez et al., 1999; Srinivasan, 2007 ).
In the present study, coherence was calculated among the 19 elec-
trodes placed on the scalp. Therefore, we obtained a 361-coherence
spectra symmetric matrix showing the relationship between all elec-
trode sites within the recorded EEG frequency band (0 –30 Hz).To begin with, ‘the connectivity degree ’of
each electrode (electrode
of interest: EOI) was estimated with respect to the others. This was done
by averaging the coherence spectrum for each of the rows of the co-
herence spectra matrix excluding the coherence spectrum of each EOI.
Thus, 19 averaged coherence spectra representing the connectivity
degree of each electrode were obtained. This procedure was performed
for each subject from the LA group and the HA group. Subsequently, 31
columns corresponding to the frequency values from 0 to 30 Hz of the
coherence spectra were selected. A one-way-ANOVA with Tukey ’s
honest signi ﬁcant di ﬀerence (HSD) corrections was performed to assess
which of the recording sites showed the most signi ﬁcant di ﬀerences
within a 95% to 99% con ﬁdence interval, with respect to the means of
the connectivity degree among all the electrodes. The Frequency factor
was also tested using a similar procedure for each electrode inter-
connection.
Another one-way-ANOVA with Tukey ’s HSD corrections was per-
formed to elucidate which of the electrode inter-connections presented
the most signi ﬁcant di ﬀerence within a 95– 99% con ﬁdence interval,
and they were selected by setting two thresholds of p < 0.05 andp < 0.01, respectively. The coherence spectra in the diagonal (19) of
the coherence spectra matrix were removed along with the lower tri-
angular coherence spectra matrix (171). Consequently, the analysis
included only the remaining 171 coherence spectra values.
3. Results
3.1. Behavioral performances
The HA group had a signi ﬁcantly greater number of correct re-
sponses ( F
(1, 38) = 30.131, p< 0.001, η2= 0.442), and faster reaction
times ( F(1, 38) = 14.362, p< 0.01, η2= 0.274) than LA. In addition, a
ratio-related di ﬀerence in the performance was found for the amount of
correct responses ( F(1, 38) = 89.732, p< 0.001, η2= 0.703), and for
the reaction times ( F(1, 38) = 41.570, p< 0.001, η2= 0.442). Namely,
responses were more accurate when evaluating longer ratios. However,
no signi ﬁcant interaction was found between group and ratio
(p = 0.11).
3.2. Electrophysiological results
Table 1 shows the frequencies in which coherence reached the most
signiﬁcant di ﬀerences between the groups. A noteworthy ﬁnding is that
the performance of the numeric comparison task elicits signi ﬁcant
