59 coherence group di ﬀerences that involve frequencies from almost all
the traditional frequency bands, although most within the beta spec-
trum. Interestingly, LA showed higher coherence in theta and alpha
bands, while it was signi ﬁcantly greater for HA in the beta band, par-
ticularly at higher beta frequencies.
The analysis also identi ﬁed the scalp locations in which greater
coherence di ﬀerences were obtained between the groups. Despite the
extensive connectivity pattern shown, the more signi ﬁcantly coherence
values were reached by recording sites predominantly distributed overthe right hemisphere, regardless of group membership. The left section
ofFig. 1 shows the scalp locations with signi ﬁcant between-group co-
herence di ﬀerences.
Moreover, analysis of the speci ﬁc connectivity between the scalplocations, marked as those with greater coherence di ﬀerences between
the groups, shows a distinctive pattern for LA and HA in the resultantgraph (the right section in Fig. 1 shows the connectivity graphs in both
groups). As it is depicted in Fig. 1, the LA-group has a more extended
coherence topographic pattern that mainly involves frontoparietal
areas, predominantly a ﬀecting the right hemisphere, while compara-
tively, a more bilateral and predominantly parietal connectivity is ob-served in the HA group. The bottom part of the Fig. 1 illustrates a
comparison of the coherence matrices obtained from both groups indelta, theta, alpha, and beta frequency bands.
Fig. 2 compares the changes in the absolute power of the two groups
of children across the time –frequency domain at parietal locations.
Most of the visible changes across this domain predominantly occurred
