4. Discussion
As expected, LA ’s behavioral performance was more inaccurate than
that of HA, con ﬁrming previous reports about the relationship observed
between math di ﬃculties and the processing of numerical magnitudes
(De Smedt and Gilmore, 2011; Iuculano et al., 2008; Rousselle and
Noël, 2007 ). In addition, the “distance e ﬀect”which has been su ﬃ-
ciently supported by several studies on numerical processing (e.g.,
Banks and Flora, 1977; Moyer and Landauer, 1967; Schwarz and
Heinze, 1998 ), can be observed in the results from both groups. How-
ever, the distance e ﬀect was not signi ﬁcantly di ﬀerent between the
groups, probably because the relationship between discriminability and
size-ratio is modulated by task demands and familiarity with the
compared stimuli ( Leibovich, Ashkenazi, Rubinsten, & Henik, 2013 ).
The problem size was originally conceived as a variable to be balancedby the present experimental design. Therefore, an exhaustive analysis of
the interaction between arithmetic achievement and problem size was
beyond the scope of this research, thus representing a limitation to befurther investigated in future studies.
LA children showed signi ﬁcantly lower IQ compared to their peers.
It is not surprising because dyscalculia has been found as comorbid in
children with lower IQ levels ( 2005; Shalev, Manor, Auerbach, & Gross-
Tsur, 1998 ). However, it is important to emphasize that none of the
participants had an IQ score lower than 90, which corresponds to anaverage level.
It has been largely debated whether numerical processing operates
within a specialized brain module or if this type of processing runs in amore generalized system used to process both numerical and non-nu-
merical magnitudes. Several studies have evaluated comparative judg-
ments on di ﬀerent kinds of numerical and non-numerical magnitudes,
and they have reported both distinct and overlapping neural popula-tions (e.g., Cohen, Lammertyn, & Izard, 2008; Dormal, Dormal, Joassin,
& Pesenti, 2012; Fias, Lammertyn, Reynvoet, Dupont, & Orban, 2003;Pinel, Piazza, Le Bihan, & Dehaene, 2004 ). In this regard, a recent
quantitative meta-analytic study seems to support the hypothesis thatregions along the parietal and frontal cortex host a general magnitude
processing system for numerical magnitude processing (See
Sokolowski, Fias, Mousa, and Ansari (2017b) , for a comprehensive re-
view).
A greater involvement of frontal regions during task performance
was found in the LA group. This ﬁnding is consistent with behavioral
studies showing slower development of number-related competencies
in LA and learning-disabled children, along with working memory
deﬁcits ( Arsalidou and Taylor, 2011 ). It also coincides with behavioral
studies of group di ﬀerences speci ﬁcally, delays in ﬂuency of number
processing and slower development of number-related competencies in
LA and learning-disabled children and more working memory de ﬁcits
in these children ( Geary,
 Hoard, Nugent, & Bailey, 2012).
In general, low EEG coherence between frontal and parietal regions
has been associated with poor executive performance ( Teramoto et al.,
2016 ). Moreover, it has been reported that frontal coherence in delta
and beta frequencies positively correlated with memory and executivefunction performance ( Fleck, Kuti, Brown, Mahon, & Gayda-Chelder,
2016 ). However, brain imaging studies have revealed that functional
activation associated with numerical task performance is not restrictedto frontal and parietal cortices, but also includes regions related with
the dorsal and ventral visual pathways, as well as sub-cortical structures
Fig. 2. The spectral power (dB/Hz) of the parietal locations in children with di ﬀerent arithmetic achievements while performing a symbolic magnitude comparison
task is shown in time –frequency distribution illustrations.A.A. González-Garrido et al. Brain and Cognition 124 (2018) 57–63
61 (Arsalidou and Taylor, 2011; Kaufmann, Wood, Rubinsten, & Henik,
2011 ).
From this angle, greater frontal involvement in LA children might be
interpreted as an e ﬀort to recruit additional cognitive resources to ful ﬁll
task demands. This could be because frontal brain regions seem to host
the magnitude representations of the numbers (see Sokolowski, Fias,
Bosah Ononye, and Ansari (2017a) , for an extensive review), but they
are also involved in numerical tasks ( Arsalidou and Taylor, 2011 ).
Considering that there is an ontogenetic specialization of the left in-ferior parietal, and the lateral occipito-temporal cortices for mental
arithmetic and the processing of symbolic visual stimuli, respectively
(see Ansari (2008) , for an extensive review), the greater frontal parti-
cipation in LA might represent an overexpression of the fronto-parietaldevelopmental dynamic, probably denoting a lower specialization of
the numerical processing. However, this interpretation should be taken
cautiously, due to the limited spatial resolution of the EEG analysis
tools.
In contrast to what was observed in LA, the more focalized co-
herence found in HA over parietal areas might re ﬂect the numerical
processing per se, probably suggesting a higher degree of automation or
system specialization in this group of children with better arithmetic
skills.
Previous studies regarding EEG spectral parameters have shown the
involvement of theta, alpha and delta bands in arithmetic processing
and developmental changes therein. Recently, Hesse, Schmitt,
Klingenhoefer, and Bremmer (2017) described a bilateral increase in
evoked theta power while performing a visual task in which di ﬀerent
numerosity was presented as task-irrelevant stimuli. These variations intheta band were interpreted as evidence of a pre-attentive processing of
numerical visual information. Moreover, the dynamic change of at-
tentional demand during information processing has been related to
alpha activity ( Wei, Zhao, Yan, Duan, & Li, 1998 ). In this context, the
diﬀerences observed in the temporal oscillations of these EEG bands
suggest that arithmetic skills seem to mainly a ﬀect the processing
phases subsequent to encoding. This notion seems to agree with the
ﬁndings of Thevenot, Fanget, and Fayol (2007) , who developed an
operand recognition paradigm for studying the strategies used by in-dividuals to solve arithmetic problems, and found that high-skilled in-
dividuals relied preferably on retrieval strategies while less-skilled in-
dividuals resort to nonretrieval strategies.
There is su ﬃcient evidence suggesting a direct association between
numerical processing and changes in other EEG frequency bands,
however the involvement of the beta band is still poorly known. Indeed,
the presented results show that most of the spectral coherence di ﬀer-
ences between the groups occurred in the beta band hence suggesting amajor role of this EEG band in distinguishing among children based on
arithmetic numerical abilities. In this regard, previous reports on
changes in beta activity during mathematical problem solving ( Lin,
Jung, Wu, She, & Jung, 2015; Mizuhara et al., 2005 ), arithmetic tasks
(Widagdo, Pierson, & Helme, 1998), and during the learning process on
how to solve proportional reasoning tasks ( Vecchiato et al., 2013 )
suggest the need for further exploration of the association between the
beta band spectrum and math processing skills.
Interestingly, HA showed greater coherence on most of the upper
beta power frequencies (20 –30 Hz), which have been associated with
successful integration over central and parietal electrodes, probablyreﬂecting general control processes that can facilitate temporal in-
tegration ( Geerligs and Akyürek, 2012 ).
 This greater coherence might
also be interpreted as part as a more e ﬃcient attentional top-down
processing in which beta band oscillations may relate not only to theinvolvement of top-down processing but also to the content of the top-
down signal (see Engel and Fries, 2010, for review).
It is also important to highlight that the di ﬀerences found between
the groups were not restricted to the beta band. Given that EEG co-
herence represents a solid measure of functional connectivity in the
human cortex, the present results suggest that symbolic numericalcomparisons in children may involve a more complex functional in-
tegration of several brain networks, in which math achievements might
be related with speci ﬁc dynamic functional interconnections.
4.1. Limitations of the present study
The present study has three main limitations. The ﬁrst one con-
cerning the restricted number of artifact-free EEG epochs included inthe analysis, and its impact on the electrophysiological expression of
the evaluated processes. The second concerning the lack of direct
functional evidence from the neuroanatomical sources involved in the
numeric processing, thus restricting the theoretical interpretation of the
results, which is a topic that should be addressed in future studies. And
ﬁnally the third, that we were unable to apply a realistic head geometry
model that would adjust to the exact age of our sample even though thiswould have been ideal.
5. Conclusions
Middle childhood di ﬀerences in mathematical achievement are il-
lustrated by EEG coherence analyses and underlying brain functional
dynamic while comparing symbolic magnitudes. The present results
suggest that di ﬀerent math skills represent dissimilar degrees of a
number-processing specialization system that probably involves severalcomplex interacting neural networks with a distinct topographic dis-
tribution; mainly a ﬀecting the processing steps subsequent to the en-
coding phase and probably encouraging the choice of the cognitivestrategy more suitable to the available processing resources.
Nevertheless, further studies are necessary to elucidate if numerical
comparison task-related functional connectivity is directly associated
with domain-general factors that participate in mathematical learning,
such as, working memory, reasoning, and processing speed, among
others. We also believe it is essential that future research aims to clarifythe seemingly important role of the EEG beta band in this particular
type of cognitive processes.
6.Conﬂicts of interest
None.
