4.1. EEG Preprocessing 
The raw EEG signals were preprocessed usin g the EEGLAB toolbo x. First, the sam-
pling frequency was down-sampled from 1000 Hz to 200 Hz. Filtering operations were 
performed on the EEG signals by bandpass ﬁlters (1–75 Hz) and trap ﬁlters (49–51 Hz) to 
eliminate the high and low frequency noise an d IF interference. A global averaging refer-
ence was applied for re-referencing to enhance the signal. The bad channels were cor-
rected by removing the bad channel, while th e original signals were decomposed by in-
dependent component analysis (ICA) and the ar tifactual components such as the ophthal-
mic, oculomotor, EMG, and ECG values were re moved from the original signals to obtain 
relatively pure EEG data. The EEG samples ob tained under each task were divided by a 
time window of 3 s. A total of 1080 EEG samp les were collected from each subject, and 
the EEG signals were categorized into four fr equency bands, delta (1–3 Hz), theta (4–8 
Hz), alpha (8–12 Hz), and beta (12–30 Hz) using the Bu tterworth ﬁlter. 
