4.1. EEG Preprocessing
The raw EEG signals were preprocessed using the EEGLAB toolbox. First, the sam-
pling frequency was down-sampled from 1000 Hz to 200 Hz. Filtering operations were
performed on the EEG signals by bandpass filters (1–75 Hz) and trap filters (49–51 Hz)
to eliminate the high and low frequency noise and IF interference. A global averaging
reference was applied for re-referencing to enhance the signal. The bad channels were
corrected by removing the bad channel, while the original signals were decomposed by
independent component analysis (ICA) and the artifactual components such as the oph-
thalmic, oculomotor, EMG, and ECG values were removed from the original signals to
obtain relatively pure EEG data. The EEG samples obtained under each task were divided
by a time window of 3 s. A total of 1080 EEG samples were collected from each subject, and
the EEG signals were categorized into four frequency bands, delta (1–3 Hz), theta ( 4–8 Hz ),
alpha (8–12 Hz), and beta (12–30 Hz) using the Butterworth filter.
