2Tel.:  +30  28210  32716.1. Introduction
In  recent  years  analyses  of  hemodynamic  and  electrophysi-
ological  data  using  algorithms  derived  from  graph  theory  have
been  applied  extensively  to  the  study  of  brain  networks  at
rest  and  during  performance  of  cognitive  tasks  [1–3] .  While
the  body  of  research  devoted  to  the  neurobiological  bases
of  math-related  cognitive  functions  is  rapidly  rising  in  recent
years,  very  few  studies  have  examined  underlying  neuronal
networks.  In  school-aged  children  older  than  approximately  9
http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.neulet.2014.05.048
0304-3940/© 2014  Elsevier  Ireland  Ltd.  All  rights  reserved. M.  Vourkas  et  al.  /  Neuroscience  Letters  576  (2014)  28–33  29
years,  activation  patterns  are  similar  to  those  observed  in  adults
[4–6] .
Tools  derived  from  network  science  have  been  particularly  use-
ful  in  efforts  to  construct  dynamic  models  of  function-speciﬁc  brain
networks.  In  these  conceptualizations  network  nodes  are  repre-
sented  by  voxels  (or  regions  of  interest  in  MRI/fMRI  data),  scalp
electrodes  or  magnetic  sensors,  or  estimated  intracranial  sources
derived  from  EEG  or  MEG  data.  Despite  recent  progress  in  graph
theoretical  analysis,  important  issues  remain  unresolved,  includ-
ing  methods  to  compare  networks  across  experimental  conditions
and  groups  [8,9] ,  where  the  number  of  connections  per  node,  the
number  of  links  (edges),  and  the  overall  size  of  the  network,  may
affect  the  results.
A  relatively  novel  approach  to  graph  modeling  is  based  on  min-
imum  spanning  tree  (MST)  indices  derived  from  a  weighted  graph.
MST  analyses  are  used  to  deﬁne  subgraphs  by  ensuring  that  all
nodes  are  connected  to  each  other  without  forming  circles  or  loops
[9–12] .  The  nodes  of  the  MST  are  the  same  as  in  the  original  graph
(for  N  nodes,  there  are  exactly  N−1  links).  Graphs  obtained  for
different populations or  experimental  conditions  can  be  directly
compared  on  the  basis  of  quantitative  indices,  graphically  outlined
in Fig. 1A  (suppl.).
Supplementary  Figure  related  to  this  article  can  be  found,  in  the
online version, at  http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.neulet.2014.05.048 .
Very  few  studies  have,  to  date,  explored  neurophysiological  cor-
relates  of  mathematical  cognition  using  graph  analysis  [13–15] .
Graph  analysis  relying  on  MST  indices  has  been  used  sparsely
to  describe  surface-level,  electrophysiological  connectivity  pat-
terns  (indicative  of  network  integration)  comparing  age  groups  [9],
patients  suffering  from  neurological  disorders  or  healthy  individu-
als  (e.g.  [7,16,17] ).
The  present  study  examined  surface-level  connectivity  pat-
terns,  utilizing  MST  indices,  in  school-age  children  with  typically
achieving  on  math  tests  while  engaged  in  subtraction  and  sim-
ple  addition  tasks.  EEG  data  were  also  obtained  from  an  age
and  verbal  IQ-matched  group  of  students  demonstrating  persis-
tent  difﬁculty  in  acquiring  basic  calculation  skills  through  Grades
3–5.  The  goal  of  the  study  was  to  assess  systematic  individual
variability  in  the  outline  of  sensor-level  neural  networks  as  a
function of  task  difﬁculty  and  arithmetic  skill  as  well  as  to  ﬁnd
the  between  the  group  differences.  It  was  hypothesized  that  EEG
frequencies  known  to  be  involved  in  long-range  regional  inter-
dependencies  (i.e.,  theta,  alpha)  would  show  MST  parameters
indicative  of  less  integrated  topology  in  the  more  difﬁcult,  subtrac-
tion  task.  Moreover,  MST  parameters  in  higher  frequency  bands
(beta),  presumed  to  be  mainly  involved  in  interregional  connec-
tivity,  were  expected  to  show  MST  parameters  indicative  of  less
integrated,  local  activity  (more  segregated)  with  increasing  task
demands.
2.  Materials  and  methods
2.1.  Participants
With  permission  from  the  University  of  Crete,  School  of
Medicine  Ethics  Committee  (in  agreement  with  the  Declaration  of
Helsinki)  and  the  Research  Department  of  the  Greek  Institute  of
Education,  and  after  parents  signed  an  informed  consent,  1382  stu-
dents  attending  Grade  3  were  screened  for  math  difﬁculties,  using
the  Greek  Math  Screening  Test  (GMST,  [18] )  consisting  of  13  sim-
ple  calculation  problems  (Time  1).  Two  groups  of  students  were
selected  based  on  their  performance:  a  low  performance  group  of
students  scoring  below  the  16th  percentile  on  GMST  (n  =  122),  and
a typical  performance  group,  scoring  above  the  35th  percentile  on
GMST  (n  =  122).  Parental  consent  for  further  cognitive  assessmentwas  obtained  for  124  students  who  were  administered  a  follow  up
cognitive  and  comprehensive  math  assessment  at  the  beginning  of
Grade  4  (Time  2).  Fifty  one  students  met  the  inclusion  criteria  for  the
EEG  study:  Estimated  WISC-III  Full  Scale  IQ  >  80,  age-adjusted  score
above  the  25th  percentile  on  standardized  word  and  pseudoword
reading  tests,  and  age-adjusted  T  score  lower  than  70  points  on
any  of  the  eight  Child  Behavior  Checklist-Parent  Version  syndrome
scales  assessing  attention  and  behavior  problems.  Students  in  the
math  disability  group  (MD;  n  =  20,  11  boys,  9  girls)  scored  below  the
16th  percentile  on  the  Neuropsychological  test  Battery  for  Number
Processing  and  Calculation,  whereas  students  in  the  math  non-
impaired  group  (NI;  n  =  31,  21  boys,  10  girls)  had  total  NUCALC
scores  above  the  50th  percentile.  All  were  right-handed  with  nor-
mal  or  corrected  to  normal  vision.  As  shown  in  Table  IA  (suppl.),  the
two  groups  were  comparable  on  gender  distribution,  age,  and  VIQ,
although  on  average  NI  participants  outperformed  MD  students  on
PIQ  and  Digit  Span  standard  scores.  EEG  recordings  on  all  students
were  obtained one year  later  (Time  3).  At  that  time  group  assign-
ment  was  veriﬁed  for  all  students  based  on  repeated  administration
of NUCALC.
Supplementary  Table  related  to  this  article  can  be  found,  in  the
online version, at  http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.neulet.2014.05.048 .
2.2.  Cognitive  and  math  assessment
At  Time  2  (Grade  4)  the  following  tests  were  administered  to
students  who  met  the  screening  criteria  to  exclude  intellectual,
reading  and  behavior  problems:  Vocabulary  and  Block  Design  sub-
scales  of  the  Wechsler  Intelligence  Scale  (WISC-III  [19] )  to  provide
a  rough  estimate  of  PIQ  and  VIQ,  respectively,  and  Digit  Span;
Word  and  Pseudoword  reading  subscales  from  the  Test  of  Reading
Proﬁciency  (TORP  [20] );  Greek  Math  Screening  Test  (GMST  [18] );
Neuropsychological  test  Battery  for  Number  Processing  and  Calcu-
lation  (NUCALC  [21] ),  for  a  more  detailed  assessment  of  math  skills
including  mental  calculation  (addition,  subtraction);  Child  Behav-
ior Checklist-Parent  Version  (CBCL  [22] )  to  assess  externalizing  and
internalizing  behavior  problems.  At  T3  (Grades  5  and  6)  all  stu-
dents were readministered  GMST  and  the  addition,  subtraction  and
multiplication  subscales  of  NUCALC  (timed  tests).
2.3.  Electroencephalographic  recordings
EEG  was  recorded  from  29  electrode  sites  according  to  a
modiﬁed  international  10/20/system  using  an  Electrocap  while
participants  performed  two  math  tasks  (addition  and  subtrac-
tion)  and  during  visual  ﬁxation  (control  condition).  Recordings
were  obtained  with  CONTACT  Precision  Instruments  ampliﬁers
and  digitized  on  a  DATAQ  AD  Converter.  The  children  were
seated  in  a  comfortable  chair  in  a  light-  and  sound-attenuated
room.
The addition  task  involved  16  single-digit  addition  problems
whereas  the  more  demanding  subtraction  task  consisted  of  16  cal-
culation  problems  involving  subtraction  of  a  single-digit  number
from  a  two-digit  number.  Each  problem  was  presented  above  a
two-digit  number  which  represented  either  a  correct  or  an  incor-
rect  result  (one  or  two  units  greater  or  smaller  than  the  correct
sum)  with  a  relative  probability  of  0.50.  The  nominal  intertrial
interval  was  set  to  2  s.  Participants  were  instructed  to  press  one
mouse  key  to  indicate  a  correct  equation  and  the  other  key  to  indi-
cate  an  incorrect  sum  or  difference.  For  each  task  12  s  of  EEG  were
recorded  with  a  star  presented  during  the  break  between  tasks
when  no  recording  was  made.  The  EEG  waveforms  were  moni-
tored  online  by  the  experimenter  who  initiated  presentation  of
the stimuli  upon  detecting  an  artifact-free  period.  Recording  was
paused  during  periods  of  frequent  artifacts  to  allow  participants 30  M.  Vourkas  et  al.  /  Neuroscience  Letters  576  (2014)  28–33
to  re-engage  in  the  task.  The  correspondence  between  keys  and
type  of  answer  was  counterbalanced  across  participants  as  was
the  order  of  conditions.  All  electrode  impedances  were  kept  below
5  k˝.  High-  and  low-pass  ﬁlters  were  set  at  0.004  Hz  and  200  Hz,
respectively,  and  sampling  rate  at  500  Hz.  Ofﬂine,  a  single  8  s
epoch  (4096  samples)  was  selected  per  participant  and  condition
covering  a  period  during  which  the  participant  was  engaged  in
three  consecutive  calculations  and  the  EEG  was  free  from  visible
artifacts.
Graph analyses  were  performed  in  the  following  frequency
bands,  theta  (4–6.5  Hz),  alpha1  (6.5–9  Hz),  alpha2  (9–12  Hz),
and  beta  (12–30  Hz),  with  BRAINWAVE  v.9.54  (C.J.  Stam,
http://home.kpn.nl/stam7883/brainwave.html ).  Weighted  graphs
were  constructed  from  Phase  Lag  Index  (PLI)  values,  which  calcu-
late  the  asymmetry  of  the  distribution  of  phase  differences  between
two  time  series.  The  values  of  PLI  reﬂect  true  interactions  that  are
unaffected  by  ﬁeld  spread,  volume  conduction,  or  the  presence  of
common  sources contributing to  both  electrodes  in  a  pair  [23] .
Graphs  were  constructed  from  PLI  matrices  for  each  frequency  band
using the minimum  spanning  tree  (MST)  method,  which  relies  on
a  ﬁxed  number  of  nodes  and  edges,  and  is  independent  of  average
coupling strength [9].  The  MST  consists  of  the  strongest  connec-
tions  in  the  entire  weighted,  undirected  graph  so  that  the  sum
of the weighted  path  length  is  minimized  without  forming  cycles
[16,24,25] .  This  method  is  considered  as  more  suitable  relative  to
the  traditional  small-world  model  in  identifying  crucial  “hubs”  in
the  network  (i.e.,  nodes  of  particular  importance  for  global  infor-
mation  ﬂow  [3]).
The  following  parameters  characterizing  the  MST  of  each  partic-
ipant  and  condition  were  computed:  Maximum  Degree  (DEG:  the
highest  number  of  connections  formed  by  each  node),  Leaf  Number
(L:  the  number  of  nodes  with  Maximum  Degree  =  1).  Leaf  number
presents  an  upper  bound  to  the  diameter  of  the  tree  (DIAM),  which
is  the  largest  distance  between  any  two  nodes  of  the  tree.  Additional
indices  included  Eccentricity  (ECC:  the  longest  distance  between
a  given  node  and  any  other  node,  measured  in  number  of  edges),
Betweenness  Centrality  (BC:  the  fraction  of  shortest  paths  between
any  pair  of  nodes  that  are  running  through  a  particular  node),  Tree
Hierarchy  (Th:  an  estimate  of  the  balance  between  diameter  reduc-
tion and  overload  prevention),  and  Degree  Correlation  (R:  an  index
of  whether  the  degree  of  a  node  is  inﬂuenced  by  the  degree  of  its
neighboring  vertices).  A  given  graph  is  considered  as  Assortative
if  R  >  0,  and  Disassortative  if  R  <  0.  Betweeness  Centrality,  Degree
Correlation  and  Eccentricity  reﬂect  the  importance  of  individual
nodes.  Less  integrated  graphs  are  characterized  by  a  small  Leaf
Number,  low  Maximum  Degree,  large  Diameter,  and  high  Eccen-
tricity.  More  highly  integrated  graphs  have  a  small  Diameter,  a  large
Leaf  Number,  and  low  Eccentricity.
2.4.  Statistical  analyses
MST  indices  were  submitted  to  separate  ANOVAs  with  group
as  the  between-subjects  variable,  and  repeated  measures  for
Task  (Fixation,  Addition,  Subtraction).  MST  indices  that  char-
acterize  individual  nodes  (BC,  DEG,  and  R)  in  each  frequency
band  were  submitted  to  separate  ANOVAs  with  group  as  the
between-subjects  variable,  and  repeated  measures  for  Task
(Fixation,  Addition,  Subtraction),  Hemisphere  (left,  right),  Area
(fronto-central,  temporo-parietal),  and  Electrode  (F3/4,  F7/8,  FC3/4,
and  FT7/8  for  fronto-central  and  T3/4,  TP7/8,  CP3/4,  and  P3/4
for  temporo-parietal).  The  degree  and  direction  of  associations
between  MST  indices  demonstrating  signiﬁcant  ANOVA  results
and performance  on  corresponding  NUCALC  tasks  was  evaluated
through  Pearson  correlation  coefﬁcients.Table  1
