3.  Results
3.1.  Behavioral  assessments
Performance  on  the  GMST  and  NUCALC  subscales  (Table  IA
suppl.) showed that  the  NI  participants  signiﬁcantly  outperformed
their  MD  peers  on  both  accuracy  (p  <  .01)  and  speed  measures
(p  <  .0001)  and  that  the  magnitude  of  these  differences  persisted
across  T2  (4th  Grade)  and  T3  (5th  or  6th  Grade).
3.2. Network parameters
Table IIA (suppl.)  summarizes  MST  parameter  values  for  each
group.  Signiﬁcant  (p  <  .05)  task  effects  were  documented  for  several
MST indices  as  shown  in  Table  1.  These  effects  were  character-
ized  by  linear  trends  across  the  Fixation,  Addition,  and  Subtraction
tasks.  Overall,  results  indicated  that  Tree  Hierarchy  (theta  band),
Diameter  and  Eccentricity  (alpha  bands)  were  lowest  for  Subtrac-
tion  and  highest  during  Fixation.  These  linear  trends  were  reversed
in  the  beta  band  with  highest  Diameter,  Eccentricity,  and  Degree
Correlation  for  Subtraction,  lower  for  Addition,  and  lowest  for  Fix-
ation.  Additionally,  Leaf  Numbers  in  the  beta  band  were  smallest
during  Subtraction  as  compared  to  Addition  and  Fixation.  Addi-
tionally,  there  was  a  Group  effect  for  Degree  Correlation  in  alpha2
(MD  >  NI).  Analyses  assessing  interactions  of  Task  and  Group  with
scalp  location  (Area)  and  hemisphere  failed  to  reveal  signiﬁcant
effects.
Supplementary  Table  related  to  this  article  can  be  found,  in  the
online  version,  at  http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.neulet.2014.05.048 .
Across  groups,  moderate,  signiﬁcant  correlations  were  found
between  the  majority  of  MST  indices  where  task  effects  were  found,
and  performance  on  NUCALC  tasks.  These  results  are  shown  in
Table  2.  Perhaps  the  most  notable  ﬁnding  was  that  Eccentricity
and  Diameter  in  the  alpha2  band  was  positively  correlated  with
Subtraction  Speed  (i.e.,  higher  MST  values  were  associated  with
slower  performance  on  the  most  demanding  math  task).  More-
over,  Eccentricity  and  Diameter  in  the  alpha1  and  beta  bands  during
the  Addition  task  correlated  positively  with  Addition  Accuracy  and
negatively  with  time  to  complete  NUCALC  additions.  Thus,  higher
overall Eccentricity  and  Diameter  of  the  surface  network  were  asso-
ciated  with  better  performance  on  the  least  challenging  task.  The M. Vourkas  et  al.  /  Neuroscience  Letters  576  (2014)  28–33  31
