4. Discussion
The present study examined  aspects  of  brain  network  organi-
zation  using  the  MST  method  in  children  with  and  without  mathdifﬁculties  during  performance  of  arithmetic  tasks  that  varied  in
processing demands. Results indicated  that  whenever  a  task  main
effect  was  found,  the  linear  trend  was  also  signiﬁcant  suggesting
a  progressive modulation  of  the  corresponding  parameter  with
increased  task  difﬁculty.  Although  the  study  of  interdependency
measures  as  indices  of  functional  neuronal  connectivity  is  still  in
its  infancy,  certain  assumptions  can  be  made  with  respect  to  the
potential  signiﬁcance  of  these  measures  at  the  level  of  psychologi-
cal  functions.  A  very  basic  outline  of  the  results  which  were  evident
across  achievement  groups  can  be  summarized  as  follows:
First,  Tree  Hierarchy  in  the  theta  band  was  lowest  during  the
more  demanding  subtraction  task,  indicative  of  a  more  “line-like”
or  less  integrated  topology.  This  is  in  accordance  with  the  purported
Fig. 1.  Representative  MST  tree  in  the  alpha2  band  for  an  NI  participant  during  addition  and  subtraction. 32  M.  Vourkas  et  al.  /  Neuroscience  Letters  576  (2014)  28–33
role  of  theta  band  oscillations  in  long-range  cortical  signaling  [26] ,
assuming  that  the  more  complex  math  task  is  likely  to  engage  a
more  anatomically  complex  and  distributed  network  [4].
Second,  the  subtraction  task  was  associated  with  lower  Diame-
ter  and  Eccentricity  values,  compared  to  the  addition  and  ﬁxation
conditions,  in  the  alpha1  and  alpha2  bands .  Taken  together  these
ﬁndings  reveal  a  less  “line  like”  (or  more  “star-like”)  topology
during  subtraction  in  these  bands.  Increased  activity  in  alpha1
and  alpha2  bands  is  often  found  during  cognitive  tasks,  usu-
ally  in  combination  with  activity  in  higher  frequencies  [27] .
Long-range  synchronizations  between  neuronal  assembles  have
been  described  in  several  studies  during  engagement  of  cognitive
processes,  known  to  be  involved  in  demanding  calculation  tasks,
such  as  working  memory  [28,29] .  In  contrast  to  the  theta  band,  MST
parameters  in  the  alpha  bands  were  indicative  of  greater  network
integration  as  task  demands  increased.  In  particular,  Diameter  and
Eccentricity  estimates  may  be  suggestive  of  a  network  that  con-
tained  a greater number  of  nodes  crossed  by  shortest  paths,  thus
more  centralized  and  integrated  in  overall  layout.  Importantly,  cor-
relational results indicated  that  the  more  centralized/integrated
the  network  in  the  alpha  bands  was  the  more  efﬁcient  the  per-
formance on the  timed  NUCALC  subtraction  task.
Third,  the  pattern  of  task-related  changes  in  MST  parameters
was very distinct  in  the  higher  frequency  range  (beta  band) ,  which
is  generally  considered  as  mainly  involved  in  intraregional  connec-
tivity  [30–32] .  In  this  band,  performance  of  the  more  demanding
subtraction  task  was  associated  with  higher  diameter,  eccentric-
ity,  and  Degree  Correlation  values  as  compared  to  addition  and
ﬁxation.  This  pattern  of  MST  values  suggests  more  line-like  local
networks,  further  demonstrating  a  high  degree  of  assortativity  (i.e.,
greater  tendency  for  nodes  showing  similar  connection  patterns  to
be  interconnected).
A  puzzling  outcome  of  the  present  study  was  the  failure  to
ﬁnd  signiﬁcant  differences  between  age-  and  IQ-matched  achieve-
ment  groups,  which  may  be  accounted  for  in  several  ways.  For
instance,  it  is  possible  that  regional  dysfunction  reported  previ-
ously  in  MD  children  during  performance  of  math  tasks  by  fMRI
and  MEG  studies  is  not  accompanied  by  functional  altered  con-
nectivity  detectable  by  surface  EEG  recordings.  It  is  also  possible
that the  task-related  differences  found  in  the  present  study  more
closely  reﬂect  task  variations  in  overall  difﬁculty  (and  the  associ-
ated  modulation  of  the  degree  of  engagement  of  attentional  and
working  memory  processes),  rather  than  differential  engagement
of  processes  specialized  for  arithmetic  calculations.
Results  were  in  general  agreement  with  expectations  regard-
ing  the  roles  of  oscillations  in  different  frequencies  in  regional
brain  connectivity.  There  we  a  number  of  methodological  limi-
tations.  For  instance,  connectivity  patterns  were  assessed  at  the
sensor  level,  preventing  a  detailed  assessment  of  cortico-cortical
interdependencies  and  corresponding  network  outlines.  Moreover,
PLI  was  computed  on  relatively  long  EEG  segments  which  were
not  precisely  time-locked  to  the  presentation  of  calculation  prob-
lems.  This  method  was  adopted  in  order  to  include  a  wide  set  of
cognitive  operations  involved  in  calculation  in  view  of  the  highly
variable  time  frame  for  completing  each  problem  by  school-aged
children,  especially  those  experiencing  math  difﬁculties.  Although
this  choice  may  have  affected  the  generalizability  of  the  results  it
will  be  necessary  to  compare  our  results  with  MST  indices  derived
from  stimulus-time-locked  data.
5. Conclusions
The  present  study  represents  one  of  the  ﬁrst  attempts  to  estab-
lish links  between  cognitive  task  demands  and  brain  network
features  in  the  form  of  MST  parameters.  A  potentially  promisingresearch  direction  would  target  network  hubs  which,  in  line  with
our  ﬁndings  regarding  assortativity,  may  tend  to  be  more  closely
connected  to  other  centrally  located  hubs,  in  response  to  height-
ened  processing  demands.  The  existence  of  such  hubs  has  been
recently  postulated  on  the  basis  of  Diffusion  Tensor  Weighted  data
[33]  as  a  characteristic  feature  of  a  “rich-club”  brain  organization.
Future  studies  exploring  this  network  feature  would  probably  need
to  take  into  account  connectivity  patterns  in  multiple  frequency
bands, concurrently,  estimated  in  real  time,  i.e.,  during  the  unfold-
ing  of  the  targeted  cognitive  function,  in  order  to  isolate  network
features  that  are  more  intimately  linked  to  task  component  pro-
cesses.
